"Coburg Peak is a rocky peak located at an elevation of 783 meters in Erul Heights on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, Antarctica. It overlooks Cugnot Ice Piedmont to the northeast. The peak is named after the Bulgarian royal house of Coburg (Saxe-Coburg-Gotha) which existed from 1887 to 1946."
Siniger Nunatak is a rocky hill located in the upper course of Russell East Glacier on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, Antarctica. The nunatak rises to over 500 meters. Siniger Nunatak is named after the settlement of Siniger in Southern Bulgaria.
Harald Kaas was a Norwegian architect. He was born in Christiania (now Oslo), Norway on May 19, 1868. Kaas studied at the Norwegian National Academy of Craft and Art Industry, Baugewerkschule in Eckernförde, and Polytechnicum in Munich. He worked in the Colony of Natal in South Africa for a few years. From 1908 to 1914, he was employed by the Norwegian State Railways and designed stations on the Arendal Line, Bergen Line, and Solør Line. Harald Kaas passed away on December 5, 1953, and was buried on May 20, 1954, at Vår Frelsers gravlund in Oslo.
Utus Peak is a rocky peak rising to 1217 m in Trakiya Heights on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, Antarctica. The peak is named after the ancient Roman town of Utus in Northern Bulgaria.
Everest Food Products Pvt Ltd, known as Everest Spices, is an Indian company that specializes in manufacturing, distributing, and exporting ground spices and spice mixtures under the brand name Everest. Everest has been recognized as a Superbrands three times in 2003, 2006, and 2009, and has also received the FMCG Consumer Reaction Award. The company began aggressive television advertising in 2003 and by 2005, had captured 30% of the branded pure spices market in India. Everest is based in Mumbai and is considered India's largest spices brand, with over 20 million households regularly using their products. The brand is available in over 400,000 outlets across more than 1,000 towns in India, selling over 3.7 billion packs of Everest products annually. Everest also exports its products to various countries including the US, Middle East, Singapore, Australia, New Zealand, and East Africa. Everest Spices competes with MDH, another major player in the market with a 12% market share.
Jallo Park, also known as Jallo Wildlife Park, was established in 1978. It is a public recreation and wildlife site located in Lahore District, Punjab, Pakistan. The park covers a large area and is one of the three main wildlife parks in Lahore, along with Changa Manga and Lahore Zoo Safari. Jallo Park is situated to the east of Lahore city. The park offers various facilities including a Forest Research Centre, Wildlife Breeding Center, restaurants, coffee shops, a theme park, a sports complex, swimming pool, and a large lake for fishing and boating. It is currently funded by the Punjab Wildlife and Parks Department of the Government of Punjab. Access to Jallo Park is easy via taxi, TransLahore buses, and Lahore City Commuter trains that stop at Jallo Railway Station. The Botanical Garden Jallo is now part of this extensive wildlife park.
Paul L. Foster is an American businessman. Paul L. Foster is the chairman of the board of Western Refining. Western Refining is a Fortune 200 and Global 2000 oil refiner and marketer. Western Refining is based in El Paso, Texas.
Júlia Hajdú was a Hungarian composer and pianist. Júlia Hajdú was born into a Jewish family in Budapest. Júlia Hajdú died in the same city.
The American Repertory Ballet (ARB) is a ballet company based in New Jersey. The company was founded by Audrée Estey in 1963 as the Princeton Regional Ballet Company. In 1978, it became a professional company and was renamed Princeton Ballet Company. It was later renamed American Repertory Ballet in 1990. The former Garden State Ballet merged with ARB during the 1995-1996 season. ARB is a founding resident company of the New Brunswick Performing Arts Center.
"L'Oisans is a region in the French Alps, located in the départements of l'Isère and Hautes-Alpes. The region corresponds to the drainage basin of the River Romanche and its tributaries, including Eau d'Olle, Lignarre, Sarenne, Vénéon, and Ferrand. The geographical definition of Oisans coincides with the former cantons of Le Bourg-d'Oisans and La Grave. Oisans covers parts of the massifs of Belledonne, Taillefer, Grandes Rousses, Arves, and Écrins. The highest point in the region is the mountain of "Pic Lory," a subpeak of the Barre des Écrins, reaching a height of 4,088 metres. The most symbolic peak is la Meije, also known as the "Queen of the Oisans." Oisans is known for its mountain chains, valleys, rivers, streams, and plains, making it a popular tourist destination for both winter and summer sports. The region regularly hosts events like the Tour de France, Super-Biker, World of Snowboarding, Skiing World, Bike Festival, Andros Trophy, and the Criterium Cyclist of Dauphiné Libéré. The main access road to Oisans is the provincial road 1091, formerly known as RN 91, starting in the town of Livet-et-Gavet. Bourg d'Oisans is considered the capital of the territory, situated at the center of six valleys. Other significant towns in the region include Les Deux Alpes, Livet-et-Gavet, and Huez."
"The Voca People is an ensemble based in Israel. They specialize in vocal theater, combining a cappella and beat box vocals to replicate the sounds of an orchestra. The Voca People have performed in various countries including Spain, the USA, Hungary, Italy, France, England, and Israel. They engage the audience in their performances and adapt their songs based on the country they are in, incorporating local elements such as language and audience participation."
"Pseudopostega cretea is a moth of the family Opostegidae. Pseudopostega cretea was described by Edward Meyrick in 1920. Pseudopostega cretea is known from the eastern half of North America. Pseudopostega cretea is found in southern Canada, including Ontario, and south to northern Florida, west to south-eastern British Columbia, and Texas. The length of the forewings of Pseudopostega cretea is 3.9–4.6 mm. Adults of Pseudopostega cretea have been recorded from May to July in the southern United States and from June to August across the northern part of its range."
"Wilk Elektronik is a Polish manufacturer of computer memory under the brand name "GOODRAM". Wilk Elektronik is based in Łaziska Górne. After the bankruptcy of Qimonda, Wilk Elektronik remains the only European producer of RAM modules."
Maibritt Kviesgaard is a former Danish handball player. Maibritt Kviesgaard has played on the Danish national team. Maibritt Kviesgaard competed at the 2010 European Women's Handball Championship, where the Danish team placed fourth. Maibritt Kviesgaard was voted into the All-Star Team as Best Right Wing. Maibritt Kviesgaard was born on May 15, 1986.
The 2011 Nile Basin Tournament was an association football tournament organized by the Egyptian Football Association. The tournament took place in January 2011. All fixtures are listed on FIFA.com with a 'Friendly' weight status, meaning that results will impact the participating nations' FIFA World Rankings.
The 1977 Talladega 500 was a race in the NASCAR Winston Cup Series. The event occurred on August 7, 1977, at Talladega Superspeedway in Talladega, Alabama.
The 2011 National League Division Series (NLDS) were two best-of-five playoffs that determined the teams for the 2011 National League Championship Series. Three divisional winners and a wild card team played in two series. TBS televised all games in the United States, except for Game 3 of the Brewers-Diamondbacks series, which aired on TNT due to scheduling conflicts with the ALDS. The regular season ended on September 28, with the National League playoffs starting on October 1. MLB's playoff format ensured no matchups between teams from the same division in the Division Series. Home field advantage was given to the team with the better regular-season record, except for the wild card team. The matchups were: Philadelphia Phillies vs. St. Louis Cardinals (Cardinals won 3-2) and Milwaukee Brewers vs. Arizona Diamondbacks (Brewers won 3-2). This was the first postseason meeting between the Phillies and Cardinals, as well as the Brewers and Diamondbacks. The Brewers-Diamondbacks series was the first postseason series played between teams in ballparks with retractable roofs since the strike-shortened 1981 season. Both National League Division Series matchups went to a deciding Game 5, a rare occurrence since 1981.
"Austins Bridge is an American Christian country band. Austins Bridge was originally formed in Austin, Texas. The band consists of Justin Rivers and Jason Baird."
The 1906 USC Methodists football team was an American football team representing the University of Southern California during the 1906 college football season. The team competed independently under head coach Harvey Holmes and had a record of 2–0–2.
"Eros Vlahos is an English-Greek actor and comedian. Eros Vlahos was born on January 13, 1995. Eros Vlahos is known for his roles as Cyril Gray in "Nanny McPhee and the Big Bang", Jake Farley in "Summer in Transylvania", and Lommy Greenhands in "Game of Thrones". Eros Vlahos also appeared in the television series "Da Vinci's Demons" as Nico Machiavelli."
Andrew Pierce is a journalist, editor, author, broadcaster, and political commentator. Andrew Pierce was born as Patrick J Connolly in 1961.
"The First Presbyterian Church in Jamaica is located in Jamaica, Queens, New York City. The church was organized in 1662, making it the oldest continuously serving Presbyterian church in the United States."
David Jason Latour is an American comic book artist and writer. David Jason Latour has worked for Image, Dark Horse, Marvel, and DC comics. David Jason Latour is known for his work on titles such as "Wolverine", "Winter Soldier", "Southern Bastards", and "Spider-Gwen". David Jason Latour was born in 1977.
The KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven, also known as Communication Tower, is a self-supporting telecommunications tower located in Rotterdam, Netherlands. It was built in 1962 and is the tallest structure in Rotterdam and one of the tallest structures in the Netherlands. The tower is made of reinforced concrete with a metal transmitter at the top and at least one observation deck about halfway up.
The 2011 South Florida Bulls football team represented the University of South Florida (USF) in the 2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season. The Bulls played their home games at Raymond James Stadium in Tampa, Florida. The 2011 college football season was the 15th season overall for the Bulls, and their seventh season as a member of the Big East Conference. This was the second season with Skip Holtz as the head coach. They finished the season 5–7, 1–6 in Big East play to finish in a tie for seventh place. USF failed to qualify for a post-season bowl ending its streak of six consecutive bowl trips dating back to 2005.
"The Times of Indonesia" was an English-language newspaper published in Indonesia from Jakarta. It was founded in 1952, making it the first English-language daily in independent Indonesia. The founding editor, Mochtar Lubis, also edited "Indonesia Raya" at the time and had close ties to the army leadership. In 1953, Lubis resigned due to the pressures of editing both newspapers, and Charles Tambu from Ceylon took over as managing editor. Following the Revolutionary Government of the Republic of Indonesia revolt, the publishing license for "The Times of Indonesia" was revoked on October 31, 1960, leading to the discontinuation of the newspaper.
Acrocercops orthostacta is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Acrocercops orthostacta is known to be found in Bihar, India. Acrocercops orthostacta was described by Edward Meyrick in 1918. The hostplant for Acrocercops orthostacta is "Sida cordifolia".
"Driving Wheel", also known as "Drivin' Wheel" or "Driving Wheel Blues", is a blues song first recorded by Roosevelt Sykes, also known as "The Honey Dripper", in 1936. This influential early blues composition has been covered by various artists, including Junior Parker and Al Green, whose versions became hits on the record charts.
"Gannutz Glacier is a glacier located in Victoria Land, Antarctica. It flows north from the Bowers Mountains and enters Rennick Bay between Weeder Rock and Stuhlinger Ice Piedmont. The glacier was first mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after Theodore P. Gannutz, a biologist who worked at Hallett Station and Palmer Station. Gannutz Glacier is situated on the Pennell Coast, which is a region of Antarctica between Cape Williams and Cape Adare."
"Gargoyle Ridge is a rock ridge located at the south end of the Cobham Range in the Churchill Mountains of Antarctica. The name was given by the Holyoake, Cobham, and Queen Elizabeth Ranges party of the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (1964–65) due to the unique wind-carved rock buttresses on top of the ridge."
"Garrard Glacier is a glacier located in the Queen Alexandra Range of Antarctica. It drains eastward from the névé between Mount Lockwood and Mount Kirkpatrick, eventually entering Beardmore Glacier south of Bell Bluff. The British Antarctic Expedition, 1910–13, originally named it "Garrard Glacier," although it had previously been known as Bingley Glacier by Ernest Shackleton in 1908. The New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (1961–62) surveyed the area and decided to keep the name Bingley Glacier due to priority, renaming the previously unnamed feature as Garrard Glacier. The glacier is named after Apsley Cherry-Garrard, a zoologist who was part of the British Antarctic Expedition."
"Gatson Ridge is a jagged ridge in Antarctica. It is long and runs east from the southern part of Bowling Green Plateau in the Brown Hills of the Cook Mountains. Gatson Ridge was named after Karl W. Gatson, a topographic engineer from the United States Geological Survey (USGS). Karl W. Gatson was part of the joint 1975–76 USGS – British Antarctic Survey project. The project aimed to establish control points for Landsat mosaics of Palmer Land and to establish geodetically tied independent survey nets in the Ellsworth Mountains and Antarctic Peninsula. The goal was to create a worldwide reference system using Doppler satellite control."
"Gdynia Point is located on Dufayel Island in Ezcurra Inlet, Admiralty Bay, King George Island, part of the South Shetland Islands. It was named in 1979 by the Polish Antarctic Expedition after Gdynia, Poland, a port city on the Baltic Sea."
Chuck Compton is an American professional football player. Chuck Compton was born on January 13, 1965, in Atwater, California. Chuck Compton played in the National Football League.
Cape Geology is a gravel-covered point located at the western limit of Botany Bay in Granite Harbour, Victoria Land, Antarctica. It was named by the Western Geological Party of the Terra Nova Expedition (1910–13) who set up their base there.
Geodetic Glacier is a glacier located on the Scott Coast of Victoria Land, Antarctica. It flows east from Bettle Peak along the north side of the Thomas Heights into Bowers Piedmont Glacier. The name Geodetic Glacier was given by the New Zealand Geographic Board in 1993. The name is associated with geodesy, which is the branch of applied mathematics concerned with measuring the shape of the earth and the precise location of points on its surface.
"Isohypsibius is a genus of water bear or moss piglet, a tardigrade in the class Eutardigrada. Isohypsibius belongs to the class Eutardigrada."
James Higginbotham was a distinguished professor of Linguistics and Philosophy. James Higginbotham was a Fellow of the British Academy. James Higginbotham was affiliated with the University of Southern California, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Columbia University, and the University of Oxford. James Higginbotham was a Fellow of Somerville College, Oxford.
"Mount Goldthwait is a prominent mountain located in the Sentinel Range, Antarctica. Mount Goldthwait has a height of 3,815 meters and is situated 2.5 nautical miles south of Mount Dalrymple. Mount Goldthwait was discovered by the Marie Byrd Land Traverse Party of 1957–58, led by Charles R. Bentley. The mountain was named after Richard P. Goldthwait, who was a consultant for the Technical Panel on Glaciology at the U.S. National Committee for the IGY and later became the Director of the Institute of Polar Studies at Ohio State University."
"The Goodwin Nunataks are a group of nunataks located west of the Marshall Mountains in Antarctica, near Walcott Neve. They were named after Michael L. Goodwin, who was a geomagmetist and seismologist with the United States Antarctic Research Program at South Pole Station in 1960."
"Gordon Peak is a rock peak located at the northwest end of the Robin Heights in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. It was photographed from the air by the Third German Antarctic Expedition (1938–39) and mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos by the Norwegian–British–Swedish Antarctic Expedition (NBSAE) (1949–52) and from air photos by the Norwegian expedition (1958–59). Gordon Peak was named after Robin de Quetterville Gordon, who was the third in command and a physicist with the NBSAE."
"Eohypsibiidae is a family of water bear or moss piglet, tardigrades in the class Eutardigrada. It contains the following species in three genera: Amphibolus, Eohypsibius, and Austeruseus. The species under Amphibolus include Amphibolus mahunkai, Amphibolus markevichi, Amphibolus nebulosus, Amphibolus smreczinskii, Amphibolus volubilis, and Amphibolus weglarskae. The species under Eohypsibius include Eohypsibius nadjae and Eohypsibius terrestris. The species under Austeruseus include Austeruseus balduri, Austeruseus faroensis, and Austeruseus rokuri."
"Gould Peak is a peak located north of Tennant Peak in the southern group of the Rockefeller Mountains on Edward VII Peninsula in Marie Byrd Land, Antarctica. Gould Peak was discovered by the Byrd Antarctic Expedition in 1929. It was named by Richard E. Byrd in honor of Charles ("Chips") Gould, who was a carpenter on the expedition."
"Graptolite Island is an island located in the north-east part of Fitchie Bay, off the south-east portion of Laurie Island in the South Orkney Islands of Antarctica. James Weddell's chart from 1825 shows two islands in this area. The existence of a single island was confirmed in 1903 by the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition led by William Speirs Bruce. The island was named Graptolite Island due to the discovery of what were initially believed to be graptolite fossils. However, further analysis revealed that the fossils on Graptolite Island were actually the remains of ancient plants."
"Gratton Nunatak is a bare, linear nunatak located at the south side of the mouth of McCarthy Glacier in Antarctica, where it meets Reedy Glacier. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy from surveys and air photos taken between 1960 and 1964. The nunatak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in honor of John W. Gratton, a construction mechanic at Byrd Station in 1962."
"Grautskåla Cirque is a cirque located north of The Altar in the Humboldt Mountains of Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. It was discovered and mapped by the Third German Antarctic Expedition, 1938–39, and later remapped by the Sixth Norwegian Antarctic Expedition, 1956–60. The cirque was named Grautskåla, which means 'the mash bowl,' due to its appearance and its proximity to Schussel Cirque. Grautskåla Cirque is known for its extreme cold temperatures."
John Woolfe was a British racing driver from England. John Woolfe specialized in sports car racing. John Woolfe was born on March 23, 1932, and passed away on June 14, 1969. John Woolfe tragically lost his life in a crash during the first lap of the 1969 24 Hours of Le Mans race. This incident led to the abolishment of the traditional "Le Mans start" the following year.
Hailstorm Island is a rocky island located between Cameron Island and the east end of Burnett Island in the central part of the Swain Islands, Antarctica. It was first roughly mapped from air photos taken by U.S. Navy Operation Highjump in 1946–47 and included in a 1957 survey of the Swain Islands by Wilkes Station personnel under Carl R. Eklund. The island was named by Eklund in honor of Radioman Kenneth J. Hailstorm, a member of the U.S. Navy and part of the 1957 wintering party at Wilkes Station during the International Geophysical Year.
"Hales Peak is a peak located on Mount Cabeza in the northeast part of Brabant Island, Palmer Archipelago, Antarctica. Hales Peak was named after Stephen Hales, an Englishman and curate of Teddington. Stephen Hales was known for estimating blood pressure and making significant contributions to hygiene. Hales Peak was mapped from air photos taken by Hunting Aerosurveys Ltd in 1956–57."
"Hale Glacier is a glacier located just east of Mount Simpson on Thurston Island, Antarctica. It flows southwest to the Abbot Ice Shelf in Peacock Sound. The glacier was delineated from air photos taken by U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6 in January 1960 and was named after Lieutenant Bill J. Hale, U.S. Navy, a helicopter pilot who made exploratory flights to Thurston Island in February 1960. Gould Knoll is a mostly ice-covered rock knoll that rises on the east margin of the glacier, where it enters the Abbot Ice Shelf. It was named after William G. Gould, a specialist from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, known for his work in archiving Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer (AVHRR) satellite images, including those used for AVHRR image maps of the Antarctic continent."
The 2011 New York Red Bulls season was the club's seventeenth year of existence, as well as its sixteenth season in Major League Soccer, the top-flight of American soccer. The Red Bulls had a disappointing season in 2011, failing to meet their goals of consistency, a deep run in the MLS Cup Playoffs, and vying for the Supporters Shield. The team struggled with inconsistency, barely making it to the playoffs and falling in the quarterfinals. Manager Hans Backe initially aimed for the Shield but later blamed international call-ups for the team's shortcomings. The average MLS regular season and playoff home attendance for the New York Red Bulls in 2011 was 20,000.
Constant Mews is a Professor of Medieval Thought and Director at the Centre for Studies in Religion and Theology at Monash University in Melbourne. He specializes in medieval religious thought, particularly focusing on the medieval philosopher and theologian Peter Abelard, as well as interfaith dialogue. Mews is known for discovering and publishing the original letters exchanged between Peter Abelard and his lover, Heloise. Constant Mews was born in 1954 and holds a D. Phil ("Oxon").
"Western Cattle in Storm" is a $1 stamp issued by the United States Post Office Department as part of the 1898 Trans-Mississippi Issue. The stamp is one of nine commemorative postage stamps in the series, which marked the 1898 Trans-Mississippi Exposition held in Omaha, Nebraska. The breed of cattle used in the stamp were meant to represent the ruggedness of the American West, but actually derive from the Highlands of Scotland. The design originated in a John MacWhirter painting depicting cattle in a winter storm in central Scotland. An engraving of this painting by C. O. Murray was used without permission by an American cattle company. The painting, entitled "The Vanguard," was later discovered to be a depiction of Scottish cattle in a storm in Scotland. The image was adopted for the $1 stamp design by Raymond Ostrander Smith, the staff designer of the Bureau of Engraving and Printing at the time. The frame and vignette of the stamp were engraved by Marcus W. Baldwin, and the numerals and lettering were done by Douglas S. Ronaldson.
The Moore Mountains are a group of mountains located north of New Year Pass in the Queen Elizabeth Range in Antarctica. These mountains were discovered in 1957 by the New Zealand southern party of the Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition (1956–58) and were named after R.D. Moore, who was the Treasurer of the Ross Sea Committee.
Chernobyl Way is an annual rally held on April 26 in Belarus to commemorate the Chernobyl disaster. The first rally took place in 1989 with demands to address the consequences of the catastrophe. Around 30,000 participants marched from LUCH, Minsk Watch Plant, to the Square of Independence. In 1996, the largest Chernobyl Way rally was held in Minsk to mark the 10th anniversary of the disaster. Approximately 50,000 people gathered at the Academy of Sciences and marched on Independence Avenue. Clashes with the police occurred, leading to the dispersal of demonstrators by OMON. Several political activists, including Yury Khadyka, Lyavon Barshchewski, Vyachaslau Siuchyk, and Vincuk Viačorka, were detained. Following the rally, opposition leader Zianon Pazniak left the country. The staff of the Maksim Bahdanovič Literary Museum began assisting the arrested and their families, leading to the establishment of the Viasna Human Rights Center.
Moreton Point is a geographical point located north of Return Point at the western end of Coronation Island in the South Orkney Islands, which are situated off the coast of Antarctica. Moreton Point was approximately mapped by Captains George Powell and Nathaniel Palmer in 1821. The name "Moreton Point" was given by the personnel of Discovery Investigations aboard the "Discovery II" during their mapping of the islands in 1933.
Morrell Reef is a reef located off the southeast coast of Bouvetøya, near Cape Fie. It was first charted in 1898 by a German expedition led by Carl Chun and recharted in December 1927 by a Norwegian expedition under Captain Harald Horntvedt. The reef was named after Captain Benjamin Morrell, an American sealer who visited the northwest side of Bouvetøya in the "Wasp" in 1822, potentially making the first landing on the island. Bouvetøya is the island where Morrell Reef is located.
The Moss Braes are west-facing slopes situated west of Robin Peak on Signy Island, in the South Orkney Islands off Antarctica. They were named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1990 from the extensive moss banks on the dissected rocky slopes.
"Moser Glacier is a glacier located in Antarctica. Moser Glacier flows into Andvord Bay, southeast of Arago Glacier, on the west coast of Graham Land. The glacier was charted by the Belgian Antarctic Expedition led by Adrien de Gerlache from 1897 to 1899. It was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1960 in honor of German physicist Ludwig F. Moser, who invented stereoscopic photography in 1844."
Maurice Brantley is a professional boxer. Maurice Brantley was born on September 19, 1968, in Kansas City, Missouri. Maurice Brantley competes in the Middleweight division.
"Kansas Glacier is a glacier located in Antarctica. It is a steep glacier that is long and drains northeast from Stanford Plateau to enter Reedy Glacier just north of Blubaugh Nunatak. The glacier was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy from surveys and air photos taken between 1960 and 1964. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in honor of the University of Kansas in Lawrence, Kansas, which has sent a number of research personnel to Antarctica."
"36 Greatest Hits!" is a box set released in 2010 by American singer Frank Sinatra. This box set includes 36 songs that he recorded for his own label, Reprise. Frank Sinatra is an American singer.
"The Toe is a point marking the south side of the entrance to Harmony Cove and the north-west side of the entrance to Varvara Cove on the west side of Nelson Island, in the South Shetland Islands. This descriptive name seems first to appear on a chart based upon a 1935 survey by DI personnel on the "Discovery II". Harmony Cove and Varvara Cove are located on Nelson Island in the South Shetland Islands. The name "The Toe" was given to this point based on a 1935 survey conducted by DI personnel on the "Discovery II"."
Mount Kaschak is a peak located west of Gambacorta Peak in the southern Neptune Range of the Pensacola Mountains, Antarctica. It was named after John P. Kaschak, an aviation machinist at Ellsworth Station during the winter of 1958. The peak was mapped from United States Geological Survey surveys and U.S. Navy air photos taken between 1956 and 1966.
Kehle Glacier is a glacier located in Antarctica. It drains the western slopes of the Worcester Range and is situated near Mount Speyer and Mount Dawson-Lambton. The glacier flows southwest into Mulock Glacier. Kehle Glacier was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in 1964 in honor of Ralph Kehle, a glaciologist who worked at Little America V during 1959-60.
Germaine Poinso-Chapuis was a French politician. Germaine Poinso-Chapuis was born on March 6, 1901, in Marseille, Bouches-du-Rhône. Germaine Poinso-Chapuis was the first woman to hold a Cabinet-level post in the French government. Germaine Poinso-Chapuis's political convictions have been influenced by both Catholic and feminist traditions.
"Kelley Massif is a mountain massif located in Palmer Land, Antarctica. Kelley Massif is situated west of the Eland Mountains and along the south side of Clifford Glacier. The United States Geological Survey mapped Kelley Massif in 1974. Kelley Massif was named after Captain Hugh A. Kelley, U.S. Navy, who was the Commander of Antarctic Support Activities during Operation Deep Freeze 1968 and 1969."
"Kelley Nunatak is a nunatak located on the north side of Leverett Glacier in Antarctica, northeast of Mount Gould. Kelley Nunatak was mapped by the United States Geological Survey from ground surveys and U.S. Navy air photos between 1960 and 1963. The nunatak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in honor of Herbert O. Kelley, who served as a radioman with the Byrd Station winter party in 1958."
Mount Randall is a mountain located in the Victory Mountains, Victoria Land. It rises to 3,000 m at the south end of Hackerman Ridge. The mountain is situated 2 nautical miles west of Mount Riddolls and 3.5 nautical miles northeast of Mount Burrill. Mount Randall was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in 1994 after Richard R. Randall, a geographer and cartographer who served as the Executive Secretary of the U.S. Board on Geographic Names from 1973 to 1993. Richard R. Randall was responsible for geographic nomenclature in Antarctica. He succeeded Meredith F. Burrill, after whom Mount Burrill was named, as Executive Secretary. Randall and Burrill collaborated to lead a significant period of American geographic names research.
Ranney Nunatak is a nunatak located in the southwest extremity of Gutenko Nunataks, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land. Ranney Nunatak was first mapped by the United States Antarctic Service (USAS) during 1939–41. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Charles R. Ranney, who was an ionospheric physicist at Byrd Station in 1969.
Mount Kendrick is an ice-covered mountain located in Antarctica. It is situated on the east side of the Nilsen Plateau at the head of Bartlett Glacier, within the Queen Maud Mountains. The mountain was named after Captain H.E. Kendrick, who served as the Operations Officer on the staff of the Commander, U.S. Naval Support Force, Antarctica, during U.S. Navy Operation Deep Freeze 1967.
"The Kester Peaks are three aligned rock peaks located south of Mount Malville on the east side of the Forrestal Range in the Pensacola Mountains of Antarctica. They were mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after Larry T. Kester, a photographer with U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6 during Operation Deep Freeze in 1964."
Peniston Lamb is a British politician. Peniston Lamb held the title of 1st Viscount Melbourne. Peniston Lamb's son was also a British politician. Peniston Lamb's son served as a Member of Parliament for Newport from 1793 to 1796 and for Hertfordshire from 1802 to 1805.
Acrocercops delicata is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is found in Java, Indonesia. The larvae of Acrocercops delicata feed on the leaves of "Nephelium lappaceum", their host plant.
"Acrocercops lophonota is a moth. Acrocercops lophonota belongs to the family Gracillariidae. Acrocercops lophonota is found in Java, Indonesia."
Ravn Rock is a submerged rock located in the center of Neptunes Bellows, the entrance to Port Foster, Deception Island, in the South Shetland Islands. It was charted by the French Antarctic Expedition under Charcot, 1908–10. The rock was named after the whale catcher Ravn, which was based at Deception Island during that time.
Mount Lupa is an ice-covered mountain in Antarctica. It is over high and located between Romulus Glacier and Martin Glacier, close east-southeast of Black Thumb and east of the head of Rymill Bay on the west coast of Graham Land. The mountain was first roughly surveyed in 1936 by the British Graham Land Expedition led by John Rymill. It was later resurveyed in 1948-49 by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey, who gave it the name Mount Lupa. This mountain is situated near the heads of Romulus and Remus Glaciers, and its name comes from the mythological story of the she-wolf (Lupa) that fed the twins Romulus and Remus after they were thrown into the Tiber.
Mount Lymburner is a mountain located in Antarctica. It stands high and is situated west-northwest of Mount Weems near the north end of the Sentinel Range in the Ellsworth Mountains. Mount Lymburner was discovered by Lincoln Ellsworth during his trans-Antarctic flight on November 23, 1935. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in honor of J.H. Lymburner, who was an assistant pilot on Ellsworth's expedition.
The American Arachnological Society (AAS) is a scientific organization founded in 1972. The society aims to promote the study of arachnids and facilitate cooperation between amateur and professional arachnologists. They publish the "Journal of Arachnology" and hold annual meetings in various locations across the United States. Membership is open to individuals who share the society's objectives.
"Lystad Bay is a bay located on the west side of Horseshoe Island in Marguerite Bay, Antarctica. It was first surveyed in 1936–37 by the British Graham Land Expedition led by John Rymill. The bay was also visited by the USMS "North Star" of the United States Antarctic Service in 1940. The name Lystad Bay was proposed by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in honor of Captain Isak Lystad of the "North Star"."
Lyons Cone is a cone-shaped peak located north-northeast of the Matterhorn in the Asgard Range, Victoria Land, Antarctica. It rises to an elevation of on the ridge that separates the heads of Lacroix Glacier, Newall Glacier, and Suess Glacier. The peak was named after American geochemist William Berry Lyons by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names. William Berry Lyons is known for his expeditions to the Himalayas, Greenland, Iceland, and Antarctica from 1980 to 1997. He served as the chief scientist of the McMurdo Dry Valleys Long-Term Ecological Research field team from 1993 to 1997. In 1988-89, Lyons was part of a University of New Hampshire field party that conducted glaciochemical investigations and collected two deep ice cores from the upper Newall Glacier in the vicinity of Lyons Cone.
"Spodnje Hoče is a settlement in northeastern Slovenia. Spodnje Hoče is the administrative centre of the Municipality of Hoče–Slivnica. Spodnje Hoče is located below the eastern Pohorje Hills on the right bank of the Drava River south of Maribor. The area belongs to the traditional region of Styria. The municipality is part of the Drava Statistical Region."
"Lucian Flemming is a football player. Lucian Flemming was born on November 19, 1966. Lucian Flemming is from Anguilla. Lucian Flemming has represented the Anguilla national team."
"Carl Nielsen composed the symphonic poem 'Pan and Syrinx' for a concert in Copenhagen on February 11, 1918."
"SN 1998aq is a supernova. SN 1998aq is located in galaxy NGC 3982. SN 1998aq was discovered in 1998 by amateur astronomer Mark Armstrong."
Murphys Ice Cream is a food company based in Dingle, County Kerry, Ireland. Murphys Ice Cream uses the milk of Kerry cattle and offers a variety of coffees, ice creams, and desserts. Seán and Kieran Murphy founded Murphys Ice Cream in Dingle in 2000 with the aim of creating the best ice cream globally. They produce a range of traditional and unique flavors, such as brown bread and sea salt.
Louis Dufresne was a French ornithologist and taxidermist. He was born on January 18, 1752, in Champien, near Peronne, and passed away on October 11, 1832. Dufresne was known for his work as a naturalist on board the "Astrolabe" during a voyage of discovery that took him to various locations including Madeira, Tenerife, Trinidad, Brazil, Cape Horn, Concepción, the Sandwich Islands, Alaska, and China. In 1793, he became a taxidermist and curator at the Museum d'Histoire Naturelle, where he classified and arranged collections of invertebrates and vertebrates. Dufresne popularized the use of arsenical soap for preserving birds and built a significant collection of specimens. His private collection was purchased by the University of Edinburgh in 1819, which later became part of the National Museums Scotland. In 1829, Dufresne was awarded the Legion of Honour before passing away from lung disease.
"Born Again in Dixieland" is a song co-written and recorded by Canadian country music artist Jason McCoy. The song was released in June 1997 as the lead single from his album "Playin' for Keeps". It reached #3 on the "RPM" Country Tracks chart in September 1997 and also won a SOCAN Song of the Year award.
Brandon Tauszik is a photographer and filmmaker based in California. In 2011, Tauszik began covering the doomsday prophesies of Harold Camping and the Family Radio ministry. In 2014, Tauszik pioneered GIF-based storytelling with "Tapered Throne", a portrait of Oakland's black barbers. He has directed the music videos for rapper Antwon's "Helicopter" and "Living Every Dream", as well as producer RL Grime's "Heard Me".
"Diphenolic acid is a carboxylic acid with the molecular formula C17H18O4. Its IUPAC name is 4,4-bis(4-hydroxyphenyl)pentanoic acid. Diphenolic acid can be prepared by the condensation reaction of phenol with levulinic acid in the presence of hydrochloric acid. It is a solid at room temperature, melting at 168–171 °C and boiling at 507 °C. According to its MSDS, diphenolic acid is soluble in ethanol, isopropanol, acetone, acetic acid, and methyl ethyl ketone, but insoluble in benzene, carbon tetrachloride, and xylene. Diphenolic acid may be a suitable replacement for bisphenol A as a plasticizer. Diphenolate esters have been used to synthesize epoxy resins as a replacement for the diglycidyl ether of bisphenol A. The diglycidyl ethers of n-alkyl diphenolate esters have similar thermomechanical properties to the diglycidyl ether of bisphenol A when cured, but the viscosity and glass transition temperature vary as a function of the ester length. Diphenolate esters have also been used to synthesize polycarbonates with a potential for water solubility."
"Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps" is an album by Death in June released in November 2010. The album was available for download on iTunes in November 2010, and a limited CD version with bonus tracks was released with only 3,000 copies. Additionally, the album was released in three separate 2x10" picture disc editions and a USB version containing MP3 & FLAC files. This album represents a significant departure from their previous neofolk sound, as it is entirely piano-led under the name 'Totenkopf Torch Songs'. The 'Lounge Corps' section of the album features reworked versions of well-known Death in June tracks like 'Rose Clouds of Holocaust' and 'Fall Apart', presented as instrumental versions.
Netty Simons, formerly known as Rothenberg, was an American pianist, music editor, music educator, and composer. Netty Simons was born on October 26, 1913, and passed away on April 1, 1994.
"Beware the Gonzo" is a 2010 romantic comedy-drama film. The film was written and directed by Bryan Goluboff. Ezra Miller stars as the eponymous Gonzo, a high school student who creates an underground newspaper. Zoe Kravitz, Jesse McCartney, Griffin Newman, Campbell Scott, and Amy Sedaris appear in supporting roles. The title of the film refers to a style of first-person confrontational journalism developed by Hunter S. Thompson in the early 1970s. "Beware the Gonzo" debuted at the Tribeca Film Festival in April 2010.
The Mystic Schooners are a collegiate summer baseball team based in Mystic, Connecticut. The franchise is one of the oldest in the New England Collegiate Baseball League. Originally known as the Eastern Tides and later the Thread City Tides in Willimantic, Connecticut, the team was purchased by former Boston Red Sox General Manager Dan Duquette in 2004. The team was initially called the Berkshire Dukes and played at the Dan Duquette Sports Academy in Hinsdale, Massachusetts before moving to Pittsfield in 2005. The team changed its name to the Pittsfield American Defenders in 2008 after being bought by the ownership group that owned the American Defenders of New Hampshire. Despite initial struggles, the team's performance improved, and in 2011, they relocated to Mystic, Connecticut and became the Mystic Schooners.
The Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway, also known as Hangyong high-speed railway or Hang-Yong Passenger Dedicated Railway, is a China Railway High-speed line connecting the cities of Hangzhou and Ningbo in Zhejiang province. The railway spans approximately [insert distance], with a design speed of [insert speed]. In the railway's short name, "Hang" stands for Hangzhou, and "Yong" is a traditional short name for Ningbo. Originally scheduled to open in June 2012, the completion of the project was postponed multiple times. Test operations began in early 2013, and commercial operations officially started on 30 June 2013. The line runs parallel to the Xiaoshan–Ningbo railway.
Mount Paine is a mountain located in Antarctica. Mount Paine is part of the La Gorce Mountains in the Queen Maud Mountains. Mount Paine has a height of 3,330 meters. Mount Paine was discovered in December 1934 by the Byrd Antarctic Expedition geological party led by Quin Blackburn. Mount Paine was named after Stuart D.L. Paine, who was the navigator and radio operator of that expedition.
Manfred Osten is a German poet and cultural historian. Manfred Osten was born on January 19, 1938, in Ludwigslust, Mecklenburg. He escaped to the Federal Republic of Germany in 1952. Manfred Osten studied law, philosophy, musicology, and literature in Hamburg and Munich. He earned a doctorate with a thesis on the concept of natural law in Schelling's early writings. Manfred Osten joined the diplomatic service of the Federal Republic of Germany after his studies. He had diplomatic postings in France, Cameroon, Chad, Australia, Japan, and Hungary. From 1995 to 2004, he served as the Secretary-General of the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation. Manfred Osten holds honorary doctorates from the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences, University of Pécs, University of Bucharest, and Alexandru Ioan Cuza University of Iaşi. In 1993, he received the Order of the Rising Sun from the Japanese government. He is a member of the Academy of Sciences and Literature in Mainz and was admitted to the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany in 2008. Manfred Osten's works include "Die Erotik Pfirsichs" (The Eroticism of the Peach), "Das Geraubte Gedächtnis" (Stolen Memory), "Goethes Entdeckung der Langsamkeit" (Goethe's Discovery of Slowness), "Die Kunst, Fehler zu Machen" (The Art of Making Mistakes), and "Im Kerngehäuse" (In the Core). He is also known for his skill in playing the viola and his interest in the music of Robert Schumann.
Frank Keller is a professor of computational cognition at the School of Informatics, University of Edinburgh and director at the Institute for Language, Cognition and Computation. Frank Keller received his B.S. from the University of Stuttgart and his Ph.D. from the University of Edinburgh. He also served as a postdoc at Saarland University and Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Additionally, he managed the European Network on Vision and Language Committee and was a member of the European Association for Computational Linguistics' governing board.
The South Fork Eel River Wilderness is a wilderness area located in Mendocino County, California. The wilderness was added to the National Wilderness Preservation System through the Northern California Coastal Wild Heritage Wilderness Act in 2006 (Public Law 109-362). The Department of the Interior's Bureau of Land Management (BLM) is responsible for managing the area. The wilderness is divided into two sections: the Red Mountain unit, dominated by Red Mountain and the Cedar Creek (South Fork Eel River) drainage, and the Cahto Peak unit, consisting of several Douglas fir forest watersheds. The Red Mountain unit features unique vegetation cover due to its reddish soil, including species like Sargent cypress, Red Mountain buckwheat, and Red Mountain stonecrop. The area is designated as a Research Natural Area (RNA) / Area of Critical Environmental Concern (ACEC). The red soil on Red Mountain is classified as Littlered series, an Ultisol with high iron oxide content. The Cahto Peak unit includes a pristine watershed designated as a Biosphere Reserve, National Natural Landmark, and Hydrologic Benchmark.
"Atheism in Christianity" is a 1968 book by the Marxist philosopher Ernst Bloch. The book presents a different perspective on the Christian/atheist debate. According to Gareth Jenkins from "Socialist Review," Bloch argues that there are liberatory elements within Christianity that socialists can align with.
"Gunnestad Glacier is a glacier in Antarctica. Gunnestad Glacier is located between Mount Widerøe and Mount Walnum in the Sør Rondane Mountains. Gunnestad Glacier was mapped by Norwegian cartographers in 1957. The mapping was based on air photos taken during the U.S. Navy Operation Highjump in 1946–47. Gunnestad Glacier was named after Lieutenant Alf Gunnestad, a pilot who was part of the Norwegian expedition led by Lars Christensen in 1933–34."
"Guile Island is an island located southwest of Duchaylard Island in the Biscoe Islands of Antarctica. It was discovered and named by the British Graham Land Expedition led by John Rymill from 1934 to 1937. The UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee named it in 1959. The island has multiple landing places, but the presence of underwater rocks makes approaching it dangerous, requiring caution and cleverness."
"Blues Run the Game" is a song from 1965 by the American singer-songwriter Jackson C. Frank. The song served as the opening track on Frank's self-titled debut album.
"Gruendler Glacier is a tributary glacier located in Victoria Land, Antarctica. It drains the northern slopes of the Malta Plateau near Mount Hussey and flows north into Trainer Glacier. The glacier was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after James D. Gruendler, a member of the United States Antarctic Research Program glaciological party to Roosevelt Island in 1967–68."
Trail Glacier is a mountain glacier located on the southern side of Mount Menzies. It is approximately 5 nautical miles long and 3 nautical miles wide. The glacier originates from a snowfield at around 2,750 m and descends down a steep slope for at least 900 m vertically before merging with the ice sheet. The glacier was mapped from ANARE air photos and surveys of the Prince Charles Mountains in 1960-61. It was named by the Antarctic Names Committee of Australia (ANCA) in honor of D.S. Trail, a geologist who led an ANARE field party to this feature in December 1961.
Grimes Glacier is a glacier located in the Heritage Range of the Ellsworth Mountains in Antarctica. Grimes Glacier descends from the east side of Anderson Massif. The glacier was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after Master Chief Equipmentman Paul D. Grimes, U.S. Navy. Paul D. Grimes supervised the construction crews during the relocation of Williams Air Field at McMurdo Sound as part of U.S. Navy Operation Deep Freeze 1965.
Trinity Nunatak is a large nunatak located in the stream of the Mawson Glacier, approximately 5 nautical miles (9 km) north of the Convoy Range in Victoria Land. It was mapped in 1957 by the New Zealand Northern Survey party of the Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition (1956–58). The name Trinity Nunatak was given due to its three summits.
"Trollkjelneset Headland is a snow-domed headland located between Krylvika Bight and the mouth of Jutulstraumen Glacier in Queen Maud Land. It was mapped by Norwegian cartographers during the Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition (NBSAE) from 1949 to 1952 and later by the Norwegian expedition in 1958-59. The headland was named Trollkjelneset, which means cape of the troll's cauldron."
Trousers Rock is a rock with a prominent wave-cut arch. Trousers Rock is located immediately west of Cook Rock and 0.3 nautical miles northeast of Vindication Island in the South Sandwich Islands. Trousers Rock was charted in 1930 and was given this descriptive name by DI personnel on the "Discovery II".
Mount Dodge is a peak in Antarctica, located in the Prince Olav Mountains. It is mainly ice-free and sits at the confluence of Holzrichter Glacier and Gough Glacier. Mount Dodge was discovered by the U.S. Ross Ice Shelf Traverse Party (1957–58) led by A.P. Crary. It was named after Professor Carroll W. Dodge, who studied lichens and lichen parasites during the Byrd Antarctic Expedition (1933–35).
"Dogwatch Saddle is a snow saddle located between Mount Brøgger and Mount Morrison in the Prince Albert Mountains, Victoria Land. It separates the glacial catchments of Benson Glacier and Cleveland Glacier. In January 1990, a field party from the New Zealand Antarctic Research Programme set up a temporary camp on the saddle. The name Dogwatch Saddle commemorates the late-night hours spent at this location."
"Punchbowl Glacier is a glacier located in Antarctica. It flows southwards between Poibrene Heights and Metlichina Ridge, entering the north end of Exasperation Inlet, north of Jorum Glacier, on the east side of Graham Land. The glacier was surveyed by Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) in 1947 and 1955. The name given by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) describes the shape of the glacier, as it is surrounded by mountains."
"Gouvernøren Harbor is a harbor located on the east side of Enterprise Island, near Pythia Island in Wilhelmina Bay, Antarctica. The harbor was named by whalers after the whaling vessel "Gouvernøren I" was wrecked there in 1916."
Frank Teruggi, Jr. was an American student, journalist, and member of the Industrial Workers of the World from Chicago, Illinois. Frank Teruggi, Jr. was a victim of General Augusto Pinochet's military after the September 11, 1973 coup d'état against Socialist President Salvador Allende. A Chilean court in 2014 found that the United States played a key role in Frank Teruggi, Jr.'s murder.
Edgware Way Grassland, also known as Edgware Way Rough, is a 6.7 hectare Site of Metropolitan Importance for Nature Conservation located in Edgware, within the London Borough of Barnet. The site is home to Edgwarebury Brook and contains remnants of a planned railway viaduct and embankment. Originally intended as an extension of the Northern line from Edgware to Bushey, the project was abandoned due to the establishment of the Green Belt post-Second World War, resulting in the cancellation of associated developments. A portion of the area serves as the Environment Agency's Edgwarebury Park Flood Storage Area. The grassland within the reserve is typical unimproved London Clay grassland, featuring damp, herb-rich areas with rare plant species like great burnet, sneezewort, and devil's bit scabious. The brook is bordered by sedges and water-cress, and the reserve is a habitat for breeding birds such as yellowhammer and spotted flycatcher. Edgware Way Grassland is adjacent to Edgwarebury Park and can be accessed via a public footpath from Edgware Way, starting just west of the junction with Spur Road.
Jean Khayat is a Tunisian fencer. Jean Khayat was born on May 3, 1942. Jean Khayat participated in the individual foil and sabre events at the 1960 Summer Olympics.
Robert E. Rich Jr. is an American billionaire. Robert E. Rich Jr. is the chairman and majority owner of Rich Products Corporation. Rich Products Corporation is the largest family-owned frozen foods manufacturer in the US. Rich Products Corporation is based in Buffalo, New York. Robert E. Rich Jr. has a net worth of $5.65 billion as of August 2017.
CBZ Bank Limited, also known as CBZ Bank, is a commercial bank in Zimbabwe. CBZ Bank Limited is one of the financial services institutions licensed by the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe, which is the central bank and national banking regulator in the country.
Phyllocnistis intermediella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae, known from Florida, U.S.A. The hostplants for the species include "Mastichodendron foetidissimum" and "Sideroxylon pallidum". They mine the leaves of their host plant. The mine is found on the underside of the leaf. It has the form of a long, whitish, irregular serpentine just below the epidermis, confined to one side of the leaf and not crossing the main rib.
Easton Land District is a land district in Western Australia. Easton Land District is located within the Kimberley Land Division in the Kimberley region of the state.
Waachiim Spiritwolf is a Native American professional mixed martial artist. Waachiim Spiritwolf last competed in the Welterweight division. Waachiim Spiritwolf competed for King of the Cage, Tachi Palace Fights, Bellator, and Strikeforce. Waachiim Spiritwolf has been a professional competitor from 2006 until 2015.
Phyllocnistis nepenthae is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Phyllocnistis nepenthae is known from Sumatra, Indonesia. The hostplant for the species is "Nepenthes tobaica".
The Complete Fighter's Handbook is a supplemental rulebook published in 1989 for the 2nd edition of the "Advanced Dungeons & Dragons" fantasy role-playing game.
The Complete Wizard's Handbook is a supplementary rulebook. It was published in 1990 for the 2nd edition of the Advanced Dungeons & Dragons fantasy role-playing game.
"On Physical Lines of Force" is a paper written by James Clerk Maxwell in 1861. Maxwell derived the equations of electromagnetism and discussed the concept of "molecular vortices" to model Faraday's lines of force. He had previously studied electricity and magnetism in his paper "On Faraday's Lines of Force" presented to the Cambridge Philosophical Society in 1855/6. Maxwell drew analogies between the density of the medium and magnetic permeability, as well as between transverse elasticity and dielectric constant. By referencing an experiment by Wilhelm Eduard Weber and Rudolf Kohlrausch from 1856, Maxwell connected the speed of light with the propagation of waves in this medium. This paper marked a significant advancement in classical electrodynamics and spurred progress in vector calculus. It is regarded as a pivotal publication in the history of physics and science, akin to Einstein's "Annus Mirabilis papers" and Newton's "Principia Mathematica."
The Staten Island Tunnel is an abandoned, incomplete railway/subway tunnel in New York City. It was intended to connect railways on Staten Island (precursors to the modern-day Staten Island Railway) to the BMT Fourth Avenue Line of the New York City Subway, in Brooklyn, via a new crossing under the Narrows. Construction began in 1923, and the tunnel was excavated into the Narrows before New York City Mayor John Hylan canceled the project in 1925. The tunnel lies dormant under Owl's Head Park in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn. Modern proposals for completion of the tunnel have come from New York City Councilman Lewis Fidler and State Senator Diane Savino. Savino stated that if built, the tunnel would cost $3 billion and would improve quality of life for Staten Islanders, reduce traffic, and increase the attractiveness of the borough for investment.
"Caloptilia wakayamensis is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Caloptilia wakayamensis is known from Honshū island, Japan. The wingspan of Caloptilia wakayamensis is 10–11 mm. The larvae of Caloptilia wakayamensis feed on Acer palmatum, probably mining the leaves of their host plant."
Jenderal Soedirman University, abbreviated as UNSOED, is a public university located in Purwokerto, Central Java, Indonesia. It was established on September 23, 1963, and named after Jenderal Soedirman (General Sudirman), the first commander-in-chief of the Indonesian Army during the country's fight for independence. UNSOED is the only public university in the ex-Banyumas residency, with a total of 25,782 active students in 2008. Approximately 35% of the students are from the local Banyumas region, while the rest come from other regions in Indonesia, including Sumatera and Sulawesi. The university enrolls about 5000 students annually and provides various facilities and activities such as a students economic union (KOPMA), scholarships, medical services, life insurance, libraries, laboratories, student learning center, student activity center, web-based academic information system, academic infrastructure, arts and sports organizations, and dormitory.
The Rijeka Thermal Power Station, also known as TE Rijeka or TE Urinj, is an oil-fired power station located east of Rijeka in Kostrena, Croatia. It was constructed between 1974 and 1978 and consists of one generation unit with a capacity of 320 MW. The turbine for the power station was supplied by Ansaldo Energia, who also received the engineering, procurement, and construction contract. The boilers were provided by Waagner-Biro. The power station is owned and operated by Hrvatska elektroprivreda. Its annual production varies, averaging 917 GWh, but only reached 141 GWh in 2011. There are plans for decommissioning in 2020 due to pollution concerns, and currently, the Rijeka Thermal Power Station is offline, with the ability to resume generation within 160 hours of notice.
Phyllonorycter pygmaea is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Japan (the islands of Hokkaidō, Kyūshū, Shikoku, and Honshū), Korea, and the Russian Far East. The wingspan of Phyllonorycter pygmaea is 5-5.5 mm. The larvae of Phyllonorycter pygmaea feed on "Castanea crenata", "Quercus acutissima", "Quercus crispula", "Quercus mongolica", and "Quercus serrata". They mine the leaves of their host plant, creating a ptychonomous blotch mine on the underside of the leaf.
The Karadağ Border General Forces Corps of the Ottoman Empire was a corps under the command of the Ottoman Western Army during the First Balkan War. It was formed in the vicinity of Yakova (Gjakova) and Pirzerin (Prizren) with remnant units of İpek Detachment and Priştine Detachment. The headquarters of the corps was established in Derbe-i Bala (Debar) on November 9, 1912.
Nikolay Nikolayevich Leonov is a Russian professional association football official and a former player. Nikolay Nikolayevich Leonov was born on November 1, 1955.
South Barrier is a rocky ridge descending southward from Budd Peak along the east margin of Fiftyone Glacier and terminating at Lambeth Bluff in southern Heard Island. The descriptive name was applied by ANARE (Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions) in 1948.
Mount Sourabaya is a mountain located 1 nautical mile northwest of Mount Darnley on Bristol Island in the South Sandwich Islands. It was named by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in 1971. The name is derived from the whaling factory ship Sourabaya, which witnessed an eruption of the island in 1935. The most recent eruption of Mount Sourabaya occurred between April 19 and April 23, 2016.
"Søråsen Ridge is a ridge located in Queen Maud Land. Søråsen Ridge separates the Quar and Ekström Ice shelves. The ridge was first mapped and named "Søråsen" by the Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition, 1949–52."
Somers Glacier is a glacier located on Kiev Peninsula, on the west coast of Graham Land. It flows northwest into Trooz Glacier. The glacier was first charted by the British Graham Land Expedition (BGLE) led by Rymill from 1934 to 1937. It was named by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in 1959 in honor of Henri Somers, who was the chief engineer of the BelgAE's ship Belgica. The Belgica explored the area in 1897-1899.
Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell was an Irish peer, soldier, and polo player. Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell was born on February 4, 1909, and passed away on March 2, 1999. Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell was awarded the DSO, LVO, and DL titles.
Cecil Jensen was an American editorial cartoonist. Cecil Jensen was born in Ogden, Utah. Cecil Jensen studied at the Chicago Academy of Fine Arts. After moving to California, Cecil Jensen worked at the "Los Angeles Illustrated Daily News" and eventually became an editorial cartoonist.
The 1996 Stockholm Open was a men's tennis tournament played on indoor carpet courts at the Kungliga tennishallen in Stockholm, Sweden. It was part of the World Series of the 1996 ATP Tour. The tournament, in its 28th edition, took place from November 4 to November 10, 1996. Thomas Enqvist, seeded third, emerged as the winner of the singles title for the second consecutive time.
"Jihad and Genocide is a book written by Richard L. Rubenstein. The book was published in 2011."
Yana Rattigan, born Yana Stadnyk on January 20, 1987 in Lviv, Ukrainian SSR, USSR, is a wrestler. Yana Rattigan competes internationally for Great Britain and England. She finished 5th in the 48 kg category at the 2009 World Wrestling Championships and was 7th in the same weight category at the 2010 World Wrestling Championships. Yana Rattigan won silver medals at the 2010 and 2013 European Wrestling Championships, being the first woman to achieve this for Britain. In 2014, representing England, she won another silver medal at the Commonwealth Games.
William Madison McDonald, also known as "Gooseneck Bill", was an American politician, businessman, and banker who had a significant impact in Texas during the late nineteenth century. He was part of the Black and Tan faction and held various positions within the Republican Party of Texas. McDonald was a prominent leader in two black fraternal organizations and served as Grand Secretary of the state's black Masons for 50 years. In 1906, he established Fort Worth's first African-American-owned bank, which survived the Great Depression. McDonald provided loans to black businessmen and is believed to have been the first black millionaire in Texas.
"Sunnylvsfjorden is a fjord in Stranda and Fjord in the Møre og Romsdal county of Norway. Sunnylvsfjorden is one of the innermost branches of Storfjorden. The fjord reaches below sea level at its deepest point near Skrenakken. Geirangerfjorden branches off to the west from Sunnylvsfjorden. Storfjorden splits into Norddalsfjorden to the east and Sunnylvsfjorden to the south near the village of Helsem. Hellesylt is located at the end of Sunnylvsfjorden. Me-Åkernes farm is situated on a cliff on the north side of the fjord. The former municipality of Sunnylven was centered around this fjord."
"Léon Danchin was a French artist known for his drawings of animals, primarily sporting dogs. He was also a sculptor. Danchin was born in Lille, France on June 21, 1887. He was the second of six children of Albert and Margaret Danchin. The Danchin family originated from Anchin in Hainaut, northern France. In 1919, Danchin married Simone Meesemaecker and moved his family to Chantilly, near Paris. His artwork sold well in France, Belgium, the United States, and England. Danchin later relocated to Bergues in French Flanders, where he frequently hunted and drew many renowned hunting scenes. Galerie Hautecœur in Paris currently manages the reproductions of Danchin's art."
"IIFL Holdings Limited, formerly known as India Infoline Limited, is an Indian financial services company based in Mumbai. The organization was founded by Nirmal Jain. IIFL and its group companies have investments from Canadian investor Prem Watsa, private equity firm General Atlantic, and CDC Group. IIFL is one of the top financial conglomerates in India and the leading independent financial services firm in terms of market capitalization. Nirmal Jain serves as the Chairman of the group, while R Venkataraman is the Group Managing Director and Co-Promoter."
George Menzies was a rugby league player and coach from New Zealand. He represented New Zealand at three World Cups and coached the team at another World Cup. In 2007, he was honored as the greatest New Zealand had ever produced. George Menzies was born on September 30, 1930, and passed away on March 16, 2016.
Raging Fighter is a fighting video game. Raging Fighter was developed and published by Konami for the Nintendo Game Boy. Raging Fighter was first released in Japan on March 26, 1993, and later released in North America and Europe in June 1993.
Dr. S. M. Pandit, also known as Sambanand Monappa Pandit, was a popular painter known for his Realism style. He was prominent during a time when traditional Indian art movements were prevalent. His work often depicted scenes from classical Indian literature such as the Ramayana and the Mahabharata, as well as themes from contemporary cinema. Pandit's paintings featured romantic characters like Radha-Krishna and Nala-Damayanti, as well as heroes and heroines from Hindi cinema. He was also known for illustrating film posters, magazines, and calendar art. His mythological paintings and calendar art are still highly regarded today. Pandit's unique style emphasized the physical attributes of his subjects, portraying them as muscular and beautiful, often set in cinematic settings.
"Get Dumb" is a 2007 single by Swedish DJs Axwell, Steve Angello, and Sebastian Ingrosso, along with Dutch DJ Laidback Luke. The song charted in the Netherlands, peaking at #45.
The North Island snipe, also known as the little barrier snipe or tutukiwi, is an extinct species of bird in the sandpiper family, Scolopacidae, that was endemic to New Zealand.
Thomas Jeffery Parker was a zoologist. Thomas Jeffery Parker was a Fellow of the Royal Society. Thomas Jeffery Parker worked in New Zealand.
Crataegus opaca, also known as the western mayhaw, is a shrub or small tree found in the southern United States. It is part of the hawthorn species and produces fruits known as "mayhaws".
"TARKI Social Research Institute is a research centre located in Budapest, Hungary. TARKI specializes in applied socioeconomic research in various areas such as social stratification, labour markets, income distribution, intergenerational transfers, tax-benefit systems, consumption, lifestyle patterns, and attitudes. The senior staff at TARKI all have PhD's and many hold professorial appointments at major universities."
"Irene Hickson was an American catcher who played in the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League. Irene Hickson was born on August 14, 1915, and passed away on November 24, 1995. Irene Hickson was 27 years old when she was signed by the league for its inaugural season. Irene Hickson had a .171 lifetime batting average and was known as an opportune hitter with runners in scoring position. She was a solid fielding catcher with a strong throwing arm and was a good handler of pitchers. Irene Hickson collected 2,388 putouts and 561 assists in 621 games, with only 130 errors for a .958 career fielding average. She was a member of two champion teams and won the batting title in the 1943 championship series. In 1946, she set a record with five walks received in a single game."
Herbert Blankenhorn was a German diplomat. He was born on December 15, 1904 in Mülhausen and passed away on August 10, 1991 in Badenweiler. Blankenhorn was a member of the Foreign Office starting from 1929 and later joined the Nazi Party (NSDAP) in 1938. He served as a counsellor in the German legation in Bern, Switzerland. Philippe Mottu, encouraged by Canon de Bavier, the Procurator of the Abbey of St. Maurice in the Vatican, met Blankenhorn and discovered he was actually anti-Nazi. Blankenhorn played a role in the German resistance during the Third Reich. In 1943, he established the economy department of the German legation in Bern and eventually became the Head of the Foreign Office. After 1945, he became one of the most influential German professional diplomats. Blankenhorn joined the CDU in 1946 and went on to serve as the West German ambassador to Italy, France (1963-1965), and the United Kingdom (1965–1970). He was the son of officer Karl Blankenhorn (1878-1963).
"Museum of Slavonia is the largest general-type museum in Croatia. Museum of Slavonia was established in 1877 in Osijek. Since 1946, it is located in the City Magistracy building, constructed in 1702 for the purposes of the Vienna Chamber, town government, and police. Among the museum's numerous collections, the most prized are the Roman Mursa and numismatic collections. The Museum's library contains more than 70,000 books."
Kurt Blecha was a German politician. He was a member of the Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED) and served as the head of the press office and chairman of the Council of Ministers of the GDR. Blecha was born in Ústí nad Labem, Czechoslovakia. He joined the Nazi Party in 1941 and was later drafted into military service, ending up in Soviet captivity in 1943. After being active in the National Committee for Free Germany, he joined the SED in 1946. Blecha was involved in the Board of the Journalists Association of the GDR from the 1950s to 1989. He received awards such as the Patriotic Order of Merit in 1983 and 1988. His daughter, Sigrid, was the second wife of East German foreign buyer Alexander Schalck-Golodkowski.
Krzysztof Pyskaty is a Polish footballer. Krzysztof Pyskaty was born on January 18, 1974 in Dębica. Krzysztof Pyskaty plays for Limanovia Limanowa.
Jeremy R. Paul is a Dean. Jeremy R. Paul was the Dean of Northeastern University School of Law. Jeremy R. Paul was born on July 22, 1956. Jeremy R. Paul served as the Dean of Northeastern University School of Law from 2012 until June 2018.
Amhlaoibh Mór mac Fir Bhisigh was an Irish poet, cleric, and historian. Amhlaoibh Mór mac Fir Bhisigh passed away in 1138.
"Do Dooni Chaar is a 2010 Indian Hindi family comedy-drama film. The film was produced by Arindam Chaudhuri from Planman Motion Pictures and written and directed by debutant director Habib Faisal. The lead roles in the film were played by Rishi Kapoor, Neetu Singh, Aditi Vasudev, and Archit Krishna. The story revolves around a middle-class school teacher who strives to keep his family happy during tough economic times and dreams of owning a car. This movie also marked the return of the Kapoor pair as a lead couple on the silver screen after a hiatus of over 30 years. The directorial debut film was the first live-action Hindi film to be distributed by Disney World Cinema. It went on to win the National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Hindi at the 58th National Film Awards."
Brakšķi Station is a railway station. Brakšķi Station is located on the Tukums II – Jelgava Railway. Tukums II – Jelgava Railway is a railway line.
"Södermanland Runic Inscription 352 or Sö 352 is a Viking Age memorial runestone located at Linga, which is about two kilometers south of Järna, Stockholm County, Sweden. The inscription depicts a ship with an anchor and a portion of the runic text uses same-stave bind runes on the ship mast."
Emblemaria biocellata, also known as the Twospot blenny, is a species of chaenopsid blenny. It is commonly found in coral reefs in Venezuela, French Guiana, and Colombia, located in the western Atlantic Ocean. The males of this species can reach a maximum length of TL, while the females can reach a maximum length of SL.
"Juraj Dančík is a Slovak former football player. Juraj Dančík was born on February 21, 1982."
The 2010–11 Basketball League of Serbia season was the 5th season of the Basketball League of Serbia, the highest professional basketball league in Serbia. It was also the 67th national championship played by Serbian clubs, including the nation's previous incarnations as Yugoslavia and Serbia & Montenegro. The regular season consisted of 182 games, with each of the 14 teams playing 26 games. The regular season started on October 9, 2010, and concluded on March 12, 2011.
"Pogamasing station is a flag stop station operated by Via Rail. Pogamasing station is located in Pogamasing, Ontario, Canada along the Sudbury – White River train route."
"Operation Dragon Strike was a NATO counter-insurgent mission in Kandahar province, Afghanistan. The operation targeted Taliban forces and commenced on September 15, 2010."
Rosemary's Billygoat is an American heavy metal/hard rock band formed in Los Angeles South Bay in 1991. The band consists of singer Mike Odd, guitarist Neal Gargantua, bassist Pat Trick, and drummer Paul Bearer. Influenced musically and visually by Alice Cooper, Rob Zombie, Gwar, Kiss, and Black Sabbath, Rosemary's Billygoat is best known for their theatrical horror-themed stage shows. These shows incorporate comically absurd props and stunts such as pyrotechnics, fire breathing, electric chairs, mock crucifixion, flaming pentagrams, and various costumed monsters and creatures. Musically, the band has been described as "aggro and dark yet jovial", showcasing an "oozing brew of doom, stoner metal, dark psychedelic rock, and hardcore punk". Over the last two decades, Rosemary's Billygoat has attracted a strong cult following in the Los Angeles punk and metal underground. They have shared stages with cult bands like Gwar, W.A.S.P., The Dickies, Circle Jerks, 45 Grave, and Haunted Garage. In 2013, the "OC Weekly" newspaper ranked Rosemary's Billygoat number 10 on their list of the ten greatest shock rock bands of all time.
Geoffrey Norman Gaunt was a Spitfire pilot during the Battle of Britain. He served in the RAF as part of No. 609 Squadron West Riding of Yorkshire Squadron RAF. He was killed in action on 15 September 1940. Gaunt was from a well-known textile family and screen star James Mason was a cousin. He was buried in his family plot at Salendine Nook Baptist Church with his grandparents and later his father was also buried there in 1958. He was good friends with David Moore Crook. Geoffrey Norman Gaunt served with 609 Squadron Auxiliary Air Force before the war and received some flying training with the unit. He was commissioned into the Auxiliary Air Force in April 1940 and completed his training at the Flying Training School at Cranwell, Lincolnshire in June and July 1940. Gaunt then went to 7 Operational Training Unit at Hawarden, near RAF Sealand, in the North Wales-Chester area. After converting to Spitfire Mark Ones there, Geoffrey Gaunt rejoined 609 Spitfire Squadron on 16 August 1940 at Warmwell in Dorset, close to Weymouth, for the protection of Portland Naval Base and places from Bristol, Somerset, Dorset, Devon, and Cornwall. Earlier, in May 1940 609 West Riding squadron flew sorties in support of Operation Dynamo - the evacuation of the British Expeditionary Force from Dunkirk during the Battle of France. One-third of the squadron's pilots were lost during a three-day period. In the Battle of Britain, which started in July 1940, the squadron operated from Middle Wallop, with half the squadron operating from the forward base at Warmwell in Dorset. During August 1940, the squadron destroyed 46 enemy aircraft but nearly all the pre-war auxiliary pilots were lost, either killed or missing. In October 1940, 609 became the first squadron to achieve 100 confirmed aerial victories. Geoffrey Gaunt had rejoined 609 Squadron on 16 August and got into many combats through the month. He shared in the destruction of a Messerschmitt BF110 fighter on 25 August which was shared Destroyed with P/O Noel Agazarian, who was later a Battle of Britain fighter ace. Geoffrey Gaunt was killed on 15 September 1940 when he was shot down during an attack on German bombers over London. His Spitfire, R6690, crashed and burned out near Kenley. This day was later known as "Battle of Britain Day" as the continued strength of the RAF fighter defence decided Hitler to postpone and then cancel his planned invasion of Britain. David Crook wrote a book titled Spitfire Pilot, published by Faber and Faber in 1942, which describes his friends including Geoffrey Gaunt who were killed, one by one as the Battle of Britain carried on through 1940. The book immortalizes these men and Crook also, for he was to die along with his friends in wartime. These included: Geoffrey Gaunt, Noel Agazarian, John Dundas, and Phillip "Pip" Barran. A Spitfire flown by "Aggy" Agazarian and pilots including David More Crook, John Dundas, (also killed, like Agazarian and Crook in wartime) hangs today in the Imperial War Museum at Lambeth, London. A Memorial Hut to 609 West Riding squadron, complete with a replica Spitfire, a series of wartime portraits of these pilots, relics and memorabilia is at Elvington Airfield for the Yorkshire Air Museum, near York, in tribute to these men like Geoffrey Gaunt who were killed in wartime.
Legions of Thyatis is an adventure module published in 1990 for the "Dungeons & Dragons" fantasy role-playing game.
"Eriogonum spectabile is a rare species of wild buckwheat known as Barron's buckwheat. It is endemic to Plumas County, California, specifically found in Lassen National Forest near Chester. There are around 250 individuals of this species. It thrives in scrubby, forested mountain habitat on glaciated andesite substrates. Discovered in 1997 and classified as a new species in 2001, this small shrub grows in a compact mat up to 25 centimeters wide and 15 centimeters tall. The stems have woolly foliage, with oval leaves up to 2 centimeters long by 1 centimeter wide. The plant blooms with slender, erect flowering stems that bear umbels of white flowers, which turn pink as they age. The flowers are hairy, glandular, and approximately half a centimeter long. The primary threat to this species is logging, with additional risks including herbivory, competition with other plants, climate change, and alterations in the fire regime of its native forest."
"The Heart Specialist is a 2006 American romantic comedy-drama film. The film was written, produced, and directed by Dennis Cooper. The cast includes Wood Harris, Zoe Saldana, Brian J. White, and Mýa. Originally titled Ways of the Flesh, the film premiered at the 2006 Boston Film Festival. It remained unreleased until 2011 when it was granted a limited theatrical release by Freestyle Releasing."
The Boston Bridge is a structure that crosses the Youghiogheny River between Versailles and Elizabeth Township, Pennsylvania. The bridge, which opened in 1931, carries Pennsylvania Route 48 on two relatively narrow lanes. Many of its features were carefully preserved during a 1989 rehabilitation, down to its original pedestrian railings. Designed entirely for vehicular traffic, the structure changed the future of Elizabeth Township; the lack of streetcar tracks led to the abandonment of a line that served the then-rural community's small industrial settlements, while the newfound ease of access for motorists to the area's manufacturing regions opened up the township to suburbanization.
"Štajerska Vas is a village located in the Municipality of Slovenske Konjice in Slovenia. Štajerska Vas is situated northeast of Loče. The village is part of the traditional region of Styria and is now included in the Savinja Statistical Region. Štajerska Vas was established in 1999 when it was administratively separated from Spodnji Jernej."
Thomas Edwardston was an Augustinian friar. He was born at a place called Edwardston in Suffolk. Thomas Edwardston studied at the University of Oxford and obtained the D.D. degree. He became a friar eremite of the order of St. Augustine at the monastery of Clare in his native county and eventually became prior. Thomas Edwardston served as confessor to Lionel, duke of Clarence, and accompanied him to Italy for his marriage with the daughter of the Duke of Milan. Upon his return to England, Thomas Edwardston took on archiepiscopal duties, although the specific diocese is unknown. He passed away at Clare on May 20, 1396, and was buried in his monastery. Thomas Edwardston authored "Sermones Solemnes", "Determinationes Theologicæ", and "Lecturæ Scholasticæ".
"Nandanpur is a Vidhan Sabha constituency. Nandanpur is located in Paschim Medinipur district in the Indian state of West Bengal."
The Localism Act 2011 is an Act of Parliament that changes the powers of local government in England. The aim of the act is to facilitate the devolution of decision-making powers from central government control to individuals and communities. The measures affected by the Act include an increase in the number of elected mayors, referendums, and the "Local authority’s general power of competence" which states "A local authority has power to do anything that individuals generally may do". One notable outcome of the act has been the combined authorities formed by local authorities pooling their powers of transport and economy and gaining certain functions delegated from central government. As a result, there have been calls for legislation to bring about further devolution to the Core Cities Group, leading to the introduction of the Cities and Local Government Devolution Act 2016.
"Acalyptris krugeri is a moth of the family Nepticulidae. Acalyptris krugeri was described by Vári in 1963. Acalyptris krugeri is known from South Africa, specifically from Kruger National Park. The larvae of Acalyptris krugeri feed on Schotia brachypetala."
Atesh Salih is an actor, male model, and interior designer. Atesh Salih is recognized for his work with Giorgio Armani and has been featured in photo shoots for fashion magazines like Wallpaper*, GQ, and Vogue Hommes. Additionally, he has modeled for brands such as Cerruti and Swatch.
Sin Du-ho is a South Korean fencer. Sin Du-ho was born on October 13, 1934. Sin Du-ho competed in the individual and team foil and épée events at the 1964 Summer Olympics.
Jim Jumani Johansson, also known legally as Jim Jumani Immanuel Masauko Kamuzu Banda, was a Malawian-Swedish man who claimed to be the son of the late Malawian President Hastings Kamuzu Banda. He changed his name to Jim Jumani Immanuel Masauko Kamuzu Banda. Johansson's claim and resemblance to the former dictator raised questions about Banda's legacy. He gained celebrity status in Malawi due to his striking similarity to the former president and his efforts to prove his identity through legal means. Focus Gwede, the head of Banda's Special Branch of Secret Police Services, supported Johansson's claim by stating that Banda had fathered three children.
Mary Knight Wood Mason was an American pianist, music educator, and composer. She was born in Easthampton, Massachusetts, to Lieutenant-governor, manufacturer, and philanthropist Horatio G. Knight and Mary Ann Huntoon Knight. She received her education at Charlier Institute in New York City and Miss Porter's School in Farmington, Connecticut, where she studied music with Karl Klauser, Benjamin Johnson Lang, and Henry Holden Huss. Knight married Charles Greenleaf Wood of Boston in 1879 and Alfred Bishop Mason of New York in 1914. After her second marriage, she resided in New York City and spent summers at a cabin in the Catskill Mountains. She passed away in Florence, Italy.
Ahmed Walid Ferhat is an Algerian professional footballer. Ahmed Walid Ferhat was born on July 22, 1986 in El Harrach, Algiers Province. Ahmed Walid Ferhat plays as a forward for the Algerian Ligue 2 club Olympique de Médéa. Olympique de Médéa is a football club based in Algeria.
The Mikhailovsky Palace is a grand ducal palace in Saint Petersburg, Russia. It is located on Arts Square and is an example of Empire style neoclassicism. The palace currently houses the main building of the Russian Museum and displays its collections of early, folk, eighteenth, and nineteenth-century art. It was originally planned as the residence of Grand Duke Michael Pavlovich, the youngest son of Emperor Paul I. The palace was gifted to Grand Duke Michael and his new wife, Grand Duchess Elena Pavlovna, by the Emperor in 1825. The palace was inherited by their daughter, Grand Duchess Catherine Mikhailovna, and eventually bought back for the state by Emperor Nicholas II. The palace was extensively renovated to fit its new role as the Russian Museum, with some of the interiors retained and new wings added.
"Marcel Rooney, O.S.B. was the eighth Abbot Primate of the Benedictine Confederation. Marcel Rooney was born on September 20, 1937. Marcel Rooney professed solemn vows on September 12, 1958, and was ordained to the priesthood on September 21, 1963. Marcel Rooney was elected Abbot of Conception Abbey on April 14, 1993, blessed on May 10, 1993, elected Abbot Primate and Abbot of Sant’Anselmo on September 18, 1996, and resigned on September 3, 2000."
Rehar is a small town located in Bijnor district, Uttar Pradesh state, India.
"From the Towers of the Moon" is an opera by Robert Moran with a libretto by Michael John LaChiusa. The opera is based on the classic Japanese tale "Princess Kaguya" or "The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter", which narrates the story of a princess from the Moon who visits Earth. Moran was inspired by the story known to him as "The Tale of the Shining Princess" and a film adaptation titled "Princess from the Moon" by Kon Ichikawa in 1987. This opera, Moran's third, was commissioned and premiered by the Minnesota Opera in 1992. Additionally, four excerpts were composed for string quartet and recorded as "Music from the Towers of the Moon" by the Balanescu Quartet.
The 31st Golden Raspberry Awards, also known as the Razzies, took place on February 26, 2011, at the Barnsdall Gallery Theatre in Hollywood, California. This parodic award ceremony aimed to recognize the worst films of 2010. The nominations were revealed on January 24, following the Razzies tradition of preceding the Academy Awards by one day. "The Last Airbender" was the standout winner of the night, receiving five awards, including Worst Picture.
The Ganesha University of Education is a university located in Singaraja, Bali, Indonesia. The university was previously known as IKIP Singaraja.
A PhD-MBA or MBA-PhD is a dual degree program offered by schools of science, engineering, or social science, jointly with business schools. The program generally lasts four to eight years and results in the candidate earning both a Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) degree and a Master of Business Administration (MBA) degree. Students may apply to the joint program before matriculating to either program or after matriculating to the PhD program. The program often attracts entrepreneurs and venture capitalists. Some of the leading PhD-MBA programs are offered by universities like: * The Wake Forest University PhD/MBA program was established in 1999 and was the first of its type in the nation. The program is a joint degree between the Wake Forest University Graduate School of Arts and Sciences and the Wake Forest Schools of Business. Dr. Dwayne Godwin is the program director. The degrees are earned concurrently, and the average time to awarding both degrees is 5.2 years. * The University of Delaware's Department of Biological Sciences and the Alfred Lerner College of Business and Economics jointly administer this program since 2006. * Dartmouth in the USA since 2009, * Yale University, Yale Graduate School of Arts and Sciences with Yale School of Management * University of Miami * Penn State College of Medicine * The alliance of two members of Sorbonne University and the Collège des Ingénieurs: UMPC for Sciences and Technology and Paris-Sorbonne for Humanities in France since 2009, * or the similar alliance of KIT and the Collège des Ingénieurs in Germany since 2010, * National University of Singapore since 2011. These programs are aimed at creating entrepreneurs and future technology leaders.
Saleem Safi is a Pakistani journalist, columnist, defence analyst, and current affairs TV talk show anchorperson. Saleem Safi was born on March 7, 1968. Saleem Safi is fluent in Urdu.
Shuhei Fukuda is a Japanese professional baseball player. Shuhei Fukuda was born on February 2, 1989. Shuhei Fukuda currently plays for the Chiba Lotte Marines in the Nippon Professional Baseball league. Shuhei Fukuda previously played for the Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks. Shuhei Fukuda also played for the Brisbane Bandits in the Australian Baseball League in 2010. Shuhei Fukuda signed with the Chiba Lotte Marines on November 26.
"Weymouth Lifeboat Station is the base for Royal National Lifeboat Institution (RNLI) search and rescue operations at Weymouth in Dorset, England. The first lifeboat was stationed in the town in 1869. Since 2002, it has operated an all-weather lifeboat (ALB) and an inshore lifeboat (ILB)."
"Pirlitor was a medieval fortress located in Mount Durmitor, in Old Herzegovina (part of present-day Montenegro). It was situated at the edge of the deep canyon of the Tara River. Only a part of the wall at the fortress's highest point remains today. Pirlitor is positioned 16 km from the town of Žabljak, at an altitude of approximately 1450 meters. The fortress overlooked the medieval road connecting Nikšić and Pljevlja, where the road descended from Durmitor's Lake Plateau into the canyon. Pirlitor is not mentioned in medieval sources, but it is believed to have been the court of Voivode Sandalj Hranić on the Lake Plateau, where his successor Voivode Stjepan Vukčić negotiated peace with the Ragusans in 1453. According to Serbian epic poetry, Pirlitor belonged to Voivode Momčilo, a man of immense size and strength who possessed magical attributes, including a winged horse named Jabučilo and a sabre with eyes. His sister Jevrosima was the legendary mother of Prince Marko, a prominent figure in Serbian epic poems."
"Departing" is the second full-length album by the Canadian indie rock band The Rural Alberta Advantage. It was released on March 1, 2011, on Paper Bag Records in Canada and Saddle Creek Records in the United States. The album received positive reviews, with "The Globe and Mail" recommending it as a must-hear for 2011. It was also longlisted for the 2011 Polaris Music Prize. The song "Tornado '87" on the album is about the Edmonton tornado that occurred on July 31, 1987, when band leader Nils Edenloff was living in the city.
Joan Perry, originally known as Elizabeth Rosiland Miller, was an American film actress, model, and singer. Joan Perry was also known as Betty Miller during her modeling career. Joan Perry was born on July 7, 1911, and passed away on September 16, 1996.
"Yale Publishing Course (YPC) is a program located on the campus of Yale University in New Haven, Connecticut. The program is designed for magazine, book, and online publishing professionals. It focuses on teaching leadership skills in today's global and digital environment. The curriculum is tailored for middle and upper-level professionals from around the world. Speakers include publishing and media executives, as well as faculty from the Yale School of Management and Yale University Press staff. The program is the only advanced-level program for senior managers in the publishing industry. It combines plenary sessions with smaller group discussions on specific issues and case studies. Topics covered include strategic planning, financial management, entrepreneurship, new technology, legal challenges, licensing, marketing internationally, and the future of digital dissemination. Faculty office hours are available for one-on-one meetings with students."
"Kalungu District is located in Central Uganda. The district is named after its main town, Kalungu, where the district headquarters are situated."
Phyllonorycter acaciella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is found in southern Europe, excluding the Iberian Peninsula and Balkan Peninsula. The larvae of Phyllonorycter acaciella feed on Ulmus glabra, Ulmus laevis, and Ulmus minor. They create a weakly folded tentiform mine on the leaves of their host plant, with the folded side being ochraceous. The pupa of Phyllonorycter acaciella is blackish and is found within the mine, enclosed in a loose cocoon.
Maura McNiel was an American feminist. Maura McNiel was born on April 11, 1921. Maura McNiel passed away on July 18, 2020, at the age of 99. Maura McNiel was actively involved in the Dallas women's movement for over forty years. Maura McNiel's contributions include paving the way for women's studies, modern social work, advocacy for abused women, promotion of the Equal Rights Amendment, and the passage of Title IX.
"Bhandgaon is a village located in Parner taluka in Ahmednagar district of Maharashtra, India."
Ali S. Khan is an American physician. Ali S. Khan was the Director of the Office of Public Health Preparedness and Response at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Since July 2014, Ali S. Khan has been serving as the Dean of the College of Public Health and Retired Assistant Surgeon General at the University of Nebraska Medical Center in Omaha, Nebraska.
Patharwadi is a village in Parner taluka in Ahmednagar district of Maharashtra, India. The population of Patharwadi is between 3000 to 3500. The village includes small sections like Bodagewadi, Ghodoba vasti, Khillarwasti, and Derul Mala. Most students study at Nighoj for their secondary education as there is only a Z. P primary school in the village. About 10% of the population lives in Mumbai. The village is known for its Yatra and saptah. Bodagewadi also has a temple of Malganaga Devi. The famous Pot Holes of Nighoj are only 2 km away from Bodagewadi. Bodagewadi is famous for Lezim Mandal and Kranti Yuva Group.
"Pimpri Pathar is a village located in Parner taluka in Ahmednagar district of Maharashtra, India."
Treemont Manor is a historic home located in Colonie, Albany County, New York. It was built in 1929 and is an "L" shaped Georgian Revival style mansion surrounded by a formal English garden. The main house is two and one half stories with a gable roof, and there is a two-story servant's wing attached. Additionally, there is a contributing guest house on the property. Treemont Manor was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1985.
The Knocks is an American electronic music duo consisting of Ben "B-Roc" Ruttner and James "JPatt" Patterson. They have released music on labels such as Kitsuné, Big Beat Records, Neon Gold, and Atlantic Records. The duo is known for their remixes featured on HypeMachine, Beatport, and various DJs' set lists. Some of their popular singles include "Classic" featuring Powers, "I Wish (My Taylor Swift)" with Matthew Koma, and "Kiss The Sky" featuring Wyclef Jean. Their debut album, "55", was released on March 4, 2016, followed by their sophomore album, "New York Narcotic", on September 28, 2018. The album includes singles like “Ride or Die” featuring Foster the People and “Brazilian Soul” featuring Sofi Tukker.
"Cousin Sarah is a horror film. Cousin Sarah was released in October 2011. Jenni Gold directed the film. Leah Pipes stars in the film. Multi-Valence Productions and Willoughby Pictures produced the film. The story was by Alexander Garcia, with Alexander Garcia as the writer, and Nathaniel Morin as co-writer."
"The Infinity Concerto" is a fantasy novel written by Greg Bear in 1984. The story follows teenager Michael Perrin on his quest to understand the concept of a "Song of Power" and why he is believed to have the ability to create one. He is transported to another realm where he encounters beings known as the "Sidhe" who have interfered in Coleridge's poem "Kubla Khan" to prevent the creation of "Songs of Power". The novel was followed by "The Serpent Mage" in 1986.
Mark Hodgson was a British trade union leader. He was born in Hull and grew up in Sunderland. Hodgson studied at Diamond Hall School and took an apprenticeship as a plater in the shipyard. He joined the United Society of Boilermakers and Iron and Steel Shipbuilders and became the Tyne and Wear delegate on the union's executive council in 1913. From 1923 to 1936, he served as the union's chairman and later became its general secretary. During World War II, Hodgson negotiated on behalf of members and held various local and national positions. In 1938, he was awarded the OBE, and in 1945, he received a knighthood. Hodgson stepped down as secretary in 1948 and took on the role of chairman of the Northern Regional Board for Industry, serving until 1965.
Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton was a key investor and developer in Western Canada, specifically in Winnipeg, Vancouver, and Calgary. The town of Nanton, Alberta, and twelve streets in various cities are named after him. He dedicated himself to supporting the Great War, contributing over half of his fortune and working tirelessly to aid Canadian soldiers in Europe. In 1917, he was knighted by George V and became a Knight of the Order of St. John of Jerusalem. He passed away while serving as President of The Dominion Bank in Toronto, but his legacy is closely tied to Winnipeg, where he lived for over forty years and was laid to rest.
Masai Ujiri is a Nigerian-Canadian professional basketball executive and former player. Masai Ujiri is the president of basketball operations of the Toronto Raptors in the National Basketball Association (NBA). Masai Ujiri was born on July 7, 1970. Masai Ujiri started his career as a scout in 2002 for the Orlando Magic and then the Denver Nuggets. In 2008, Masai Ujiri joined the backroom staff of the Toronto Raptors. Masai Ujiri returned to the Nuggets in 2010 as general manager and executive vice president of basketball operations. Masai Ujiri was named the NBA Executive of the Year in 2013. Masai Ujiri returned to the Raptors as general manager and later became the president of basketball operations. Masai Ujiri relinquished his title as general manager to Jeff Weltman in 2016. Bobby Webster succeeded Jeff Weltman as general manager. Masai Ujiri helped the Toronto Raptors win their first NBA championship in 2019. Masai Ujiri was shoved by a law enforcement officer at a basketball game on June 14, 2019, and claimed that this occurred because he is black.
Los Trancos Creek is a creek that flows from Monte Bello Ridge on the northeast slope of the Santa Cruz Mountains to its confluence with San Francisquito Creek at Stanford University in California, United States. The creek forms the boundary between northwestern Santa Clara County and southeastern San Mateo County. Los Trancos Creek is named after the Spanish words "Las Trancas," which mean "barriers" or "cattle guards." Monte Bello Ridge, Santa Cruz Mountains, San Francisquito Creek, Stanford University, California, United States, Santa Clara County, and San Mateo County are all related to the geography and location of Los Trancos Creek.
Selçuk Baştürk is a Turkish professional footballer. Selçuk Baştürk was born on April 29, 1986 in Üsküdar, İstanbul. Selçuk Baştürk plays as a defender for Kozanspor. Selçuk Baştürk started his career with Fenerbahçe A2 and Mersin Büyükşehir Belediyespor, and also played for Turgutluspor. His contract will end on May 31, 2011 according to his profile in the Turkey Football Federation.
Van Denbergh-Simmons House is a historic home located in Colonie, Albany County, New York. The house was built in three phases: the northeast section between about 1720 and 1760, the northwest section around 1790, and the south section in 1847. The northeast section is a -story Dutch house with a 1-story porch. The northwest section is a -story ell with a large kitchen and bee hive oven. The south section is a 2-story Italian Villa style addition with a hipped roof and a large square tower at the northwest corner. The property also includes the remains of a barn foundation. Van Denbergh-Simmons House was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1985.
The Chapter of Toledo is a meeting of the heads of the different provinces of the Order of Saint Augustine in Toledo, Spain in 1589. This meeting is considered an important part of the history of the order because this gave birth to the so-called Augustinian Recollection, through the so-called “Fifth Determination”. Today, both the Order of Augustinian Recollects and the Order of Discalced Augustinians trace their beginnings from the fifth determination which says: "Since there is among us, or at least maybe, some who have greater love for monastic perfection and want to follow a more austere plan of life, we ought to favour their legitimate desire by not placing obstacles to the Holy Spirit; having previously consulted our most Reverend Father General and implored his leave, we determine that in our Province three or more monasteries of men and as many of women be designated or established; in them a more austere kind of life is to be practised; its manner is to be regulated, after mature reflection, by the Father Provincial with his definitorum."
Goodrich School is a historic school building located in Colonie in Albany County, New York. It consists of a one-story, gable roofed rectangular brick building built about 1922 with a one-story, rectangular hipped roof wing dated to about 1926. On the south side are a series of two additions completed during the 1950s. The building is in the Classical Revival style and features a prominent portico with curved underside supported by six Doric order fluted columns. Atop the roof is an octagonal wood cupola with a copper roof. Goodrich School was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2000.
The Monastery of Saint Saviour is a Catholic Franciscan monastery located on 1 Saint Francis Street, east of the New Gate in the Old City of Jerusalem. The site was purchased from the Georgian Orthodox Church in 1560 with permission by Sultan Suleiman the Magnificent of the Ottoman Empire, and the monastery was constructed in stages. The church building was erected in 1885, with renovation in 1985. The site includes a printing press, an organ workshop, a library, and a Catholic school.
Jiří Jech is a Czech football referee. Jiří Jech was born on December 22, 1975. Jiří Jech was a full international for FIFA from 2007 to 2010. Jiří Jech served as a referee in the 2010 World Cup qualifiers.
John Brandard was an English lithographic artist born in Birmingham in 1812 and passed away in London on December 15, 1863. He was known for designing illustrated title-pages for sheet music in a style described as pretty but weak by Michael Bryan. John Brandard was the second son of Thomas Brandard, an engraver and copperplate printer, and Ann. He began his career as an engraver and later worked with the lithographic printers M. & N. Hanhart, producing designs for Louis-Antoine Jullien. Brandard's work with chromolithographs was highly sophisticated, using multiple stones to create images with red, blue, and gold colors. He focused on ballet and opera, with his portraits of dancers admired by Degas. Brandard lived a lavish lifestyle, charging 20 guineas for his artwork and arriving at theatres in his own coach and horses. He passed away at his home in Chalk Farm, north London. Collections of his work can be found at various institutions in the UK and America.
Robert Arp is an American philosopher. Robert Arp was born on March 20, 1970. Robert Arp is known for his work in ethics, modern philosophy, ontology, philosophy of biology, cognitive science, evolutionary psychology, religious studies, and philosophy and popular culture. Robert Arp works as an adjunct professor teaching philosophy courses in the classroom and online. Robert Arp teaches at numerous schools in the Kansas City, Missouri area and other areas of the United States.
"Dwan Hurt was an American basketball coach and dean at Junipero Serra High School. He was named 2010 State Coach of the Year by Cal-Hi Sports and Daily Breeze Coach of the Year in 2010. Hurt coached the Serra Cavaliers, his high school alma mater, to the 2010 California Interscholastic Federation Division III Boys Basketball State Championship. He also led Serra to the State Division IV title in 1993. Hurt passed away in his sleep on November 25, 2016."
Seaview Hospital is a historic tuberculosis sanatorium located in Willowbrook on Staten Island, New York. The complex was planned and built between 1905 and 1938. Seaview Hospital is now a national historic district and was the largest and most costly municipal facility for the treatment of tuberculosis in the United States at that time.
"Martin Cox is a former Canadian Football League wide receiver. Martin Cox played college football at Vanderbilt University. In his first CFL season with the Ottawa Rough Riders, he caught 32 passes for 546 yards and 7 touchdowns, earning him the Frank M. Gibson Trophy as the top rookie in the CFL East. Martin Cox also played for the Toronto Argonauts and Winnipeg Blue Bombers. He concluded his career in 1983 in the United States Football League with the Tampa Bay Bandits."
Samba Diakité is a professional footballer. Samba Diakité was born on January 24, 1989. Samba Diakité was born in France and has Malian citizenship. Samba Diakité plays as a midfielder. Samba Diakité is a member of the Mali national team. Samba Diakité plays for the Kuwaiti club Al Tadhamon SC.
Horizon Nuclear Power is a British energy company. Horizon Nuclear Power was established in 2009. The head office of Horizon Nuclear Power is located in Gloucester. Horizon Nuclear Power is owned by Hitachi. On January 17, 2019, Horizon suspended its UK nuclear development programme.
Peter Sainthill was a Member of Parliament for Tiverton in Devon, England. He was a strong supporter of the Royalist side in the Civil War. Peter Sainthill was born on July 8, 1593, and passed away on August 12, 1648. He was known for his culture and unaffected simplicity of character. Peter Sainthill was the subject of a Puritan verse satire called "Peter's Banquet" or "The Cavalier in the Dumps" written around 1645.
"Nkhaba is an 'inkhundla' of Swaziland, located in the Hhohho District. Nkhaba's population was 15,704 according to the 2007 census. Areas under Nkhaba include Jubukweni, Mhlosheni (formerly Forbes Reef) next to Malolotja Game Reserve, Hawane, Mahebedla east and west, Mnyokane, Malanti, Luvinjelweni, etc. Nkhaba is known as one of the coldest places in Swaziland."
Timpisini is an "inkhundla" of Swaziland. Timpisini is located in the Hhohho District. The population of Timpisini as of the 2007 census was 8,471.
"Rottøya is an island located in Aure municipality in Møre og Romsdal county, Norway. Rottøya is situated between the mainland and the larger island of Ertvågsøya. To the north of Rottøya lies the small island of Ruøya. The Mjosund Bridge spans the Mjosundet strait, connecting Rottøya to Ertvågsøya to the west. The Smalsund Bridge crosses the Smalsundet strait, linking Rottøya to Ruøya to the north. The Aursundet strait is situated to the east of the island."
Alppila Upper Secondary School is a school located in Helsinki, Finland. The school was founded in 1959. The current principal is Susanna Kalmari. Alppila Upper Secondary School is also known as Alppilan Lukio. It is a Finnish school with around 700 students.
Die Streuner is a German band specializing in medieval music. Die Streuner, also known as "The Strays" in English, was formed in 1994. The band frequently performs at markets and festivals.
"Nishikawa Castle was a branch castle of the Saigo Clan in the Mikawa region during the Age of Warring States in Japan. The name Nishikawa means "west river" in Japanese. There are no extant structures on the site of the castle, though alterations to the topography, such as earthen ramparts and a dry moat, are readily apparent. An explanatory signboard is posted by the trail leading up to the main courtyard. Nishikawa Castle site is located in Ishimaki-Nishikawa-cho, Toyohashi in Aichi Prefecture."
Benachiba Chelia is a town and commune located in Sidi Bel Abbès Province in northwestern Algeria.
El Ghedir is a town and commune in Skikda Province in Algeria. Skikda Province is located in north-eastern Algeria.
"Drea is a town and commune located in Souk Ahras Province in north-eastern Algeria. Drea is situated in the north-eastern region of Algeria."
Terraguelt is a town and commune in Souk Ahras Province in Algeria. Terraguelt is located in north-eastern Algeria.
Guellal is a town and commune in Setif Province in north-eastern Algeria. Guellal is located in Algeria. Guellal is situated in the north-eastern part of Algeria.
Jennifer Hens is an Australian sports shooter. Jennifer Hens was born on August 1, 1986. Jennifer Hens participated in the women's 10 metre air rifle event at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
Nina Christen is a Swiss sports shooter. Nina Christen was born on February 7, 1994. Nina Christen competed in the women's 10 metre air rifle event at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
Everett Owen Alldredge was an American archivist and records manager. He was born and raised in Mount Vernon, Indiana. Alldredge completed his undergraduate studies in history at DePauw University. He joined the staff of the National Archives in 1940 and served as Assistant Archivist for Records Management from 1959 to 1971. Alldredge was also president of the Society of American Archivists from 1963 to 1964. He received the Emmett Leahy Award in 1969. Alldredge passed away from cancer two years after his retirement on September 9, 1973.
"Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital, also known as Larue D. Carter Memorial Hospital, is a historic hospital complex and national historic district located in Indianapolis, Indiana. The district resources were developed between 1930 and 1951 by the Veterans Administration and encompass 15 contributing buildings, 2 contributing sites, 2 contributing structures, and 5 contributing objects on the hospital campus. The main complex is connected by an enclosed corridor and consists of the main hospital building (1931), kitchen/mess hall/boiler house/attendants' quarters, general medical building (1939), and recreation building (1941). The buildings reflect the Colonial Revival and Classical Revival styles of architecture. The name of the eponymous Dr. Carter had previously been attached to the state's first intensive-treatment psychiatric hospital, a facility within a large assembly of buildings (which then also included both the University of Indiana Indianapolis campus and the V.A. Hospital), in recognition of his leadership role in the state's Mental Health Association, at a time when the Civil War-era Central State Hospital psychiatric facility, in the same city, was being pilloried as an obsolete relic reflecting inhumane approaches to mental illness. This V.A. facility was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2012."
The 1988–89 SK Rapid Wien season was the 91st season in club history. SK Rapid Wien is a football club.
Ralf Baartmans, known by his stage name Ralvero, is a Dutch DJ and record producer. Ralf Baartmans was born in Roosendaal, Netherlands. Ralvero is affiliated with Spinnin' Records, the label through which he has released most of his singles.
"Pierre Adamoli was a French collector. Pierre Adamoli was a bibliophile. Pierre Adamoli lived during the Age of Enlightenment."
"Owl Peak is located in the northern Teton Range within Grand Teton National Park, Wyoming. It is situated just east of Elk Mountain and west of Jackson Lake, across from Lizard Creek Campground. The easiest access to the peak is by boat to the Berry Creek Trailhead at Wilcox Point, then heading west on the Owl Creek Trail. Hiking along Berry Creek and Owl Creek trails, off-trail access to the summit can be achieved with a steep ascent. To the north of the mountain, the Tetons merge into the Yellowstone Plateau, while to the south lies Webb Canyon."
Azamn is an Arabic newspaper based in the Sultanate of Oman on the Arabian Peninsula. The Omani government suspended Azamn on August 9, 2016, after a report about senior Omani officials pressuring the country's judiciary in an inheritance case. Subsequently, on September 26, a court ordered the permanent closure of Azamn.
Les Sanguinaires is a French television film directed by Laurent Cantet. The film was part of the 2000, Seen By... project.
"Knight-Hennessy Scholars is an international graduate-level scholarship program for study at Stanford University. The program was established in 2016. It aims to prepare students for leadership roles in addressing complex global issues by finding creative solutions. Scholars receive full funding to pursue any graduate degree at Stanford and have opportunities for leadership training, mentorship, and experiential learning across various disciplines."
Home BancShares, Inc. operates as Centennial Bank. Home BancShares, Inc. is a bank holding company based in Conway, Arkansas. Home BancShares, Inc. is one of the largest banks in the United States. Centennial Bank operates 165 branches in Arkansas, Alabama, Florida, and New York City.
The 1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships took place from June 1 to 4, 1988 at Hayward Field at the University of Oregon in Eugene, Oregon. The event aimed to determine the individual and team national champions of men's and women's collegiate Division I outdoor track and field events in the United States. It was the 66th annual men's championships and the seventh annual women's championships. This was the Ducks' sixth time hosting the event and the first since 1984. UCLA and LSU emerged as the top teams in the men's and women's categories, respectively. This victory marked the eighth men's team title for UCLA and the second for LSU's Lady Tigers. LSU went on to secure a record eleven consecutive national championships between 1987 and 1997.
"Red Konga, also known as Konga Roja in Spanish, is a Mexican drama film directed by Alejandro Galindo. The film was released in 1943 and features María Antonieta Pons and Pedro Armendáriz in starring roles."
Gerze Tunnel is a highway tunnel located in Sinop Province, northern Turkey. It is part of the Sinop-Samsun Highway within the Black Sea Coastal Highway. The construction of Gerze Tunnel was carried out by the Turkish Cengiz Construction Company. The tunnel consists of twin tubes, each carrying two lanes of traffic in both directions. It is flanked by Demirciköy Tunnel in the northwest and Yenikent Tunnel in the southeast on the same highway. Gerze Tunnel was opened to traffic on March 26, 2014.
Mitoguardin 1 is a protein. Mitoguardin 1 is encoded by the MIGA1 gene. In humans, Mitoguardin 1 is encoded by the MIGA1 gene.
Jorrit Croon is a Dutch field hockey player. Jorrit Croon was born on August 9, 1998. Jorrit Croon plays as a midfielder or forward. Jorrit Croon is a member of the sports team Bloemendaal. Jorrit Croon is also a member of the Dutch national team.
The 2016 Rose of Tralee was the 58th edition of the annual Irish international festival held on 22–23 August 2016. The competition was televised live on RTÉ television. 65 women from all over the world took part during the Rose of Tralee festival with 32 going on to the live shows. This was the first year that all 65 roses were invited to Tralee before being reduced to 32 for the live shows. On 22 August on the first night of the live shows, Matt O'Connor, a Fathers4Justice campaigner, stormed onto the stage as Lisa Reilly, the Cavan Rose, was being interviewed. Cameras panned away from the scene towards Reilly's mother and father before advertising a competition. While the competition was being shown, security tackled the man to the ground and escorted him off the stage to the exit where gardai awaited for him. He was not arrested as he had a ticket for the event. The show resumed shortly afterwards and Lisa Reilly admits she broke down after the entire ordeal off stage. On 23 August, Chicago Rose Maggie McEldowney was crowned as the 2016 Rose of Tralee. The 27-year-old works as the director of development at a Catholic high school in the south side of Chicago, and her family hails from Derry and Wicklow. It was the third time Chicago has won the contest after winning in 1960 and 1987. After receiving her crown, she was serenaded by country singer Nathan Carter who sang "The Rose of Tralee". John Slowey won the escort of the year. An average of 618,000 viewers watched the second night of the competition on RTÉ according to the official TAM/Nielsen ratings.
Hassan Hameed, commonly known as Dakey, is a Maldivian retired footballer who played as a goalkeeper. Hassan Hameed was born on March 18, 1980. Hassan Hameed is currently the goalkeeping coach for Super United Sports.
The Independence 20, also known as the Freedom Independence 20, is an American sailboat designed by Gary Mull for disabled sailors. It was first built in 1999. The boat was initially constructed by Tillotson Pearson in the United States for Freedom Yachts and later by Catalina Yachts. The Independence 20 shares the same hull as the Catalina Yachts-built Aero 20.
The 1990–91 St. Francis Terriers men's basketball team represented St. Francis College during the 1990–91 NCAA Division I men's basketball season. The team was coached by Rich Zvosec, who was in his third year at the helm of the St. Francis Terriers. The Terrier's home games were played at the Generoso Pope Athletic Complex. The team has been a member of the Northeast Conference since 1981. The Terriers finished their season at 15–14 overall and 8–8 in conference play. At the end of the regular season Rich Zvosec was named NEC Coach of the Year and Ron Arnold was named NEC Newcomer of the Year. Over 29 games, Lester James made 149 field-goals on 215 field-goal attempts, producing a 69.3 field-goal percentage that is 16th all-time in NCAA history.
"Sam Sing Kung Temple, also known as the Three Saints Temple, is a Chinese temple located in Sandakan, Sabah, Malaysia. The temple was built in 1887, making it the third oldest temple in Sandakan, following the Goddess of Mercy Temple and Tam Kung Temple. Additionally, Sam Sing Kung Temple is a part of the Sandakan Heritage Trail."
"Pierre Bénichou was a French journalist. Pierre Bénichou was honored as a Commandeur. Pierre Bénichou was born on March 1, 1938. Pierre Bénichou passed away on March 31, 2020."
"Robin Koch is a German professional footballer. Robin Koch plays as a defender for Premier League club Leeds United and the German national team. Robin Koch has previously played for Eintracht Trier II, Eintracht Trier, 1. FC Kaiserslautern II, 1. FC Kaiserslautern, and SC Freiburg. Robin Koch has also represented Germany at the under-21 level. In August 2020, Robin Koch signed for Leeds United ahead of their Premier League return."
Tom Baumgart is a German professional footballer. Tom Baumgart was born on November 12, 1997. Tom Baumgart plays as a forward for Erzgebirge Aue.
Monopoly Streets is a video game based on the board game of the same name. Monopoly Streets is part of the Monopoly video game series. The game was developed by EA Salt Lake and published by Electronic Arts. Monopoly Streets was released on the PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, and Wii on October 26, 2010.
"Re Daniel Dawal Migel 3 is a 2004 Sri Lankan Sinhala comedy, action film. It was directed by Roy de Silva and produced by Soma Edirisinghe for E.A.P Films. The film is the third and final installment of the Re Daniel Dawal Migel film franchise and a sequel to the 2000 film 'Re Daniel Dawal Migel 2'. The lead roles were reprised by the comic duo Bandu Samarasinghe and Tennyson Cooray, along with Dilhani Ekanayake, Jayantha Bopearachchi, and Sanoja Bibile. The music for the film was composed by Somapala Rathnayake. Although the film was a blockbuster hit in Sri Lanka's cinema theatres, it was considered a failure when compared to the first two installments. 'Re Daniel Dawal Migel 3' is the 1031st Sri Lankan film in the Sinhala cinema."
"Mohamed Reda Abaci is a former Algerian footballer. Mohamed Reda Abaci was born on August 8, 1975. Mohamed Reda Abaci represented the Algeria national football team and scored 1 goal in 8 appearances."
"Maziar Kouhyar is an Afghan professional footballer. Maziar Kouhyar was born on September 30, 1997. Maziar Kouhyar plays as a midfielder. Maziar Kouhyar most recently played for EFL League One side Walsall. Maziar Kouhyar is the first Afghan to play professionally in Great Britain."
"ATPase phospholipid transporting 9A is a protein. ATPase phospholipid transporting 9A is encoded by the ATP9A gene. ATPase phospholipid transporting 9A is found in humans."
Revaz Nadareishvili is a Georgian Greco-Roman wrestler. Revaz Nadareishvili was born on June 21, 1991. Revaz Nadareishvili won a bronze medal at the 2017 World Wrestling Championships. Revaz Nadareishvili competed in the men's Greco-Roman 98 kg event at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Revaz Nadareishvili was eliminated in the round of 16 by Elis Guri.
Enrique Mathet was a French businessman and landowner. Enrique Mathet was one of the founders of General Alvear. Enrique Mathet served in the first Municipal committee of the commune.
Bestamak is a town located in the Aktobe Region of west Kazakhstan.
"The Testament of Aga Koppanyi is a Hungarian adventure film released in 1967. The film is based on the novel of the same name by István Fekete."
The 1944 United States presidential election in Minnesota took place on November 7, 1944. Minnesota was won by the Democratic candidate, incumbent President Franklin D. Roosevelt, who won the state over New York Governor Thomas E. Dewey by a margin of 62,448 votes, or 5.55%. Nationally, Roosevelt was re-elected to an unprecedented fourth term as president, with 432 electoral votes and a comfortable 7.5% lead over Dewey in the popular vote. However, Roosevelt would not serve the entirety of his fourth term, as he died within a half-year after winning his final election. Roosevelt was the only president of the United States who was elected to more than two quadrennial terms. The 22nd Amendment, ratified on February 27, 1951, ensures that Roosevelt will continue to hold this record indefinitely, as the said amendment prohibits any person from serving more than two and a half terms as president.
Yoav Raanan is an Israeli former Olympic diver. Yoav Raanan was born on January 15, 1928. Yoav Raanan was born in Cairo, Egypt.
Emma di Resburgo is a melodramma "eroico" in two acts by Giacomo Meyerbeer. It was the composer's sixth opera and the third that he wrote for an Italian theatre. The libretto in Italian by Gaetano Rossi is set in Scotland. Meyerbeer's opera had its premiere at the Teatro San Benedetto Venice on June 26, 1819.
Philipp Pflieger is a German long distance runner. Philipp Pflieger was born on July 16, 1987. Philipp Pflieger specializes in the marathon. Philipp Pflieger competed in the men's marathon event at the 2016 Summer Olympics and finished in 55th place. In 2018, Philipp Pflieger competed in the men's marathon at the 2018 European Athletics Championships in Berlin, Germany, but did not finish his race.
Tewelde Estifanos is an Eritrean long distance runner. Tewelde Estifanos was born on November 2, 1981. Tewelde Estifanos specializes in the marathon. Tewelde Estifanos competed in the men's marathon event at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Tewelde Estifanos finished in 60th place with a time of 2:19:12.
Evansville Journal News, also known as the Citizens Bank Building-Evansville Journal Building, is a historic commercial building located in downtown Evansville, Indiana. It was built in 1910 and is a two-story, Beaux-Arts style brick building with a limestone front. The building was originally built to house a newspaper. It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982.
The 1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships were part of the first annual NCAA swim meet to determine the team and individual national champions of men's collegiate swimming and diving in the United States. The championship took place at Scott Natatorium in Annapolis, Maryland, hosted by the United States Naval Academy. Only individual championships were officially contested during the first thirteen NCAA-sponsored swimming and diving championships. Unofficial team standings were kept, but a team title was not officially awarded until 1937. Northwestern is recognized as this year's unofficial team champion, marking the first title for the Wildcats.
Buly Da Conceição Triste is a sprint canoeist from São Tomé and Príncipe. Buly Da Conceição Triste was born on July 4, 1991. Buly Da Conceição Triste competed in the men's C-1 1000 metres event at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Buly Da Conceição Triste's time of 4:46.396 in the semifinals did not qualify him for the finals. Buly Da Conceição Triste was the flag bearer for São Tomé and Príncipe at the Parade of Nations. Buly Da Conceição Triste won a gold, a silver, and a bronze medal at the 2019 African Games.
"Night Striker" is a video game developed and published by Taito for the Taito Z System in 1989. The player controls an armoured car to shoot enemy invaders and destroy a terrorist organization. The game combines elements from Sega's "Space Harrier" and "Out Run". Different versions of "Night Striker" were released for Sega Mega-CD in 1993, Sony PlayStation in 1995, and Sega Saturn as "Night Striker S" in 1996. A version was also included in the "Taito Memories II Gekan" compilation for PlayStation 2 in 2007. The game received mixed reviews, with the Mega-CD version criticized for poor graphics. The music for "Night Striker" was composed by Taito's Zuntata sound team and has been released separately. It is important to note that the game was only released in Japan.
The Kings River Viaduct is a planned series of bridges and embankments carrying California High-Speed Rail over the Kings River in Fresno County and Kings County, California. The site is between the Fresno and Kings–Tulare stations, roughly east of Laton and north of Hanford. The structure is planned to be over long because three river channels must be crossed, two of which were created by floods in the 1860s. In the vicinity of the crossing, the Kings River consists of three widely separated river channels collectively known as the Kings River Complex. From north to south, these are Cole Slough, Dutch John Cut, and the Old Kings River, all of which flow in a westerly direction. Cole Slough and the Old River separate at the People's Weir, the largest weir in the Kings River system. The Old River was the main course of the river until two floods in 1861 and 1867, the first of which created Cole Slough and the second of which caused it to become the river's new main course. Since then the Old River has been dry except when river flows are exceptionally high. Dutch John Cut diverges from Cole Slough east of the bridge site, and joins the Old River to reform the main channel of the Kings River to the west of the bridge site. Cole Slough is then mostly diverted into several canals in the vicinity of Laton. Dirt excavation sites in the vicinity of the bridge will be reused as groundwater recharge basins once construction is complete.
Rugby sevens at the 2018 Commonwealth Games was held on the Gold Coast, Australia from April 13 to 15. The rugby sevens competition took place at Robina Stadium. This marked the sixth time the men's competition was held, starting from its debut at the 1998 Games, with the introduction of women's rugby sevens. A total of sixteen men's teams and eight women's teams, consisting of 312 athletes (12 per team plus one traveling reserve), competed in each respective tournament.
"Behold the Dreamers is a debut novel by Imbolo Mbue. The novel was published in 2016 and focuses on two families in New York City during the 2008 financial crisis. One family is the Jonga family, immigrants from Cameroon, and the other is the wealthy employers, the Edwards family."
"Cristiano Lombardi is an Italian footballer. Cristiano Lombardi was born on August 19, 1995. Cristiano Lombardi plays as a right winger. Cristiano Lombardi is currently playing for Serie B club Salernitana, on loan from Lazio."
The 1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships took place at the Malkin Athletic Center at Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts. It was part of the 12th annual NCAA swim meet to determine the team and individual national champions of men's collegiate swimming and diving in the United States. Only individual championships were officially contested during the first thirteen NCAA-sponsored swimming and diving championships. Unofficial team standings were kept, but a team title was not officially awarded until 1937. Michigan is recognized as this year's unofficial team champion, marking the sixth such title and the second consecutive win for the Wolverines.
"Wanaparthy district is a district in the Indian state of Telangana. Wanaparthy district is located 143 km from the state capital Hyderabad. Wanaparthy district is also an assembly Constituency in Telangana state. Wanaparthy district is a famous historical site in Telangana and had served as the capital of Wanaparthy Samsthanam. Wanaparthy district was previously part of Mahabubnagar district."
"Abner, the Invisible Dog" is a 2013 American comedy film. The film was directed by Fred Olen Ray and written by Pat Moran. The main cast includes Daniel Zykov, Molly Morgen Lamont, David DeLuise, and David Chokachi.
"Crack'ed" is a target shooting video game developed by Robert Craig (credited as Robert Neve) for the Atari ST and released by Atari Corporation in 1988. An Atari 7800 port was published the same year. In "Crack'ed," the player must protect bird eggs by shooting predators. An Atari 2600 version was in development, but never released.
"Romany Love is a British musical film released in 1931. The film was directed by Fred Paul and features Esmond Knight, Florence McHugh, and Roy Travers. Romany Love was produced at Isleworth Studios as a quota quickie."
Les Mason is an American politician. Les Mason was born on October 11, 1954. Les Mason is a member of the Republican party. Les Mason represents the 73rd district in the Kansas House of Representatives. Les Mason has been serving in this position since 2014.
Monopoly Star Wars is a video game released in 1997. It is part of the Monopoly franchise and is based on the board game set in the Star Wars fictional universe. The game was developed by Artech Studios and published by Hasbro Interactive. It was exclusively released for Microsoft Windows computers. The game follows the traditional Monopoly gameplay rules but with a "Star Wars" theme, featuring famous characters and locations from the franchise.
"Hermann Czech is an Austrian architect. Hermann Czech was born on November 10, 1936. Hermann Czech was born and currently resides in Vienna. Hermann Czech has a private practice in Vienna."
"Ala Ela is a Telugu film released in 2014. The film was directed by Aneesh Krishna and produced by Ashok Vardhan. The cast includes Rahul Ravindran, Hebah Patel, Kushi, Bhanu Sri Mehra, Vennela Kishore, and Shani Salmon. The music for the film was composed by Bheems Ceciroleo and cinematography was done by Sai Sri Ram. Ala Ela was released on November 28, 2014."
Imron Cotan is an Indonesian diplomat. Imron Cotan was born on December 21, 1954. Imron Cotan served as the Ambassador of Indonesia to Australia from 2003 to 2005. Imron Cotan also served as the Ambassador of Indonesia to China from 2010 to 2013.
Scott McCarthy is a Canadian weightlifter. Scott McCarthy competes in the 77 kg category and represents Canada at international competitions. Scott McCarthy has competed at world championships, most recently at the 1999 World Weightlifting Championships.
"Kuanysh Rymkulov, also known as Qwanış Rımqulov (Куаныш Рымкулов or Қуаныш Рымқұлов), is a Kazakhstani male weightlifter. He competes in the 85 kg category and represents Kazakhstan at international competitions. Kuanysh Rymkulov participated in the 1996 Summer Olympics in the 83 kg event and also competed at the 1999 World Weightlifting Championships."
"Basket of deplorables" is a phrase from a 2016 presidential election campaign speech delivered by Democratic nominee Hillary Clinton on September 9, 2016. Clinton used this phrase to describe half of the supporters of her opponent, Republican nominee Donald Trump, stating that they are racist, sexist, homophobic, and xenophobic. The next day, she expressed regret for her statement, clarifying that she did not mean to label half of the supporters in that way. The Trump campaign later used this phrase against Clinton during and after the election. Some Trump supporters embraced the "deplorable" label as a form of reappropriation. There were discussions among journalists and political analysts about the impact of this incident on the election's outcome. In her 2017 book "What Happened," Clinton acknowledged that this was one of the factors contributing to her loss.
Clovis Morales is a Honduran long distance runner. Clovis Morales was born on February 27, 1949. Clovis Morales holds Honduran records in the 3000m, 10000m, and marathon events. Clovis Morales participated in the Men's 5000 metres at the 1968 Summer Olympics.
Theodor Johansen is a Danish badminton player. Theodor Johansen was born on September 8, 1992.
Alonso Guzmán y Talavera was a Roman Catholic prelate. Alonso Guzmán y Talavera was appointed the first Bishop of Trujillo in 1577.
Zhao Jingyi was a general of the Chinese Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms Period state Later Tang. He served as one of the emperor's chiefs of staff ("Shumishi") from 928 to 929. Before becoming chief of staff, he held the position of deputy military governor of Tianxiong Circuit, which is headquartered in modern Handan, Hebei. Zhao Jingyi passed away on March 24, 929, while still serving as "Shumishi". Unfortunately, there is no biography of him in the "Old History of the Five Dynasties" or the "New History of the Five Dynasties", so there is limited information available about his career.
Krzysztof Bartnicki is a Polish translator, writer, musician/composer, lexicographer, and Joyce scholar. Krzysztof Bartnicki was born in 1971. Krzysztof Bartnicki's translations into English include poetry of Stanisław Dróżdż and Bolesław Leśmian. Krzysztof Bartnicki is the author of several Polish-English dictionaries.
Bedopassa Buassat is a Bissau-Guinean freestyle wrestler. Bedopassa Buassat was born on September 20, 1992. Bedopassa Buassat competed in the men's freestyle 97 kg event at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Bedopassa Buassat was eliminated in the round of 32 by Magomed Ibragimov.
The 2017 Milwaukee Brewers season was the 48th season for the Brewers in Milwaukee, the 20th in the National League, and 49th overall. The Brewers were managed by Craig Counsell in his third season as manager. They finished the season 86–76 to finish six games behind the Chicago Cubs in the National League Central Division. The Brewers finished one game behind the Colorado Rockies for the second Wild Card spot.
The 2017 St. Louis Cardinals season was the 136th for the St. Louis Cardinals of Major League Baseball (MLB). The Cardinals are a franchise based in St. Louis, Missouri. It was the 126th season for the Cardinals in the National League (NL), and their 12th at Busch Stadium III. The Cardinals missed the playoffs for a second consecutive season.
"Second Firsts" is a book published in 2013 by Christina Rasmussen, a crisis intervention counselor. In the book, she introduces a new model of grief based on the science of neuroplasticity. Rasmussen describes grief as a catalyst for redefining identity and outlines the process of "reentry", which is returning to life.
"Wang Lumin is a Chinese Greco-Roman wrestler. Wang Lumin was born on December 7, 1990. Wang Lumin participated in the men's Greco-Roman 59 kg event at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Wang Lumin was eliminated in the repechage by Arsen Eraliev."
Erwin Frey was an American sculptor and educator. Erwin Frey is best known for his George Armstrong Custer memorial. Erwin Frey was born on April 21, 1892 and passed away in 1967 or 1968.
Emre Akbaba is a Turkish footballer. Emre Akbaba was born on October 4, 1992. Emre Akbaba plays as a midfielder for the Süper Lig side Galatasaray. Galatasaray is a football club based in Turkey.
"Rodrigo de Beniambras or Rodrigo di Beniambras was a Roman Catholic prelate. Rodrigo de Beniambras served as the Bishop of Santorini from 1527 to 1535. Santorini is the location where Rodrigo de Beniambras served as a bishop."
Dark social media, dark social, or dark traffic, are social shares that do not contain any digital referral information about the source. Dark social is different from sharing on public social networking services like Facebook, as it is done privately through IRC channels, emails, SMS, or copy-and-paste. It is not related to the content but focuses on the traffic of online sharing. In 2014, Dark Social accounted for 69% of sharing activities globally, while Facebook only held 23%. The exact nature of dark social media remains unknown, with the term "dark" implying an element of mystery or invisibility, similar to dark energy in astronomy.
"Felix Geisler is a German footballer. Felix Geisler was born on March 20, 1997. Felix Geisler plays as a midfielder for Energie Cottbus."
Aquimarina spongiae is a bacterium. Aquimarina spongiae belongs to the genus Aquimarina. Aquimarina spongiae has been isolated from the sponge Halichondria oshoro. Halichondria oshoro is found in the coastal area of Jeju in Korea.
Adrian Ropes was an Egyptian-born English television actor. Adrian Ropes appeared in British television series such as "Emergency – Ward 10", "The Human Jungle", "The Avengers", "Randall and Hopkirk", and "Budgie". Adrian Ropes was born on May 8, 1941, and passed away on March 11, 2004.
Qandariyah is a village in northern Aleppo Governorate, northern Syria. Qandariyah is situated on the northern Manbij Plain, halfway between Jarabulus and the lower course of Sajur River. The village is located about west of the Euphrates River and about south of the border to the Turkish province of Gaziantep. Qandariyah had 888 inhabitants as per the 2004 census. Qandariyah administratively belongs to Nahiya Jarabulus within Jarabulus District. Nearby localities include Ghassaniyah to the west, al-Bir Fawqani to the north, and Yusuf Bayk to the east.
Peel's Bill, or the 1819 Act for the Resumption of Cash Payments, marked the return of the British currency to the gold standard. The Bank Restriction Act 1797 had seen paper money replacing convertibility to gold and silver due to the financial pressures of the French Revolutionary Wars. Peel's Bill was controversial in its passing and generated debate and conflict over the decades that followed.
Natural gas is a primary energy source in Israel, mainly used for electricity production and to a lesser degree in industry. Israel started producing natural gas from its own offshore gas fields in 2004. Between 2005 and 2012, Israel imported gas from Egypt via the al-Arish-Ashkelon pipeline, which was terminated due to the Egyptian Crisis of 2011-14. As of 2014, Israel produced over 7.5 billion cubic meters of natural gas a year and had 199 billion cubic meters of proven reserves of natural gas as of the start of 2016. In early 2017, Israel began exporting natural gas to the Kingdom of Jordan.
"Khruli is a village located in Poltava Oblast, Ukraine. Khruli is subordinated to Lokhvytsia Raion."
Jakob Franck was a German philologist and teacher. Jakob Franck contributed over 300 biographical entries to the German General Biographical Dictionary, known as "Allgemeine Deutsche Biographie." Jakob Franck lived from February 18, 1811, to September 17, 1884.
"Sonia Shirsat is a Fado singer from Ponda taluka, Goa, India. She has been referred to as "the ambassador of Goan music to the world" and has performed across India and the world, often during cultural and music events in Goa. Sonia Shirsat sings in 13 different languages. As of 2019, she has been promoting Fado in Goa by holding training and introductory classes in various parts of the region."
The 1952 West Riding County Council election was held on Saturday, 5 April 1952. The election took place in the administrative county of the West Riding of Yorkshire, which excluded the county boroughs of Barnsley, Bradford, Dewsbury, Doncaster, Halifax, Huddersfield, Leeds, Rotherham, Sheffield, Wakefield, and York. The whole council of ninety-six members was up for election, with each county electoral division returning one councillor. After the election, the composition of the council was as follows: Labour Party: 61, Conservative Party: 28, Independents: 4, Liberal Party: 3.
"Rajkiya Engineering College, Kannauj, is a government engineering college located in Kannauj, Uttar Pradesh, India. It is a constituent college of Dr. A.P.J. Abdul Kalam Technical University in Lucknow. The college had its temporary campus at Harcourt Butler Technical University in Kanpur before shifting to its permanent campus in July 2017. The college offers Bachelor's programs in electrical engineering, computer science engineering, electronic engineering, and civil engineering. Admission to the college is through an entrance test (UPSEE) conducted by AKTU, Lucknow."
The 2016 Nigeria Entertainment Awards is the 11th edition of the Nigeria Entertainment Awards. The event was hosted by Richard Mofe Damijo and Ebbe Bassey. It took place on September 4 at the BMCC Tribeca Performing Arts Center in New York City, U.S.
Kilfane Church is a medieval church and National Monument located in County Kilkenny, Ireland.
Sanchez of Bel Air is an American sitcom. Sanchez of Bel Air aired on USA Network from October 3 to December 26, 1986.
Lucia Aniello is an Italian-born American director, writer, and producer. Lucia Aniello is best known for her work on Comedy Central's "Broad City". Lucia Aniello has directed and written episodes of "Broad City", as well as the miniseries "Time Traveling Bong" and the 2017 film, "Rough Night". Aniello resides in Los Angeles with her boyfriend and comedic partner Paul W. Downs, with whom she co-wrote "Rough Night".
The 6th Asia Pacific Screen Awards were held in Queensland, Australia in late 2012.
Heikki Hietanen was a Finnish swimmer. Heikki Hietanen was born on August 30, 1914, and passed away on May 27, 2000. Heikki Hietanen competed in two events at the 1936 Summer Olympics.
Koinonia of West Georgia, commonly referred to simply as Koinonia, was a private, non-denominational Christian, accredited center for independent studies located on the Carrollton-Villa Rica border in the U.S. state of Georgia. It was founded in 1997 originally as a school for high school students, but over the years evolved into a K-12 format school. Koinonia only had classes on Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays, leaving Mondays and Fridays free. Some students coming out of Koinonia succeeded in different areas in which other students from "traditional" schools have struggled.
The Rebellion Festival, formerly known as Holidays in the Sun and the Wasted Festival, is a British punk rock festival that was first held in 1996. The festival has received coverage from mainstream press sources such as The Guardian, The Independent, The Daily Telegraph, and Kerrang. The first festival in 1996 took place at the Winter Gardens in Blackpool, England, where it is still held today, although in some years it has also been held in nearby Morecambe. The festival has also been organized under different brand names in various countries including Australia, United States, Japan, Germany, Netherlands, Italy, Belgium, the Basque Country, Ireland, and Austria. It is a family-run event that celebrates Punk music along with bands from other alternative genres, Glam Rock artists, and bands from the 1960s and 1970s. The festival features up to seven music stages, an acoustic stage, a literary stage, a Punk Art gallery, workshops, and stalls for clothes, music, and other products. Each year, over 300 acts perform at the festival over a four-day period, usually held on the first weekend in August from Thursday to Sunday. The festival has a positive relationship with Blackpool Council and the local community, and has been involved with local charities. Another punk festival, Nice 'N Sleazy in Morecambe, originated as an offshoot of Wasted in Morecambe, the 3B's (Breakfast, Beer, Bands) Festival, offering campsite accommodation with an unofficial stage. The Boomtown Rats' performance at the 2015 festival gained national attention when lead singer Bob Geldof criticized other bands and the audience for their fashion preferences. The 2020 event was canceled due to the Covid-19 pandemic and was replaced with an online festival.
"IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016) was a major professional wrestling event. The event was scripted and produced by the wrestling company International Wrestling Revolution Group (IWRG). The event took place on August 3, 2016, at Arena Naucalpan in Naucalpan, State of Mexico, Mexico. In the main event, Dragon Fly defeated Demonio Infernal in a "Lucha de Apuestas" match, forcing him to unmask and reveal his real name, José Antonio Rojas. In the semi-final match, Judas el Traidor defeated Black Terry, furthering their storyline feud. The show also featured three additional matches."
Annamanum plagiatum is a beetle species in the Cerambycidae family. It was described by Per Olof Christopher Aurivillius in 1913 under the genus "Orsidis". Annamanum plagiatum is found in Borneo and Malaysia.
"Talgat Ilyasov is an Australian wrestler. Talgat Ilyasov was born on February 25, 1981. Talgat Ilyasov competed in the men's 74 kilogram freestyle wrestling competition at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Talgat Ilyasov currently holds the position of President of Wrestling Australia."
Abdullah Öztürk is a Turkish para table tennis player of class 4 and Paralympian. He represented Turkey at the 2012 Summer Paralympics in London, United Kingdom. In 2014, he won the silver medal in the Team C5 event at the World Para Table Tennis Championships in Beijing, China along with Ali Öztürk and Nesim Turan. He also took the gold medal in the Team C4 event at the 2016 Lignano Master Open in Italy with his teammates Ali Öztürk and Nesim Turan. Abdullah Öztürk captured the gold medal in the individual C4 event at the 2016 Summer Paralympics in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. He won the bronze medal in the Team C4-5 event of the Paralympics with his brother Ali Öztürk and teammate Nesim Turan. As of April 2019, Abdullah Öztürk ranks second in the world list of his disability class.
Vicenta Chávez Orozco, also known as María Vicenta de Santa Dorotea, was a Mexican Roman Catholic nun. She was the founder of the Servants of the Holy Spirit and the Poor. Orozco was born on February 6, 1867, and passed away on July 30, 1949. She was admitted to a hospital in Guadalajara with pneumonia, where she had a radical call to help others. After recovering, she fulfilled this promise and later established her own religious order to continue her mission. Orozco was beatified and made a Servant of God on April 13, 1978, by Pope Paul VI. She was later named Venerable by Pope John Paul II on December 21, 1991, and beatified on November 9, 1997.
"Cahuilla Creek is a tributary stream of Wilson Creek, which is a tributary of Temecula Creek and the Santa Margarita River in Riverside County, California. Cahuilla Creek flows southwest through the Anza Valley and Cahuilla Valley in the Cahuilla Indian Reservation to Wilson Creek. The mouth of Cahuilla Creek is at its confluence with Wilson Creek at an elevation of . The source of Cahuilla Creek is at , at an elevation of 5,800 feet, on the west slope of Thomas Mountain 0.6 miles west-southwest of Tool Box Spring. Wilson Creek is located 7 miles south-southwest of Cahuilla Mountain and 20 miles south-southeast of San Jacinto."
"Two of the Earthly Branches" is a work for string quartet composed by He Xuntian in 1983.
Josef Schäffer is an Austrian track and field athlete. Josef Schäffer was born on July 2, 1891 in Moravia. Josef Schäffer competed in the 1912 Summer Olympics. He participated in the decathlon, shot put, discus throw, and two-handed discus throw. In the decathlon, he finished tenth with a score of 6568.585. He placed thirteenth in the shot put and twenty-ninth in the regular discus throw. However, he managed to come sixteenth in the two-handed discus throw.
Ross Creek Aerodrome is located just east of Ross Creek, next to Shuswap Lake in British Columbia, Canada.
Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel was a British Army officer of the East India Company. He was born in 1789 and passed away on March 11, 1865. Steel's father was barrister David Steel, and his mother was Mary Winde, the daughter of Scudamore Winde, a judge of the Supreme Court of Jamaica. Steel joined the East India Company's service as a cadet in 1805 and was promoted to lieutenant in the Madras Army in 1806. He was involved in the Third Anglo-Maratha War of 1817–18 and was slightly wounded. Steel was promoted to captain in 1821 and joined the 51st native infantry in 1824. He served in various roles, including on the quartermaster-general's staff at Nagpur and in the First Anglo-Burmese War in 1826. In 1832, Steel was promoted to major and served as secretary in the military department at Madras from 1832 to 1845. He participated in the capture of Coorg in 1834 and was promoted to lieutenant colonel the following year. Steel was appointed a Companion of the Order of the Bath in the 1838 Coronation Honours. In 1845, he was appointed military auditor-general and promoted to colonel of the Madras fusiliers in 1847. Steel commanded the Madras army during the Second Anglo-Burmese War in 1852–53 and was knighted as a Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath in December 1853. He was promoted to major general and given the command of the Pegu division and the Martaban provinces in 1854. Steel returned to England in 1856 and was promoted to lieutenant general in 1861. He married Elizabeth Margaret, the eldest daughter of Lieutenant Colonel William Read, in 1840. His eldest son, Col. Charles Steel, served in the Crimean War with the 12th Lancers and was present at the Siege of Sevastopol. Col. Charles Steel married Anna Caroline Wood, the daughter of Rev. Sir John Page Wood, 2nd Baronet. Sir Scudamore Winde Steel passed away at his home in Hyde Park, London, in 1865.
Palit Microsystems, Ltd. is a Taiwanese-based company founded in 1988. It specializes in manufacturing graphic cards based on NVIDIA & ATI graphic chipsets. The company's factories are located in China, with offices in Taipei (Taiwan), a logistics center in Hong Kong, and a branch office in Germany. Palit Microsystems operates under two major brands, Palit and Gainward, targeting different global markets. They also have other brands like Daytona, Galaxy (GALAX), Vivkoo, Yuan, KFA2, and XpertVision. Additionally, Palit Microsystems provides contract manufacturing services for graphics cards. In 2013, the company surpassed ASUSTek to become the largest graphics card vendor by volume. Their monthly maximum capacity is 1,200,000 units. As of 2011, Palit held a production share of about 20-25% in the global market for graphics solutions. In Russia, Palit had over 40% market share, and in Ukraine, about 30%. In 2005, Palit Microsystems acquired the Gainward brand, company, and branch Gainward Europe GmbH for $1 million from Taiwan-based TNC Industrial.
Noah Mascoll-Gomes is a competitive swimmer from Antigua and Barbuda. Noah Mascoll-Gomes was born on May 27, 1999. Noah Mascoll-Gomes represented Antigua and Barbuda at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro. Noah Mascoll-Gomes competed in the men's 200 metre freestyle event. Noah Mascoll-Gomes finished 44th in the heats and did not advance to the semifinals. Noah Mascoll-Gomes had the honor of being the flag bearer for Antigua and Barbuda in the closing ceremony.
Kyle Dodd is a South African BMX cyclist. Kyle Dodd was born on February 11, 1994. Kyle Dodd competed in the men's BMX event at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Kyle Dodd finished 6th in his heat during the quarterfinals and did not advance to the semifinals.
Garrett W. Hagedorn was an American Republican Party politician. Garrett W. Hagedorn served in the New Jersey Senate, representing the 40th Legislative District from 1968 until his death. Garrett W. Hagedorn was born and raised in Midland Park, New Jersey. Garrett W. Hagedorn attended the schools of the Eastern Christian School Association, located in Paterson, New Jersey.
Dámaso José Lescaille Tabares was a Cuban revolutionary, journalist, intelligence officer, and ambassador. Dámaso José Lescaille Tabares was born on December 11, 1934, and passed away on January 27, 2014.
Myles Gaskin is an American football running back. Myles Gaskin plays for the Miami Dolphins in the National Football League (NFL). Myles Gaskin was born on February 15, 1997. Myles Gaskin played college football at Washington.
Richard I. Gregory is a Professor in the Departments of Biological Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, and Pediatrics at Harvard Medical School. He is also the Principal Investigator in The Stem Cell Program in the Division of Hematology/Oncology at Boston Children's Hospital. Additionally, he is a Principal faculty member of The Harvard Stem Cell Institute and a 2008 Pew Scholar. Gregory received his PhD from Cambridge University, UK in 2001, focusing on genomic imprinting at the Babraham Institute. He conducted his postdoctoral work at the Fox Chase Cancer Center and the Wistar Institute in Philadelphia, where his research centered on mechanisms of miRNA biogenesis and function, supported by a Jane Coffin Childs Research Fellowship.
"Khalid Assar is an Egyptian table tennis player. Khalid Assar was born on December 10, 1992. Khalid Assar participated in the Men's Singles event at the 2016 Summer Olympics."
"The Porch Fields is an area of medieval farmland located outside Trim, Ireland. It features a medieval roadway that is recognized as a National Monument."
Hot and sour noodles is a dish originating from Sichuan, China and is a popular part of Sichuan Cuisine. The noodles are made from starch derived from peas, potato, sweet potato, or rice.
Oxford Hawks Hockey Club is a field hockey club based at Banbury Road North in Oxford. The club was founded in 1938. Some fixtures are held at other venues including Gosford Hill School, St Edward's School, and Headington School in Oxford. The club runs seven men's and seven women's teams, as well as a large junior section. The men's first XI team plays in the Men's England Hockey League Division One South, while the women's first XI team competes in the England Hockey League Investec Conference West.
The Waterford Bridge, formerly known as Bridge L0327 and now designated as Bridge L3275, is a historic steel truss bridge located over the Cannon River in Waterford Township, Minnesota, United States. It was built in 1909 and is one of the state's earliest bridges to use rigid connections instead of pinned connections. This bridge is unique as it is the only known road bridge in Minnesota where some of the rigid connections are fastened with bolts rather than rivets. The Waterford Bridge was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 2010 due to its significance in engineering. It is a rare surviving example of Minnesota's once-common camelback through truss bridges and is notable for its early and uniquely transitional rigid connections.
"Below Her Mouth is a 2016 Canadian erotic romantic drama film. The film was directed by April Mullen and written by Stephanie Fabrizi. The film stars Natalie Krill as Jasmine and Erika Linder as Dallas. The story revolves around two women in Toronto who meet and start a passionate love affair. The cast also includes Tommie-Amber Pirie, Mayko Nguyen, Elise Bauman, Melanie Leishman, and Sebastian Pigott."
"Truly Madly Guilty" is a novel by Australian author Liane Moriarty. The story revolves around Sam and Clementine, a married couple trying to juggle work and family life. Their lives take a dramatic turn after attending a barbecue party hosted by Clementine's friend Erika, leading to a series of events involving intrigue, lust, and betrayal. The book was published in July 2016 by Flatiron Books. Shortly after its release, Reese Witherspoon and Nicole Kidman acquired the film rights for the novel. Witherspoon and Kidman were already working on a television miniseries adaptation of Moriarty's previous novel, "Big Little Lies".
"The Asia Spelling Cup is an annual spelling bee in Southeast Asia. The event is organized by Qooco, a mobile language learning solutions provider. The first Asia Spelling Cup was held in Singapore in 2013, followed by events in Bali, Indonesia in 2014, and Bangkok, Thailand in 2015. The 2016 Asia Spelling Cup took place at the Conrad Hotel in Bangkok, Thailand on November 12, 2016, and the 2017 event was held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia on November 12, 2017. The competition attracts primary and secondary school students from various Asian countries, including Malaysia, Thailand, China, and Indonesia. The 2013 event featured Singaporean students."
The 2016 Sun Belt Conference football season was the 16th season for the Sun Belt Conference in operating a football league and was part of the 2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season. The season began on September 1 with a game between Appalachian State and Tennessee. This season marked the third season for the Sun Belt since realignment in 2014, which added Idaho and New Mexico State as the tenth and eleventh members. Both teams were previously independents before joining the conference. The Sun Belt Conference is classified as a "Group of Five" conference under the College Football Playoff format, along with the American Athletic Conference, Conference USA, the Mid-American Conference, and the Mountain West Conference. The Sun Belt football conference for this season included 11 members: Appalachian State, Arkansas State, Georgia Southern, Georgia State, Idaho, Louisiana–Lafayette, Louisiana–Monroe, New Mexico State, South Alabama, Texas State, and Troy. The conference championship was determined by win-loss record within the conference. Arkansas State entered the season as the defending Sun Belt champions, having gone undefeated in 2015 conference play. However, they lost to Louisiana Tech in the New Orleans Bowl with a score of 28–47.
Alexus Laird is a Seychellois swimmer. Alexus Laird was born on March 11, 1993. Alexus Laird competed in the Women's 100m backstroke at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
Mohamed Saadaoui is a Tunisian freestyle wrestler. Mohamed Saadaoui was born on May 11, 1995. Mohamed Saadaoui competed in the 86 kg division at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Mohamed Saadaoui was eliminated in the first bout. Mohamed Saadaoui started wrestling in 2005.
Jean-François Berruyer was a French general known for his role in the French Revolutionary Wars. He was born on October 25, 1741, in Lyon and passed away on April 17, 1804, in Paris. In 1792, he became the 1st Commander of the Army of the Interior, which was independent from the Army of the North and the Army of the Centre. Later, in 1803, he was appointed as the Commandant and Governor of Les Invalides from 1797 to 1804.
Borbála Sóthy is a Hungarian swimmer. Borbála Sóthy was born on December 21, 1916. Borbála Sóthy competed in the women's 400 metre freestyle at the 1936 Summer Olympics.
Binary Capital was an early stage venture capital firm based in San Francisco. The firm focused on early-stage consumer technology companies. The founders' previous investment experience included roles at General Catalyst Partners, Benchmark Capital, Lightspeed Venture Partners, and Bain Capital Ventures. Binary's first fund managed $125 million. Their second fund was slated to manage $175 million, although in the wake of co-founder Justin Caldbeck's sexual harassment scandal, the fund's limited partners voted to shut it down. In June 2017, Caldbeck took an indefinite leave of absence following allegations of unwanted sexual advances by several female startup founders. The firm issued a statement denying the allegations. Reid Hoffman of Greylock Partners and the Founder of LinkedIn, issued a piece in response. Days later, Caldbeck issued a statement no longer denying the allegations and publicly apologizing. Entrepreneur Brendan Mulligan wrote a piece on Medium about Caldbeck's statement. Following this announcement, due to pressure from the media and Limited Partners in the fund, Caldbeck resigned as did new Partner Matt Mazzeo from Lowercase Capital. Jonathan Teo, the last remaining Managing Partner of the fund, issued a statement on Facebook, acknowledging that he knew of Caldbeck's harassment of women from the past and had not acted on it. In March 2018, venture capital firm Lerer Hippeau took over the management of Binary’s first fund. The firm completed takeover of Binary’s second fund in April 2018.
The 1973 NCAA University Division Swimming and Diving Championships took place in March 1973 at the University of Tennessee Student Aquatic Center in Knoxville, Tennessee. This was the 50th annual NCAA-sanctioned swim meet to determine the team and individual national champions of University Division men's collegiate swimming and diving in the United States. Indiana emerged as the top team, securing their sixth consecutive and sixth overall title.
"Lærke Buhl-Hansen is a Danish sailor. Lærke Buhl-Hansen was born on March 30, 1992. Lærke Buhl-Hansen participated in the women's RS:X event at the 2016 Summer Olympics."
"The Florida Fire Frogs are a baseball team based in North Port, Florida. They were members of Minor League Baseball's Florida State League and were the Class A-Advanced affiliate of the Atlanta Braves from 2017 to 2020. The affiliation with the Atlanta Braves was terminated after the 2020 season, leaving the team's future uncertain. Founded in 2017, the Fire Frogs were originally located in Kissimmee, Florida, which is part of the Greater Orlando metropolitan area. They were scheduled to play their home games at CoolToday Park in 2020, after previously playing at Osceola County Stadium."
"Akkystau, also known as Aqqystau, is a town in Atyrau Region, southwest Kazakhstan. Akkystau is located at an altitude below sea level."
Steven Holt is the Iowa State Representative from the 18th District. Steven Holt is a Republican. Steven Holt has been serving in the Iowa House of Representatives since 2015. Steven Holt was born on January 28, 1958.
"Gülşah Düzgün is a Turkish Paralympian goalball player. Gülşah Düzgün was born on September 25, 1995. Gülşah Düzgün is a member of the national team."
Juan Camilo Quintero is the former director of Ruta N and the founder of Tecnnova. Quintero has served as the Secretary of Productivity for Antioquia and was a secretary in the cabinet of former Medellín mayor Anibal Gaviria. He led Medellín's efforts to host the Youth Olympic Games in 2018. Currently, he heads the Antioquia Section of ANDI and later was designated as the leader of the Entrepreneurship and Innovation department after cutting resources.
Cherry Branch is a stream located in Cedar County, Missouri. It was named after the cherry timber found in the area.
"Drillia rimata is a species of sea snail. Drillia rimata is a marine gastropod mollusk. Drillia rimata belongs to the family Drilliidae."
The 1973 Nottinghamshire County Council election was held on Thursday, 12 April 1973. The election resulted in the Labour Party winning an overall majority of seats on the council. The election was the first to take place to the new non-metropolitan county council of Nottinghamshire as defined by the Local Government Act 1972, which had reformed local government in England and Wales. The council acted as a "shadow authority" until 1 April 1974, when it gained control from its predecessor county council, which had been established by the Local Government Act 1888. Nottingham was included within the administrative county of Nottinghamshire for the first time as a non-metropolitan district. Nottingham would subsequently regain independent control over its affairs when it became a unitary authority in 1998.
Katorah Hortense Marrero, known by her stage name Young M.A, is an American rapper and entrepreneur. The abbreviation "M.A" in her stage name stands for "Me Always." She gained recognition with the hit single "Ooouuu," reaching the top 20 of the Billboard Hot 100 and accumulating over 300 million views on YouTube. Young M.A received nominations for BET and MTV Artist of the Year and Female Hip-Hop Artist of the Year. She has appeared on magazine covers, global ad campaigns for Google Pixel 2, Beats By Dre, and Pandora, and performed on "The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon" with Alicia Keys. In 2018, she was featured on Forbes 30 Under 30 and launched the KWEENZ Foundation with her mother. Young M.A has also received a proclamation from New York City.
Bolesław Romanowski was a submarine commander in the Polish Navy during World War II. Bolesław Romanowski was born on March 21, 1910 and passed away on August 12, 1968.
Henrique Haddad is a Brazilian sailor. Henrique Haddad was born on May 28, 1987, in Rio de Janeiro. Henrique Haddad and Bruno Bethlem participated in the men's 470 event at the 2016 Summer Olympics and placed 23rd. In 2019, Henrique Haddad won the Snipe World Championship.
Jan Drenth is a Dutch chemist. Jan Drenth was born on February 20, 1925. Jan Drenth was a professor of structural chemistry at the University of Groningen from 1969 to 1990.
Giuditta del Vecchio is an Italian actress. Giuditta del Vecchio is known for her roles in the 1992 Canadian film "Léolo" and the 1996 Italian film "The Nymph". Giuditta del Vecchio is featured prominently on the cover of the 1996 re-release of the album "Tiger Bay" by the English band Saint Etienne.
"Grevillea eryngioides, commonly known as the curly grevillea, is a shrub belonging to the genus Grevillea. It is native to the eastern Wheatbelt and western Goldfields-Esperance regions of Western Australia. The shrub typically grows to a height of and has non-glaucous branchlets. It has simple dissected leaves with a blade that is in length and wide. The plant blooms from September to January, producing a terminal inflorescence with yellow or purple flowers, followed by a globose glaucous viscid fruit that is long."
"When the Dead Return" is a 1911 American motion picture produced by Kalem Company and directed by Sidney Olcott. The leading roles are played by Gene Gauntier, Jack J. Clark, and JP McGowan. The cinematography is done by George K. Hollister.
"Bhaini Salu is a village. Bhaini Salu is located in the Ludhiana East tehsil of Ludhiana district, Punjab."
"Sonai is a town in the Cachar district in the Indian state of Assam. Sonai is also the name of a circle and block in the town. The River Sonai flows through Sonai, joining with the Barak River near Dungripar Village. Chandragiri Park and an archaeological site, including a temple of the Kachari Kingdom at Shivtilla (Changutilla) near Madhab Chandra Das College (MCD College), are popular places to visit in Sonai."
"Louis Perceau was a French polygraph. Louis Perceau used several pseudonyms including "Helpey bibliographe poitevin", "Dr. Ludovico Hernandez", "Alexandre de Vérineau", "Un vieux journaliste", "Radeville et Deschamps", and "Marquis Boniface de Richequeue", sometimes jointly with Fernand Fleuret."
The AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup, previously known as the AFC U-20 Futsal Championship, is the primary youth futsal competition among the Asian Football Confederation nations. The tournament was first held in 2017 and is played biennially. Starting from 2021, the competition will be renamed from the "AFC U-20 Futsal Championship" to the "AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup".
Tekla Teresa Łubieńska was a Polish playwright, poet, and translator. Tekla Teresa Łubieńska was born on June 6, 1767, in Warsaw and died on August 15, 1810, in Kraków.
"Talwandi Koka is a village in Bhulath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. It is located away from Bhulath and district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch, who is an elected representative."
Silica sulfuric acid is a solid acid. Silica sulfuric acid is prepared by soaking silica gel with sulfuric acid. Silica sulfuric acid, also known as SSA, is used as a catalyst in various organic synthesis processes. It is considered a cheap, nonhazardous, and easy to handle solid acid catalyst with high acidity.
Fresh Sunday is a Chinese cooking-variety show. Fresh Sunday is hosted by He Jiong and Jackson Wang. Fresh Sunday airs every Sunday on Hunan TV.
Stephen Panasuk is an American football quarterback. Stephen Panasuk was born on January 19, 1989. Stephen Panasuk is currently a free agent.
Chan Shih-chang is a Taiwanese professional golfer. As an amateur, Chan won the 2004 Hong Kong Amateur Open and competed in the 2006 Asian Games, winning the bronze medal in the men's team event. Chan turned professional in 2008 and has competed on several tours in Asia: Asian Tour, Asian Development Tour, PGA Tour China, and OneAsia Tour. He has had the most success on the Asian Development Tour where he has six wins, including three in 2014 when he finished second on the Order of Merit. He won once on PGA Tour China in 2015. His biggest win came at the 2016 King's Cup, an event co-sanctioned by the Asian Tour and the European Tour. Later in 2016, he won the Asia-Pacific Open Mitsubishi Diamond Cup in Japan, an event co-sanctioned by the Japan Golf Tour and the Asian Tour.
"Bholapur is a village. Bholapur is located in the Ludhiana East tehsil of Ludhiana district, Punjab."
The 2016–17 Scottish Youth Cup was the 34th season of the Scottish Youth Cup, organized by the Scottish Football Association for its member clubs. The tournament was for the under-20 age group, previously under-19. Motherwell were the defending champions after winning the 2016 final against Heart of Midlothian.
The Concept 40 is an American sailboat designed by Gary Mull and first built in 1981. The boat was built by Concept Yachts in the United States and also by Hyundai in Seoul, South Korea. The design was later developed into the Kalik 40 and the Ocean 40.
Tomoka Correctional Institution is a state prison located in Daytona Beach, Volusia County, Florida. It is owned and operated by the Florida Department of Corrections. The facility has security levels including minimum, medium, and close, and was opened in 1981 with a maximum capacity of 1263 prisoners. In June 2008, Tomoka correctional officer Donna Fitzgerald was stabbed to death by an inmate. An investigation by the DOC's inspector general blamed the warden and officials for security breaches, neglect of duty, and ineptitude. In 2014, eight Tomoka inmates died in custody, making it the highest number among Florida state prisons. The FDLE declined to release information on some of the deaths. Nicholas Lindsey is also mentioned in the text.
"Igando is a community in Alimosho local government area of Lagos State, South-Western Nigeria. On July 26, 2016, suspected Niger Delta militants attacked the town, resulting in casualties and property damage. Alimosho General Hospital is situated in Igando."
Kristian Brymora is an Australian professional football player. Kristian Brymora was born on October 23, 1998. Kristian Brymora last played for the Australian National Premier Leagues Northern NSW side Broadmeadow Magic FC. Broadmeadow Magic FC is a football club based in Australia.
Arthur Ormston is an English association footballer. Arthur Ormston was born on June 3, 1900 in Alnwick. Arthur Ormston played for eight different clubs in the Football League during the interwar period. Arthur Ormston made his Football League debut with Chesterfield during the 1921–22 season. Arthur Ormston played for Durham City, Coventry City, Barrow, Wigan Borough, Oldham Athletic, Bradford City, Bristol Rovers, and Oldham again. Arthur Ormston also made appearances for Blyth Spartans, Stalybridge Celtic, and Macclesfield.
"Idol Memories is a Japanese idol anime television series produced by Seven Arcs Pictures and Happy Elements. It is a "hybrid anime" with the first half being typical animation and the second half featuring a live-action segment with the anime's voice actresses. Katsuya Kikuchi directed the anime with scripts by Hiroshi Oonogi, and I've Sound produced the music. Idol Memories premiered on October 3, 2016, on Tokyo MX and later aired on AT-X."
The 2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy was a senior international figure skating competition held in September 2016 at the Eissportzentrum Oberstdorf. It was part of the 2016–17 ISU Challenger Series. Medals were awarded in the disciplines of men's singles, ladies' singles, pair skating, and ice dance.
"Castle Rock Mountain is located in the Beartooth Mountains in Montana. It is one of the tallest peaks in the Beartooth Mountains and the tenth-tallest in Montana. The mountain is situated in the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness, on the border of Custer and Gallatin National Forests. Castle Rock Mountain is flanked by the Sundance Glacier to the north and the Castle Rock Glacier to the south. The nearest taller mountain to Castle Rock Mountain is Castle Rock Spire to the east."
Okada Manila is a casino resort and hotel complex situated on the Entertainment City gaming strip in Parañaque, Metro Manila, Philippines. The establishment was founded and overseen by Japanese billionaire Kazuo Okada, with a total construction cost of approximately 250 billion Yen and a development period of 7 years.
"Daulowal is a village in Bhulath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. It is located away from Bhulath and district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch who is an elected representative of the village as per the Constitution of India and Panchayati raj (India)."
Hotel Monterey is a 1973 American silent documentary film directed by Chantal Akerman. It is Akerman's first feature film. In 2013, an article in the "Village Voice" stated that "Hotel Monterey", along with two other Akerman films, "La Chambre" and "News from Home" are a "not-to-be-missed event" as part of MoMa's “To Save and Project” film series.
Raipur Rajputan is a village in Bhulath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. Raipur Rajputan is located away from Bhulath and district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch who is an elected representative of the village as per the Constitution of India and Panchayati raj (India).
"Nadala is a village in Bholath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. Nadala is located away from Bhulath and district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Municipal Councillor, who is an elected representative of the village as per the constitution of India and Municipality (India)."
"Aero Engine Corporation of China (AECC) is a Chinese state-owned aerospace manufacturer focused on the design and development of aeroengine and related technology. The company was established on August 28, 2016. AECC was capitalized with US$7.5 billion with AVIC and COMAC as shareholders, China's two main state aerospace companies. The corporation consists of 46 affiliate companies, including 22 engine companies, several institutes, 3 aeroengine-repairing factories, and some other small companies. The main institutes under AECC are Beijing Institute of Aerial Materials, Shenyang Engine Design and Research Institute, China Gas Turbine Research Institute, China Aero Power Machine Research Institute, Guizhou Aero-Engine Research Institute, and China Aero Power Control System Institute. The main subsidiaries of AECC are Harbin Dong'an Engine Manufacturing Company, Shenyang Liming Engine Manufacturing Company, Chengdu Engine Manufacturing Company, Xi'an Aero-Engine Manufacturing Company, Liyang Engine Manufacturing Company, and Shanghai Commercial Aero-Engine Manufacturing Company."
"ABC Country is a digital radio station. ABC Country is available on mobile devices, DAB+ digital radio, digital TV, and online. Some self-help retransmissions in WA and Qld also carry the station's programme stream. ABC Country is owned and operated by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation."
The Cadell Fault is a geological fault located in the Riverina area of New South Wales and Victoria within Australia. It impacts the courses of the Murray River, Edward River, Wakool River, Goulburn River, and Campaspe River. The fault is known for changing the course of rivers due to seismic activity. It is visible as a continuous earthen ridge along the Cobb Highway between Deniliquin and Echuca, extending further south into Victoria. The fault is likely named after Francis Cadell, an early pioneer and river trader on the Murray River.
The Trumbull Correctional Institution is a medium-security prison for men located in Leavittsburg, Trumbull County, Ohio. It is operated by the Ohio Department of Rehabilitation and Correction. The facility first opened in 1992 and currently has a population of 1,529 state inmates with mixed minimum, medium, and close (maximum) security levels.
"The Ashi River is a right tributary of the Songhua in eastern Manchuria. The Ashi River flows through Harbin's Acheng District in the People's Republic of China."
Krishnananda Agamavagisha, also known as Mahamahopadhyaya Krishnananda Bhattacharya, was a Kulin Bengali Brahmin from Nabadwip, Nadia district. He was a renowned Pandita and Sadhaka of the Tantra tradition who lived around 1575 CE. Krishnananda Agamavagisha is the author of the "Tantrasara" and is considered one of the four pillars of Shreehatta origin scholars in Nabadwip, along with Raghunatha, Raghunandana, and Vishvambhara (Chaitanya). He introduced the Navya Tantric-scripture, "Tantrasara," and worked for Sanatana Philosophy.
Marugalpatty is a village in Theni District, Tamil Nadu, India. Marugalpatty is located 18 km west of Periyakulam and 15 km south of Andipatti.
Grand Casino Portorož is the oldest casino in Slovenia. It is located in Portorož and is owned and operated by Casino Portorož d.d. The casino underwent renovation in 2012.
Saeed Ghani is a Pakistani politician. Saeed Ghani is the current Provincial Minister of Sindh for Labour, Education and Literacy and Human Resources. Saeed Ghani has been a member of the Provincial Assembly of Sindh since August 2018. Saeed Ghani was also a member of the Provincial Assembly of Sindh from July 2017 to May 2018. Saeed Ghani is a Member of the Senate of Pakistan.
"Museum Masuuni Brunou is a museum about the industrial history of Juankoski, Finland. The museum is located in the old blast furnace building next to the rapids, which are now used for hydro electricity production. The Juankoski Heritage Society, established in 1990, aims to preserve the cultural and historical heritage of the area. The museum, opened in 1991 by the society, showcases products of the foundry, local history, and the lives of the inhabitants. The museum's name, 'Blast furnace Brunou,' is derived from the building's original purpose and one of the founders of the foundry, Brynolf Brunou. The main entry hall features displays on the transition from peasant to iron worker and the evolution of the factory from an ironworks to a cardboard mill. The second floor exhibits products from the foundry, while other floors host changing displays on various themes. The museum primarily houses products from the ironworks of the 1900s and is open during the summer months from June to August."
"Florentine Junction, also known as Pillinger’s Creek, Risby’s Junction, Florentine Rail Yard, and Florentine Depot, is the terminus of the Derwent Valley Railway. The Derwent Valley Railway is a 3’ 6” narrow gauge railway that operates from New Norfolk in Tasmania, Australia. The station opened in 1936 but closed in the mid-twentieth century when the railway beyond Kallista was closed."
Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal is an Indian sprinter. Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal was born on March 5, 1982. Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal specializes in the 400 metres event. Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal participated in the 4 × 400 metres relay event at the 2016 Summer Olympics. In July 2016, Muhammed was part of the relay team that broke the national 4 × 400 metres relay record at Bangalore and qualified for the Olympics. The quartet of Muhammed, Mohammad Anas, Ayyasamy Dharun, and Arokia Rajiv clocked 3:00:91, rewriting the national record of 3:02.17 set by themselves four weeks earlier in Turkey. The performance also helped the relay team jump to 13th place in the world rankings.
"Make Votes Matter is a political pressure group based in the United Kingdom. Make Votes Matter campaigns for replacing the first-past-the-post voting system with proportional representation for elections to the British House of Commons."
Johnny Laws is an American Chicago blues guitarist, singer, and songwriter. Johnny Laws was born on January 12, 1943. Johnny Laws has been a regular performer for over half a century in Chicago's South Side clubs. Johnny Laws has released two albums, including "Burnin' in My Soul". "Blues & Rhythm" magazine in November 1999 noted, "It's a real shame that Johnny Laws has been unjustly ignored in the past... This is an enjoyable CD... Full marks to those folks at Electro-Fi." Johnny Laws' version of McKinley Mitchell's "End of the Rainbow" demonstrates his versatility and vocal range. In an April 1999 editorial leader, the "Toronto Star" remarked that "South Side Chicago fave Johnny Laws... [is] winning plaudits for his seductive, soul-drenched blues."
"The Giraldilla International is an international badminton tournament held in Cuba. The competition has been organized annually since 2000 and is now considered a young supraregional Badminton Championship. The tournament is named after the unofficial symbol of the city of Havana, 'La Giraldilla,' which is a bronze weathervane in the female figure on the oldest fortress of the city, the Castillo de la Real Fuerza. The organizer of the tournament is the Cuban Badminton Association in cooperation with the Badminton Pan Am continental federation. In 2013, the tournament was classified as 'Future Series' by the Badminton World Federation (BWF), and since the fifteenth event in March 2014, Giraldilla has been classified as 'International Series' level. The tournament offers a prize pool for players who reach at least the semi-finals, with the current prize pool being $5,000. The XVI edition of the tournament was held in March 2015 in Havana."
"Ask the StoryBots" is an American live action/animated children's television series based on the characters from the StoryBots educational website and videos. It premiered exclusively on Netflix on August 12, 2016. Originally created and produced by JibJab Bros. Studios, the StoryBots media franchise was fully acquired by Netflix in May 2019. In its first season, the series was nominated for an Annie Award, was a finalist for a Peabody Award, was nominated in the International category at the British Academy Children's Awards, and received six nominations for the Daytime Emmy Awards, including Outstanding Preschool Children's Animated Program. It won the 2017 Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Interactive Media - Enhancement to a Daytime Program or Series. The second season, which premiered on Netflix on August 24, 2018, received the Annie Award for Best Animated Television Production for Preschool Children and won two Daytime Emmy Awards for writing and directing. "Ask the StoryBots" also inspired a holiday special, "A StoryBots Christmas", also on Netflix, which won two Daytime Emmy Awards. Starting in its second season, "Ask the StoryBots" has been translated into 22 languages and is available for streaming on Netflix in 190 countries. The third season premiered on August 2, 2019. A trailer for the new episodes was launched on YouTube ahead of the season's premiere.
Henry Stuart Carter, also known as H. Stuart Carter, was a Virginia lawyer. He served part-time for twelve years representing Bristol, Virginia, and Washington County in the Virginia House of Delegates. Carter was a member of the Byrd Organization and participated in its Massive Resistance to racial integration.
"Sailor Jack's Reformation is an American silent film. It was produced by Kalem Company and directed by Sidney Olcott. The leading roles in the film were played by Gene Gauntier, Jack J. Clark, and JP McGowan."
"Nuns in Jeopardy is a novel. Nuns in Jeopardy was written by the Australian author Martin Boyd."
The Holmes Correctional Institution is a state prison located in Bonifay, Holmes County, Florida. It is owned and operated by the Florida Department of Corrections. The facility, opened in 1988, has a maximum capacity of 1185 prisoners and includes security levels such as minimum, medium, and close. In February 2011, Holmes correctional officer Col. Greg Malloy was killed in an exchange of gunfire while assisting in the manhunt for local killer Wade Williams.
Armenia Airways is an Armenian carrier. Armenia Airways is based at Zvartnots International Airport in Yerevan, Armenia.
Nihat Hatipoğlu is a Turkish academician and theologian. Nihat Hatipoğlu was born on May 11, 1955 in Diyarbakır, Turkey.
Metlan Khairabad is a village in Bhulath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. It is located away from Bhulath and the district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch who is an elected representative.
The Chantry Island Lighthouse, officially known as Chantry Island Lightstation Tower, is a lightstation on Chantry Island, off the coast of Southampton, Ontario in Lake Huron. It was constructed in the years 1855 through to 1859, by John Brown of Thorold, Ontario, under the authority of the Province of Canada and is recognized as one of the six Imperial Towers. Virtually identical, they were completed in 1858-1859 on Lake Huron and Georgian Bay and are among the few lighthouses on the Great Lakes made of cut limestone and granite. The lighthouse was planned in about 1850 due to underwater shoals of massive granite boulders making navigation in the area dangerous. The first beacon on the island (1857) was provided by a temporary fixed light which was replaced by the tower. The actual lighthouse was first lit on 1 April 1859. The tower and the keeper's dwelling have been extensively restored. The dwelling is listed on the Canadian Register of Historic Places while the Lightstation Tower is listed on the National Historic Sites of Canada. However, because the island is a bird sanctuary, only one company has a license to offer tours of the property and only on a limited basis. All other access to the island is prohibited.
Emirates Flight 521 was a scheduled international passenger flight from Thiruvananthapuram, India, to Dubai, United Arab Emirates, operated by Emirates using a Boeing 777-300. On 3 August 2016, the aircraft carrying 282 passengers and 18 crew crashed while landing at Dubai International Airport. All 300 people on board survived the accident; 32 were injured, 4 were seriously injured. An airport firefighter died during the rescue operation and another 7 were injured. The accident is the only hull loss of an Emirates aircraft.
Jean-Joseph Rive was a French bibliographer, librarian, and revolutionary leader. Jean-Joseph Rive was born on May 19, 1730, and passed away on October 20, 1791.
Bonnie Burton is an author, journalist, comedian, actress, and show host. Bonnie Burton was born on July 12, 1972. Bonnie Burton is based in San Francisco. Bonnie Burton is known for arts & crafts books like "The Star Wars Craft Book." Bonnie Burton has appeared on web series such as "Geek DIY" on Stan Lee's "World of Heroes" YouTube channel, "Ask Bonnie," Wil Wheaton's "TableTop," and Felicia Day's "Vaginal Fantasy Book Club." Bonnie Burton has worked as a Senior Editor and Social Media Strategist at StarWars.com for Lucasfilm and was a staff writer for "Star Wars Insider" magazine for 10 years. Bonnie Burton is currently working as a freelance writer specializing in topics for young child and teen audiences.
"God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)" is a single released in 2012 by Pete Seeger featuring Lorre Wyatt & Friends. The song was produced and arranged by Richard Barone and Matthew Billy, and released by Billy Barone Productions. It was originally recorded in 2010 aboard the Hudson River Sloop Clearwater, shortly after the BP Oil Spill in the Gulf of Mexico. The spill is referenced in the lyrics of the song. This single marked Seeger's final release. The recording session was filmed live aboard the Sloop as it sailed along the Hudson River. The music video, directed by Damien Drake, can be found on YouTube. The single is available for download on iTunes, Amazon.com, and other digital retailers. The song and video were released on Election Day, November 6, 2012.
The 30th Filmfare Awards took place on September 25, 1983. "Prem Rog" received 12 nominations, "Nikaah" received 11 nominations, and "Bazaar" and "Shakti" received 7 nominations each. "Prem Rog" and "Shakti" both won 4 awards, making them the most-awarded films at the ceremony. "Prem Rog" won Best Director for Raj Kapoor and Best Actress for Padmini Kolhapure, while "Shakti" won Best Film and Best Actor for Dilip Kumar. Dilip Kumar set a record by winning Best Actor for the 8th time for his role in "Shakti."
Rachel Berger is an Australian comedian, actress, and writer. She was born in Israel to Polish Jewish parents and emigrated to Melbourne at the age of five. Berger is known for her stand-up comedy shows such as "Perfect", "Clenched Buttocks", "Loose Cannon", "The She Comic", "Comedy Siren", and "Berger Republic". In 2008, she wrote and performed "Hold the Pickle", a monologue about her parents' experiences during the Second World War. The show was nominated for three Green Room Awards. In 2010, Berger appeared in the Australian production of "Calendar Girls". She also provided the UK voice for Calimero in the 2013 reboot. Berger is the author of "Whaddya Mean You're Allergic to Rubber?" and co-hosts "The Conversation Hour" on Radio 774 ABC in Melbourne with Jon Faine.
"Puthanathani is a city located in Malappuram district, Kerala, India. The town is situated on National Highway 66, between Kottakkal and Valanchery. Puthanathani also has roads leading to Vailathur (and hence Tirur) and Thirunavaya."
"Safaripark Beekse Bergen is the largest wildlife zoo in the Benelux region. It is home to approximately 1,250 animals from over 150 species, including small mammals and large birds. The park is located between the cities of Tilburg and Hilvarenbeek in the south of the Netherlands. Visitors can watch zebras and giraffes on the spacious savannahs. Safaripark Beekse Bergen offers various safari options such as walksafari, carsafari, bussafari, and boatsafari. The park is owned by the company Libéma Exploitatie BV. One unique feature of the park is that visitors can explore it with their own car, without a fence separating them from the animals. They may encounter leopards, zebras, and even have their car 'washed' by a giraffe. Visitors can also take a bus or boat to explore the park. The park also features a bird show and all animals have a strict diet."
"Dimitar Kapinkovski is a retired Macedonian football player and current coach. Dimitar Kapinkovski was born on May 27, 1975. Dimitar Kapinkovski recently managed FK Pelister as an interim coach."
The Cheltenham Badlands are located in Caledon, Ontario. The site occupies an area of approximately 0.4 square kilometers and features exposed and highly eroded Queenston Shale. The Cheltenham Badlands are a significant educational site due to the readily visible geologic processes. The red color and unique topography of the exposed shale make this a popular tourist site. The site is a Provincial Earth Sciences Area of Natural and Scientific Interest (ANSI) since it is considered one of the best examples of "badlands topography" in Ontario.
The Saurashtra people, or Saurashtrians, are an Indo-Aryan ethno-linguistic Hindu community of South India who speak the Saurashtra language. They predominantly reside in the Indian states of Tamil Nadu, Kerala, Andhra Pradesh, and Karnataka. Saurashtrians trace their ancestry to the historical region of Saurashtra in Western India. Their migration to Southern India was due to the forays and desecration of the Somnath temple triggered by frequent Muslim invasions, notably by Mahmud Ghazni. They were a prominent industrious and prosperous mercantile community of merchants and weavers in southern India until the 20th century. Saurashtrians are Brahmins, also known as Saurashtra Brahmins. They are classified based on their gotra, or patrilineal descent. The majority of the people are Vaishnavas, with a significant proportion of Shaivas as well. They are known by their unique family names and use titles such as Sharma, Rao, Iyer, Iyengar, and Achary as their surnames, belonging to linguistic minorities.
Team Differdange–Geba is a continental cycling team based in Luxembourg. The team participates in UCI Continental Circuits races.
Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra is the current Crown Prince of the Malaysian state of Kelantan. He was proclaimed as the Crown Prince of Kelantan on October 18, 2010, upon the accession of his elder brother, Sultan Muhammad V, as the 29th Sultan of Kelantan. Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra is the second of four children of the late Sultan of Kelantan, Sultan Ismail Petra, and Raja Perempuan Tengku Anis. His two younger siblings are Tengku Muhammad Fakhry Petra and Tengku Amalin Aishah Putri. His eldest brother is the Sultan of Kelantan, Sultan Muhammad V, the fifteenth Yang di-Pertuan Agong of Malaysia.
Michael R. Fuljenz is a numismatist, author, and businessman. Michael R. Fuljenz was born in 1954. Michael R. Fuljenz is currently the president of Universal Coin & Bullion, a precious metals trading company based in Beaumont, Texas.
"The Virtuous Scoundrel is a French comedy drama film from 1953. The film was directed and written by Sacha Guitry. The film stars Michel Simon and Louis de Funès."
Jaroslav Benda was a Czech painter, graphic artist, author, and designer of postage stamps and posters. He was born on April 27, 1882, in Prague and passed away on January 12, 1970. Benda's work significantly influenced the development of Czech book graphics. He graduated from the School of Applied Arts in Prague and served as the editor of the magazine "Světozor" from 1907 to 1912. Benda also advised publishers Jan Laichtr and Jan Štenc on book modifications. In 1920, he became a Professor of Applied Arts at the School of Applied Arts and later served as the rector from 1926 to 1928. Some of his notable students included Zdeněk Seydl, Jaroslav Šváb, Antonín Strnadel, Jiří Trnka, and Antonín Homolka.
"The Perfect Circle is a Bosnian film directed by Ademir Kenović. The film is set in Sarajevo during the siege of 1992-1996. It was written by Kenović, Pjer Žalica, and Abdulah Sidran. The title of the film comes from the character "Hamza" portrayed by Mustafa Nadarević, who has the ability to draw perfect circles on paper."
The Egypt national rugby union team represents Egypt in rugby union. The national team was formed after the separation of the Arabian Gulf national rugby union team. In September 2011, the under 20 Egyptian rugby national team traveled to Lebanon to play two matches against Lebanon's national team. Egypt emerged victorious in both matches with scores of 51-5 and 14-10. The captain of the team is Ahmed Elmohamady.
James Leroy Wright Sr. was an American professional basketball player. James Leroy Wright Sr. played in the American Basketball Association (ABA) for two seasons, from 1967 to 1969. He was a member of the Pittsburgh Pipers and won the ABA Finals in 1968. James Leroy Wright Sr. was born on May 6, 1938, and passed away on March 21, 2020.
"Oru Small Family is a 2010 Malayalam film directed by Rajasenan. The film stars Rajasenan, Seetha, Kailash, and Ananya."
Michel-Thomas Labrecque was a Canadian Roman Catholic bishop. Michel-Thomas Labrecque served as the Bishop of Chicoutimi, Quebec from 1892 to 1927. Michel-Thomas Labrecque was born on December 30, 1849 and passed away on June 3, 1932. Chicoutimi is located in Quebec, Canada.
The Sivel SD28 is an Italian aerobatic monoplane designed and built by Sivel Aeronautica. The SD28 features side-by-side seating for two with dual controls. It is powered by a Lycoming AEIO-320-D piston engine mounted on the nose and has a fixed nosewheel landing gear.
The 2011 Maryland Terrapins football team represented the University of Maryland in the 2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season. It was the Terrapins' 59th season as a member of the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC) and its seventh within the framework of the ACC Atlantic Division. Ralph Friedgen did not return for his 11th season as head coach. Maryland's out-of-conference schedule included a continuation of the long-standing rivalry with West Virginia and a neutral site game against Notre Dame at FedExField, the Washington Redskins' stadium.
The 1942 European Amateur Boxing Championships took place in Breslau, Germany from January 20 to 25. There were 97 fighters from 11 countries participating: Germany, Hungary, and Italy had 16 boxers each, while Croatia, Denmark, Finland, Netherlands, Slovakia, Spain, Sweden, and Switzerland also had representatives. The results of the championships were later annulled by AIBA due to World War II.
Rich Raddon is an American entrepreneur. Rich Raddon sold his first venture MOVIECLIPS to Fandango. Rich Raddon works in the media technology space. Currently, Rich Raddon is the co-founder and co-CEO of ZEFR. ZEFR is a company that provides technology solutions for content owners and brands on YouTube.
Thomas H. McNeil was an American football player and lawyer. Thomas H. McNeil was born on February 29, 1860, and passed away on October 1, 1932. Thomas H. McNeil was the first University of Michigan football player to be the starting quarterback in consecutive years. He led the Michigan football team to undefeated seasons in 1884 and 1885. Thomas H. McNeil later became a lawyer practicing in Missouri.
The 1903 Kentucky Derby was the 29th running of the Kentucky Derby. The race took place on May 2, 1903 and offered a purse of $6,000.
The church of San Martín de Tours de Frómista in Frómista, province of Palencia, Spain, was built in the 11th century in Romanesque style. It is located on the Way of St. James to Santiago de Compostella.
The 2003 Windsor and Maidenhead Borough Council election occurred on May 1, 2003, in Berkshire, England. The election was held to select members of the Windsor and Maidenhead Unitary Council. There were boundary changes compared to the previous election in 2000, resulting in a reduction of one seat. The Liberal Democrats gained control of the council, taking over from no overall control.
Lauren Smith is a name associated with various individuals and characters:* Lauren Smith (badminton) is a British badminton player born in 1991.* Lauren Smith (cricketer) is an Australian cricket player born in 1996.* Lauren Smith (swimmer) represented Great Britain at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships.* Lauren Lee Smith is a Canadian actress born in 1980.* Lauren "Betty" Smith is the mother of Blythe Baxter in the "Littlest Pet Shop" (2012 TV series).
The Petrești mine is located in Cluj County, Romania. It is situated 52 km north-east of Cluj-Napoca and 478 km northwest of Bucharest. The mine is known for having one of the largest bentonite reserves in Romania, estimated at 6.3 million tonnes.
Chugoku Electric Power Company is an electric utility operating in the Chūgoku region of Japan. It is the sixth largest by electricity sales among Japan's ten regional power utilities. The company operates the Shimane Nuclear Power Plant. In 1982, Chugoku Electric Power Company proposed building a nuclear power plant near the island of Iwaishima, but faced opposition from many residents and the island's fishing cooperative. In January 1983, almost 400 islanders staged a protest march, sparking a series of over 1,000 protests. Since the Fukushima nuclear disaster in March 2011, there has been increased opposition to construction plans for the plant.
Monkey Thieves, also known as Rebel Monkeys, is a documentary series produced by National Geographic. The series examines the habits and social interactions of rhesus macaques in Jaipur, India. Specifically, it focuses on the "Galta Gang," a troop of sixty monkeys that reside in the Galta Temple, a Hindu temple on the outskirts of Jaipur.
"Smin Peak is a peak located in Antarctica. Smin Peak rises to 850 meters in the southeast foothills of Louis-Philippe Plateau on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land. The peak is partly ice-free and overlooks Cugnot Ice Piedmont to the east and south. Smin Peak is named after the settlement of Smin in Northeastern Bulgaria."
Konush Hill is an ice-covered hill located in Antarctica. It rises to 550 m in the north foothills of Louis-Philippe Plateau on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land. Konush Hill overlooks Sestrimo Glacier to the east and Lafond Bay to the north. The hill is named after the settlements of Konush in Haskovo Province, Southern Bulgaria.
Houshmand Almasi was an Iranian fencer. He competed in various events at the 1964 Summer Olympics. Colonel Almasi, who was also the president of the Iranian Fencing Federation, played a significant role in the establishment of the Asian Fencing Confederation. He presented the proposed Constitution of the AFC at the FIE Congress during the 1972 Munich Olympic Games in Germany and later became the first president of AFC.
The International Association for Translation and Intercultural Studies (IATIS) is a forum. IATIS was founded in August 2004. Juliane House is the President of IATIS. Mona Baker, Şebnem Susam-Sarajeva, and other linguists are members of its Executive Council. The secretariat of IATIS is located in Seoul, South Korea.
Knut Are Tvedt is a Norwegian encyclopedist. Knut Are Tvedt was born on April 29, 1952. Knut Are Tvedt is the editor of the encyclopedias "Store norske leksikon" and "Oslo byleksikon". Knut Are Tvedt's main interests are the history and politics of Oslo.
"Wahyu Gunawan is an Indonesian footballer. Wahyu Gunawan was born on November 10, 1985 in Malang, East Java. Wahyu Gunawan currently plays for Deltras in the Indonesia Super League. Wahyu Gunawan plays as a defender and midfielder."
Pernovo is a settlement in the Municipality of Žalec in Slovenia. Pernovo lies in the Hudinja Hills in the traditional region of Styria. The municipality is part of the Savinja Statistical Region. The local church in Pernovo is dedicated to Saint Oswald and belongs to the Parish of Galicija. The church is a medieval building with significant rebuilding in the 17th and 19th centuries.
"Acrocercops panacivermiforma is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from New Zealand. The wingspan is about 10 mm. There is a separate South Island form. The larvae feed on "Nothopanax simplex" and "Nothopanax sinclairii". They mine the leaves of their host plant. The mine has the form of a simple gallery throughout, and is vermiform in character, the loops being very closely applied to one another, but never crossing. The mine changes direction as it progresses, crossing the leaf in curved sweeps from edge to midrib. The mine is on the upper surface of the leaf and is pale green in color. The frass is finely granular, pale in color, and occupies a broad band in the central third of the gallery. The South Island form of the mine differs somewhat, expanding into a relatively large blotch. The entire mine is on the upper surface of the leaf and is pale green in color. The midrib forms a barrier in its basal two-thirds. The blotch is irregular in shape, with rounded irregularities. The frass is finely granular, black, and scanty. Old mines become white and conspicuous."
Andrei Posnov is a professional ice hockey player. Andrei Posnov currently plays for Vityaz Chekhov in the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL). Andrei Posnov was born on November 19, 1981. Andrei Posnov was selected by the New Jersey Devils in the 4th round (128th overall) of the 2001 NHL Entry Draft.
"Belegali is a village located in Dharwad district of Karnataka, India."
"Porsön is a peninsula and residential area in Luleå, Sweden. Porsön had 5,476 inhabitants in 2010 and is home to a large number of students. Luleå University of Technology and the business park "Aurorum" are located in the area."
"Taj Mahal is a 1963 film based on the historical legend of the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan and his construction of the Taj Mahal in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal. The film was a commercial success and is best known for its award-winning music at the Filmfare awards."
"Love Vibes is a Japanese manga by Erica Sakurazawa. Love Vibes was adapted into a 2009 live action film titled 'Kakera: A Piece of Our Life'."
"Kei Rail is a railway project in South Africa. The Eastern Cape government restored rail services between AmaBhele and Mthatha, on an abandoned branch from the East London-Springfontein main line. Passenger services restarted in March 2008. The local Department of Roads and Transport leases the network from Transnet Freight Rail, and Sheltam Grindrod operates trains. The project was part of a broader development plan for the region. The line has also been used by the Phelophepha health train. ECDORT planned several other projects to restore disused infrastructure in the province. However, funding is threatened, and the service is not connected with the rest of the South African rail network. Kei Rail suspended services in November 2010 but resumed in June 2011. 20 coaches were repossessed by Transnet Rail Engineering and sold to an Angolan railway operator in September 2011."
József Marosi is a Hungarian fencer. József Marosi was born on October 16, 1934. József Marosi won a silver medal in the team épée and a bronze in the team foil events at the 1956 Summer Olympics.
"Hurstbourne Priors is a small village and civil parish in the Basingstoke and Deane district of Hampshire, England. The nearest town to Hurstbourne Priors is Whitchurch, located approximately 1.8 miles (3.1 km) north-east from the village. The church of St Andrew the Apostle, located in Hurstbourne Priors, is the oldest existing church in the Diocese of Winchester. In the churchyard, you can find the grave of noted Irish baritone Harry Plunket Greene (1865-1936), along with his two sons Richard (born 1901) and David (born 1904). Additionally, Finnish industrialist and diplomat Ossian Donner is also buried in the churchyard."
"Dar Sad District is a district located in the Aden Governorate, Yemen. The population of the district was recorded to be 79,712 inhabitants in 2003."
"Wadi Ar Ruqub is a wadi in Yemen. Wadi Ar Ruqub flows past the village of Al Khayalah. The village of Al Khayalah was affected by the flooding of Wadi Ar Ruqub in October 2008."
"The Letter for the King" is a book by the Dutch writer Tonke Dragt, first published in 1962. A sequel, "Geheimen van het Wilde Woud," was published in 1965, and a collection of follow-up short stories, "Het gevaarlijke venster en andere verhalen," in 1979. "De brief voor de koning" was chosen as the best Dutch youth book of the latter half of the 20th century. The book has been translated into Danish, English, German, Greek, Estonian, French, Indonesian, Italian, Japanese, Polish, Czech, Spanish, and Catalan.
Christopher Augustine Reynolds was an Irish Roman Catholic bishop. Christopher Augustine Reynolds became the first Archbishop of Adelaide in Australia. Christopher Augustine Reynolds lived from 1834 to 1893.
"The Economics of English Mining in the Middle Ages is a study of English mining from the Norman invasion in 1066 to the death of Henry VII in 1509. England's economy was primarily agricultural during this period, but the mining of iron, tin, lead, silver, and later coal, played a significant role in the English medieval economy."
John Óge Burke was an Irish gentleman and soldier. He was one of the sons of John na Seamar Burke. John Óge Burke participated in the Nine Years' War (Ireland) alongside his brothers, John na Seamar Burke and William Burke, Lord of Bealatury. However, he was captured in the first week of 1601. The Annals of the Four Masters, "sub anno" 1601, detail John Óge Burke's fate. He was ordered to be put to death by the Earl of Ormond on the orders of the Lord Justice of Ireland for his actions of harassing and plundering the Queen's people while in the company of O'Donnell. John Óge Burke was taken prisoner in O'Meagher's country of Ikerrin by some of the gentlemen of the Butlers and was executed in the month of June.
Jesús Clavería Domínguez is a Spanish former futsal player. Jesús Clavería Domínguez was born on January 4, 1968. Jesús Clavería Domínguez is best known for his time as a goalkeeper with Inter Movistar. Inter Movistar is a futsal team.
Juban District is a district located in the Dhale Governorate, Yemen. The district had a population of 42,397 inhabitants as of 2003.
"Ash Sharyah District is located in the Al Bayda Governorate in Yemen. In 2003, the district had a population of 33,873 inhabitants."
"Sawma'ah District is a district in the Al Bayda' Governorate, Yemen. In 2003, the district had a population of 44,873 inhabitants."
Jovana Marjanović is a beauty pageant contestant. Jovana Marjanović was born in Novi Sad, Yugoslavia, around 1987. Jovana Marjanović represented Serbia and Montenegro in the Miss Earth 2005 pageant. The Miss Earth 2005 pageant took place in Quezon City, Philippines on October 23, 2005. Jovana Marjanović was crowned Miss Earth-Fire, which is the 3rd runner-up title.
Juan Manuel Villa Gutiérrez is a Spanish retired footballer. Juan Manuel Villa Gutiérrez played as a midfielder. Juan Manuel Villa Gutiérrez was born on September 26, 1938.
Richard Bacach Burke was the Clanricarde and Chief of the Name. He died in 1538. Richard Bacach Burke was the son of Ulick Fionn Burke. In 1538, he succeeded his cousin, John mac Richard Mór Burke, as Clanricarde but was deposed by his nephew, Ulick na gCeann Burke, in the same year. All subsequent chiefs of the Galway Burkes would descend from Ulick, while Richard Bacach Burke's descendants disappeared into obscurity.
Karl Schellscheidt is an American soccer player, educator, and entrepreneur. Karl Schellscheidt was born on April 28, 1968, in Union, New Jersey. Karl Schellscheidt is the son of soccer coach and player Manfred "Manny" Schellscheidt. Karl Schellscheidt attended Roselle Catholic High School and graduated in 1986.
Claude Piegts was born on January 1, 1934, in Castiglione, French Algeria. He was shot by firing squad in France at the Fort du Trou d'Enfer on June 7, 1962. Claude Piegts was a pied-noir and a member of the Organisation armée secrète (OAS). He was part of the OAS's Commando Delta and took part in the assassination of the Police Commissar of Algiers, leading to his condemnation to death.
"Luce County Airport is a county-owned public-use airport located in Newberry, Luce County, Michigan, United States. It is part of the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems for 2017–2021 and is classified as a basic general aviation facility."
Byline Bank is a bank headquartered in Chicago. Byline Bank is the primary subsidiary of Byline Bancorp, Inc., a bank holding company. Byline Bank operated 57 branches as of December 31, 2019, with 56 of them located in the Chicago metropolitan area. Byline Bank is the 4th largest Small Business Administration lender.
"The Head of the Hooch Regatta, previously known as the Head of the Chattahoochee Regatta, is a 2-day rowing regatta held annually on the first full weekend in November in Chattanooga, Tennessee. The event is co-hosted by the Atlanta Rowing Club and the Lookout Rowing Club, with assistance from the St. Andrews Rowing Club. The Hooch organization is run entirely by volunteers. The regatta has been praised for its laid-back and hospitable atmosphere by "Rowing News Magazine". Competitors come from over 30 states and several foreign countries, with participants ranging from high school crews to adult masters rowers aged 80 and above. The regatta features a variety of events for men's, women's, and mixed boats in different categories including youth, novice, college, club, varsity collegiate, championship, and masters."
"Mac OS X Lion is the eighth major release of macOS. Mac OS X Lion was publicly previewed at the "Back to the Mac" Apple Special Event on October 20, 2010. Mac OS X Lion brought developments from Apple's iOS to the Mac, including an easily navigable display of installed applications and support for the Mac App Store. The first developer's preview of Lion (11A390) was released to subscribers to the Apple Developer program on February 24, 2011. Lion was released to manufacturing on July 1, 2011, and its final release was via the Mac App Store on July 20, 2011. Over one million Lion sales were reported on the first day of its release, and over six million copies were sold worldwide. Lion is the final release overseen by Bertrand Serlet, considered the "founding father of Mac OS X"."
Il Castello di Atlante is an Italian progressive rock band. The band is based in Vercelli. Il Castello di Atlante was founded in 1974 and released its debut album in the early 1990s. Since then, the band has released 9 albums.
Frank Neuner is a professor of Clinical Psychology at the Faculty of Psychology and Sports Science at Bielefeld University. Frank Neuner was born in 1971.
Vincenzo Alessandri was an Italian Knight of Malta who later became a buccaneer. He died in 1657. There are references to another "Vincenzo Alessandri" who served as the Venetian ambassador to Persia in the 16th century, but it is unlikely that they are the same person based on the provided date of death.
"Katro is a traditional mancala game played by the Betsileo people in the Fianarantsoa Province of Madagascar. Alex de Voogt first described the game in 1998."
"Office 365 is a line of subscription services offered by Microsoft as part of the Microsoft Office product line. The brand encompasses plans that allow use of the Microsoft Office software suite over the life of the subscription, as well as cloud-based software-as-a-service products for business environments, such as hosted Exchange Server, Skype for Business Server, and SharePoint, among others. All Office 365 plans include automatic updates to their respective software at no additional charge, as opposed to conventional licenses for these programs—where new versions require purchase of a new license. Microsoft launched Office 365 on 28 June 2011, aimed originally at corporate users as a successor to Microsoft Business Productivity Online Suite (BPOS). With the release of Microsoft Office 2013, Microsoft expanded Office 365 to include new plans aimed at different types of businesses, along with new plans aimed at general consumers, including benefits tailored towards Microsoft consumer services such as OneDrive. On 21 April 2020, the consumer and small business plans of Office 365 were renamed Microsoft 365, which emphasizes productivity features and services outside of the core Microsoft Office software suite. All products that were called Office 365 were renamed as Microsoft 365 on the same day. In the fourth quarter of fiscal year 2017, Office 365 revenue exceeded that of conventional license sales of Microsoft Office software for the first time."
"Sivan Levy is an Israeli singer-songwriter, filmmaker, and actress. Sivan Levy was born on June 4, 1987."
Westland Studios is a recording studio located in Dublin, Ireland. Westland Studios is situated on Lombard Street, which is less than a minute's walk from Pearse Station. Westland Studios was opened in 1985 and closed in August 2018. From 1985 to 2010, it was managed by Tom Costello and his daughter Deirdre Costello. From 2010 until its closure in 2018, it was leased out to producer and engineer Alwyn Walker.
"Al Hali District is a district located in the Al Hudaydah Governorate, Yemen. The district had a population of 168,071 inhabitants as of 2003."
"Al Marawi'ah District is a district in the Al Hudaydah Governorate, Yemen. The district had a population of 129,527 inhabitants in 2003."
"Sukhnah District is a district of the Al Hudaydah Governorate in Yemen. In 2003, the district had a population of 59,652 inhabitants."
"Bayt al-Faqih District is a district in the Al Hudaydah Governorate, Yemen. The district had a population of 241,300 inhabitants in 2003."
"Hays District is a district located in the Al Hudaydah Governorate of Yemen. As of 2003, the district had a population of 45,436 inhabitants."
Pico del Caballo, Cerro del Caballo or simply Caballo is a mountain in the Sierra Nevada, Spain. It is 3,011 meters high and is the westernmost three thousander of the range.
Phyllonorycter trifoliella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Phyllonorycter trifoliella is known to be found in Estonia, Georgia, Latvia, Lithuania, and the Krasnodar Region of Russia. The larvae of Phyllonorycter trifoliella feed on "Lathyrus roseus" and "Trifolium" species. They create mines on the leaves of their host plant.
"Phyllonorycter triflorella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Phyllonorycter triflorella is found in France, Corsica, Sardinia, Italy, and Croatia. The larvae of Phyllonorycter triflorella feed on "Argyrolobium zanonii", "Calicotome villosa", "Cytisus villosus", and "Genista sericea". The larvae create an upper-surface tentiform mine on the leaves of their host plant. Pupation of Phyllonorycter triflorella occurs within the mine."
Lower Wyke is a village located in the Basingstoke and Deane district of Hampshire, England. Lower Wyke is part of the civil parish of St. Mary Bourne. The nearest town to Lower Wyke is Andover, which is situated approximately southeast from the village.
Bani Al Harith District is a district in the Amanat Al Asimah Governorate, Yemen. It was founded by a sub-clan of Banu Harith. As of 2003, the district had a population of 184,509 inhabitants.
"The Big Us" was a radical underground newspaper published in Cleveland, Ohio starting in September 1968. The paper's politics reflected the views of SDS. The editors were Carol Cohen McEldowney and Carole Close. The paper's headquarters were in a church coffeehouse/youth center called The Outpost near the Case Western Reserve University campus. In May 1969, McEldowney left to work in an antiwar GI coffeehouse in South Carolina. The paper changed its name to "Burning River News" in October 1969. In 1970, it merged with the "Buddhist Third-Class Junkmail Oracle" to become the "Burning River Oracle". It later changed its name to "Burning River" and published its last few issues in July 1970. "The Big Us" was a member of both the Underground Press Syndicate and the Liberation News Service. Contributors included local underground cartoonists Dave Sheridan and Fred Schrier.
Eric "Tower" Mathoho is a South African football central defender. Eric Mathoho was born on May 1, 1990, in Thohoyandou. He currently plays for Kaizer Chiefs and the South Africa national team. In 2019, Mathoho was wrongfully accused of scamming many women from Venda. The victims went on a live interview with Phalaphala Fm where Mathoho was also present. In July 2020, Eric Mathoho's elder sister Balanganyani passed away at the age of 41, and the cause of her death was not disclosed to the media. Six months after his sister's death, Eric lost his father, Johannes Ntshavheni Mathoho, whose passing was reported in the media on January 7, 2021.
The Moravská gobelínová manufaktura, also known as MGM, is a tapestry manufactory located in Valašské Meziříčí, Czech Republic. It has been involved in creating handmade classical and artistic tapestries for over fifty years. Considered the first tapestry manufactory in Czechoslovakia, it is the only workshop of its kind in Moravia and Czech Silesia. The manufactory collaborates with Czech artists and architects and focuses on preserving traditional manual techniques. The school of Gobelin tapestry, founded by Rudolf Schlattauer, has been active for over a hundred years.
Iuri Osip'ovi is a Soviet Olympic fencer. Iuri Osip'ovi was born on March 16, 1937. Iuri Osip'ovi competed in the individual and team foil events at the 1956 Summer Olympics.
Little Somborne is a hamlet and civil parish located in the Test Valley district of Hampshire, England. The nearest town to Little Somborne is Stockbridge, which is approximately 2.3 miles (3.5 km) north-west of the hamlet.
Charles W. Thompson, also known as Maxwell Street Jimmy Davis, was an American electric blues singer, guitarist, and songwriter. He collaborated with John Lee Hooker and recorded an album for Elektra Records in the mid-1960s. Thompson was a regular street musician on Maxwell Street in Chicago for over 40 years. He is best known for his songs "Cold Hands" and "4th and Broad", and he was also referred to as Jewtown Jimmy.
"Eosopostega armigera is a moth species belonging to the family Opostegidae. It was described by Puplesis and Robinson in 1999. Eosopostega armigera is found exclusively in the Moluccas region of Indonesia."
Bill Congreve is an Australian writer, editor, and reviewer of speculative fiction. Bill Congreve has published the work of Australian science fiction and horror writers under his MirrorDanse imprint.
"King, Queen, Joker" is a 1921 American silent feature farce. It was written and directed by Sydney Chaplin, who is the elder half-brother of Charlie Chaplin. The film was produced by Famous Players-Lasky and distributed through Paramount Pictures. It was shot in England, France, and the United States. Only a small portion of the film, specifically the barbershop sequence, survives at the British Film Institute. This sequence was included in the 2011 Criterion DVD special two-disc edition release of "The Great Dictator."
"Hölty-Gymnasium is a public high school. Hölty-Gymnasium was established in 1922. Hölty-Gymnasium is located in Wunstorf, Germany."
North Village Rams is a Bermudian football club based in Pembroke Parish. North Village Rams participates in the Bermudian Premier Division.
Deportivo Mongomo is an Equatoguinean football club based in the city of Mongomo. Deportivo Mongomo participates in the Equatoguinean Premier League. Deportivo Mongomo has won the league in 1980, 1997, and 2010.
The 2007 Maui Invitational Tournament is an annual early-season college basketball tournament. The tournament took place in Lahaina, Hawaii from November 19-21 at the Lahaina Civic Center. The winning team of the tournament was the Duke Blue Devils.
"Shant TV is a private television broadcasting company in Armenia. Shant TV was founded by Arthur Yezekyan in Gyumri in 1994. Shant TV launched a full 6-hour broadcasting schedule in May 1995. Shant TV is based in Armenia."
The Battle of Cathair Cuan was a conflict that took place between 977 and 978 in Munster, Ireland. Brian Bóruma and the Dál gCais attacked, while Donnubán mac Cathail and the Viking army of Limerick defended. Brian and the Dál gCais emerged victorious, leading to the loss of the Limerick lordship and its territories to the Gaels until the Norman invasion of Ireland. It is believed that Aralt mac Ímair, the "King of the Foreigners of Munster," was killed in the battle, while Donnubán survived. Later accounts suggest that Donnubán was also eventually killed.
"I'm Jealous" is a song by the Australian rock duo Divinyls. It was released in 1995 as the lead single from their fifth studio album "Underworld". The song achieved success in Australia, reaching the top twenty and peaking at number fourteen, staying in the top fifty for nineteen weeks. It was certified gold and ranked as the sixty-fourth best-selling single of 1995. Additionally, the song was featured in the 1994 soundtrack of Melrose Place.
"Oxegen 2011 was the eighth Oxegen festival. It took place on July 8, 9, and 10 at Punchestown Racecourse in County Kildare, Ireland. The headlining acts included Arctic Monkeys, Beyoncé, Black Eyed Peas, Coldplay, Foo Fighters, and The Strokes. Christy Moore joined Coldplay on stage during the final night of the festival."
"Aamby Valley City is a township developed by the Sahara India Pariwar in Pune district in the Indian state of Maharashtra. It is located from Lonavala, from the city of Pune, and from the city of Mumbai. The township is connected by road to Mahabaleshwar and by air from Mumbai, with its own airstrip. It has an average annual rainfall of from June to September and is spread over hilly terrain. The city features 3 large man-made lakes created by constructing dams, with the largest lake being 1.5 km in length. Additionally, it includes a PGA 18 hole golf course. Aamby Valley City was designed and master planned by Gruen -Bobby Mukherji & Associates in the year 2003."
Elíseo Arango Ramos was a Colombian lawyer and diplomat. Elíseo Arango Ramos served as the fourth Permanent Representative of Colombia to the United Nations and as Minister of Foreign Affairs. Elíseo Arango Ramos was a member of the Conservative Party and the far-right group known as "Los Leopardos" (The Leopards). Elíseo Arango Ramos was born on April 16, 1900, and passed away on December 17, 1977.
Club Deportivo Libertad is a sports club from Argentina. Club Deportivo Libertad is based in the Sunchales city of Santa Fe Province. Club Deportivo Libertad is known for its association football and basketball teams.
Hakan Çelik is a Turkish journalist, columnist, radio, and television presenter. Hakan Çelik was born on September 10, 1969.
The Kirriemuir Sculptured Stones are a series of Pictish stones found in Kirriemuir, Angus, Scotland. These stones are classified as Class II and III. The presence of these stones suggests that Kirriemuir was a significant ecclesiastical center in the late first millennium AD.
The Hussaini Encyclopedia is an Arabic encyclopedia dedicated to the third Imam, Husayn ibn Ali. It focuses on his biography, thought, conduct, and the social circle of personalities around him, as well as places, chronicles, and related subjects. The encyclopedia consists of 700 volumes and over 95 million words. Sheikh Mohammed Sadiq Al-Karbassi, the author, established the Hussaini Center for Research in London in 1993. The Hussaini Encyclopedia is a historic study of al-Hussain, providing a heritage that impacts events, especially the aftermath of the battle of Karbala.
Johan Sparre af Söfdeborg was a Swedish count and general. Johan Sparre af Söfdeborg was born on January 10, 1715, in Karlskrona. Johan Sparre af Söfdeborg passed away on March 3, 1791, in Tosterup.
Hugh Allen Blackwell is an American politician. Hugh Allen Blackwell was born on July 14, 1944. Hugh Allen Blackwell is a member of the North Carolina House of Representatives, representing District 86 in Burke County. Hugh Allen Blackwell is a Harvard Law School graduate. Hugh Allen Blackwell is a partner in a law practice located in Valdese. Hugh Allen Blackwell serves as a Board of Trustees member for Western Piedmont Community College in Morganton. Hugh Allen Blackwell previously served on the Burke County School Board before entering state government.
"Mike Meade is a former running back. Mike Meade was born on February 12, 1960. Mike Meade played in the National Football League."
Janine K. Iannarelli is an aircraft broker. Janine K. Iannarelli was born on March 15, 1961. Janine K. Iannarelli entered the business aviation industry while a senior in college. Janine K. Iannarelli is the founder and president of the aircraft marketing firm Par Avion Ltd. Janine K. Iannarelli has worked for over 30 years in the business aviation industry. Janine K. Iannarelli has represented numerous corporations and private individuals worldwide in the sale and purchase of business aircraft.
"Ursprung is a settlement in Dunkelsteinerwald municipality in Melk District, Lower Austria. Ursprung is located in northeastern Austria."
The Rua Augusta Arch, also known as "Arco da Rua Augusta," is a historical stone triumphal arch located in Lisbon, Portugal, on the "Praça do Comércio." It was constructed to commemorate the city's rebuilding following the 1755 earthquake. The arch features six columns, some of which are 11m high, and is decorated with statues of various historical figures. The structure's significant height from the arch crown to the cornice gives it a sense of weightiness. The space around the arch displays the coat of arms of Portugal. At the top, there is an allegorical group created by French sculptor Célestin Anatole Calmels, symbolizing Glory rewarding Valor and Genius. Originally intended as a bell tower, the building was later transformed into an elaborate arch after more than a century.
John N. Smith is a Canadian film director and screenwriter. John N. Smith was born on July 31, 1943 in Montreal, Quebec. John N. Smith has the citizenship of Canada.
Jerome Walman is an American composer and certified instructor of the Schillinger System of Musical Composition. He studied at Boston University, Juilliard School of Music, Berklee School of Music, and at New York University under Rudolph Schramm. Walman is one of the last certified instructors of the Schillinger System. He was actively involved with Lehman Engel's BMI Musical Theater Workshop, where many of his works were performed. Walman has had productions on and off Broadway and in regional theatre. Two of his compositions, a string quartet and a wind quintet, have been performed at Carnegie Hall. He developed the Walman Method, which includes musical composition, lyrics, and book writing for theater, musical, and cinema. He is the composer of the musical "Moments: A Musical Interpretation" and "Washington Square". Walman's other works include "I Murdered Mary Finch", "From The Street", two operas, several one-act plays, and "Last Call". Walman specializes in "The Great American Songbook", theatre musicals, cabaret material, and scores for cinema. He is now retired.
William Smedley-Aston was a Victorian Pre-Raphaelite Arts & Crafts photographer and a member of the Birmingham Group of artists and the Linked Ring Brotherhood. He was also known as W. S. Aston or W. Smedley. He was instrumental in encouraging and financing early moving films through his firm, the British Biograph Co. He was married to Irene Smedley-Aston, who featured in many photographs, paintings, and drawings of the Arts and Crafts movement. They lived in London at 77 Holland Park W14 and in The Yew Trees, Henley-in-Arden. William had a famous collection of early English Furniture, Old Masters, and very early English Glass, which was auctioned off in the 1920s and early 1930s. He had three children: Michael Smedley-Aston, Rosemary Smedley-Aston, and Ivo Smedley-Aston. The family had connections to John Smedley, who constructed Riber Castle, and William's brother founded what became TI Group.
Ventoso is a village ("curazia") in central San Marino. Ventoso belongs to the castle of Borgo Maggiore. The name Ventoso means "windy" in the Italian language.
Václav Dosbaba was a Czech painter. Václav Dosbaba exhibited his work in various cities including Brno, Louny, Ostrava, Prague, Litomyšl, Zlín, the U.S., and Austria. Václav Dosbaba was born on January 8, 1945, and passed away on February 4, 2012. Václav Dosbaba was also a member of Group 4 since 1971.
"Dactyloscopus crossotus is a species of sand stargazer. It is known as the bigeye stargazer. Dactyloscopus crossotus is native to the coastal Atlantic waters of Florida, United States, the Bahamas, and Brazil. It can be found in sandy beaches at depths ranging from , occasionally down to . The bigeye stargazer buries itself in the sand to ambush prey, with only its eyes, mouth, and nose exposed. It can reach a maximum length of TL."
The Medal for Exemplary Border Service was a national award issued in the German Democratic Republic (GDR). It was established on May 28, 1954, by the Council of Ministers of the GDR with Order No. 47/54 from the Ministry of Interior on June 16, 1954. The first presentation ceremony took place on July 1, 1954, to members of the German Border Police.
Luigi Musina was an Italian boxer. He was born on April 17, 1914, in Gorizia and passed away on February 10, 1990, in Cormons. Musina achieved gold medals in the 1937 European Amateur Boxing Championships in Milan and the 1939 European Amateur Boxing Championships in Dublin. He won his final fights against Franciszek Szymura in both championships. Musina participated in various duals such as ITA vs. HUN (1936), Europe vs. USA (1936, 1937, 1939), ITA vs. USA (1937), ITA vs. POL (1938, 1939), and ITA vs. GER (1938, 1939, 1940), with a scoring record of +13 –1 =0. In April 1940, he won his first professional bout. By April 1942, he became the European champion in the Light heavyweight class and held the title until 1947. Musina ended the boxing career of former world heavyweight champion Primo Carnera, who was attempting a comeback after World War II. Carnera retired after losing two decisions and being stopped by Musina.
The 2010 Nagorno-Karabakh clashes were a series of exchanges of gunfire that occurred on February 18 on the line of contact dividing Azerbaijani and Karabakh Armenian military forces. Azerbaijan accused Armenian forces of firing on Azerbaijani positions near Tap Qaraqoyunlu, Qızıloba, Qapanlı, Yusifcanlı, and Cavahirli villages, as well as in the uplands of Agdam Rayon with small arms fire, including snipers. Three Azerbaijani soldiers were killed, and one was wounded. This engagement became the second deadliest ceasefire violation since 1994, following the 2008 Mardakert clashes.
Beatrice Lascaris di Tenda, also known as Beatrice de Tende or Beatrix, was an Italian noblewoman. She was first married to Facino Cane, who was the Count of Biandrate and a condottiero. Later, she became the wife of Filippo Maria Visconti, the Duke of Milan, who was responsible for her death. Beatrice Lascaris di Tenda lived from around 1372 to 1418.
The Macau women's national ice hockey team is the women's national ice hockey team in Macau. Macau is the location of the team.
Kirkelandet is an island in Kristiansund Municipality in Møre og Romsdal county, Norway. The island is split in two by the "Vågen" inlet, with the western half called "Kirkelandet" and the eastern half called "Gomalandet". The name of the island means "church land", since it has been the historic site of a church. Kirkelandet Church is located on the western part of the island. Kirkelandet is the main island of the city of Kristiansund, with Innlandet to the southwest, Nordlandet to the southeast, and Skorpa to the east. Norwegian National Road 70 is the main highway on the island. The Sørsund Bridge connects Kirkelandet to Innlandet, and the Nordsund Bridge connects it to Nordlandet. The Atlantic Ocean Tunnel connects Kirkelandet to Averøya to the west.
Abu Bishr Isma'il ibn Ibrahim ibn Muqsim, commonly known as Ibn 'Ulayya, was a hadith scholar, faqih, and a mufti from Basra.
"Ira Richard Gershon is a former Dean of the University of Mississippi School of Law and a current professor at the school. He was also the Founding Dean of the Charleston School of Law in Charleston, South Carolina. Gershon is known for his expertise in moving schools through the American Bar Association (ABA) accreditation process. Prior to his time at the Charleston School of Law, he was the dean of the Texas Wesleyan University School of Law in Fort Worth, Texas, which received full accreditation from the ABA in 1999. Gershon was also on the faculty of Stetson University College of Law from 1984 to 1998. He has a background in federal estate and gift taxation, federal partnership taxation, and estate planning. Gershon received his A.B. in political science from the University of Georgia in 1979, his J.D. from the University of Tennessee College of Law in 1982, and his LL.M. in tax law from the University of Florida in 1983. Gershon is married to Donna Levine, who is the Copy Chief of "Garden & Gun Magazine". They have 4 children: Michelle, Benjamin, Claire, and Eve."
"Andy Tielman was an influential Indo artist, recognized as the "godfather" of Indorock. He is considered one of the most important figures in Dutch popular music. Tielman defied the notion that early rock and roll was a phenomenon of white and black musicians from America. He was known for his wide vocal range and virtuoso guitar playing. Many Dutch musicians, including Jan Akkerman, Barry Hay, and Herman Brood, have cited him as major influences. Tielman is credited with releasing the first Dutch rock and roll single in 1958 and led the first Dutch rock band with international appeal, the Tielman Brothers. He received a Royal decoration in the Order of Orange Nassau in 2005. Tielman passed away in 2011 due to gastric cancer."
"Horse Hare" is a "Looney Tunes" cartoon produced by Warner Bros. and directed by Friz Freleng. The short was released on February 13, 1960, and features Bugs Bunny and Yosemite Sam. "Horse Hare" is notable for being the first Bugs Bunny cartoon released in the 1960s.
The 1934 European Amateur Boxing Championships took place in Budapest, Hungary from April 11 to 15. This event marked the fourth edition of the competition, which was organized by the European governing body for amateur boxing, EABA. A total of 74 fighters from 13 countries participated in the championships.
"Aïn Fezza is a town and commune located in Tlemcen Province in northwestern Algeria."
"Aïn Nehala is a town and commune located in Tlemcen Province in northwestern Algeria."
"Ouled Riyah is a town and commune located in Tlemcen Province in the north-western region of Algeria."
Chiltern Park Aerodrome is a private airfield located near Woodcote and Ipsden in Oxfordshire. It was established in 1988 and operates within RAF Benson's Military Aerodrome Traffic Zone. The airfield caters to gyroplanes, microlights, helicopters, gliders, and general aircraft. In 2011, it became the weekend home of the London Parachute School.
"Sidi Semiane is a town and commune located in Tipaza Province in northern Algeria. Sidi Semiane is situated in the northern region of Algeria."
"Nattukku Oru Nallavan is a 1991 Tamil-Hindi language action film. The film was written, produced, and directed by V. Ravichandran and also produced by N. Veersamai. The cast includes Rajinikanth, Juhi Chawla, V. Ravichandran, Anant Nag, and Kushboo in lead roles. Anant Nag made his Tamil cinema debut as the main antagonist in this film. The music for the film was composed by Hamsalekha. The film was simultaneously released in Kannada and Telugu under the title "Shanti Kranti" in 1991. Despite being dubbed in Telugu as "Police Bullet", all versions of the film failed at the box office, resulting in huge losses for Ravichandran."
"Lazharia is a town, commune, and daïra in Tissemsilt Province in northern Algeria. It is located about 74 km west of Tissemsilt and 45 km of Chlef. The daïra of Lazharia consists of three communes: Lazharia, Boucaid, and Larbaa. The city is situated at approximately 1000m above sea level on the western flank of the Ouarsenis mountains. Lazharia is predominantly populated by Berbere tribes, specifically the Beni Hendel and Beni Boukhanous."
"Akbil is a town and commune in Tizi Ouzou Province in Algeria. Tizi Ouzou Province is located in northern Algeria."
"Souamâa is a town and commune located in Tizi Ouzou Province in northern Algeria. Souamâa is situated in the northern region of Algeria."
"Gangteng Gewog is a village block in Wangdue Phodrang District, Bhutan. Gangteng Gewog is also known as Gangte or Gangtey. Gangteng Gewog's name in Dzongkha is སྒང་སྟེང་."
Shompangkha Gewog is a gewog of Sarpang District, Bhutan. Shompangkha Gewog is located in Bhutan. Shompangkha Gewog is written as ཤོམ་སྤང་ཁ་ in Dzongkha. Sarpang District is the district where Shompangkha Gewog is situated.
Gelephu Gewog is a village block in Sarpang District, Bhutan. Gelephu Gewog is part of Gelephu Dungkhag along with Serzhong, Taklai, and Bhur Gewogs. Gelephu Gewog's name in Dzongkha is "དགེ་ལེགས་ཕུ་".
"Nangkor Gewog is a gewog of Zhemgang District, Bhutan. Nangkor Gewog is located in Bhutan. Nangkor Gewog is written as ནང་སྐོར་ in Dzongkha."
"Tsamang Gewog is a gewog of Mongar District, Bhutan. Tsamang Gewog is located in Bhutan. Tsamang Gewog's official language is Dzongkha. Mongar District is the district where Tsamang Gewog is situated."
Kurnia Sandy is a retired Indonesian footballer who played as a goalkeeper. Kurnia Sandy played at Sampdoria's primavera team. Kurnia Sandy was teammates with Kurniawan Dwi Yulianto and Bima Sakti. Kurnia Sandy succeeded in breaking into the first team and became the fourth choice goalkeeper for one season during Sven-Göran Eriksson's era. When Sampdoria's first choice goalkeeper Fabrizio Ferron was red carded, Sandy was considered as a back up for Matteo Sereni, but his permit related papers were not processed in time, leading to Sampdoria's entry being denied by the FIGC. Sandy had a memorable performance during the Asian Cup, where he made at least 6 clear saves against Kuwait before being injured in a rough contact with a Kuwaiti player, resulting in a 2-2 draw. Sandy's injury forced him to recover for the rest of the tournament. Hendro Kartiko replaced Sandy and performed well, leading to Sandy losing his spot as the first choice goalkeeper in the national team to Kartiko.
Imeni Panfilova is a village located in the Almaty Region of south-eastern Kazakhstan.
Karakastek is a village located in the Almaty Region of south-eastern Kazakhstan.
Karaoy is a village located in the Ile District of Almaty Region in south-eastern Kazakhstan.
Thomas Henry Illidge was an English portrait painter. Thomas Henry Illidge was born on September 26, 1799. Thomas Henry Illidge passed away on May 13, 1851.
"Padova railway station, also known as Padua railway station or Padova Centrale, is the main station in Padua, Veneto region, northeastern Italy. It was opened in 1842 and is part of the Milan–Venice railway. The station serves as a junction for branch lines to Bologna, Bassano del Grappa, and Camposampiero (junction for the line to Calalzo). Additionally, Padova railway station is the terminus of a short goods line to Padova Interporto. The station is managed by Rete Ferroviaria Italiana (RFI), with the commercial area of the passenger building being managed by Centostazioni, both subsidiaries of Ferrovie dello Stato (FS), Italy's state-owned rail company. Train services to and from the station are operated by Trenitalia, NTV, and Thello."
Cyrtosperma merkusii, also known as Giant swamp taro, is a crop grown in Oceania, South Asia, and Southeast Asia. It is similar to taro but has bigger leaves and larger roots. It is believed to be native to Indonesia. In various regions, it is known by different names such as "puraka" in Cook Islands, "lak" in Yap, "babai" in Kiribati, "pula’a" in Samoa, "via kan" in Fiji, "pulaka" in Tokelau and Tuvalu, "simiden" in Chuuk, "swam taro" in Papua New Guinea, "navia" in Vanuatu, and "palawan" in the Philippines. The cultivation of Giant Swamp Taro is important in Tuvalu and Kiribati, providing carbohydrates in their diet. In Nepal, it is called "mane" and is harvested in January-February from tropical and subtropical forests along stream banks. The plant parts are boiled and roasted before consumption.
Juan Carlos Vellido is a Spanish actor. He was born on March 18, 1968, in Barcelona, Spain. Vellido's career spans across cinema, theater, and television. He has appeared in films such as "No somos nadie" and has collaborated with directors like Guillermo del Toro, María Ripoll, and Manuel Huerga. Vellido has also authored two literary works, "Escorzos" and "El hombre que vivía en una pecera," both published by Ediciones Martínez Roca. Additionally, he had a role in "Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides" alongside fellow Spanish actors Astrid Berges-Frisbey, Óscar Jaenada, and Penélope Cruz.
Roland Rotherham, also known as "Roly" or "Uncle Roly", is a retired British writer and lecturer specializing in medieval legends and lore, particularly those related to King Arthur, Merlin, and Glastonbury. He is also an expert in historical cookery. Rotherham holds degrees in Ancient and Medieval studies, Anglo-Saxon Culture, Heraldry, Anglo-Norman Culture, Ancient and Medieval Cultural Studies, and Education. He has traveled extensively across the globe and has served in the cavalry, including on the personal staff of HM the Queen. Rotherham is a member of The Order Of The Fellowship Of The Knights Of The Round Table Of King Arthur, the Institute of Heraldic and Genealogical Studies, and the Experimental Food Society. In the Netherlands, he is well-known for his lectures at fantasy events such as the Elf Fantasy Fair at Castle de Haar and the Midwinter Fair at the Archeon.
Hawle Wadag District is a district in the central Banaadir region of Somalia. The Bakaara Market, a neighborhood in north-central Mogadishu, is located in this district. In 2009, this region served as an operational base for Al-Shabaab, who harassed or attacked Amisom from here. Amisom's defensive line was at the Sayyid Hassan statue site, featuring Sayyid positioned on the Hiin Faniin, a Suleiman horse.
"Taleh District is a historical district located in the eastern Sool region of Somaliland. The capital of Taleh District is Taleh, which was the former headquarters of the Somali Dervish State led by the nationalist Mohammed Abdullah Hassan."
"Peter van Merksteijn Jr. is a Dutch racing driver and rally driver. Peter van Merksteijn Jr. will be driving for the Van Merksteijn Motorsport team in the 2011 World Rally Championship season. Peter van Merksteijn Jr. won the Dutch Rally Championship in 2007 in the Group N class with a Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution IX. Peter van Merksteijn Jr. made his WRC début in 2007 at the Rallye Deutschland. Peter van Merksteijn Jr. is the son of Peter van Merksteijn Sr., who raced in the WRC before and won the 2008 24 Hours of Le Mans in the LMP2 class, using a Porsche RS Spyder."
Eustache Marcadé was born in Artois and died in 1440. Eustache Marcadé was responsible for one of the first mysteries. Eustache Marcadé was a provost of Dampierre and an official of the Abbey of Corbie from 1414. He was also the dean of the "Faculté de Décret", which was the forerunner of the Faculty of laws. Eustache Marcadé was removed from office in 1427 but reinstated by a court in 1437.
"Pouteria cotinifolia is an Australian tree in the family Sapotaceae. The common names include small-leaved plum, yellow lemon, and small-leaved coondoo. It occurs in the drier rainforests from the Richmond River, New South Wales, to the Wenlock River in tropical Queensland. It belongs to the large genus Pouteria, which occurs across the tropics from South America to Indonesia and into eastern Australia. A genetic analysis found that Pouteria cotinifolia was most closely related to Pouteria eerwah, and Pouteria australis was a sister to the two species, forming a distinct group. It grows as a small tree, up to tall and a stem diameter of . It may be recognized by the small leaves, m long, wide, with a rounded tip. Flowering occurs between February and March. The fruit is glossy black, usually containing one shining light brown seed. Two varieties are recognized: Pouteria cotinifolia var. pubescens and Pouteria cotinifolia var. cotinifolia."
Arena ITSON is a 7,464-seat indoor arena located in Ciudad Obregon, Sonora. It was built in 2009 by the Sonora Institute of Technology. The arena is home to the Potros ITSON basketball team. It has 5,510 seats for basketball, including 3,600 permanent seats on risers, eight luxury suites, and 32 boxes. There is also a sports bar overlooking the arena floor with 200 seats. The arena hosts various events such as concerts, boxing matches, lucha libre, graduation ceremonies, and special events. Artists who have performed at Arena ITSON include Alejandra Guzmán, Yuri, Enanitos Verdes, Banda MS, Gloria Trevi, Camila, Moderatto, and David Bisbal.
The 2014 Tasmanian state election was held on 15 March 2014 to elect all 25 members to the House of Assembly. The 16-year incumbent Labor government, led by the Premier of Tasmania Lara Giddings, sought to win a fifth consecutive term against the Liberal opposition, led by Opposition Leader Will Hodgman. Also contesting the election was the Greens led by Nick McKim. The Palmer United Party made a significant effort in the election. The House of Assembly uses the proportional Hare-Clark system to elect 25 members in five constituencies electing five members each. Elections to the Legislative Council are conducted separately from House of Assembly elections. The election was conducted by the Tasmanian Electoral Commission. Before the election, Hodgman had indicated that he would only govern in majority. ABC News election analyst Antony Green suggested Hodgman's promise could have come back to haunt him if Palmer United were to siphon off enough votes to deny the Liberals enough seats for a majority in their own right. However, this became moot after the Liberals picked up an additional seat in every electorate except Denison, assuring them a majority. By 10:00 pm on election night, with the Liberals assured of winning at least 14 seats, Giddings conceded defeat on behalf of Labor. Ultimately, the Liberals won 15 seats, a decisive majority. Although this was just two more seats than necessary for a majority, under Tasmanian electoral practice of the time, winning 15 seats was considered a comprehensive victory. Hodgman took office on 31 March 2014, becoming only the fifth non-Labor premier in 80 years and only the third to govern in majority. Later, Giddings resigned as Labor party leader, and was succeeded by outgoing Deputy Premier Bryan Green on 31 March 2014.
Schizochitonidae is a family of polyplacophoran molluscs.
"Eochelodes is an extinct genus of polyplacophoran molluscs."
Mount Marks is an ice-covered mountain located to the north-northwest of Mount Speyer in the Worcester Range of Antarctica. It was named after Rodney Marks, an Australian citizen who passed away during astrophysical research as a member of the 2000 winter party at the National Science Foundation South Pole Station. Rodney Marks was employed by the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory and was involved in the Antarctic Submillimeter Telescope and Remote Observatory project, which is a research initiative of the University of Chicago's Center for Astrophysical Research in Antarctica (CARA). Prior to this, he had also spent the 1998 winter at the Pole as part of CARA's South Pole Infrared Explorer project.
"Martins Head is a headland located on the south side of the entrance to Legru Bay on King George Island in the South Shetland Islands of Antarctica. The name dates back to at least 1820 when it was described by Edward Bransfield, a Master in the Royal Navy, during his exploration of these islands."
"Mata Taua Peak is a prominent peak in Antarctica. Mata Taua Peak is located in the Royal Society Range, Victoria Land. The peak is high and is situated on the ridge between Matataua Glacier and Ferrigno Glacier. The name 'Mata Taua' was given by the New Zealand Geographic Board in 1994. Mata Taua means 'a scout before the troops' in Māori. From the peak, there is a view of rocky peaks to the northeast and Rampart Ridge and the Upper Staircase glacier to the southwest."
"Hjelmkalven Point is a rocky point located on the north side of Vesthjelmen Peak in Antarctica. It is situated at the east side of the mouth of Byrdbreen in the Sør Rondane Mountains. The point was mapped by Norwegian cartographers in 1946 and named Hjelmkalven by the Norwegians. The mapping was based on air photos taken by the Lars Christensen Expedition in 1936-37 and by U.S. Navy Operation Highjump in 1946-47."
"Himalia Ridge is a ridge located on the north side of the Ganymede Heights massif, northeast of Jupiter Glacier, in the eastern part of Alexander Island, Antarctica. It was photographed from the air by the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition in 1947 and mapped by D. Searle of the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey in 1960. The ridge was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1983-84 after Himalia, a moon of Jupiter, in connection with Jupiter Glacier. This site is situated within Antarctic Specially Protected Area (ASPA) No.147."
High Nunatak is an isolated nunatak located east of the Liberty Hills in the Heritage Range of the Ellsworth Mountains, Antarctica. It was named after Elmer High, a helicopter crew chief with the 62nd Transportation Detachment, who assisted the University of Minnesota geological party in this area during 1963-64.
"Hess Glacier is a glacier located in Graham Land, Antarctica. It flows east-northeast between steep rock walls to its terminus southwest of Monnier Point. The glacier was charted in 1947 by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey. It was named after Hans Hess, a German glaciologist."
Mount Hermanson is an ice-covered mountain located in the Queen Maud Mountains of Antarctica. It stands at a high altitude and is situated at the head of Cunningham Glacier, southwest of Gray Peak. The mountain was named after Captain J.M. Hermanson, who served as a U.S. Navy air operations officer at McMurdo Station from 1957 to 1958 and later as Chief of Staff to the U.S. Antarctic Projects Officer in 1959.
"Herd Point is a point located on the west side of Ferguson Bay at the southern end of Thule Island in the South Sandwich Islands. It was initially charted by a Russian expedition led by Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen in 1819–20. The point was later recharted in 1930 by personnel from Discovery Investigations aboard the ship "Discovery II." It was named after R.D. Herd of Ferguson Brothers, a company based in Port Glasgow, Scotland, who were the builders of the "Discovery II."
"Henderson Pyramid is a mountain located in Victoria Land, Antarctica. It is mostly ice-covered and stands high. Henderson Pyramid is situated south-southwest of Ugolini Peak on the west side of the Royal Society Range. The mountain was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) using surveys and U.S. Navy aerial photographs from 1956 to 1961. It was named in 1994 after Thomas E. Henderson, a USGS cartographer. Thomas E. Henderson was part of various geodetic projects, including the Ellsworth Mountains Geodetic Control Project in 1979-1980 and leading the USGS teams in northern Victoria Land and at South Pole Station in 1981-1982."
The 1987 Tokyo Indoor, also known as "Seiko Super Tennis," was a men's tennis tournament played on indoor carpet courts at the Yoyogi National Gymnasium in Tokyo, Japan. It was part of the 1987 Nabisco Grand Prix and held from October 20 to October 24, 1987. The matches were the best of three sets, and Stefan Edberg emerged as the singles champion.
"Humboldt Graben is a glacier-filled valley located in Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. The valley is long and trends north-south between the Humboldt Mountains and the Petermann Ranges. It was discovered and mapped by the Third German Antarctic Expedition led by Alfred Ritscher in 1938-39. The valley was named in association with the adjacent Humboldt Mountains."
Husky Dome is a snow dome located in the Husky Heights, between Brandau Glacier and Ramsey Glacier in the Queen Maud Mountains of Antarctica. It was named by the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition, 1961–62, after their Husky dogs which they drove to the summit of this feature.
Mount Hurley is a snow-covered massif located in Antarctica. It was discovered in January 1930 by the British Australian New Zealand Antarctic Research Expedition of 1929–31 led by Mawson. The mountain stands south of Cape Ann and south of Mount Biscoe. It was named after Captain James Francis (Frank) Hurley, a photographer who was part of the expedition. Hurley also participated in the Australasian Antarctic Expedition under Mawson from 1911 to 1914, and the Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition under Ernest Shackleton from 1914 to 1917.
"Husky Pass is a pass located in the Bowers Mountains of Victoria Land, Antarctica. It is situated between the Lanterman Range and Molar Massif, at the head of Sledgers Glacier and an unnamed tributary, leading to Leap Year Glacier. The pass was named by the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition, 1963–64, in recognition of the dog teams' efforts in hauling out of the Rennick Glacier basin into that of Lillie Glacier. Husky Pass is situated on the Pennell Coast, which is a portion of Antarctica between Cape Williams and Cape Adare."
The Hyperion Nunataks are a group of about 10 nunataks located south of Saturn Glacier and west of the Corner Cliffs in the southeastern part of Alexander Island, Antarctica. The group was first observed and photographed from the air by Lincoln Ellsworth on November 23, 1935, and mapped from these photos by W.L.G. Joerg. It was surveyed in 1949 by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey and named by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee in association with nearby Saturn Glacier, with Hyperion being one of the satellites of the planet Saturn.
"Two Step Moraine is a small area of homogeneous fine morainic debris, located in the south-facing moraines at the foot of Two Step Cliffs on Alexander Island, Antarctica. This feature contains moist soil and two sub-glacial ponds. It is notable for the abundance of mosses, algae, and cyanobacteria found in such a southern location. The name 'Two Step Moraine' was given by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1993, in connection with Two Step Cliffs."
Mount Talmadge is a mountain with a height of 2,395 meters. It is located above the steep cliffs on the west side of Koettlitz Neve, 3 nautical miles (6 km) south of Fisher Bastion in Victoria Land. The mountain was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in 1994 after John B. Talmadge, who served as the Head of the Polar Coordination and Information Section from 1984 to 1995 at the Office of Polar Programs, National Science Foundation (NSF).
The 1990 Tokyo Indoor, also known as Seiko Super Tennis, was a men's tennis tournament held at the Yoyogi National Gymnasium in Tokyo, Japan. It was part of the 1990 ATP Tour and was an ATP Championship Series event, now known as the ATP World Tour 500 series. The tournament took place from October 8 to October 14, 1990, with matches being the best of three sets. Ivan Lendl, the third seed, emerged as the singles champion.
Zeinabu Irene Davis is an American filmmaker. Zeinabu Irene Davis is a professor in the Department of Communication at the University of California, San Diego. Zeinabu Irene Davis was born on April 13, 1961. Zeinabu Irene Davis works in narrative, documentary, and experimental film.
The Oncology Nursing Certification Corporation (ONCC) is a nonprofit organization focused on certification in oncology nursing. Established in 1984, ONCC is governed by a board of directors and meets standards set by the Accreditation Board for Specialty Nursing Certification. ONCC is accredited by the National Commission for Certifying Agencies.
Ahmed Diaa Eddine was an Egyptian film director. Ahmed Diaa Eddine directed over 30 films. Ahmed Diaa Eddine studied at the Leonardo da Vinci Institute in Cairo. Ahmed Diaa Eddine lived from 1912 to 1976. Leonardo da Vinci Institute is located in Cairo.
Jabadá is a village located in the Oio Region of Guinea-Bissau. The village is situated on the southern bank of the Geba River.
Thomas Gewen was an English politician. He sat in the House of Commons between 1645 and 1660. Thomas Gewen was the grandson of Thomas and the son of Christopher Gewen of Werrington. He was educated at the Queen's College, Oxford and the Inner Temple. Thomas Gewen settled at Bradridge in Cornwall and was a joint auditor for the Duchy of Cornwall. He was deprived of his position during the Civil War for supporting the parliamentary cause. Gewen was a member of the Cornwall Committee for raising money. He served as an MP for Launceston in various Parliaments. Gewen was a supporter of Cromwell but later favored monarchy and the House of Lords. He was also a Presbyterian and known for persecuting Quakers. Gewen was the Recorder of Launceston and a Justice of the Peace. He passed away at the age of 75.
"Master of Brutality" is the debut studio album by the Japanese doom metal band Church of Misery. It was released in 2001 by Southern Lord Records. The album features tracks based on infamous serial killers such as Edmund Kemper, Peter Sutcliffe, Herbert Mullin, and John Wayne Gacy. The instrumental track "Green River" was inspired by Gary Ridgway. The first track, "Killifornia", includes samples of Kemper speaking. The artwork and booklet showcase pictures and sketches of Gacy, with the back art depicting Gacy dressed as "Pogo the Clown". Additionally, the album includes a cover of "Cities on Flame with Rock and Roll" by Blue Öyster Cult.
Tohid Tunnel, also known as Towheed Tunnel, is located in Tehran, Iran. It is the third longest urban tunnel in the Middle East. The Towheed Tunnel Project is an urban underground structure situated within the area of Chamran Highway, Towheed Square, Jomhouri Square, and Navab Highway, with a length of approximately 3 km including the tunnel and entry ramps. The construction of Tohid Tunnel set records by being completed in less than 30 months. The interior designs of the tunnel meet the highest safety requirements. The project involved the installation of utilities equipment, the manufacture and mobilization of north and south fans for combined ventilation, as well as the construction of a control building and Niyayesh shaft.
"Ghala Nefhi is a town in Eritrea. Ghala Nefhi is located in the Maekel (Central) region. Ghala Nefhi is the capital of Ghala Nefhi district."
"Aizis was a Dacian town mentioned by Emperor Trajan in his work "Dacica". Aizis is located at "Dealul Ruieni", Fârliug, Caraș-Severin, Banat, Romania. After the Roman conquest of Dacia, a castrum was built at Aizis. Aizis is also depicted in the Tabula Peutingeriana as "Azizis" on a Roman road network between Bersovia and Caput Bubali."
"The Best of Intentions" is an adventure module published in 1987 for the "Dungeons & Dragons" fantasy role-playing game.
"The Cahaboncito River is located in Guatemala."
Joshua Coyne is an American musician and composer. Joshua Coyne was born on March 5, 1993.
Mark Katic is a Canadian ice hockey player. Mark Katic currently plays for Adler Mannheim in the Deutsche Eishockey Liga. Mark Katic previously played with the New York Islanders in the National Hockey League. Mark Katic has Croatian descent.
General Shantha H.S. Kottegoda is a Sri Lankan general. General Shantha H.S. Kottegoda was born on November 6, 1949. General Shantha H.S. Kottegoda served as the seventeenth Commander of the Sri Lankan Army from July 1, 2004, to December 5, 2007. General Shantha H.S. Kottegoda has also served as the Sri Lankan Ambassador to Brazil and Thailand. In April 2019, following the Easter Sunday bombings, he was appointed as the Permanent Secretary to the Ministry of Defence. General Shantha H.S. Kottegoda has served the Sri Lankan Army for 36 years. He has been involved in the 1971 and 1987–89 JVP Insurrections as well as the Sri Lankan Civil War, participating in major operations against the LTTE in the North and East of the country. General Shantha H.S. Kottegoda has held various positions in the Army, including Chief of Staff, Colonel of the Regiment of the Sri Lanka Light Infantry, General Officer Commanding 55 Division, 51 Division, and 21 Division, and served as Director of Military Intelligence.
"Ballad of Sir Frankie Crisp (Let It Roll)" is a song by English musician George Harrison, released on his 1970 triple album "All Things Must Pass". Harrison wrote the song as a tribute to Frank Crisp, a nineteenth-century lawyer and the original owner of Friar Park – the Victorian Gothic residence in Henley-on-Thames, Oxfordshire, that Harrison purchased in early 1970. The recording features backing from musicians such as Pete Drake, Billy Preston, Gary Wright, Klaus Voormann, and Alan White. It was co-produced by Phil Spector. AllMusic critic Scott Janovitz describes the song as offering "a glimpse of the true George Harrison". Crisp's eccentric homilies inspired subsequent compositions of Harrison's. The composition gained further notability in 2009 when it provided the title for Harrison's posthumous compilation "Let It Roll". My Morning Jacket lead singer Jim James and Dhani Harrison are among the artists who have covered the song.
"Jakub Cieciura is a Polish professional football player. Jakub Cieciura was born on February 3, 1983, in Lipsko. Jakub Cieciura is currently a coach for Powiślanka Lipsko."
Burden Ironworks Office Building is a historic office building located in Troy, Rensselaer County, New York. It was built around 1880 and is a one-story, brick building with a cruciform plan. The building features gabled and hipped roofs, a central octagonal cupola, and an onion dome. Burden Ironworks Office Building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1972.
Rear Admiral Jonathon Reeve CB is a former Royal Navy officer. Rear Admiral Jonathon Reeve CB was born on October 1, 1949. Rear Admiral Jonathon Reeve CB ended his naval career as Chief of Fleet Support.
"Just Charlie" is the fifth studio album by American singer Charlie Wilson. It was released by Jive Records on December 3, 2010 in the United States. The album debuted and peaked at number 19 on the US "Billboard" 200 and at number 2 on the US Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums chart. Fantasia is the only featured guest on "Just Charlie", appearing on a remake of the Roger Troutman song, "I Want to Be Your Man". The album also includes the hit single, "You Are", which earned Wilson a career high debut on the "Billboard" Hot R&B/Hip Hop Songs chart and topped the "Billboard" Urban Adult Contemporary Chart. "You Are" remained at number one for 13 weeks on the "Billboard" UAC Chart, climbing to number 16 on the "Billboard" Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart, number 7 on the Heatseeker Songs chart, number 19 on the Christian Songs chart, and number 64 on the Radio Songs chart.
Off the Wall Productions is a theater production company based in Carnegie, Pennsylvania, USA. Off the Wall Productions is a non-profit 501 C3 organization and serves as Carnegie Stage’s Resident Professional Theater Company. They work under contract with Actors' Equity Association and produce a minimum of four plays during their season from October to May. Recently, Off the Wall Productions has focused on producing new plays written by women playwrights.
Sir George Dixon Grahame was born on April 28, 1873, the only son of Richard Grahame of Alderley Edge. He was educated at Charterhouse, specifically in Hodgsonite House, between the summer of 1887 and the autumn of 1888. Grahame entered the Diplomatic Service in 1896, serving as an attaché to the Paris Embassy in 1897, Chargé d'Affaires in Berlin in 1902, in Buenos Aires in 1903, and in Paris in 1905. He later became Minister Plenipotentiary in 1918 and British Delegate to the League of Nations in 1925. Grahame also served as Ambassador in Brussels in 1920 and in Madrid from 1928 to 1935. He held the titles of Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George (GCMG), and of the Royal Victorian Order (GCVO), as well as being a Privy Counsellor from 1920 and a member of the Grand Cross, Order of St Leopold. Grahame retired in 1935 and passed away in Rio de Janeiro on July 9, 1940. Known for his great height and vivid blue eyes, he was a notable figure in any gathering. Additionally, he had a profound knowledge of the French language.
Greenvile Collins was an officer of the Royal Navy and a prominent hydrographer. Greenvile Collins compiled "Great Britain's Coasting Pilot", which was the first survey of the country's coast undertaken by a Briton.
Guillaume Malbecque was a Flemish composer. Guillaume Malbecque was born in Soignies on August 29, 1465. Guillaume Malbecque was associated with Guillaume Dufay in Cambrai. Guillaume Malbecque was a singer in the papal chapel. In his later years, Guillaume Malbecque collaborated with Gilles Binchois and Johannes Regis in Soignies.
"S100 calcium-binding protein A15, also known as koebnerisin and S100 calcium-binding protein A7A, is a protein encoded by the S100A7A gene in humans. S100 proteins are a diverse calcium-binding family that regulate cellular and extracellular processes such as cell proliferation, differentiation, migration, and antimicrobial host defense. Koebnerisin was first identified as upregulated in psoriatic skin, indicating its involvement in the disease's lesional phenotype and the Koebner phenomenon. The protein is also of interest for its role in antimicrobial defense, innate immunity, epidermal cell maturation, and epithelial tumorigenesis."
El Siglo de Torreón is a daily paper. El Siglo de Torreón is the most important daily paper in the Comarca Lagunera, Mexico. El Siglo de Torreón was founded in 1922 in Torreón, Coahuila by Antonio de Juambelz y Bracho under the direction of Joaquin Moreno. Antonio de Juambelz y Bracho and Joaquin Moreno are associated with El Siglo de Torreón. Torreón is located in Coahuila, Mexico.
"New Shade of Blue" is a song written by John McFee and Andre Pessis. The song was recorded by the American country music group Southern Pacific. It was released in July 1988 as the second single from the album "Zuma". The song reached number 2 on the "Billboard" Hot Country Singles & Tracks chart.
P. Balasubramanian was a Member of the Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly representing the Pattukkottai constituency from 1996 to 2001. P. Balasubramanian was affiliated with the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam party.
Charles Riechelmann is a rugby union player. Charles Riechelmann was born on April 26, 1972. Charles Riechelmann was born in Tonga and later moved to New Zealand. Charles Riechelmann played for Auckland provincially and the Blues in the Super Rugby competition. Charles Riechelmann also played for the All Blacks at the international level. Charles Riechelmann played six test matches for New Zealand in 1997, scoring three tries. Charles Riechelmann was part of the Blues' 1996 and 1997 Super 12 winning teams.
Hypselodoris regina is a species of sea slug. Hypselodoris regina belongs to the family Chromodorididae.
Rajamangala University of Technology Lanna (RMUTL) is a science and technology university located in Chiang Mai Province, northern Thailand. It offers certificate (vocational), advanced certificate (vocational), undergraduate, and master's degrees.
Franz Raschid was a German professional football player and manager. Franz Raschid was born on October 18, 1954. Franz Raschid passed away on October 22, 2010.
Adil Mezgour is a Moroccan footballer. Adil Mezgour plays for Serie C2 club US Poggibonsi. Adil Mezgour was born on March 11, 1983. Adil Mezgour has spent his entire professional career in Italy. US Poggibonsi is a football club based in Italy.
"SMATSA is the Serbia and Montenegro Air Traffic Services Agency. SMATSA is a Serbian air traffic control service company based in Belgrade, Serbia. SMATSA covers the air traffic in Serbia, Montenegro, and about 55% of Bosnia and Herzegovina. On December 5, 2019, air traffic control was transferred to Bosnia and Herzegovina Air Navigation Services Agency (BHANSA)."
Andrew Schmidt is a former University of Oregon baseball player and a current Free Agent professional baseball player. He previously played for the Canberra Cavalry of the ABL (Australian Baseball League). Schmidt was born on September 2, 1986, in Atlanta, Georgia. He is most well known for winning Oregon's first home game at PK Park on February 27, 2009, as the Ducks beat Fresno State, the defending national champions, 1-0 on a walk-off single. Schmidt holds a degree with honors in Political Science and History from The University of Oregon.
"Paracletus is the fifth full-length studio album by the French black metal band Deathspell Omega. It was released on November 9, 2010, through Norma Evangelium Diaboli and Season of Mist. This album is part of a metaphysical trilogy that represents God, the Devil, and Man, following their previous albums "Si monvmentvm reqvires, circvmspice" and "Fas – Ite, Maledicti, in Ignem Aeternum". The term "paracletus" comes from the Greek word "παράκλητος (parákletos)", which means "comforter" and is another name for the Holy Spirit. Stylistically, the album continues the experimental approach of their previous work since 2004. The tracks flow continuously, forming movements of a larger piece rather than individual songs, with slight pauses between tracks 3 and 4 and between tracks 5 and 6. The track "Devouring Famine" was released as a free download by Season of Mist about three weeks before the album's official release."
Rudolf von Tiefenbach was a German military commander who served the Holy Roman Empire during the Thirty Years' War. Despite being raised a protestant, Tiefenbach joined the catholic Habsburg army in 1613. During the 1620 Battle of White Mountain, he led the "1st Division" of the Imperial Army which included the cuirassier regiment of Albrecht von Wallenstein and the horse regiment of Jean de Gauchier. When Charles Bonaventure de Longueval, Count of Bucquoy died, Tiefenbach took over part of his command. In 1631, after Torquato Conti retired from his post, Tiefenbach was elevated to the rank of Feldmarschall by the Holy Roman Emperor. In 1639 he was named a Knight of the Order of the Golden Fleece.
"D.I.O. Drogist is a Dutch pharmacy chain. D.I.O. Drogist was founded in 1992. D.I.O. Drogist operates over 170 outlets in Dutch towns. In September 2019, D.I.O. Drogist merged with another Dutch pharmacy company DA. After the merger, the D.I.O. stores were re-branded as DA stores."
The Oberhausen–Arnhem railway, also known as the "Hollandstrecke" in German, is a two-track, electrified main line railway that runs along the lower Rhine from Oberhausen through Wesel, Emmerich, and the German–Dutch border to Arnhem. It is part of the route connecting the Ruhr region to Amsterdam. This railway was opened in 1856 by the Cologne-Minden Railway Company and is one of the oldest lines in Germany. Branching off from the Duisburg–Dortmund line in Oberhausen, which is a section of the Cologne-Minden trunk line, it connects to the Rhine Railway in Arnhem leading to Amsterdam. The Oberhausen–Arnhem railway is crucial for international traffic, serving both long-distance passenger services and freight transportation. It is considered a priority project of the Trans-European Networks.
General Walter Kross is a retired United States Air Force four-star general. He served as Commander in Chief of the United States Transportation Command and Commander of the Air Mobility Command from 1996 to 1998. Kross was commissioned through Officer Training School in December 1964. Throughout his career, he flew 157 F-4 combat missions, including 100 over North Vietnam. He later transitioned to airlift and held various senior executive and congressional pilot support roles. Kross has also served in various leadership positions, including commander of a C-5 wing, director of operations and logistics during Operations Desert Shield and Desert Storm, director of operations for Air Force headquarters, commander of the provisional force for standing up Air Mobility Command, first vice commander of Air Mobility Command, commander of the 15th Air Force at Travis Air Force Base in California, and director of the Joint Staff in Washington, D.C.
František Cína Jelínek was a Czech landscape painter. František Cína Jelínek was born on June 6, 1882, in Prague-Karlín and passed away on February 3, 1961, in Prague. Prague-Karlín is a district in Prague.
"Duel of Champions is a 1961 film based on the Roman legend of the Horatii and the Curiatii. The Horatii, triplet brothers from Rome, fought a duel against the Curiatii, triplet brothers from Alba Longa, to decide the outcome of a war between their nations. The film was directed by Ferdinando Baldi and Terence Young, and the screenplay was written by Ennio De Concini, Carlo Lizzani, Giuliano Montaldo, and Luciano Vincenzoni. It was filmed at the Cinecittà Studios in Rome."
George Bugg was an Anglican deacon and curate in England. He was also a scriptural geologist who authored a two-volume book titled "Scriptural Geology". George Bugg lived from 1769 to 1851.
Sir George Parker, 2nd Baronet, of Ratton, Sussex, was an English politician. He served as a Member of Parliament (MP) for Sussex from 1705 to 1708 and again from 1710 to 1713. Sir George Parker succeeded as the second baronet on November 30, 1691, and passed away on May 14, 1727.
"Full Flava is a production team from Birmingham, England. Full Flava consists of Rob Derbyshire and Paul Solomon. They are assisted by backing singer Tee. Full Flava specializes in producing R&B and soul records. They have worked with artists such as Chantay Savage, Beverlei Brown, Ruby Turner, Carleen Anderson, Hazel Fernandes, Alison Limerick, CeCe Peniston, and Donna Gardier."
The Four-Coalition, also known as the Coalition of Four or Quad-Coalition, abbreviated to 4K, was a liberal centre-right political alliance in the Czech Republic between 1998 and 2002. The four member parties were the Christian and Democratic Union – Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU–ČSL), the Freedom Union (US), the Democratic Union (DEU), and the Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA). The 4K was formed after the creation of the Opposition Agreement by the Czech Social Democratic Party and Civic Democratic Party in the aftermath of the 1998 election to the Chamber of Deputies. The coalition aimed to provide 'real opposition' to the government. In the 2002 election to the Chamber, the KDU–ČSL and US-DEU ran on a looser joint ticket called 'Coalition' ("Koalice"), and won 31 seats and 14% of the vote—down from the combined 39 seats and 19% of votes in the 1998 election.
Kinnikinnick Creek is a shallow waterway that is part of the Scioto River watershed, flowing through southern Pickaway and northern Ross Counties in Ohio. The area through which the creek flows, which includes the villages of Wisler, Kingston, and Kinnikinnick, Ohio is known locally as the Kinnikinnick Prairie. The Kinnikinnick has two branches, the main (north) branch, and the south branch. The creek’s northern headwaters form near the Pickaway County village of Leistville, Ohio, and flow south to the confluence of the creek’s southern branch, which has its headwaters in Ross County. There, the creek begins its west-southwest path until it merges with the Scioto River north of the city of Chillicothe, Ohio. The creek was named for the Native American tobacco product kinnikinnick. The creek was a resource for Native Americans in the days before European Settlement. When white settlers moved into the region around 1800, Kinnikinnick was a significant source of fresh water for consumption and crop irrigation. The Kinnikinnick is considered a major waterway feeder for the Scioto River by The Ohio State University Extension Services. Portions are navigable by canoe.
The National Museum of Ireland – Archaeology is a branch of the National Museum of Ireland located on Kildare Street in Dublin, Ireland. The museum focuses on Irish and other antiquities, covering the history of Ireland from the Stone Age to the Late Middle Ages. Important artefacts from the museum have been featured in "The Irish Times" and the book "A History of Ireland in 100 Objects". The displays include prehistoric Ireland, Bronze Age gold work, early medieval Celtic art treasures, Viking Ireland, and Medieval Ireland. Special exhibitions also feature items from Ancient Egypt, Cyprus, and the Roman world.
Telegraph Island, also known as Jazīrat al Maqlab or جزيرة_تليغراف, and Jazīrat Şaghīr, is located in the Elphinstone Inlet or Khor Ash Sham, the inner inlet of Khasab Bay, less than 400 meters off the shore of the Musandam Peninsula, and less than 500 meters south of much larger but also much lesser known Sham Island, both of which are parts of the Sultanate of Oman. It is 160 meters long, and up to 90 meters wide, yielding an area of 1.1 hectares. The name "Telegraph" comes from the telegraph-cable repeater station built on the island in 1864. The inlet at the island is a fjord surrounded by high mountains, with notable geology in the rock strata which dip downwards under the immense pressures caused by the Arabian tectonic plate meeting and subducting beneath the Eurasian plate. In the 19th century, it was the location of a British repeater station used to boost telegraphic messages along the "Persian Gulf submarine cable," which was part of the London to Karachi telegraphic cable. Today, Telegraph Island is a reminder of the British Empire. Abandoned in the mid-1870s, the island has remained deserted and only the ruins of the repeater station and the operators' quarters can be seen. Tourism has grown in the Persian Gulf region, so the island is regularly visited by dhows carrying tourists to view the ruins and to fish and snorkel in the waters around it.
"Run into the Light" is an extended play by English singer and songwriter Ellie Goulding. It was released exclusively on the iTunes Store on August 30, 2010 by Polydor Records. The EP consists of six remixes of tracks from Goulding's debut album, "Lights", with four of them being previously unreleased. In September 2011, Goulding released a 30-minute-long mix titled "Run into the Light" to mark her partnership with Nike. The mix, created by Alex Metric, is intended to be a soundtrack for running.
"The Setai Hotel and Residences, also known as The Setai Miami Beach and The Setai South Beach, is a high rise luxury hotel and condominium located in South Beach, Miami Beach, Florida. The building has 38 floors and is 117.5 meters tall, making it one of the tallest buildings in Miami Beach. The hotel, designed by Jean-Michel Gathy, includes a recording studio and a penthouse that includes a rooftop pool and jacuzzi."
Han Min-goo is a former South Korean Minister of Defense. Han Min-goo is a former South Korean army general. Han Min-goo served as the 40th Chief of Staff of the South Korean army and the 36th Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff of the South Korean military. Han Min-goo was born on August 30, 1953.
"Let England Shake" is the eighth studio album by English singer-songwriter and musician PJ Harvey. It was released on February 14, 2011, by Island Records. The production of the album started around the time of the release of "White Chalk" in 2007, but it is a departure from the piano-driven introspection of that album. "Let England Shake" was written over a -year period and recorded in five weeks at a church in Dorset during April and May 2010. The album received numerous accolades upon its release, including being named the 2011 "Album of the Year" by 16 publications and winning the Mercury Prize in September 2011. PJ Harvey's fourth nomination overall, including her 2001 win for "Stories from the City, Stories from the Sea," made her the most successful artist in the prize's history. Additionally, the album won the Uncut Music Award in November 2011 and Album of the Year at the 2012 Ivor Novello Awards.
"Drift Fence is a 1936 American film directed by Otho Lovering. The film is also known as Texas Desperadoes (American reissue title). David S. Garber was the art director for the film."
"Cyclamen mirabile, also known as sowbread, is a flowering plant in the primrose family Primulaceae. It is a tufted, tuberous herbaceous perennial native to Turkish pine woodland and maquis in southwestern Turkey. This species belongs to the "Cyclamen cilicium" group within the genus "Cyclamen" (subgenus "Gyrophoebe", series "Cilicium"). It was identified and named in 1906. The Latin specific epithet "mirabile" means “miraculous”, referring to the blooms that appear as if by magic from the bare earth."
"The Naked Hills is a 1956 American Western film directed by Josef Shaftel. The film stars David Wayne, Keenan Wynn, and James Barton."
"The Avenging Hand" is a British crime film from 1936. It was directed by Victor Hanbury and Frank Richardson. The film stars Noah Beery, Louis Borel, and Kathleen Kelly. "The Avenging Hand" was produced at Welwyn Studios as a quota quickie. Duncan Sutherland was involved in the film's set design.
"Gütersloh Hauptbahnhof is a railway station located in Gütersloh, Germany, in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia. It is situated on the electrified, four-track main line connecting the Ruhr region to Hanover, which was opened in 1847 as part of the trunk line of the former Cologne-Minden Railway Company. The station also serves services of the Warendorf Railway that run from Münster via Rheda-Wiedenbrück and the Hamm–Minden line to Gütersloh. Gütersloh Hauptbahnhof (Hbf) is categorized as a category 4 station by Deutsche Bahn. Within the station building, there is a tourist bureau where tickets can be purchased, as well as a restaurant/bistro, a bakery, a mini-supermarket, and a station bookshop."
"Metropolitan Suite is an album by electronic music composer Larry Fast. The album was released in 1987 through Audion Records. Metropolitan Suite is the ninth and final record in Larry Fast's Synergy project."
The 2010–11 Connecticut Huskies men's basketball team represented the University of Connecticut in the 2010–2011 NCAA Division I basketball season. The Huskies were coached by Jim Calhoun and played their home games at the XL Center in Hartford, Connecticut, and on campus at the Harry A. Gampel Pavilion in Storrs, Connecticut. The Huskies are a member of the Big East Conference. The Huskies entered the year unranked and picked to finish tenth in the Big East. In November, they won the Maui Invitational Tournament for the second time. Led by Kemba Walker, they became the first school to win five conference tournament games in as many days in claiming their seventh Big East Tournament title. By winning the tournament, they were awarded an automatic berth into the 2011 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament. They advanced to their fourth Final Four with a victory over Arizona and advanced to their third National Championship game with a victory over Kentucky and beat Butler for their first championship since 2004 and third since 1999.
The Kochi Bypass is a segment of NH66 that bypasses the CBD of the city of Kochi in Kerala, India. The highway stretches 17 km from Edapally in the Ernakulam district to Aroor in Alappuzha district, via Palarivattom, Vyttila, Kundannoor, Madavana, and Kumbalam. The Government of Kerala began the preliminary works in 1973. After a slow progress, it was partially opened for traffic in the early 1980s. The section between Edapally and Vyttila had four lanes from the beginning. The rest of the carriageway was also upgraded to different sections of 4 lanes, 5 lanes, and 6 lanes by 2010. The Kochi Bypass was designed to divert truck traffic away from the city center, but now the city's growth has led to heavy suburban traffic on the bypass. The road has become the most important arterial road in Kochi and is expected to replace MG Road as the state's major commercial avenue. The S.A. Road and Kaniyampuzha Road connect the stretch with Vyttila Mobility Hub, which is said to be the biggest and most important transport hub in Kochi and one of the largest bus terminals in India.
The European Coatings Journal is an English-language trade magazine for the coatings industry. It is published by Vincentz Network. The magazine was established in 1986. According to the Informationsgemeinschaft zur Feststellung der Verbreitung von Werbeträgern, it reached about 33,000 readers per issue in 2010. The "European Coatings Journal" is an official partner of the Conseil Européen de l'Industrie des Peintures, des Encres d'Imprimerie et des Couleurs d'Arts, which is the European coatings association.
"Grevillea epicroca is a shrub species. Grevillea epicroca is endemic to south-eastern New South Wales in Australia. Grevillea epicroca grows up to 2.5 meters high. Grevillea epicroca produces clusters of red flowers between November and May in its native range. Grevillea epicroca was first formally described by Val Stajsic and Bill Molyneux. The description was published in "Flora of Australia" in 2000. The species is found on rocky escarpments in moist forests to the west of Moruya, New South Wales."
Garbis Zakaryan was a Turkish and European welterweight boxing champion of Armenian ethnicity. He was the first Turkish professional boxer and was nicknamed "Demir Yumruk" ("Iron Fist"). Garbis Zakaryan was born on June 2, 1930, and passed away on January 25, 2020.
"Parvedentulina is a genus of air-breathing land snails, terrestrial pulmonate gastropod mollusks in the family Streptaxidae. In 2002, 94 species of Parvedentulina were known, with the majority of these species being described in the same year. Additionally, 6 new species of Parvedentulina were described in 2009, and another 5 new species were described in 2010."
"The China Governess is a crime novel by Margery Allingham. The China Governess was first published in 1963 in the United Kingdom by Chatto & Windus, London. The China Governess is the seventeenth novel in the Albert Campion series."
Six teams, four from West Asia and two from East Asia, participated in the 2011 AFC Champions League qualifying play-off. The draw for the qualifying play-off took place in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia on December 7, 2010. To ensure balance, a draw was conducted to move one team (Al-Ain) from the West to the East side of the play-offs. The semi-finals and finals were played in a single match, hosted by one of the teams, with extra time and penalty shootouts used if necessary. The semi-finals occurred on February 12, 2011, and the finals on February 19, 2011. The winners from the qualifying play-off, one from West Asia and one from East Asia, progressed to the group stage to join the 30 automatic qualifiers. The losing teams from the qualifying play-off entered the 2011 AFC Cup group stage.
"Mason Foster is an American football linebacker. Mason Foster was born on March 1, 1989. Mason Foster is currently a free agent. Mason Foster was drafted by the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in the third round of the 2011 NFL Draft. Mason Foster played college football at Washington. Mason Foster has also been a member of the Chicago Bears and Washington Redskins."
"Grenagh GAA is a Gaelic Football and hurling club based in the village of Grenagh in Cork, Ireland. The club participates in Cork GAA competitions and Muskerry board competitions. In 2010, the club played in the Premier division of the Cork Intermediate Football Championship and Mid Cork Junior Hurling Championship. Grenagh GAA's local rivals are Whitechurch. The club was established in 1934."
In the 2011 AFC Cup group stage, a total of 32 teams competed, with 20 from West Asia and 12 from East Asia. This included 28 direct entries and 4 losers from the 2011 AFC Champions League qualifying play-off, with two from each region. The draw for the group stage took place in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia on December 7, 2010. The teams were divided into eight groups of four, ensuring clubs from the same country were not placed together. Each group played a round-robin format, facing each other home-and-away on matchdays scheduled for March 1-2, March 15-16, April 12-13, April 26-27, May 3-4, and May 10-11, 2011. The winners and runners-up of each group progressed to the knockout stage.
Ida Waterman, born Ida Shaw on March 10, 1852, was a stage and screen actress. She was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. Waterman appeared in over thirty Broadway productions from the late 1880s to the early 1920s. Some of her notable roles include Elise Claremont in the 1889 farce-comedy "Our Flat," Mrs. Kirke in "Men and Women" opposite Maude Adams, Mrs. Crawley in "Becky Sharp" (later adapted into the 1934 film "Becky Sharp"), and Mrs. French in "Lawful Larceny" in 1922. Waterman transitioned into silent films in the 1910s after a successful career on the Victorian and Edwardian stage. She passed away in 1941 in Cincinnati, Ohio.
"Tvååkers IF is a Swedish football club. Tvååkers IF is located in Tvååker in Varberg Municipality, Halland County."
Norman Thaddeus Vane, also known as Norman Thatteus Vein, was a screenwriter, producer, playwright, and film director. He worked on the 1968 film "Mrs. Brown, You've Got a Lovely Daughter" as a writer and later as a writer and associate producer for the movie "Lola" in the following year. Vane also wrote the screenplay for the 1972 film "1931: Once Upon a Time in New York" and directed the 1983 film "Frightmare". He continued his contributions to writing films, including "The Black Room" in 1984. Norman Thaddeus Vane was born on July 7, 1928, and passed away on May 2, 2015.
"Bir El Mokadem is a town and commune in Tébessa Province, Algeria. Tébessa Province is located in north-eastern Algeria."
Cheria is a town and commune located in Tébessa Province in north-eastern Algeria.
Frida Toveby is a Swedish handball player. Frida Toveby was born in 1982. Frida Toveby played for the club Aalborg DH and the Swedish national team. Frida Toveby participated in the 2008 Summer Olympics in China. The Swedish team placed eighth in the competition. Frida Toveby has retired from handball and is now a full-time lawyer.
Mission to the World (MTW) is the mission-sending agency for the Presbyterian Church in America. This evangelical Christian organization focuses on advancing the Great Commission through promoting Reformed and covenantal church planting movements using word and deed in strategic areas worldwide. MTW has missionaries serving in 97 countries, including 615 career missionaries, 82 short-term missionaries, 67 volunteer interns, and 1,646 trip participants. Dr. Paul Kooistra served as the coordinator from 1994 to 2014, and on July 24, 2014, Dr. Lloyd Kim was appointed as the new coordinator.
"The Scord of Brouster is a Neolithic farm site located in Shetland, Scotland. It dates back to 2220 BC with a time window of 80 years on either side. The site consists of three houses, several fields surrounded by walls, and a cairn. According to a sign at the Scord of Brouster, the climate of Shetland became wetter around 1500 BC, leading to the formation of peat near the fields, which eventually led to the permanent abandonment of the site by the farmers."
The Chen Clan Ancestral Hall, also known as the Chen Clan Academy, is an academic temple located in Guangzhou, China. It was built by the 72 Chen clans in 1894 during the Qing Dynasty for their juniors' accommodation and preparation for the imperial examinations. Over time, it was transformed into the Chen Clan's Industry College and later into middle schools. Today, it serves as the Guangdong Folk Art Museum. Situated at Zhongshan 7th Road near the Chen Clan Academy metro station, the complex consists of 19 buildings including nine halls and six courtyards. The architecture and decoration of the Chen Clan Ancestral Hall showcase traditional Chinese style and have had a significant impact on cultural and architectural developments globally. In 1988, it was designated as a "Cultural Relic of National Importance under the Protection of the State." The complex houses a diverse collection of southern China art pieces such as wood carvings and pottery.
William Morton Grinnell was a United States diplomat, lawyer, banker, and author. William Morton Grinnell was born on February 28, 1857, and passed away on February 9, 1906.
"Patvi Namdar Maharajkumar Shri Udaybhansinhji Natwarsinhji Jethwa Sahib was the last Maharajkumar or Yuvraj of Jethwa dynasty of Princely State of Porbandar. Patvi Namdar Maharajkumar Shri Udaybhansinhji Natwarsinhji Jethwa Sahib was associated with cooperative movement in post-independent India. Patvi Namdar Maharajkumar Shri Udaybhansinhji Natwarsinhji Jethwa Sahib was born on October 6, 1901 in Shrinagar, Gujarat and passed away in 1977 in Bombay. Patvi Namdar Maharajkumar Shri Udaybhansinhji Natwarsinhji Jethwa Sahib was a recipient of Padma Shri award."
"Papilin is a protein. Papilin is encoded by the "PAPLN" gene in humans. Papilin is an extracellular matrix glycoprotein."
"Black Rhythm Happening is the second album by American trumpeter Eddie Gale. The album was recorded in 1969 and released on the Blue Note label."
"Eupithecia fennoscandica is a moth of the family Geometridae. It is known from northern Fennoscandia, Russia, Siberia, and northern Mongolia. The wingspan of Eupithecia fennoscandica is 17–21 mm. This moth has one generation per year, with adults on wing in July. The larvae of Eupithecia fennoscandica feed on Viscaria alpina and can be found from mid-July to mid-August. Eupithecia fennoscandica overwinters as a pupa."
Cornelis Cels was a Flemish painter known for his portraits and religious subjects. He served as a professor and director at the Académie des Beaux-Arts de Tournai (Academy of Fine Arts, Tournai). Additionally, he was patronized as a portrait painter by the court of The Hague.
CLS Music is an independent record label based in Budapest. It was founded in 2002 as CLS Records and later changed its name to "CLS Music" in 2010. The company shifted its focus from releasing records to more wide-scope musical management. CLS Music is a major redistributor of foreign independent and electronic music releases in Hungary. Egység Média Kft, founded in 2008 by one of the owners of CLS Records, ran the CLS Music label at the end of 2013. From the second half of 2013, Egység Média started releasing music under the Egység Média / CLS Music label. In 2016, Egység Média was nominated for the IMPALA FIVEUNDERFIFTEEN campaign, which highlights Europe's most inspiring young labels. The label received the IMPALA Young Label Spotlight Award.
Jesko Friedrich is a German comedy television actor and writer. Jesko Friedrich was born on April 2, 1974 in Gießen.
Joseph Frederick Green was a British politician. He served as the Member of Parliament for Leicester West from 1918 to 1922. Green was initially involved in the Liberal Party and later joined the Independent Labour Party, Fabian Society, and Social Democratic Federation. He also served in various political associations and committees. Green contested the 1918 general election with coalition support and won against Ramsay MacDonald. However, in the 1922 general election as a National Liberal Party candidate, he lost to Alfred Hill. Green then joined the Conservative Party and worked at its headquarters.
"Carl Tersmeden was a Swedish admiral and diarist. Carl Tersmeden was born on April 23, 1715, in Larsbo bruk in Dalarna. Carl Tersmeden passed away on December 25, 1797."
The Memorial World Tour was a concert tour by Slipknot in honor of late bassist Paul Gray. The tour followed the All Hope Is Gone World Tour and included festival dates and headlining appearances. Slipknot headlined various festivals in Europe and closed off 2011 at the Rock in Rio festival in Brazil. Drummer Joey Jordison announced that former Slipknot guitarist Donnie Steele would fill in for Gray. Vocalist Corey Taylor expressed hesitancy about recording another Slipknot album due to Gray's absence. Percussionist Shawn Crahan and Taylor expressed interest in bringing the tour to the United States. Slipknot also scheduled headlining shows in Russia and Berlin. In 2012, Slipknot returned to North America for the Mayhem Festival tour. Guitarist Jim Root had to sit out multiple dates due to a burst appendix but later returned to the band. During the tour, band members wore various masks and jumpsuits from previous albums. The tour marked the last appearance of drummer Joey Jordison before his departure from the band in 2013.
Clarence Howard Clark Jr. was a financier in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. He was born in 1862 to Clarence Howard Clark Sr. He followed his father into his grandfather's business, hiring on as a clerk with E. W. Clark & Co. in 1879 and becoming a partner in 1885. He was admitted to the Philadelphia Stock Exchange in 1888 and served for 10 years as president of the Centennial National Bank. Clark died of "a stroke of apoplexy" on January 10, 1916, at the Pineland Country Club in Mullins, South Carolina. He was survived by his wife, Eleanor D. Head Clark Jr., who died Aug. 29, 1930, at her summer home in Northeast Harbor, Maine, and a son, Clarence H. Clark III. Clark III, whose own financial partnership, Kendrick & Co., failed in 1922, was a member of the First Troop Philadelphia City Cavalry, with which he served during World War I as a captain in the 310th Field Artillery. Clark III married Eleanor Townsend Clark, with whom he had two daughters, including Eleanor Yerkes, and a son, Clarence H. Clark IV, who served in the Army Air Corps during World War II. Clark IV, husband of Jean E. Clark, had a son, Clarence H. Clark V, and a daughter, Amy Clark. Clark V and his wife Kathleen had a son, Chip, and a daughter, Betsy.
"José González Ganoza was a Peruvian footballer. José González Ganoza played as a goalkeeper. José González Ganoza was born on July 10, 1954 and passed away on December 8, 1987 in the 1987 Alianza Lima air disaster. Paolo Guerrero, who is José González Ganoza's nephew, is also a football player."
Edward Walter Clark III was an investment banker. Edward Walter Clark III was associated with E. W. Clark & Co. Edward Walter Clark III passed away on November 16, 1939.
Yuriy Putrash is a Ukrainian football defender. Yuriy Putrash was born on January 29, 1990 in Mizhhirya, Zakarpattia Oblast, Ukrainian SSR. FC Mynai is the football club where Yuriy Putrash currently plays.
Louis Bélanger is a Canadian film director and screenwriter. Louis Bélanger was born in 1964 in Beauport, Quebec. Louis Bélanger has a degree in communications from UQAM. Louis Bélanger is a close friend and collaborator of filmmaker Denis Chouinard. Louis Bélanger and Denis Chouinard created several short films together before pursuing their own careers with feature films. Louis Bélanger's film "Post Mortem" won him Best Director at the Montreal World Film Festival and earned him two Genie Awards for best new director and best screenplay. Louis Bélanger began making films and long-form videos while still a student. Louis Bélanger shot videos for Télévision Suisse Romande in the late 1990s before directing his first feature, the multi-award winning "Post Mortem" in 1999. Louis Bélanger's follow-up was "Lauzon-Lauzone", a documentary about the late director Jean-Claude Lauzon, and a second feature in 2003, "Gaz Bar Blues". Louis Bélanger is influenced by the man-of-the-people-docudrama style of John Cassavetes and Ken Loach. Louis Bélanger has expressed that "there aren’t any new stories to tell; all that matters is the telling."
Orlando Nannini is an Argentine fencer. Orlando Nannini was born on July 12, 1937. Orlando Nannini competed in the individual and team foil events at the 1964 and 1968 Summer Olympics.
Walter Neurath was a British publisher. Walter Neurath co-founded Thames & Hudson in 1949 with his wife, Eva Neurath. Eric Hobsbawm has acknowledged Walter Neurath's significant contribution to the arts in Britain. Walter Neurath originally came from Vienna in 1938.
"Bayaning 3rd World is a Philippine mockumentary film. The film was directed by Mike de Leon and written by De Leon and Clodualdo del Mundo Jr. It focuses on the heroism of Philippine national hero Jose Rizal, specifically his alleged retraction of his writings against the Catholic Church during the Spanish colonization period in the country."
Chaetachme is a monotypic genus of flowering plants in the elm family containing the single species Chaetachme aristata. Its English common name is thorny elm, and it is known as muyuyu in Kikuyu. It is native to eastern and western Africa, including Madagascar. "Chaetachme aristata" is a shrub or small tree growing up to 10 meters tall. It has drooping, angular branches covered with spines up to 3.5 centimeters in length. The lance-shaped leaves are up to 11 centimeters long by 5 centimeters wide, pointed at the tip and smooth or serrated on the edges. The shrub is dioecious and sexually dimorphic, with male and female flower types borne on separate individuals. This shrub is host to the mirid bug "Volumnus chaetacme". The spiny branches of the shrub are used as fences in African villages.
Miroslav Šalom Freiberger was a Croatian chief rabbi, catechist, translator, writer, and spiritual leader. Miroslav Šalom Freiberger was educated as a lawyer and doctor of theology.
Sabri Yirmibeşoğlu was a Turkish general. Sabri Yirmibeşoğlu was born on September 1, 1928 and passed away on January 2, 2016. Sabri Yirmibeşoğlu served as the Secretary-General of the National Security Council from 1988 to 1990.
The Gaon Digital Chart is the music industry standard record chart in South Korea for singles. It is provided by the Korea Music Content Industry Association and published weekly by the Gaon Music Chart. The chart provides rankings on a weekly, monthly, and yearly basis, which are based on an aggregate of downloads, streaming, and background music. The data is compiled from online sources such as Melon, Bugs, Genie, KakaoMusic, Flo, Vibe, and Soribada. In addition to ranking all songs, separate rankings are provided for domestic and international releases. The tracking of sales began in 2009 and the results were published the following February.
Juraj Šimlovič is a freelance software developer. Juraj Šimlovič resides in Prague, Czech Republic. Juraj Šimlovič is a co-author of the extension for Wikipedia. Juraj Šimlovič is the author of various free software utilities, including TED Notepad. In December 2008, Juraj Šimlovič's team emerged victorious in the 2K Australia's Botprize artificial intelligence competition.
"Aurora Bank is a Federal Savings Bank headquartered in Wilmington, Delaware. It was founded on January 1, 1921, under the name Delaware Savings And Loan Association. In 1958, deposits made to the bank were insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation. The bank was later renamed to Delaware Savings Bank, FSB in 1988 and then to Aurora Bank, FSB in 2009. Aurora Bank was a subsidiary of Lehman Brothers Bancorp. In June 2012, Aurora Bank exited most of the financial services business. Aurora Bank offers various banking services and is regulated by the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency and the FDIC. It has offices in California, Colorado, Indiana, Missouri, Nebraska, New Jersey, and New York. Aurora Bank FSB is chartered by the Office of Comptroller of the Currency and is a member of the Federal Home Loan Bank System."
Albe Vidaković was a Croatian composer, Catholic priest, and musicologist. Albe Vidaković was born on October 1, 1914, in Subotica and passed away on April 18, 1964, in Zagreb. He was originally from Bačka, which is now part of Vojvodina, Serbia.
Samuel Bourn was an English Dissenter minister. He was the third Samuel Bourn and the second son of Samuel Bourn the Younger and his wife, Hannah Harrison, who was previously known as Hannah Taylor of Kendal. Samuel Bourn was educated at Stand grammar school in Lancashire and the University of Glasgow. In 1742, he became the dissenting minister of Rivington, Lancashire, where he had a close friendship with Hugh Willoughby, the 15th Baron Willoughby of Parham. In 1754, Bourn relocated to Norwich to assist the Presbyterian minister John Taylor, who later moved to Warrington Academy three years later.
"Picasso's Last Words (Drink to Me)" is a song by the British–American rock band Paul McCartney and Wings. It was released on their 1973 album "Band on the Run". The longest track on the album, it was not released as a single. Wings band member Denny Laine covered "Picasso's Last Words (Drink to Me)" in 2007 on his album "Performs the Hits of Wings". An abbreviated performance of the song appears on the live album "Wings over America".
Edward Whitaker Gray was an English botanist. Edward Whitaker Gray was the secretary to the Royal Society. Edward Whitaker Gray was born on March 21, 1748, and passed away on December 27, 1806. Samuel Frederick Gray, the author of "The Practical Chemist," was the nephew of Edward Whitaker Gray.
Sione Sangster Saulala is a Tongan broadcaster, politician, and former member of the Legislative Assembly of Tonga. Sione Sangster Saulala is affiliated with the Democratic Party of the Friendly Islands. Sione Sangster Saulala was born on April 9, 1974.
Cosimo Aldo Cannone is an Italian Endurance S One racing driver and a two-time World Champion. Cosimo Aldo Cannone has been racing for Cannone. Cosimo Aldo Cannone was born on March 20, 1984 in Brindisi. Cosimo Aldo Cannone is also known as "Alcan" in the world of sports.
"Santaris Pharma A/S is a biopharmaceutical company. Santaris Pharma A/S was founded in 2003 in Copenhagen, Denmark. Santaris Pharma A/S also has a branch in San Diego, California that opened in 2009. Santaris Pharma A/S was created by a merger between Cureon and Pantheco. Santaris Pharma A/S develops RNA-targeted medicines using a Locked Nucleic Acid (LNA) Drug Platform and Drug Development Engine. The company was acquired by Roche in August 2014. Santaris has worldwide exclusive intellectual property rights to the therapeutic applications of locked nucleic acid (LNA) technology. This includes ownership of over 60 patent types, ranging from chemistry to manufacturing and from therapeutic uses to drug design. With their LNA technology, Santaris works on developing drugs for a wide range of diseases using microRNA and mRNA. Their research focuses on infectious disease and metabolic disorders. They also collaborate with pharmaceuticals to develop drugs for rare genetic disorders, cancers, cardiovascular disease, and immune and inflammatory diseases."
"Chilocampyla dyariella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Florida, United States. The larvae of Chilocampyla dyariella feed on various "Eugenia" species including "Eugenia axillaris", "Eugenia foetida", "Eugenia garberi", "Eugenia procera", and "Eugenia rhombea". They create mines on the leaves of their host plants, which have a distinct appearance. The larva of Chilocampyla dyariella is cylindrical, transparent, and has 14 legs. When fully grown, it leaves the mine, changes color, and spins a cocoon. The pupa of Chilocampyla dyariella initially appears white but eventually takes on the coloration of the adult moth."
"Wheels Ain't Coming Down" is a song by the British rock band Slade. The song was released in 1979 as the opening track from their eighth studio album "Return to Base". It was written by lead vocalist Noddy Holder and bassist Jim Lea, and produced by Slade. In 1981, the song re-appeared on the band's follow-up album "We'll Bring the House Down" and was released as the second single from it in March, reaching No. 60 in the UK.
Sir Arthur Fell was an English solicitor and Conservative Party politician. Sir Arthur Fell served in the House of Commons from 1906 to 1922 representing Great Yarmouth. He was known for his opposition to free trade and his advocacy for a Channel Tunnel. Sir Arthur Fell was involved in a controversial legal case in 1906 where an election petition against him was dismissed by a biased judge.
Prudential borrowing is the set of rules governing local authority borrowing in the UK. Under prudential borrowing, the amount of debt and other liabilities most local authorities can incur is no longer capped by an upper limit. Instead, borrowing must conform to the Prudential Code, which requires that borrowing be affordable and prudential.
The Presidential Young Investigator Award (PYI) was awarded by the National Science Foundation of the United States Federal Government. The program operated from 1984 to 1991, and was replaced by the NSF Young Investigator (NYI) Awards and Presidential Faculty Fellows Program (PFF). Applicants could not directly apply for the award, but were nominated by others including their own institutions based on their previous record of scientific achievement. The award, a certificate from the White House signed by the President of the United States, included a minimum grant of $25,000 a year for five years from NSF to be used for any scientific research project the awardee wished to pursue, with the possibility of additional funding up to $100,000 annually if the PYI obtained matching funds from industry. Considered to be one of the highest honors granted by the National Science Foundation, the award program was criticized in 1990 as not being the best use of NSF funds in an era of tight budgets.
Marietta Street Artery, formerly known as "Bellwood," is a defined neighborhood in Atlanta, Georgia. It is part of the West Midtown area, also referred to as the "Westside." The neighborhood includes Marietta Street and the surrounding city blocks from 8th Street NW to North Avenue NW. It is bordered by Home Park to the north, Georgia Tech to the east, downtown Atlanta to the south, and English Avenue to the west. The area features former industrial and warehouse properties that have been repurposed into lofts, galleries, theaters, shops, restaurants, and coffee shops.
Loren Ligorio is a Croatian painter. Loren Ligorio was born on June 9, 1955. Loren Ligorio is known for his vividly-colored Arcadian landscapes. Loren Ligorio has a strong devotion to his native Dubrovnik. Loren Ligorio obtained a degree in Art History from Belgrade University in the 1970s. In 2006, a documentary was filmed about Loren Ligorio titled "Dubrovački likovni umjetnici".
The Mereni Wind Farm is a wind power project located in Constanţa County, Romania. It consists of 30 individual wind turbines with a nominal output of around 1.5 MW, delivering up to 45 MW of power, which is sufficient to power over 29,400 homes. The capital investment required for this project is approximately €50 million.
"No Sound but the Wind" is a song by British indie rock band Editors. The song is featured on "The Twilight Saga: New Moon" soundtrack. It was first played at the Glastonbury festival in 2008. Tom Smith, the band's member, revealed that he was inspired to write the song after reading Cormac McCarthy's novel "The Road". The song has become a fan favorite and a regular part of Editors' live shows. It was released as a single in 2010 and achieved chart-topping success in Belgium. The single version of the song was a live performance from the Rock Werchter festival. The song received golden record-status and later certified platinum in Belgium. Different versions of the song appear on various albums and compilations. The music video for the song features a live performance from Rock Werchter 2010. Despite its success in Belgium, the single was not released in the United Kingdom.
The Canadian Journal of Civil Engineering is a monthly peer-reviewed scientific journal established in 1974 and published by the NRC Research Press. It covers environmental, hydrotechnical, structure, and construction engineering, as well as engineering mechanics, engineering materials, and a history of civil engineering. The journal is available online in full-text HTML and PDF formats. It is the official journal of the Canadian Society for Civil Engineering. The editors in chief are Tarek Sayed from the University of British Columbia and Mike Bartlett from the University of Western Ontario.
The Palliser Region is an area in the southeast corner of Alberta, Canada. It is serviced by the Palliser Economic Partnership and borders Saskatchewan to the east and Montana to the south. The total population of the area was 112,314 in 2009, with Medicine Hat being the largest urban centre. The region is the traditional territory of the Blackfoot Confederacy and was explored by John Palliser in the 19th century. Despite its semi-arid climate, the region has become a successful agricultural centre thanks to dryland farming techniques. The region's economy is based on agriculture, oil and gas, manufacturing, defence and aerospace, and tourism. Key transportation infrastructure includes highways #1 and #3 connecting it to the rest of Canada, as well as highways #36 and #41 connecting it to the US border. The region's fastest growing economic sectors are Mining and Oil and Gas Extraction, Professional, Scientific and Technical Services, and Finance, Insurance, Real Estate, and Leasing. Employment in the region is increasing at a rate higher than the Canadian average.
"Miklós Meszéna was a Hungarian fencer. Miklós Meszéna was born on December 14, 1940, and passed away on July 29, 1995. Miklós Meszéna won a bronze medal in the team sabre event at the 1968 Summer Olympics."
The Jacksonville Rockets were a professional minor league ice hockey team based in Jacksonville, Florida. They played in the Eastern Hockey League from 1964–1972, when they folded. They were the first professional hockey team to be based in Florida. They played most of their home games at the Jacksonville Coliseum; from 1966–68 they were known as the Florida Rockets, playing some of their home games in St. Petersburg, Florida.
"Moose Factory Island is an island in the Moose River, Ontario, Canada, about from its mouth at James Bay. It is adjacent to the community of Moosonee across the Moose River, from which it is accessible by water taxi. The island is home to the community of Moose Factory. Moose Factory Island is divided into two entities: Factory Island 1 - Indian reserve that makes up the northern two-thirds of the island, belonging to the Moose Cree First Nation. Unorganized Cochrane District - Unincorporated southern third, home to the old Hudson's Bay Company post and government services, governed by the provincial Local Services Board and the federal Weeneebayko Health Ahtuskaywin that administers the hospital. Moose Factory Island is part of the Hudson Bay Lowlands, flat and made up of marine clay, underlain by sedimentary rocks. It is affected by the Arctic tides which rise and fall twice daily."
Gerd Vollum was a Norwegian politician for the Labour Party. Gerd Vollum served as a deputy representative to the Parliament of Norway from Akershus during the term 1973–1977.
Titanium Valley is a planned special economic zone in Sverdlovsk Oblast in the Urals Federal District of Russia. It will focus on creating titanium products for various industries such as aircraft, automotive, shipbuilding, and medical. The zone will be centered around the world's largest titanium producer, VSMPO-Avisma. The Russian government plans to invest at least 40 billion rubles ($1.29 billion) for the project. The purpose of the special economic zone, located in the city of Verkhnyaya Salda, is to facilitate the development and production of value-added products in the region and attract international partners. A total of 20 companies, including VSMPO-Avisma, Arvi, SR Systematics, and United Aircraft Corporation, will participate in the project, creating an estimated 20,000 jobs in the city. Companies operating in the zone will receive preferential tax treatment. Governor of Sverdlovsk Oblast Aleksandr Misharin expects these incentives to enable the companies to produce globally competitive products and generate new employment opportunities. Prime Minister Vladimir Putin announced during a visit to the region on 13 November 2010 that a decree for creating the special economic zone would be signed in two weeks. VSMPO-Avisma has already invested $700 million in preparation, and ChelPipe has spent over $630 million on modernizing its facilities. Foreign companies like Rolls-Royce Group and Goodrich Corporation are also considering establishing production facilities in the zone. The Titanium Valley project is part of Russia's efforts to modernize and diversify its economy, a key initiative during Dmitry Medvedev's presidency.
Riebiņi is a village in Latvia. Riebiņi is the center of both Riebiņi Parish and Riebiņi Municipality.
The 2010–11 Atlantic 10 Conference men's basketball season was the 35th season of Atlantic 10 Conference basketball. The 2011 Atlantic 10 Men's Basketball Tournament took place for the fifth consecutive year at Boardwalk Hall in Atlantic City, New Jersey.
The 2004 Scottish Claymores season was the tenth and final season for the franchise in the NFL Europe League (NFLEL). The team was led by head coach Jack Bicknell in his first year, and played its home games at Hampden Park in Glasgow, Scotland.
Västanå is a village located in Bromölla Municipality, Skåne County, Sweden. Västanå had 130 inhabitants in 2005.
"Berus is a village located in the municipality of Überherrn in the district of Saarlouis, Saarland, Germany. Prior to December 1973, Berus functioned as an independent municipality."
"Die Pleite is a German periodical. Die Pleite was founded and edited by George Grosz, Wieland Herzfelde, and John Heartfield. Die Pleite ran from 1919 to 1924. Die Pleite was part of the Berlin Dada scene. Die Pleite was known for its critiques of the Weimar Republic and its awareness of right-wing extremism in Europe."
Enrique de Gandía was an Argentine historian born on February 1, 1906, in Buenos Aires. He authored over a hundred books and taught at various institutions including the School of Fine Arts, University of Morón, University of Belgrano, and Kennedy University. He was also the director of the Buenos Aires Municipal Museum. Enrique de Gandía was a full member of several National Academies and received numerous awards and honors, including the Konex 1984 and the appointment as Commander of the Order of Prince Henry the Navigator by the Government of Portugal. He was known for his contributions to the Argentine School of Protocartography and his theory that the fourth peninsula of Asia on ancient maps was actually South America, as discussed in his book "Primitivos navegantes vascos".
"These Simple Truths" is the first major-label studio album by the Sidewalk Prophets, released on August 25, 2009, under Word Records. The album features the hit radio singles "The Words I Would Say" and "You Love Me Anyway." The Sidewalk Prophets primarily play in the genre of Contemporary Christian music. "The Words I Would Say" was a hit from this CD and is also included in WOW Hits 2010 and WOW Hits 2011.
"The Blithfield meteorite was found by Mr. Joseph Legree in Blithfield Township, Renfrew County, Ontario. The main mass of the meteorite is now in the Canadian National collection in Ottawa. Blithfield meteorite is classified as an enstatite chondrite, which is a group of very unusual meteorites formed in a very reducing atmosphere. It is a breccia, one of only five known enstatite chondrite breccias."
Thomas Glacier is a glacier located in the Sentinel Range of the Ellsworth Mountains. It drains the southeast slopes of Vinson Massif and flows for 17 nautical miles. The glacier was discovered by U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6 in 1959 and mapped by the United States Geological Survey. It was named after R. Admiral Charles W. Thomas, a veteran of Antarctic expeditions in the 1950s.
Bob Berkowitz is an American journalist, talk show host, and author. Bob Berkowitz is a journalist, talk show host, and author from America.
"Sir George Doughty was a British ship-owner and politician from Grimsby in Lincolnshire. He sat in the House of Commons for most of the period from 1895–1914. Doughty was born on March 13, 1854, in Grimsby to William Doughty. He was educated at the Wesleyan Higher Grade School in Grimsby and later became a merchant, a ship-owner, and a partner in the Grimsby-based firm of Hagerup, Doughty and Company Ltd. Doughty served as an alderman and Mayor of Grimsby, as well as a Justice of the Peace for the Lindsey area of Lincolnshire. He was initially a member of the Liberal Party but later joined the Liberal Unionists. Doughty was elected as the Member of Parliament for Great Grimsby in 1895, defeating Edward Heneage. He was knighted in 1904 and later became a Conservative Party MP. Doughty passed away suddenly at Waltham Old Hall, Lincolnshire, in April 1914 at the age of 60, following a period of indifferent health after an operation in New York while returning from British Columbia."
"Myrmecia croslandi is a species of bull ant native to Australia. It is also known as a jack jumper. This species can be found in various regions of Australia, including New South Wales and Queensland. Myrmecia croslandi was described by Taylor in 1991."
Tsho Rolpa, also known as Cho Rolpa, is a significant glacial lake in Nepal. The lake is situated at a high altitude in the Rolwaling Valley, Dolakha District, amidst the Himalayas. Over the past 50 years, Tsho Rolpa has expanded significantly due to glacial melting in the region.
François-Pierre Cherrier was a French-born merchant and notary in Lower Canada. He was born in Savigné-l'Évêque in Sarthe on September 3, 1717. In 1736, he came to Saint-Antoine-de-Longueuil in New France, where his uncle was a parish priest. Cherrier opened a store and became a notary for the seigneury in 1738. He married Marie Dubuc in 1743. In 1750, he was appointed as a royal notary for the parish of Longueuil. After the British conquest, his notary commission was renewed, but his finances suffered due to currency conversion. In 1765, he moved to Montreal for better prospects but returned to Longueuil in 1767. In 1770, he relocated to Saint-Denis, where his son François became a parish priest. Cherrier practiced as a notary there until 1789 and passed away in Saint-Denis at the age of 75. His sons Benjamin-Hyacinthe-Martin and Séraphin, as well as his grandson Côme-Séraphin, served in the assembly. His daughter Périne-Charles married Denis Viger and was the mother of Denis-Benjamin Viger. His daughter Rosalie married Joseph Papineau and was the mother of Louis-Joseph Papineau.
"Gregor Zore is a Slovenian football player."
"Eucosmophora chrysocosma is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Eucosmophora chrysocosma is known from Guyana. The length of the forewings is 3.4–4 mm for males and 3.7–5 mm for females. The larvae of Eucosmophora chrysocosma probably feed on a Sapotaceae species and mine the leaves of their host plant."
"Lucas Pacheco Affini, also known as Lucas Sasha, is a Brazilian professional footballer. Lucas Sasha plays as a defensive midfielder for the Greek club Aris. Lucas Pacheco Affini was born on March 1, 1990."
Li Xiaoyun, also known as Michelle Li, is a Chinese-born Australian singer. Li Xiaoyun was born on March 16, 1987. Li Xiaoyun was the runner-up in the 2009 Super Girl contest. Li Xiaoyun is currently studying at the University of Melbourne.
"CART Precision Racing is a racing video game. CART Precision Racing was developed by Terminal Reality. CART Precision Racing was published by Microsoft Studios. CART Precision Racing is compatible with Windows 95."
Crewe North Junction signal box is a signal box with a Westinghouse All Electric Style 'L' lever frame. It was commissioned on 29 March 1940 as part of a resignalling project at Crewe railway station. The signal box saw continued use until 19 July 1985 when it was decommissioned for a redesign of Crewe station and its track layout and signalling.
"Mystery Scene is an American magazine. Mystery Scene was first published in 1985. Mystery Scene covers the crime and mystery genre. Mystery Scene includes articles, profiles, criticism, and extensive reviews. Mystery Scene reviews books, films, TV, short stories, audiobooks, and reference works."
Vineet Verma is an Indian film director, screenwriter, producer, editor, 2D and 3D animator, and storyboard artist. Vineet Verma was born on November 25, 1982 in Aurangabad, State of Maharashtra, India. Aurangabad is located in the State of Maharashtra, India.
"Tombstone High School is located in Tombstone, Arizona. It is the only high school in the Tombstone Unified School District. The school, originally known as Tombstone Union High School, was established in 1922 on 605 E. Fremont Street. Over the years, several additions and improvements have been made to the campus, including a new gym in 1951, modern dressing rooms, an industrial arts building in 1963, science rooms in 1983, and a high school cafeteria in 1990. The campus also features facilities such as a band room, sports activity room, ramada locker facility, bus garage, and art room at the District Office. In 2006, a brand new school building was opened, marking a new chapter for Tombstone High School."
Henry Zouch was an English antiquary and social reformer. He was born around 1725 and died in 1795. Henry Zouch was the eldest surviving son of Charles Zouch, who was the vicar of Sandal Magna near Wakefield, and the elder brother of Thomas Zouch. He was educated at Wakefield Grammar School under the Rev. Benjamin Wilson and later attended Trinity College, Cambridge, where he graduated with a B.A. in 1746 and an M.A. in 1750. Henry Zouch was vicar of Sandal Magna from 1754 to 1789 and also served as the governor of Wakefield school from 1758 to 1764. In 1788, he became the rector of Swillington, succeeding his brother-in-law, Sir William Lowther. He was also the rector of Tankersley in Yorkshire and the chaplain to the Marchioness of Rockingham. Henry Zouch was a magistrate of the West Riding. He married Elizabeth, the daughter and heiress of William Spinke of Wakefield, who passed away in the spring of 1796 without any children. Henry Zouch passed away on 17 June 1795 and was buried in his own garden on 21 June.
Hugo Guimarães Silva Santos Almeida is a Brazilian footballer. Hugo Guimarães Silva Santos Almeida was born on January 6, 1986. Hugo Guimarães Silva Santos Almeida plays as a forward. Hugo Guimarães Silva Santos Almeida is a member of the sports team Esporte Clube Pelotas.
"Willy Tröger was a German footballer who played as a striker. Willy Tröger was born on October 2, 1928 in Zwickau and passed away on March 30, 2004 in Pirna. Willy Tröger spent his entire career with Wismut Aue. Willy Tröger made 15 appearances for the East Germany national team."
Leila Hoffman, formerly known as Rothstein, was born on June 11, 1934 in Hackney. Leila Hoffman is an English comedian, actress, and writer.
Karl Maier was a German Esperantist and a member of the Universala Esperanto Asocio. He learned Esperanto in 1924 and emigrated from Germany in 1930, living among Esperanto enthusiasts in the United States, Mexico, and Japan. Between 1935 and 1955, he resided in China. Upon returning to Germany, he successfully united several Esperantists, gaining over 300 subscribers for the Chinese magazine El Popola Ĉinio. He also promoted regular Esperanto conventions in East Berlin starting in 1960 and advocated for the legalization of the Esperanto language in the GDR. Karl Maier passed away on July 25, 2000.
"The Spirit of Democratic Capitalism" is a book written by philosopher Michael Novak in 1982. In the book, Novak explores the theological assumptions, values, and intentions of democratic capitalism. He defines democratic capitalism as a pluralistic social system that differs from traditional and socialist states. Novak identifies three power centers in society: the political sector, the economic sector, and the moral-cultural sector, emphasizing the interdependence of these sectors. He contrasts democratic capitalism with modern socialism, noting the shift from utopian ideals to criticisms of capitalism, particularly in Latin America's liberation theology movement. Novak concludes with a theological perspective on democratic capitalism influenced by Reinhold Niebuhr's realism. Irving Kristol praised the book as a significant work. The Spanish translation of the book inspired Chilean lawyer and politician Jaime Guzmán, who found it more compelling than Hayek's ideas.
The Antaifasy are an ethnic group of Madagascar residing in the southeast coastal region around Farafangana. Historically engaged in fishing and farming, many Antaifasy were forcibly conscripted into labor and taken as slaves to Antananarivo under the authority of the Kingdom of Imerina in the 19th century. Antaifasy society was traditionally divided into three groups, each governed by a king and adhering to strict traditional moral codes. As of 2013, approximately 150,000 Antaifasy people live in Madagascar.
Sir Edmund Royds was an English solicitor and Conservative Party politician. Sir Edmund Royds practiced law in London and held a country seat in Lincolnshire. He was returned to the House of Commons from 1910 to 1922 and held numerous local offices. Sir Edmund Royds was awarded the OBE and DL titles.
Mount Walshe is a bare rock peak, 2,050 m high, located on the north side of Bartlett Glacier where it meets Scott Glacier in the southern Hays Mountains, Queen Maud Mountains. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) based on surveys and U.S. Navy air photos from 1960 to 1964. The peak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Lieutenant Commander Edward C. Walshe, Jr., who served in the U.S. Navy and was stationed aboard the Arneb in Antarctica during the 1957-58 and 1958-59 seasons. He also served on the staff of the Commander, U.S. Naval Support Force, Antarctica, in 1966-67.
Masataka Yanagida is a racing driver. Masataka Yanagida was born on June 4, 1979, in Tokyo. Masataka Yanagida is from Japan.
Gianni Fabiano is an Italian footballer. Gianni Fabiano plays as a midfielder for Serie D club A.C. Mestre. Gianni Fabiano was born on July 9, 1984. A.C. Mestre is a football club in Serie D.
Roderick John Hart is a Scottish singer-songwriter, film composer, and broadcaster from Glasgow. He has released three solo records - "Bookmarks", "Sign Language", and "Road of Bones" - and one EP "The Dylan EP" with Irish artist Gemma Hayes. Hart now releases albums with his band The Lonesome Fire, the first of which was "Roddy Hart & The Lonesome Fire" produced by Patti Smith and Morrissey producer Danton Supple. The album was nominated for the Scottish Album of the Year Award in April 2014. Their second album, "Swithering", was co-produced by Paul Savage and released in late 2016. The band made their American network TV debut on "The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson" on 17 February 2014. Hart has toured and played with numerous artists including Wilco, Beth Orton, Ron Sexsmith, Dawes, The Low Anthem, LAU, Ray LaMontagne, Kris Kristofferson, Jeff Beck, Ray Davies, Jack Bruce, and others. He curates the "Roaming Roots Revue" for Celtic Connections each year and presents two weekly radio shows on BBC Radio Scotland: "The Roddy Hart Show" and "The Quay Sessions". He was Associate Musical Director on the Scottish film Sunshine on Leith and with Tommy Reilly wrote the music and lyrics for the film Anna and the Apocalypse. The duo arranged the music and wrote the score for “Our Ladies” (due for release in 2020 via Sony International) and are currently writing songs for Steven Spielberg’s revival of Animaniacs.
"Aldo Aureggi was an Italian fencer. Aldo Aureggi was born on October 6, 1931, and passed away on August 21, 2020. Aldo Aureggi won a silver medal in the team foil event at the 1960 Summer Olympics."
British Channel is a strait located in the western part of the Franz Josef Land archipelago in Arkhangelsk Oblast, Russia. It was first reported and named in 1875 by the Jackson–Harmsworth expedition. The British Channel separates the westernmost island group from the rest of the Franz Josef Land archipelago. To the north, the strait starts at the Queen Victoria Sea in a southwesterly direction. It separates Prince Georg Land to the west from the smaller Koetlitz Island and Hooker Island to the east. About two-thirds down Prince Georg Land, the channel is split in two where the Nightingale Sound continues down the coast of Prince Georg Land and the De Bruyne Sound diverts to the southeast.
Hannah Royle Taylor, also known as Annie Royle Taylor, was an English explorer and Evangelical missionary to China. She was the first Western woman known to have visited Tibet. In 1892-1893, she attempted to reach the "forbidden" city of Lhasa. Hannah Royle Taylor was born on October 7, 1855, and passed away on September 9, 1922.
Assyriella is a genus of air-breathing landsnails. Assyriella belongs to the family Helicidae. Assyriella is a terrestrial pulmonate gastropod mollusk. Assyriella is classified as a typical snail.
"Old Hippie" is a song written by David Bellamy and recorded by the American country music duo The Bellamy Brothers. It was released in April 1985 as the first single from their album "Howard & David". The song reached No. 2 on the "Billboard" Hot Country Singles chart in July 1985 and No. 1 on the "RPM" Country Tracks chart in Canada. In June 2014, "Rolling Stone" magazine ranked "Old Hippie" 95th in their list of the 100 greatest country songs.
The 2010 Japan Series was the Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB) championship series for the 2010 season. It was the 61st Japan Series and featured the Pacific League champions, the Chiba Lotte Marines, against the Central League champions, the Chunichi Dragons.
"Waugh Peak is a rock peak standing at 2,430 m, located southeast of Breyer Mesa on the west side of Amundsen Glacier in the Queen Maud Mountains. Waugh Peak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) after Douglas Waugh, who was the Chief Cartographer with the Geological Society of America from 1963. Douglas Waugh made significant contributions to the Society's Antarctic mapping program."
"Waverly Glacier is a glacier located on the south flank of Mount Tricorn in Palmer Land. This glacier flows into Wright Inlet on the east coast. Waverly Glacier was first photographed from the air by the United States Antarctic Service (USAS) in December 1940 and later by the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition (RARE) led by Ronne in 1947. The glacier was named by Ronne after Waverly, a city in New York City known for Kasco Mills. Officers of Kasco Mills, Mr. Marc Ivy and Mr. Edwin Knapp, generously contributed twenty tons of dog food to Ronne's expedition."
"Wegger Peak is a peak, 305 m high, located at the west side of the entrance to Mackellar Inlet, Admiralty Bay, on King George Island in the South Shetland Islands. The name "Le Poing" (The Fist) was given to an elevation in this area by the French Antarctic Expedition led by Charcot in 1908–10. In 1958, the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) members suggested that the name referred to all four nearby summits, resembling the knuckles of a clenched fist when viewed from the Chabrier Rock area. However, the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) deemed the collective name unsuitable and rejected it. New names were recommended by the UK-APC in 1960 for Wegger Peak and nearby Admiralen Peak. Wegger Peak is named after Ole Wegger (1859–1936), who was the director for 47 years of Framnaes Mekaniske Vaeksted, a shipbuilding company in Norway that fitted the Admiralen with a slipway for whaling."
"Welcome Nunatak is a nunatak located in the Founders Peaks, Heritage Range. Welcome Nunatak was named by the University of Minnesota Geological Party in 1963–64. The University of Minnesota Geological Party used motor toboggans during their expedition. The nunatak served as a landmark for the party, indicating they were close to their base camp at Camp Hills."
Cape Well-met is a dark headland located near the center of the north side of Vega Island, close to Trinity Peninsula. It was discovered and named by the Swedish Antarctic Expedition, 1901–04. Cape Well-met commemorates the reunion of a relief party led by Dr. J. Gunnar Andersson and the winter party led by Dr. Otto Nordenskjold after twenty months of enforced separation.
"The Nokia 1680 classic is a Nokia dual-band GSM mobile phone. It features a VGA camera, speakerphone, multimedia playback, MMS messaging, web browser, and e-mail client. The battery talk time is up to 7 hours and 40 minutes, with a standby time of 424 hours. The ringtones are Polyphonic 24 channels. Internally, it is identical to the Nokia 2630, sharing the same specifications such as the camera, operating system, and GUI, as well as pre-installed ringtones, themes, and wallpapers."
"Södermanland Runic Inscription 367 or Sö 367 is a Viking Age memorial runestone located in Släbro, Sweden. The inscription describes two men as thegns and owners of Sleðabrú, which is modern-day Släbro. Släbro is one kilometer north of Nyköping in Södermanland County, which was part of the historic province of Södermanland. The inscription also features a facial mask."
Stallergenes Greer Ltd is a biopharmaceutical company headquartered in London. Stallergenes Greer Ltd specializes in the diagnosis and treatment of respiratory allergies through immunotherapy. Stallergenes Greer Ltd is the parent company of GREER Laboratories, Inc. and Stallergenes S.A.S. Stallergenes Greer Ltd has 1139 employees as of 2019 and operates in 19 countries. The core manufacturing facilities of Stallergenes Greer Ltd are located in Europe (Antony and Amilly in France) and in the USA (Lenoir, North Carolina and San Diego, California).
Herman Bank was an American mechanical engineer. Herman Bank worked at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) from 1947 to 1984. Herman Bank was part of the "Rocket Boys" group, who were first-generation scientists and engineers of the Space Age. During his time at JPL, Bank worked on the Bumper Project, supervised the structural design for Explorer 1, and served as a supervisor on the Ranger and Surveyor missions to the Moon. In his retirement, Bank founded the Volunteer Professionals for Medical Advancement, a group of JPL and Caltech retirees focused on developing new medical technologies.
"Wensleydale Beacon is a hill situated just north of Fumarole Bay, on the west side of Port Foster, Deception Island, in the South Shetland Islands. The hill was named by Lieutenant Commander D.N. Penfold, Royal Navy, after Wensleydale in Yorkshire, England. It was charted by a British expedition 1828–31, under Foster."
Kosmas Thesprotos was a Greek scholar, priest, and theologian. Kosmas Thesprotos is also known as "Kosmas the Thesprotian". Kosmas Thesprotos lived from 1780 to 1852.
Johannes Matzen is a German former footballer. Johannes Matzen was born on February 13, 1925. Johannes Matzen scored 76 goals in the East German top-flight in 209 matches. Matzen was part of the East German team in their first-ever international match in September 1952 against Poland. Johannes Matzen won another cap in 1954.
"WeRelate.org is a wiki genealogy website. WeRelate.org provides genealogy tools and data. WeRelate.org bills itself as the world's largest freely licensed genealogy wiki with almost 5 million wiki pages. WeRelate.org's information is free, and the site is non-commercial and nonsectarian. WeRelate.org had over 2.5 million person pages, over 930,000 family pages, and 44,000 images in January 2014. WeRelate.org is supported by the Foundation for On-Line Genealogy and the Allen County Public Library in Fort Wayne, Indiana. WeRelate.org runs on the MediaWiki software."
The Guča Gora Monastery is a Roman Catholic Franciscan monastery located in the small village of Guča Gora, east of Travnik in Bosnia and Herzegovina. In the mid-19th century, Bosnian Franciscans decided to build the monastery in the area of Travnik. On May 30, 1859, the General Minister of the Franciscan Order issued a decree establishing the Guča Gora Monastery. Unfortunately, the monastery was damaged and vandalized by mujahideen fighters in June 1993.
"31 Nights of Halloween is a seasonal programming block on Freeform. It started in 1998 when the Family Channel became Fox Family and continued through the channel's transition to ABC Family and later Freeform. The block was originally known as 13 Days of Halloween and 13 Nights of Halloween. It was created in response to the success of the channel's 25 Days of Christmas, which began two years earlier. The special block aired from October 19 to Halloween night, covering the thirteen days leading up to the holiday. Since 2018, the program has been extended to air throughout the entire month of October."
Salvador Ferrando is a Mexican painter from Tlacotalpan. Salvador Ferrando specialized in portraits and landscapes, particularly of the Papaloapan and Tlacotalpan regions. There is a museum named after Salvador Ferrando in his hometown, which houses many of his works. Humberto Aguirre Tinoco, an architect, rescued many of Ferrando's works. Some of these works can be viewed at the Museo de Arte de Veracruz in Orizaba.
"Dov Levin was an Israeli jurist and served as a Supreme Court justice from 1982 to 1995. Dov Levin was born on December 1, 1925 and passed away on either June 27 or 28, 2001."
"To the Aid of Falx" is an adventure module published in 1982 for the "Advanced Dungeons & Dragons" fantasy role-playing game.
Tori Gurley is a gridiron football player. Tori Gurley was born on November 22, 1987. Tori Gurley is currently a free agent. Tori Gurley was most recently a member of the Ottawa Redblacks organization in the Canadian Football League (CFL). Tori Gurley played college football at South Carolina. Tori Gurley helped lead the Gamecocks to their first SEC East title and first SEC championship game appearance in 2010. Tori Gurley is from Rock Hill, South Carolina. Tori Gurley attended Rock Hill High School where he led the Bearcats to state championships in football and basketball as a senior. Through 2010 and 12 games, Tori Gurley's career statistics at South Carolina were 824 receiving yards with 6 touchdowns and 70 receptions. In Tori Gurley's last season for the Gamecocks, he set a school record for having no dropped passes during the 2010 season.
The Lulua Mosque, also known as the Pearl, is a mosque in Cairo, Egypt, built in 1015–16 AD. It is also referred to by various other names such as al-Lu'lu'a Mosque, Majid aasl-Luʼluʼah, Mosque of al-Lu'lu'a, Mosque of al-Lulua, Luluah Mosque, and Qabr Lu'lu'a Bint al-Muqauqis. The mosque was constructed during the reign of the third Fatimid caliph, al-Hakim, in the Fatimid architectural style. In 1919, the mosque partially collapsed but was later refurbished in 1998 by the Dawoodi Bohras, who have a religious lineage tracing back to the Fatimid Caliphate. It is situated in the southern cemetery in the Moqattam hills.
"Tapureli ruins are located in Mersin Province, Turkey."
Parož is a dispersed settlement located in the upper valley of Dobrnica Creek, a minor right tributary of the Hudinja River, in Slovenia. Parož belongs to the Municipality of Dobrna. The area is part of the traditional region of Styria. The Municipality of Dobrna is now included in the Savinja Statistical Region.
"The Elixir of Life is an adventure module published in 1983 for the fantasy role-playing game Advanced Dungeons & Dragons."
"Caloptilia coroniella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Caloptilia coroniella is found in Canada (Québec and Nova Scotia) and the United States (Maryland, Pennsylvania, Maine, Michigan, Connecticut, Vermont, and Illinois). The larvae of Caloptilia coroniella feed on various "Betula" species, such as "Betula nana", "Betula papyrifera", "Betula populifolia", and "Betula pubescens". They create mines on the leaves of their host plant."
Peak School is a coeducational preparatory school located on Plunkett's Road on Victoria Peak, Hong Kong Island, Hong Kong. The school is one of around twenty institutions in Hong Kong operated by the English Schools Foundation (ESF). Peak School opened in 1911 on the site of what is now the Victoria Peak Fire Station. In 1954, the school moved to its current premises located on Plunkett's Road. Peak School teaches students from Year One to Year Six and offers the International Baccalaureate programme. The principal of Peak School is Bill Garnett.
Caloptilia selenitis is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from New Zealand. The larvae of Caloptilia selenitis feed on "Fagus" species, including "Fagus menziesii". They mine the leaves of their host plant. The late instar larva of Caloptilia selenitis makes a pouch of two or three terminal leaves on twigs. These pouches containing larvae are shed and fall to the ground in autumn while the larvae are still present.
"Caloptilia onustella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Caloptilia onustella is found in Europe, Russia, Ukraine, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, Morocco, and Turkey. The larvae of Caloptilia onustella feed on various "Acer" species such as Acer campestre, Acer monspessulanum, Acer platanoides, and Acer pseudoplatanus. They create mines on the leaves of their host plant."
"Caloptilia quercinigrella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Caloptilia quercinigrella is known to be present in Connecticut, Illinois, Florida, Georgia, Maine, Maryland, Michigan, and Texas in the United States. The wingspan of Caloptilia quercinigrella is about 14 mm. The larvae of Caloptilia quercinigrella feed on "Quercus" species, including "Quercus nigra". They mine the leaves of their host plant by chewing a series of small holes through the leaf, both alongside the basal edge of the cone and on the adjacent area of the cone itself."
"Murder with Music is a 1941 American film directed by George P. Quigley. The film was originally released as Mistaken Identity."
"Alessandro Riguccini is an Italian boxer, kickboxer, and engineer. Alessandro Riguccini was born on March 25, 1988, in Florence, Italy. Alessandro Riguccini is managed by entrepreneur Marco Piccini and coached by Mexican trainer Fernando Fernandez. Alessandro Riguccini has an undefeated record in professional boxing with 25 wins and 21 knockouts. Alessandro Riguccini has won several titles in boxing and kickboxing, including the WBC world silver welterweight title, the world lightweight title in the World Boxing Federation, the international lightweight title in the IBF, the FECARBOX super featherweight title in the WBC, the Wako Pro middleweight full contact world champion, the Kombat League super welterweight kickboxing world champion, the Wako Pro lightweight kickboxing world champion, the unified WKA and IKTA super lightweight K1 world titles. On July 11, 2019, Riguccini obtained a master's degree with a score of 110 in computer engineering."
"Stephen Island is an ice-covered island located at the west side of Nickerson Ice Shelf, off the coast of Marie Byrd Land. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) and U.S. Navy air photos from 1959 to 1965. The island was named after Alexander Stephen, a Scottish shipbuilder known for his firm, Alexander Stephen and Sons, which built ships for expeditions to the Antarctic, including the Sir Ernest Shackleton and Admiral Richard Byrd."
"Steinemann Island is an island located off the northeast coast of Adelaide Island, approximately 10 nautical miles southwest of Mount Velain. The island was mapped from air photos taken by the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition (RARE) (1947–48) and the Falkland Islands and Dependencies Aerial Survey Expedition (FIDASE) (1956–57). It was named by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in honor of Samuel Steinemann, a Swiss physicist known for his laboratory investigations on the flow of single and polycrystalline ice."
Steel Peak is a high peak located 1.5 nautical miles north of Mount Nordhill in the east ridge of the Welch Mountains in Palmer Land. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) in 1974 and named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Captain Henry E. Steel. Captain Steel served as the Commanding Officer of USCGC Edisto during Operation Deep Freeze in 1969 and 1970, and as the Commander of the Antarctic Peninsula Ship Group in 1969.
Chrysocercops vaticae is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia. The wingspan of Chrysocercops vaticae ranges from 5.7 to 6.5 mm. The larvae of this moth feed on "Vatica bella", mining the leaves of their host plant. The mine initially appears as a linear gallery on the upper surface of the leaves, which then broadens into a blotch along the margin. In its mature state, the blotchy part contracts upward to form a narrow fold. The cocoon of Chrysocercops vaticae is boat-shaped, ochre-whitish in color, and typically has four minute bubbles on its surface.
Chrysocercops hopeella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Malaysia, specifically Pahang and Selangor. The wingspan of Chrysocercops hopeella ranges from 4.5 to 5.1 mm. The larvae of this moth feed on "Hopea nutans" and "Hopea odorata" by mining the leaves of their host plant. The mine created by Chrysocercops hopeella is similar to that of "Chrysocercops melastigmata".
Standring Inlet is an inlet located on the north coast of Jason Peninsula, Graham Land. It is 9 nautical miles long and is filled with ice shelf. The Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) surveyed it in 1953. It was named in 1956 by the FIDS in honor of Anthony J. Standring, a geologist at Hope Bay in 1953 and 1954, who visited Jason Peninsula with the survey party.
Stålstuten Ridge is a high ridge extending from the northeast side of Mount Hochlin, in the Muhlig-Hofmann Mountains of Queen Maud Land. Stålstuten Ridge was mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition (1956–60). Stålstuten Ridge was named Stålstuten, which means "the bulldozer".
Stahl Peak is a peak located 2 nautical miles east of Saburro Peak in the Ravens Mountains, Britannia Range, Antarctica. It rises to over 1800 meters. Stahl Peak is named after CMSgt. Alfred E. Stahl, who served with the 109th Airlift Wing as a Flight Engineer Superintendent during the transition of LC-130 operations from the U.S. Navy to the Air National Guard.
"Staack Nunatak is a nunatak located west of Horner Nunatak in Palmer Land. It is one of several scattered and isolated nunataks situated north of the Merrick Mountains, approximately 40 nautical miles away. The United States Geological Survey (USGS) mapped Staack Nunatak based on surveys and U.S. Navy air photos taken between 1961 and 1967. The Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) named the nunatak after Karl J. Staack, a meteorologist who worked at Byrd Station during the summer of 1965-66."
"Sennet Glacier is a glacier located in the Britannia Range. It is situated between Yancey Glacier and Merrick Glacier, flowing southward from Mount Aldrich to the Byrd Glacier. The glacier was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in association with Byrd Glacier. The name Sennet Glacier is in honor of , a submarine from the Central Group of Task Force 68 of the U.S. Navy Operation Highjump, which took place in 1946–1947 and was led by Admiral Byrd."
"Naukšēni is a village located in Naukšēni municipality, Latvia. Naukšēni is also the center of Naukšēni parish."
"Gandhi Vega is a Mexican football defender. Gandhi Vega was born on April 29, 1977 in Torreón, Mexico. Gandhi Vega last played for Irapuato FC."
Ferenc András is a Hungarian film director and screenwriter. Ferenc András was born on November 24, 1942. Ferenc András has directed 20 films since 1970. Ferenc András' film "Dögkeselyű" was entered into the 33rd Berlin International Film Festival.
The Ruban Jaune is a cycling title created in 1936 by Henri Desgrange. The award is given to the rider with the fastest average speed in a professional cycling race or stage longer than 200 km. The name is believed to have originated from the Blue Riband accolade given to the fastest passenger liner crossing the Atlantic Ocean. Desgrange changed the color to yellow to match the newsprint of L'Auto, the sports newspaper he edited. The current holder of the Ruban Jaune is Philippe Gilbert.
Sefton Glacier is a glacier about 10 nautical miles long, flowing into the south side of Byrd Glacier just west of Rundle Peaks. Sefton Glacier was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Ronald Sefton, an ionospheric physicist who was a member of the Byrd Station winter parties in 1962 and 1964.
Seely Ridge is a ridge in the Pensacola Mountains. It is 10 km long and rises to 1,240 m at the south end. Seely Ridge trends northeast from West Prongs to join Heiser Ridge in the Neptune Range. The ridge was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in 1995 after Benjamin W. Seely. Benjamin W. Seely invented the inflatable life raft in 1915 at Pensacola Naval Air Station.
Single Island is a high ice-covered island located on the west side of the Amery Ice Shelf, approximately south of Landon Promontory. It was first plotted by ANARE (Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions) based on air photos taken in 1956, initially incorrectly identified as a promontory but later corrected to be an island. The island was named by the Antarctic Names Committee of Australia (ANCA) in honor of M. Single, a senior diesel mechanic at Mawson Station in 1962, who was part of the ANARE field party that visited the area in December 1962. Tingey Rocks, two small rock features southwest of Single Island, were also discovered by ANARE and named by ANCA after R.J. Tingey, a geologist who was part of the party.
"Siren Rock is a rock located 12 nautical miles east of Mount Moses in the Hudson Mountains. Siren Rock was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) based on surveys and U.S. Navy air photos from 1960 to 1966. The rock was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Jan C. Siren, a radio scientist at Byrd Station in 1967."
Mount Skeidskneet is a mountain located at 2,600 m above sea level. It is situated on the east side of the head of Humboldt Graben at the southwest extremity of the Petermann Ranges, Wohlthat Mountains, in Queen Maud Land. Mount Skeidskneet was discovered and photographed by the German Antarctic Expedition in 1938–39. It was mapped by Norway based on air photos and surveys conducted by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition from 1956–60, and it was named Skeidskneet.
Skinner Saddle is a high, broad, snow-covered saddle between the northern part of Darley Hills and that portion of Churchill Mountains eastward of Mount Durnford. Skinner Saddle was mapped by the Northern Party of New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (NZGSAE) in 1960-61. Skinner Saddle was named after D.N. Skinner, a geologist with the party.
Skorvetangen Spur is a rock spur located 2 nautical miles southeast of Hamarskorvene Bluff in the Muhlig-Hofmann Mountains, Queen Maud Land. Skorvetangen Spur was mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition (1956–60).
"Sledgers Icefall is an icefall located midway up the Sledgers Glacier in the Bowers Mountains. Sledgers Icefall is heavily crevassed and situated just north of the tip of Reilly Ridge. The name was given by the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (NZGSAE) in 1967–68. The location of Sledgers Icefall is considered significant in relation to the use of sledges."
"Promised Day is Come is a book-length letter written by Shoghi Effendi, the head of the Baháʼí Faith in the first half of the 20th century. The letter was dated March 1941 and was intended for the Baháʼís of the West. In the letter, Shoghi Effendi discusses the coming of The Most Great Peace and the rejection of letters to the rulers of the world by Baháʼu'lláh."
The Great Famine of 1695–97, also known as the Great Famine, was a devastating famine that impacted present-day Estonia, Finland, Latvia, Norway, and Sweden. During that time, these regions were part of the Swedish Empire, except for Norway. The most severely affected areas were the Swedish province of Finland and Norrland in Sweden. This famine coincided with the "seven ill years," a period of widespread famine in Scotland during the 1690s.
The 1985 French Figure Skating Championships took place in Belfort for singles and pairs and in Angers for ice dance. Skaters competed in the disciplines of men's singles, women's singles, pair skating, and ice dancing on the senior level. The event was used to help determine the French team for the 1986 World Championships and the 1986 European Championships.
Gilson Gomes do Nascimento, also known as Gilson, is a Brazilian footballer. He was born on May 15, 1986, in Campo Grande. Gilson plays as a left back for Botafogo-SP.
"Nikon Salon" is the name given to exhibition spaces and activities run by Nikon in Japan. The first salon, Ginza Nikon Salon, opened in January 1968 in Ginza, Tokyo, to celebrate the 50th anniversary of Nippon Kōgaku (later renamed Nikon). This was followed by the Shinjuku Nikon Salon in Shinjuku, Tokyo, and the Osaka Nikon Salon in Umeda, Osaka. The Nikon Salon also hosts a biannual international photography contest, offers free portfolio reviews, and presents awards for the best exhibitions at the salons: the Ina Nobuo Award, the Miki Jun Award, and two Miki Jun Inspiration Awards every December. All activities at the Nikon Salon are open to photographers regardless of the camera gear they use.
"Teen Ta Tseang Keun, meaning "Heaven's Great General", was a Chinese constellation located in the region of "Lóu". It was situated between Andromeda and Triangulum. Allen identified Chinese star names based on the work of Williams and Reeves. However, Allen's identification lacked the last word "kuen" and he also transliterated it as "Tsien Ta Tseang"."
"Law Glacier is a glacier located between the south end of the Queen Elizabeth Range and the MacAlpine Hills. It gradually descends east-northeast from the Antarctic polar plateau to Bowden Névé. The glacier was named by the New Zealand party of the Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition (1956–58) in honor of B.R. Law, who was the Deputy-Chairman of the Ross Sea Committee."
Thioredoxin domain-containing protein 3 (TXNDC3), also known as spermatid-specific thioredoxin-2 (Sptrx-2), is a protein found in humans. It is encoded by the NME8 gene, also known as the "TXNDC3" gene, located on chromosome 7.
"Matemwe is a village located on the north-eastern coast of Unguja, the main island of the Zanzibar Archipelago. The economy of Matemwe is primarily based on seaweed farming and fishing. The village is home to various projects such as an education initiative focused on providing computer literacy to the local population and the Dada cooperative, which aims to create job opportunities for Zanzibari women through the production of handmade cosmetics and food products. Additionally, there is a charity school in Matemwe called Tamani Foundation, offering education to local students including nursery school and adult education programs in English, Math, and Computer skills.One of the main attractions of Matemwe is its beach, known as the longest beach in Zanzibar. The beach experiences tides, so visitors are advised to check tide schedules before planning a visit. However, for those staying in Matemwe, the tide is high twice every 24 hours. The beach is peaceful and not crowded with beach boys. Internationally, Matemwe is famous for its pristine white sand beaches and limited tourist infrastructure, making it an exclusive vacation spot. The village is bordered by a lagoon, coral reef, and the Mnemba atoll, a popular spot for snorkeling and scuba diving where various fish species can be observed such as giant trevallies, trumpetfishes, anthiases, groupers, and snappers."
"Sparkle in Her Eyes" is a single by Canadian country music artist Terry Carisse. The single was released in 1979 and was the first from his album "Story of the Year". The song achieved the number one spot on the "RPM" Country Tracks chart in Canada in February 1980. Terry Carisse is a Canadian country music artist. The album "Story of the Year" was released in 1979. The "RPM" Country Tracks chart topper in Canada was in February 1980.
Jacek Gabrusewicz is a Polish footballer. Jacek Gabrusewicz was born on February 10, 1982. Jacek Gabrusewicz currently plays for OKS 1945 Olsztyn. OKS 1945 Olsztyn is a football club.
"Andrzej Stretowicz is a Polish footballer. Andrzej Stretowicz was born on February 23, 1976. Andrzej Stretowicz played in the Ekstraklasa for Stomil Olsztyn."
"Poland Comes First, also known as PJN, was a centre-right, conservative liberal political party in Poland. It was formed as a breakaway group from Law and Justice (PiS). By early 2011, the party had members in the Sejm, Senate, and European Parliament. Poland Comes First ceased to exist in December 2013 when it merged with a new party led by Jarosław Gowin called Poland Together. The party was founded as a moderate, liberal splinter from Law and Justice, criticizing their shift to the right. More pro-free market than PiS, Poland Comes First also criticized the slow pace of economic reforms by the Civic Platform government. In the European Parliament, its members sat in the European Conservatives and Reformists group. The party was affiliated with the Alliance of European Conservatives and Reformists."
Mount Lanning is a mountain located in the northern portion of the Sentinel Range, Ellsworth Mountains, Antarctica. It is situated at the south side of Newcomer Glacier, southeast of Mount Warren. Mount Lanning forms the north extremity of Sostra Heights and overlooks Sabazios Glacier to the southwest and Anchialus Glacier to the southeast. The mountain was first mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy from surveys and air photos taken from 1957–59. It was named after 1st Lieutenant Delmar L. Lanning of the United States Air Force, who was involved in establishing South Pole Station during the 1956–57 season.
"Lanz Peak is a peak located near the extreme northern end of the Sentinel Range in the Ellsworth Mountains of Antarctica. It was discovered by Lincoln Ellsworth on November 23, 1935, during his trans-Antarctic flight. The peak was named after Walter J. Lanz, a radio operator who participated in three Ellsworth Antarctic expeditions between 1933 and 1936."
"Larson Glacier is a tributary glacier located in Antarctica. It drains northwest from La Gorce Peak in the Alexandra Mountains and enters the south side of Butler Glacier on Edward VII Peninsula. The glacier was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy from surveys and air photos taken between 1959 and 1965. It was named after helicopter pilot Lieutenant Commander Conrad S. Larson, U.S. Navy, who was the officer in charge of the helicopter detachment aboard the icebreaker during Operation Deep Freeze in 1955-56."
"Rosser Ridge is a rock ridge located in the Pensacola Mountains. It is 4 nautical miles (7 km) long and marks the north limit of the Cordiner Peaks. The ridge was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos taken between 1956 and 1966. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Earl W. Rosser, a topographic engineer who worked in the Pensacola Mountains from 1965 to 1966."
Mount Ruegg is the culminating peak with an elevation of 1,870 m. It is located on the divide between DeAngelo Glacier and Moubray Glacier in the Admiralty Mountains, Victoria Land. Mount Ruegg was named by the New Zealand Antarctic Place-Names Committee (NZ-APC) in honor of Captain H. Ruegg, who served as a nautical advisor to the Marine Department of New Zealand. Captain H. Ruegg visited the Ross Sea area in 1956.
Mount Leek is a mountain located west of Spear Glacier in the northeast part of the Hauberg Mountains, in Palmer Land, Antarctica. It was first observed from the air by the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition, 1947–48, and was mapped by the United States Geological Survey from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1961–67. Mount Leek was named after Gouke M. Leek, a glaciologist at Byrd Station during the summer of 1965–66.
Leibert Cirque is a cirque located between Mount Electra and Mount Dido on the south side of the Olympus Range in the McMurdo Dry Valleys of Antarctica. The cirque opens south to the Labyrinth. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in 2004 after Gregg Leibert, a PHI helicopter pilot who worked with the United States Antarctic Program for seven consecutive field seasons starting from 1996-97 onwards.
Leslie Peak is a rock outcrop with a conical peak at its south end, located about south of Mount Cook in the Leckie Range, Antarctica. It was identified from Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions air photos and was named by the Antarctic Names Committee of Australia after Leslie Miller. Leslie Miller was a radio officer at Mawson Station in 1964 and a member of one of the survey parties that conducted a tellurometer traverse passing through the Leckie Range in 1965.
Mount Levick is a prominent mountain located in the Deep Freeze Range of Victoria Land, Antarctica. It stands at the northwest side of Tourmaline Plateau. Mount Levick was first charted by the Northern Party of the British Antarctic Expedition, 1910–13. It was named after George Murray Levick, who was a surgeon with the expedition and a member of the Northern Party.
"Lientur Channel is a channel between Lemaire Island and Bryde Island connecting Paradise Harbor with Gerlache Strait, off the west coast of Graham Land, Antarctica. Lientur Channel was first roughly charted by the Belgian Antarctic Expedition, 1897–99. The channel was named by the fourth Chilean Antarctic Expedition (1949–50) after the "Lientur", one of the ships used during this expedition."
"Lind Ridge is a ridge located in the Ames Range of Marie Byrd Land, Antarctica. Lind Ridge forms the south wall of Coleman Glacier. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy from surveys and air photos taken between 1959 and 1965. The ridge was named in honor of Larry W. Lind, a glaciologist who worked at Byrd Station during 1968-1969. The naming was done by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names."
"Lind Glacier is a glacier located in Graham Land, Antarctica. Lind Glacier flows west from Alencar Peak into the southern part of Collins Bay on the west coast of Kiev Peninsula. The glacier was first charted by the Fourth French Antarctic Expedition led by Jean-Baptiste Charcot from 1908 to 1910. It was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1959 in honor of James Lind, a Scottish pioneer in naval hygiene. James Lind is known as the "founder of modern naval hygiene" and was the first to publish a convincing account of experimental work establishing the dietary cause and cure of scurvy in 1755."
Marielli Sfakianaki-Manolidou is a Greek writer, singer, and composer. Marielli Sfakianaki-Manolidou was born on January 12, 1945.
"Nékmaria is a town and commune in Mostaganem Province, Algeria. Nékmaria is located in Achacha District. According to the 1998 census, Nékmaria has a population of 9,104."
"Katherine Richardson may refer to: Catherine Richardson, an American author and counselor. Cathy Richardson, an American singer-songwriter. Katharine Richardson, a British mountain climber. Katherine Richardson Christensen, an American-Danish oceanographer. Kathy Kreag Richardson, an American Republican politician. Katie Richardson, an Australian beauty pageant winner."
"Schloss Salzdahlum was a former summer palace built by Anthony Ulrich, Duke of Brunswick-Wolfenbüttel in 1684. It was dismantled in 1813 but parts of it can still be seen in the town of Salzdahlum. Located between Braunschweig and Wolfenbüttel, the palace was the location where Frederick II of Prussia married Elisabeth Christine of Brunswick-Wolfenbüttel, Queen of Prussia in 1733. The large art collection that used to be kept there is largely intact and can be viewed locally at the Herzog Anton Ulrich Museum."
"Moussa Germain Sanou is a professional footballer. Moussa Germain Sanou is a goalkeeper. Moussa Germain Sanou was born on May 26, 1992. Moussa Germain Sanou is from Burkina Faso. Moussa Germain Sanou plays for the Championnat National 2 club Paris 13 Atletico."
The Lowland and Border Pipers' Society was formed in the early 1980s. The society aims to promote the study and playing of cauld-wind (bellows-blown) bagpipes from Northern England and south-east Scotland, including the Scottish smallpipes, pastoral pipes, and border pipes. The organization hosts events and competitions, provides instructional materials, and publishes a journal called "Common Stock." The title of the journal refers to the arrangement of drones on Lowland bagpipes, which are grouped together in a "common stock" rather than being separately attached to the bag like on the Great Highland bagpipe. The society has been instrumental in the revival of bellows bagpipe traditions in Scotland.
"Warramboo Land District is a land district in Western Australia. It is located within the North-West Land Division. The district includes the town of Mount Magnet and the former towns of Boogardie, Lennonville, and Paynesville."
Andritany Ardhiyasa is an Indonesian professional footballer. Andritany Ardhiyasa was born on December 26, 1991. Andritany Ardhiyasa plays as a goalkeeper and captain for both Liga 1 club Persija Jakarta and the Indonesia national team. Andritany Ardhiyasa's older brother, Indra Kahfi, is also a football player and plays for Bhayangkara FC. Persija Jakarta is a Liga 1 club. Bhayangkara FC is a football club. Indra Kahfi is a football player. The Indonesia national team is a national sports team.
"Nookawarra Land District is a land district in Western Australia. Nookawarra Land District is situated within the North-West Land Division."
Mount Mair is a mountain rising to 780 m between Brandt Cove and Larsen Harbor, Drygalski Fjord, South Georgia. Mount Mair was named by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) after Bruce F. Mair, a British Antarctic Survey (BAS) geologist. Bruce F. Mair conducted extensive geological mapping in the area during the 1974-75 and 1976-77 field seasons.
"Sufficient unto the day is the evil thereof" is an aphorism. It appears in the Sermon on the Mount in the Gospel of Matthew chapter 6 — Matthew 6:34. The aphorism implies that we should not worry about the future, as each day already contains enough burdens and suffering. In Hebrew, the same sentiment is expressed in the Rabbinic Jewish saying "dyya l'tzara b'shaata" (דיה לצרה בשעתה), meaning "the suffering of the (present) hour is enough for it". The original Koine Greek text reads ἀρκετὸν τῇ ἡμέρᾳ ἡ κακία αὐτῆς ("arketon tē hēmera hē kakia autes"). Alternative translations include: "Each day has enough trouble of its own." (New American Standard Bible) and "There is no need to add to the troubles each day brings" (Today's English Version). This sentiment is also similar to the Epicurean advice of writers such as Anacreon and Horace — "quid sit futurum cras, fuge quaerere" (avoid asking what the future will bring). However, some interpretations of Jesus's sermon suggest that God knows everyone's needs.
The Department of Employment, Economic Development and Innovation (DEEDI) was a Queensland Government department focused on employment, economic development, and innovation in Queensland. It was established on March 26, 2009, and was later divided into multiple agencies after a change of Government on March 24, 2012. The functions of the former department are now managed by various departments including the Department of State Development, Infrastructure and Planning, Queensland Treasury and Trade, Department of Education, Training and Employment, Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry, Department of Natural Resources and Mines, Department of Energy and Water Supply, Department of Science, Information Technology, Innovation and the Arts, Department of National Parks, Recreation, Sport and Racing, Department of Tourism, Major Events, Small Business and the Commonwealth Games. The Department of Employment, Economic Development and Innovation included units such as Business Development, Employment and Indigenous Initiatives, Industry Development, Invest Queensland, Mines and Energy, Office of Clean Energy, Primary Industries and Fisheries, Queensland's Energy Futures, Office of Racing, Rural and Regional Communities, Science and Innovation, Tourism Queensland, Trade Queensland, and Skilled and Business Migration.
Kyarra Land District is a land district in Western Australia. Kyarra Land District is situated within the North-West Land Division. The towns within Kyarra Land District include Cue, Meekatharra, Nannine, and Austin.
Johan Georg Frederik Ræder was a Danish civil servant and writer. He was born in Copenhagen. He was the son of Colonel Jacob Thode Ræder and had siblings named Carl Gustav Valdemar Ræder and Oscar Alexander Ræder. In 1869, he had a son named Hans Henning Ræder. Johan Georg Frederik Ræder enrolled as a law student in 1853 and graduated in 1860. He worked in various positions in the Ministry of the Duchy of Schleswig and the Magistrate of Copenhagen. He authored the historical work "Danmark under Svend Estridsen og hans Sønner" in 1871 and the judicial handbook "Forsørgelse af trængende efter dansk Ret" in 1892. Johan Georg Frederik Ræder passed away in 1909.
"Ajaikapada Bhairava Temple is dedicated to Ekapada Bhairava, an aspect of Shiva, located in Jagatsinghpur district of Odisha, India."
Andrea Spyropoulos is a British nurse, clinical strategist, and a past president of the Royal College of Nursing (RCN). Andrea Spyropoulos holds the titles RGN, SCM, and RNT.
The Santa Maria Mountains are a 16-mi (26 km) long mountain range in central-northwest Arizona, specifically in northwest Yavapai County. The range is situated in a region known for its mesas and mountain ranges in the northwest of Arizona's transition zone. The Santa Maria Mountains are located east of the transition zone's northwest perimeter, alongside the parallel Aquarius and Mohon Mountains. Tucker, Arizona, a townsite, is positioned 8 mi east and is situated just west of Chino Valley, AZ. Tucker is centrally located in the small Williamson Valley.
The 2011 CONCACAF Champions League Final was the final of the 2010–11 CONCACAF Champions League. The match was contested in a two-leg aggregate format between April 20–27, 2011. The winners earned the right to represent CONCACAF at the 2011 FIFA Club World Cup, entering at the quarterfinal stage.
"The Latin Grammy Award for Best Cumbia/Vallenato Album is presented annually at the Latin Grammy Awards. The award recognizes excellence in Latin recording artists and cultural diversity. It is given to solo artists, duos, or groups with albums containing at least 51% new recordings. The award has only been won by artists from Colombia. The first recipient was Los Hermanos Zuleta for "Cien Días De Bohemia" in 2006. Peter Manjarrés and Emiliano Zuleta have each won two awards in this category. Binomio de Oro de América has the most nominations without a win, with four."
Robert Corfou is a French football manager and former player. Robert Corfou was born on December 2, 1942. Robert Corfou has managed the Republic of the Congo national team. Robert Corfou has also worked with the Cameroon and Ivory Coast national football teams. Robert Corfou played for Entente Bagneaux Fontainebleau Nemours. Robert Corfou has served as a regional Technical director for the French national football team.
Michael Noyk was a solicitor and Irish republican politician. He was born in Telšiai, Lithuania, to a Jewish couple, Isaac Noyk and Esther Chana Raivid. Noyk was educated at The High School, Dublin, and Trinity College Dublin. He worked as a solicitor and was a close associate of Arthur Griffith, supporting the cause of Irish republicanism. Noyk joined Sinn Féin after the Easter Rising and defended several Irish Republican Army prisoners. He played significant roles in elections and during the Irish War of Independence, working with Michael Collins in the Department of Finance. Noyk married Mabel Stein, had four children, and lived in Dublin. He passed away in London in 1966 and received a military funeral by the IRA's Dublin Brigade.
"Wabamun Generating Station was a coal-fired power station owned by TransAlta. It was located next to the village of Wabamun in Alberta. The station primarily used sub bituminous fuel from the Whitewood mine. Unit 3 was retired in 2002, Units 1 and 2 on December 31, 2004, and Unit 4 on March 31, 2010. On August 11, 2011, the main building was demolished by a controlled implosion. Future plans for the site include high rise condos and a waterfront."
The Cam River, also known as Ruataniwha, is a small river in Canterbury, South Island, New Zealand. It is a tributary of the Kaiapoi River, which in turn is a tributary of the Waimakariri River. The Cam / Ruataniwha originates east of Rangiora and flows south across the Canterbury Plains towards Kaiapoi. It has two named tributaries, North Brook and South Brook, both originating in Rangiora, along with several unnamed streams and drainage canals. The river's name was officially changed to Cam River / Ruataniwha by the Ngai Tahu Claims Settlement Act 1998. The Cam River is home to a small population of Brown trout and Chinook salmon, with the North Brook and South Brook streams serving as spawning grounds. However, Middle Brook is silted, preventing trout from spawning in that area.
The 2010–11 Washington State Cougars men's basketball team represented Washington State University during the 2010–11 NCAA Division I men's basketball season. The team played its home games on Jack Friel Court at Beasley Coliseum in Pullman, Washington. They were members of the Pacific-10 Conference and were led by second-year head coach Ken Bone. The team finished the season with a record of 22–13, 9–9 in Pac-10 play. They lost in the quarterfinals of the 2011 Pacific-10 Conference Men's Basketball Tournament to rival Washington. Subsequently, they were invited to the 2011 National Invitation Tournament where they advanced to the semifinals at Madison Square Garden but lost to Wichita State.
"Hello, Dexter Morgan" is the 11th and penultimate episode of the fourth season of the Showtime TV series, Dexter, which aired on December 6, 2009. The police team tries to get Christine Hill to talk while Dexter frames another man to catch Arthur Mitchell, also known as the Trinity Killer.
Dan DaSilva is a Canadian professional ice hockey winger. Dan DaSilva was born on April 30, 1985. Dan DaSilva currently plays for EHC Black Wings Linz in the Austrian Hockey League (EBEL). EHC Black Wings Linz is a team in the Austrian Hockey League.
The 1916 Buffalo High School, also known as Buffalo-Tower City Senior High School, is a property in Buffalo, North Dakota that was listed on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP). It is located near the center of Buffalo, near the Old Stone Church which is also NRHP-listed. The school was built in 1916 in Classical Revival style by A.J. O'Shea and Meineke Building Co. At the time of the listing, the property was owned by the Buffalo Historical Society. The listing included one contributing building.
James W. Van Inwagen Jr. was an American businessman and a member of the Tiffany family. He played college football for the University of Michigan from 1888 to 1891 and was captain of the 1891 Michigan Wolverines football team. After graduating from Michigan, he operated the Tiffany Enameled Brick Company in Illinois with his father, James Van Inwagen Sr. He later moved to New York where he served as the president of the Tiffany Electric Manufacturing Company, the maker of Tiffany Never-Wind Clocks.
Richard Brooks Holder was a Scotch-Irish American professional baseball player. His career spanned 17 seasons, all in the minor leagues. Holder played for various teams in the Pacific Coast League, including the San Francisco Seals, Hollywood Stars, Oakland Oaks, and Portland Beavers. He had a career minor league batting average of .295 with 2,540 hits, 417 doubles, 117 triples, and 98 home runs in 2,492 games. Despite being left-handed, Holder initially played as a second baseman before transitioning to an outfielder. Sports journalist David Halberstam described Holder as a "great hitter with good speed" but noted his defensive struggles. In 2004, Holder was inducted into the Pacific Coast League Hall of Fame.
The 2011 Arena Football League season was the 24th season in the history of the league. The regular season began on March 11, 2011 and ended on July 23, 2011. The Jacksonville Sharks, in their second year of existence, defeated the Arizona Rattlers 73–70 in ArenaBowl XXIV on August 12, 2011 to conclude the playoffs.
Lucy Somerville Howorth was an American lawyer, feminist, and politician. Lucy Somerville Howorth witnessed the ratification of the Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution in Nashville, Tennessee on August 18, 1917. This event inspired her lifelong fight for the civil rights of minorities and women. Lucy Somerville Howorth is also known for her New Deal legislative efforts.
Cosmic Research is a bimonthly peer-reviewed scientific journal established in 1963. It is published by MAIK Nauka/Interperiodica and online by Springer Science+Business Media. The editor-in-chief is Timur M. Eneev from the Keldysh Institute of Applied Mathematics. The journal is a continuation of the Soviet-Russian publication "Artificial Earth Satellites" from 1960 to 1964.
Lačna Gora is a settlement located in the southern Pohorje Hills, north of Oplotnica in eastern Slovenia. This area is part of the traditional Styria region. The Municipality of Oplotnica is now included in the Drava Statistical Region.
"Gishan Dissanaike is a financial economist. Gishan Dissanaike holds the Adam Smith Professorial Chair in Corporate Governance at the University of Cambridge. Gishan Dissanaike was the Head of the Finance & Accounting Subject Group at Judge Business School, University of Cambridge. Gishan Dissanaike was also the Director of the Cambridge MPhil Programme in Finance, a program involving the Faculty of Economics, Faculty of Mathematics, and Cambridge Judge Business School."
"Tasmantrix thula is a moth of the family Micropterigidae. It is known from eastern Australia, specifically northern Queensland, from Devils Thumb to Mossman Gorge in the north and from Herberton State Forest to Mission Beach. The forewing length is 3.2 mm for males and 3.8 mm for females. The forewing ground color is dark blackish-brown with strong purple iridescence. There are three shining white fasciae and a subtle pattern of silvery-white scale patterns in the apical third. The hindwing is uniformly dark-grey scaled with weak bronzy sheen."
John Hartwell Cocke II was an American military officer, planter, and businessman. During the War of 1812, Cocke served as a brigadier general in the Virginia militia. After his military career, he invested in the James River and Kanawha Company and played a role in establishing the University of Virginia with Thomas Jefferson. The family estate he built at Bremo Plantation is now recognized as a National Historic Landmark.
The Transports de Martigny et Régions (TMR) company in the Valais canton of Switzerland operates bus and coach services and two electric railway lines: Martigny–Châtelard Railway (MC), narrow gauge, with the "Mont-Blanc Express" and Martigny–Orsières Railway, standard gauge, with the "Saint-Bernard Express". The company is the result of merging Martigny–Orsières Railway (MO) and the Martigny–Châtelard Railway (MC) in 2001 with the official date 2000-01-01 to form the Transports de Martigny et Régions.
"BTN CLS Knights Indonesia is a basketball club based in Surabaya, East Java, Indonesia. BTN CLS Knights Indonesia competes in the ASEAN Basketball League. The home games of BTN CLS Knights Indonesia are held at GOR Kertajaya Surabaya."
The 1984 Virginia Slims of Houston was a women's tennis tournament played on indoor carpet courts at the Astro Arena in Houston, Texas in the United States. It was part of the 1983 Virginia Slims World Championship Series. The tournament, which was the 14th edition, took place from January 30 to February 5, 1984. Third-seeded Hana Mandlíková emerged as the winner of the singles title.
Ryan Stig is an Australian professional rugby league footballer. Ryan Stig was born on November 7, 1989. Ryan Stig currently plays for the Limoux Grizzlies in the Elite One Championship. Limoux Grizzlies is a rugby team. Ryan Stig previously played for the Newcastle Knights in the National Rugby League. Newcastle Knights is a rugby team.
Great Northern Freight Warehouse is a red brick warehouse in Fargo, North Dakota. It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1990. The warehouse was built in 1902 and later expanded in the Chicago and/or Commercial Style architecture. The building is significant for its history and architecture. It is long and narrow in plan, with the eastern end featuring a two-story section built in 1923, likely replacing an office section of the original 1902 building, which functions as a headhouse.
Gombe is a municipality in Butambala District in Uganda. Gombe is the main municipal, administrative, and commercial center of the district. Gombe is also the site of the district headquarters.
Annick Level is a French fencer. Annick Level was born on December 5, 1942. Annick Level participated in the 1964 and 1968 Summer Olympics.
"Soulstice is a downtempo/electronic soul band. Soulstice is associated with the US based record labels Om Records and Uno Recordings. The band was formed in 1995 through a collaboration between Gabriel Rene and Andy Caldwell. The band members include Gina Rene (vocals), Gabriel Rene (keyboards), Mei-Lwun (DJ turntable), and Andy Caldwell (keyboards and producer). Gina Rene and Gabriel Rene are siblings of Chris Rene, a contestant on US "The X Factor" season 1. Andy Caldwell has pursued a solo career and produced artists through Uno Recordings, a music label he founded in 2004. Soulstice has released three albums: "Illusion" (2001), "Mixed Illusions" (2001), and "In the Light" (2011)."
Stanisław Szostak was a colonel of the Polish Armoured Corps. He was born in Berazino, Belarus, to Władysław Szostak and Maria Nieciejowska of Hrynica. Unfortunately, he was injured in a car accident and passed away in 1961. He is laid to rest at Brompton Cemetery in London.
"Dungeon Defenders is a multiplayer video game developed by Trendy Entertainment. Dungeon Defenders combines the genres of tower defense and action role-playing game. The game is based on a showcase of Unreal Engine 3 called "Dungeon Defense". Players control young apprentices of wizards and warriors in a fantasy setting, defending against hordes of monsters. A sequel, Dungeon Defenders II, was released in 2015."
"Gretna High School is a public high school located in Gretna, Virginia. The average attendance at Gretna High School is 650 students per year. Between 2008 and 2010, Gretna High School underwent renovations along with other schools in Pittsylvania County, including Tunstall Sr. High School, Dan River High School, and Chatham High School. Gretna High School has achieved five Virginia football state championships since 2003."
"HkB 600 were electric teak wagons used on the Oslo Metro in Oslo, Norway. 12 double-car multiple units were built by Skabo Jernbanevognfabrikk and AEG from 1951 to 1956. Each train was long and could carry 40 standing and 120 seated passengers. The maximum speed was . The wagons were taken out of use in 1995 and replaced with OS T2000 wagons."
"Never Mind the Sex Pistols, Here's the Tribute is a tribute album dedicated to the punk rock band the Sex Pistols."
"Pål Rock is a rock located between Per and Oskeladden Rocks in the Arkticheskiy Institut Rocks at the northwest extremity of the Wohlthat Mountains, Queen Maud Land. Pål Rock was discovered and photographed by the German Antarctic Expedition, 1938–39, and mapped by Norway from air photos and surveys by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition, 1956–60. Pål Rock was named after Paul."
The Warwickshire Group is a lithostratigraphic unit of rock strata within the British Carboniferous system. In the Pennine Basin, it is younger than the Coal Measures Group and is considered to be of late Westphalian and Stephanian age. In the South Wales Coalfield, it includes the Pennant Sandstone Formation and the Grovesend Formation, containing the youngest Carboniferous rocks in Britain. The name Warwickshire Group replaced earlier names like Barren Coal Measures and Red Measures, referring to coal-barren red-beds overlying productive coal measures. It is named after the Warwickshire Coalfield where it is most extensively developed.
Hotinja Vas is a village in the Municipality of Hoče–Slivnica in northeastern Slovenia. Hotinja Vas is located on the edge of the flatlands on the right bank of the Drava River south of Maribor. Hotinja Vas is part of the traditional region of Styria. The municipality is now included in the Drava Statistical Region. The village chapel-shrine in Hotinja Vas dates back to 1921.
Cubilin is a protein. Cubilin is encoded by the "CUBN" gene in humans.
Zahara Rubin is an Israeli sculptor, painter, and artist. Zahara Rubin was born in 1932.
Alireza Jalili Loghman is an Iranian professional football player. Alireza Jalili Loghman was born on February 9, 1979. Alireza Jalili Loghman last played for Tractor Sazi in the Iran Pro League. Tractor Sazi is a football club based in Iran.
The American College of Pediatricians (ACPeds) is an advocacy group of pediatricians and healthcare professionals in the United States. It was founded in 2002 and reportedly had between 150 and 200 members in 2005, increasing to 500 physician members in 2016. The group's main focus is advocating against abortion and the adoption of children by gay or lesbian individuals, as well as promoting conversion therapy. ACPeds' views on parenting differ from those of the American Academy of Pediatrics, particularly regarding the connection between sexuality and parenting abilities. The Southern Poverty Law Center has labeled ACPeds as a hate group for promoting what they consider to be "anti-LGBT junk science." Additionally, mainstream researchers, including the director of the US National Institutes of Health, have accused ACPeds of misusing or mischaracterizing their work to further the organization's political agenda.
"Mariedals IK is a Swedish football club. Mariedals IK is located in Borås in Borås Municipality, Västra Götaland County."
The Trinity Gower D Scribe, also known as Scribe D, was a professional scribe and copyist of literary manuscripts during the late fourteenth and early fifteenth centuries in London, England. Scribe D is well-known to students of late Middle English manuscripts.
Mount Dow is a mountain located at the south side of Novosilski Glacier, west of the north end of Mount Carse in South Georgia. It was surveyed by the South Georgia Survey between 1951 and 1957. Mount Dow was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in honor of American whaling historian George F. Dow, known for his work "Whale Ships and Whaling: A Pictorial History of Whaling During Three Centuries".
"The Dragons Back is a ridge located in the western part of the La Grange Nunataks, Shackleton Range. The ridge rises to an elevation of . It was photographed from the air by the U.S. Navy in 1967 and surveyed by the British Antarctic Survey from 1968 to 1971. The name 'Dragons Back' was given by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1971 due to the spikes on the ridge crest resembling a dragon."
"Dufek Head is an ice-covered headland located northeast of Tyree Head on Ross Island. The headland is situated at the east side of the terminus of Aurora Glacier. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in 2000, in connection with Tyree Head, in honor of Rear Admiral George J. Dufek of the U.S. Navy, who served as Commander of the U.S. Naval Support Force Antarctica from 1954 to 1959. Dufek Coast, Dufek Massif, and Dufek Mountain are also named after Dufek."
"Duthoit Point is a point located at the eastern tip of Nelson Island in the South Shetland Islands. The point has been documented on charts dating back to 1822. It was recharted by Discovery Investigations in 1934-35 and was named after Arthur Duthoit, who was a draftsman in the Admiralty Hydrographic Office at that time."
"Eadie Island is an island located between Aspland Island and O'Brien Island in the South Shetland Islands of Antarctica. The island was first charted in February 1820 along with its neighboring islands during a survey conducted by Edward Bransfield and William Smith. A year later, a Russian expedition led by Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen rediscovered the islands and referred to them as "Ostrova Tri Brata" (Three Brothers), including Aspland, Eadie, and O'Brien Islands. Eadie Island was named after the dockyard manager of the Melbourne Harbour Trust in Williamstown, Australia, by Lieutenant L. C. Hill of the Royal Naval Reserve, who was the captain of the "Discovery II" involved in survey work in the area in 1936–37."
"Edwards Glacier is a glacier located in Antarctica. It drains the east slopes of the Daniels Range between Thompson Spur and Schroeder Spur in the Usarp Mountains of Victoria Land. The glacier was first mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy in the 1960s and 1970s. It was named after Lloyd N. Edwards, a geologist with the United States Antarctic Research Program. The glacier is situated on the Pennell Coast, which is a region of Antarctica between Cape Williams and Cape Adare."
Norman Madhoo is a former professional darts player. Norman Madhoo was born on April 9, 1964 in Guyana and later became an American citizen. He has won the Caribbean and South American Masters three times, in 2003, 2009, and 2010. Madhoo competed in the PDC World Darts Championship multiple times, facing players like Steve Smith, Ken MacNeil, and Devon Petersen. In 2012, he emerged victorious in the Florida Open by defeating Don Carrico in the final.
"Erehwon Nunatak is a small nunatak in Ellsworth Land, Antarctica. Erehwon Nunatak is located northwest of Henkle Peak. Erehwon Nunatak was discovered in January 1985 by a joint United States Geological Survey – British Antarctic Survey geological party led by Peter D. Rowley. The name Erehwon Nunatak is derived from "nowhere" spelled backwards, suggested by Rowley due to the uncertain location during bad weather."
"Explora Knoll is an undersea knoll. Explora Knoll was named after the Antarctic science ship F.S. Explora. The name was proposed by Dr. Heinrich Hinze from the Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research in Bremerhaven, Germany. The name was approved by the Advisory Committee for Undersea Features in June 1997."
Mount F. L. Smith is a mountain located in the Queen Alexandra Range of Antarctica. It stands at a height of high and is situated northeast of Mount Fox. The mountain was discovered by the British Antarctic Expedition, 1907–09, and was named after F.L. Smith, a London tobacconist who supported the expedition.
"Bright Ideas is the fifth studio album by Portastatic. It was released on Merge Records on August 23, 2005. This album was the first one by Portastatic that was entirely recorded in a modern studio. Previous albums were either partially or completely recorded on a Portastudio 4-track recorder. The album was recorded at Tiny Telephone Studio in San Francisco, California and engineered by Tim Mooney."
Fantome Rock is a dangerous rock located in Bird Sound, South Georgia, south of Gony Point on Bird Island. It was discovered by personnel from Discovery Investigations aboard the "Discovery" between 1926 and 1930. The UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee named it in 1963 after a motor cutter that was lost in heavy seas near this rock during a survey of the area in February-March 1961.
"CityVille is a casual social city-building game developed by Zynga. CityVille was released in December 2010. A sequel, "CityVille 2", was released in December 2012. CityVille was shut down on April 30, 2015. Players had been given a notice prior to the shutdown."
Education City Stadium is a football stadium located in Al Rayyan, Qatar, in preparation for the 2022 FIFA World Cup. The stadium has a unique jagged diamond shape and can accommodate 45,350 spectators. It is situated within the Qatar Foundation's Education City, surrounded by various university campuses. The stadium is easily accessible for fans from both Qatar and neighboring Bahrain, with a high-speed rail journey of only 51 minutes. After the FIFA World Cup, 25,000 seats will be retained for use by university athletic teams. On September 3, 2020, the stadium hosted its first official match as part of the 2020-21 Qatar Stars League.
"Bazaari is the name given to the merchant class and workers of bazaars in Iran. They are involved in traditional trade centered on the bazaar and Islamic culture. Bazaari played a significant role in the 1979 Iranian Revolution. They resist Western influence and maintain close ties with the Shia ulama. Bazaari have been influential in Iranian history, supporting various movements and protests. They continue to be part of the ruling elite in Iran today."
"Overclockwise" is the twenty-fifth episode of the sixth season of the animated sitcom "Futurama", which originally aired on September 1, 2011, on Comedy Central. The episode was written by Ken Keeler and directed by Raymie Muzquiz. In this episode, Bender is overclocked by Cubert Farnsworth, leading to an increase in computing ability until he becomes omniscient and can foresee future events. Meanwhile, Cubert and Professor Farnsworth are taken to court by Mom for violating Bender's license agreement, and Fry's relationship with Leela faces challenges. Keeler originally wrote the episode as a potential series finale. Prior to its airing, Comedy Central Insider released preview materials for the episode, including storyboards, concept art, and a preview video clip. "Overclockwise" received positive reviews from critics for its premises and humor, although some felt that the episode struggled to maintain its plot coherence.
Francis Paré is a Canadian professional ice hockey forward. Francis Paré was born on June 30, 1987. Francis Paré is currently playing under contract with HC Dinamo Minsk of the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL). HC Dinamo Minsk is a team in the KHL.
Monchique Islet is a small uninhabited islet off the coast of the island of Flores, west of the village of Fajã Grande, in the western part of the Portuguese archipelago of the Azores. It is the westernmost point of Portugal and, if considered part of Europe (although it sits on the North American Plate), is Europe's westernmost point as well. The islet is approachable only by boat and the deep bay provides opportunities for scuba diving during the day in the summer. The islet and the waters around it are protected for their rich biodiversity, with ninety-six species of flora and fauna identified, including brown algae, limpets, barnacles, and Mediterranean rainbow wrasse.
Glen Goodall is a Canadian former professional ice hockey player. Glen Goodall last played for ERC Ingolstadt in the Deutsche Eishockey Liga (DEL). Glen Goodall was born on January 22, 1970. Glen Goodall was selected by the Detroit Red Wings in the 10th round (206th overall) of the 1988 NHL Entry Draft.
"Erik M. Conway is a historian at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory at the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena. Erik M. Conway was born in 1965. Erik M. Conway completed a Ph.D. from the University of Minnesota in 1998. 'High-Speed Dreams' (2005) is a book by Erik M. Conway. In 'High-Speed Dreams', Conway discusses U.S. government sponsorship of supersonic commercial transportation systems. 'Realizing the Dream of Flight' (2006) is another book by Erik M. Conway. 'Blind Landings' (2007) is a book written by Erik M. Conway. 'Science and Exploration' (2007) is a secondary-level education text co-authored by Erik M. Conway. 'Atmospheric Science at NASA' was published in 2008. 'Merchants of Doubt' (2010) is a book co-authored by Erik M. Conway and Naomi Oreskes. Erik M. Conway and Naomi Oreskes also co-authored an article in the Winter 2013 issue of 'Daedalus' titled 'The Collapse of Western Civilization: A View from the Future'."
"Rhododendron periclymenoides, commonly known as pink azalea and pinxter flower, is a shrub in the heath family. It is native to eastern North America, ranging from Alabama to New Hampshire. This species is often found in riparian areas and in both wet and dry forests. It blooms with showy pink flowers in the spring, characterized by long stamens and a sweet scent similar to petunias. The leaves are bright green and ovate, and the trunk grows to a certain height. Like other members of the genus, this plant contains toxins throughout its parts. Rhododendron periclymenoides is a popular horticultural plant. There is an unconfirmed sighting of this species in O'Leno State Park in Columbia County, Florida, near the Santa Fe River."
"Table Dancer" is a song by Canadian recording artist Keshia Chante from her third album "Night and Day". The song was co-written by Keshia Chante and produced by Alex Greggs. It was released on October 5, 2010, via Chante's official website and later on October 12 via iTunes Canada. "Table Dancer" features a dance pop production and lyrics inspired by women letting loose and table dancing for fun.
"The Insidious Lie" is Craig's Brother's third full-length album. It was available for streaming online at www.CraigsBrother.com on Christmas Day 2010 and released as a digital download on January 24, 2011. The song "Crutch" was excluded from the download version to be included as a bonus track on a Japanese release later. According to vocalist Ted Bond, the album focuses on spirituality, drug use, sex, and war, as the band re-evaluates their position as Christians and punk rockers. "The Insidious Lie" was also the title of a blog entry by Ted Bond from October 6, 2006, discussing the music industry.
"How Do You Solve a Problem Like Roberta?" is the eleventh episode of the second season of the American animated television sitcom "The Cleveland Show". It aired on Fox in the United States on January 16, 2011. The episode had guest appearances by Wilmer Valderrama and cast members of the show "Glee". In this episode, after Cleveland criticizes her parenting skills, Donna lets him deal with Roberta by himself. This episode came in third with 5.5 million viewers.
The Black Theater Alliance Awards (BTAA) were initiated in 1995. The Black Theater Alliance Awards (BTAA) were established in 1995. The Black Theater Alliance Awards (BTAA) were founded in 1995.
"Måøy Chapel is a chapel located in Frøya municipality, Trøndelag county, Norway. It is situated in Mausund village on Måøya island. The church is part of the Frøya parish within the Orkdal prosti in the Diocese of Nidaros. Built in 1939 in a long church style, it was later expanded in 1974-1975. Bishop Tord Godal consecrated the renovated chapel on March 23, 1975. The chapel has a seating capacity of about 250 people."
"A Species Odyssey is a French documentary film. A Species Odyssey was directed by Jacques Malaterre. A Species Odyssey was first broadcast on January 7, 2003 on France 3."
"The Passionate Stranger is a British drama film from 1957. The film was directed by Muriel Box and features Margaret Leighton and Ralph Richardson. It incorporates a film within a film concept, where the "real" part is in black-and-white and the "fictional" part is in color. The interior scenes were filmed at Shepperton Studios, with location shooting in Chilworth, Surrey. Box described the film as a satire on romance and the consequences of mixing it with reality."
"Commentaries on the Constitution of the United States" is a three-volume work written by Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States Joseph Story and published in 1833. In these "Commentaries", Story defends the power of the national government and economic liberty. Story's objective was to bring before the reader the true view of the government's powers as maintained by its founders and friends, confirmed and illustrated by the actual practice of the government.
Hinoe uma is a term in Japanese and bing wu in Chinese, written as 丙午, which means "fire horse" in Chinese. Hinoe uma is the 43rd combination of the sexagenary cycle. It is believed that people born in this year have a very strong personality, leading to a sharp decline in birthrates in Japan.
Nupsskåka Valley is an ice-filled valley located at the southwest side of Nupsskarvet Mountain in the Kurze Mountains of Queen Maud Land. It was mapped from surveys and air photos by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition (1956–60) and was named Nupsskåka, which means the peak shaft.
Mount Noxon is a peak located in the Walker Mountains on Thurston Island. It is situated at the head of Myers Glacier. The peak was identified from air photos taken during the U.S. Navy Operation Highjump in December 1946. It was officially named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Sergeant W.C. Noxon from the United States Marine Corps (USMC). Sergeant W.C. Noxon served as a navigator on aerial photographic flights over this area conducted by U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6 in January 1960.
"Nepal Peak is a peak with a height of 1203 meters, located at the north end of Goorkha Craters in the Cook Mountains. The peak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in association with Goorkha Craters, also known as Gurkha, a name given by R.F. Scott during 1901-04. The Gurkhas, who are from the present-day nation of Nepal, have their homeland in Nepal."
Mount Nesos is the remnants of a volcanic core, over 400 m high, projecting through the ice near the southwest end of White Island, in the Ross Archipelago. Named by the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (NZGSAE) (1958–59) from the Greek word nesos (nisos), meaning island, and referring to the fact that although isolated by the ice sheet the hill is a part of White Island.
Mount Nervo is a mountain in Antarctica, standing 1,070 meters tall, located 3 nautical miles (6 km) north of Mount Coulter in the Schmidt Hills portion of the Neptune Range, Pensacola Mountains. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) using surveys and U.S. Navy air photos from 1956–66. Mount Nervo was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of George W. Nervo, a radioman at Ellsworth Station during the winter of 1958.
Nichols Snowfield is a snowfield located in the north part of Alexander Island, Antarctica. It is 22 nautical miles long and 8 nautical miles wide. The snowfield is bounded by the Rouen Mountains and Elgar Uplands to the east and Lassus Mountains to the west. It was first sighted and roughly mapped by the British Graham Land Expedition (BGLE) in 1937. It was later mapped in detail from air photos taken by the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition (RARE) in 1947-48, by Searle of the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) in 1960. The snowfield was named after Dr. Robert L. Nichols, who was the head of the Department of Geology at Tufts University and a senior scientist of the Ronne expedition.
"Niggli Nunataks is a group of nunataks located near Mount Wegener in the Read Mountains, Shackleton Range. The nunataks rise to 1,470 m and were photographed from the air by the U.S. Navy in 1967. They were surveyed by the British Antarctic Survey (BAS) from 1968 to 1971. The United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) named the nunataks in 1971 after Paul Niggli, a Swiss geologist known for introducing the cataloguing of magma types by molecular or Niggli values. Paul Niggli was a Professor of Geology at the University of Zurich."
Mount Nilsen is a peak located 4 nautical miles (7 km) west-southwest of Mount Paterson in the Rockefeller Mountains on the Edward VII Peninsula. It was discovered in 1929 by the Byrd Antarctic Expedition and was named by Byrd in honor of Captain Nilsen from the Norwegian whaler C.A. Larsen, which assisted the City of New York through the pack ice.
Alex Haija is a rugby league player from Papua New Guinea. Alex Haija represented the Kumuls in the 2010 Four Nations tournament.
"More Johnny's Greatest Hits" is a compilation album by Johnny Mathis. It was released by Columbia Records on June 22, 1959. The album contains the A- and B-sides of five singles, including "Teacher, Teacher" and "The Flame of Love." "Teacher, Teacher" was the B-side of the track "All the Time" from "Johnny's Greatest Hits." The album debuted on "Billboard" magazine's Best Selling LP's chart in July 27 and stayed for 93 weeks, reaching number two for two weeks. It received Gold certification from the Recording Industry Association of America on January 12, 1962.
Christopher Haigh is a British historian specializing in religion and politics around the English Reformation. Christopher Haigh was a Student and Tutor in Modern History at Christ Church, Oxford and a University Lecturer at Oxford University until his retirement in 2009. Christopher Haigh was educated at Churchill College, Cambridge and the University of Manchester. Haigh was a significant revisionist in Tudor historiography and on the English Reformation. Haigh's writings highlighted the complexity and variation of religious reform at a parish level, challenging orthodox understandings. Haigh also downplayed the importance of anticlericalism before 1530. Christopher Haigh's revisionist approach aligned with other historians like Eamon Duffy in Tudor historiography.
"Waldron Glacier is a channel glacier located on the east side of Porpoise Bay, between Sandford and Morse Glaciers. It was identified from aerial photos taken during the U.S. Navy Operation Highjump (1946–47). The glacier was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Thomas W. Waldron, who served as the captain's clerk on the brig Porpoise during the United States Exploring Expedition (1838–42) led by Wilkes."
"Waldron Spurs are a group of rocky spurs located at the east side of the terminus of Shackleton Glacier in the foothills of the Queen Maud Mountains. They were discovered by the United States Antarctic Service (USAS) during 1939–41 and were named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Lieutenant Commander James E. Waldron, a pilot with Squadron VX-6 in 1957–58."
San Miguel F.C. Caudillos, also known as San Miguel F.C. Warlords, is a football club that competes in the Segunda División Profesional. The club is located in San Miguel de Allende, Guanajuato, Mexico. San Miguel F.C. Caudillos is considered one of the weaker teams in the 2nd Division, having suffered significant defeats in matches such as 5-0 against Jaiba Brava del Tampico-Madero, 6-1 against Bravos de Nuevo Laredo, and a 3-1 loss to Ébano F.C. In the Clausura 2011 season, the team finished at the bottom of the division and zone board with a total of 8 points.
"Chuang Tse and the First Emperor is a novel. The novel was written by Italian author Anna Russo. The novel was published in 2010. The story in the novel challenges the reader's perception of reality."
The Romaine River is a river in the Côte-Nord region of the Canadian province of Quebec. The Romaine River flows south into the Gulf of Saint Lawrence. It should not be confused with the Olomane River, which is located to the east and shared the same name for a long time.
The Edward C. Roberts House is a historic building located in Davenport, Iowa, United States. The house has been listed on the National Register of Historic Places since 1984.
"Tasmanida norfolkae is a squat lobster. Tasmanida norfolkae belongs to a monotypic genus in the family Munididae."
Britt Johansen is a Norwegian handball player. Britt Johansen played 156 matches for the Norway women's national handball team from 1978 to 1985. Britt Johansen participated at the 1982 World Women's Handball Championship, where the Norwegian team placed seventh.
"The 3. Liga Süd-West is a part of Germany's Rugby union league system, overseen by the German Rugby Federation. It is positioned below the 2nd Rugby-Bundesliga South/West, the second tier of rugby in Southern Germany, and above the Rugby-Regionalliga, the fourth tier. This league includes teams from Bavaria, Baden-Württemberg, Hesse, Rhineland-Palatinate, and North Rhine-Westphalia. Additionally, clubs from the Saarland and Luxembourg may also participate in the future."
"Bobovo pri Šmarju is a settlement located in the hills northeast of Šmarje pri Jelšah in eastern Slovenia. The area historically belonged to Styria. The Municipality of Šmarje pri Jelšah is now part of the Savinja Statistical Region."
"Šentvid pri Grobelnem is a village. Šentvid pri Grobelnem is located in the Municipality of Šmarje pri Jelšah in eastern Slovenia. Šentvid pri Grobelnem is situated on the regional road from Šmarje to Celje. The area of Šentvid pri Grobelnem was historically part of Styria. The Municipality of Šmarje pri Jelšah is now part of the Savinja Statistical Region."
Woodsend is a hamlet in the civil parish of Aldbourne in Wiltshire, England. Woodsend had a population of 84 in 1851 but decreased in size in the early 20th century. A Wesleyan Methodist chapel was built around 1845 and closed in 1913. A National school for about 20 pupils was opened in 1855 and closed before 1913.
"Nena de Hiroshima is the second album by Argentine band Todos Tus Muertos released in 1991. This is the only album recorded for Radio Trípoli label. Todos Tus Muertos is an Argentine band."
Innico Maria Guevara-Suardo was born on June 4, 1744, in Naples and passed away on April 25, 1814, in Catania. Innico Maria Guevara-Suardo was a member and leader of the Order of Saint John, also known as the Sovereign Military Order of Malta.
Thomas Gleadowe-Newcomen, 2nd Viscount Newcomen, known as The Honourable Sir Thomas Gleadowe-Newcomen, Bt, was an Irish politician. He was born on September 18, 1776, and passed away on January 15, 1825. Gleadowe-Newcomen was the son of Sir William Gleadowe-Newcomen, 1st Baronet, and Charlotte, the only child and heiress of Charles Newcomen of Carrickglass, County Longford. Charlotte had been created Baroness Newcomen in 1800 and Viscountess Newcomen in 1802. He served as the High Sheriff of Longford in 1801 and succeeded his father as a Knight of the Shire for County Longford from 1802 to 1806. In 1817, he succeeded his father as the second Baronet and his mother as the second Viscount Newcomen. However, as an Irish peerage, it did not entitle him to a seat in the House of Lords. Lord Newcomen passed away at the age of 48 in January 1825, leading to the extinction of all his titles. He inherited Newcomen Bank in Dublin, but after a banking failure in the 1820s, he tragically took his own life in his office.
Joaquim Teixeira was a Portuguese footballer who played as a forward. Joaquim Teixeira played mainly at Benfica and won six major titles. Joaquim Teixeira's career spanned eleven seasons in Primeira Liga, where he played 169 matches and scored 93 goals.
Philip de Valognes, Lord of Ringwood, Benvie, and Panmure, was an Anglo-Norman Scottish noble. He served as the Lord Chamberlain of Scotland between 1165-1171 and 1193-1214. Philip was the fifth son of Roger de Valognes and Agnes filia John. He arrived in Scotland around 1165 during Malcolm IV's reign and became an attendant of William the Lion. Valognes was captured by William Marshal during a tournament in Le Mans, Duchy of Maine, France in 1175 and was later ransomed. He was granted the lands of Panmure in Angus and Benvie in the Carse of Gowrie. Philip was appointed as Chamberlain of Scotland to William, serving from 1165 to around 1171 and from around 1193 to 1214. He continued in this role on Alexander II's accession in 1214 and was succeeded by his son William upon his death the following year. Philip also granted lands in Ringwood, Roxburghshire, to Melrose Abbey and an acre of land in Stinchandhaven to Coupar Angus Abbey. He passed away on November 5, 1215, and was laid to rest at Melrose Abbey.
James Cottriall is a musician. James Cottriall was born on January 1, 1986, in Stratford upon Avon, England. James Cottriall is active predominantly in Austria and partly living in Los Angeles, California. James Cottriall gained fame in Austria with his first single, "Unbreakable", which spent twenty weeks in the Austrian top 40 charts in summer 2010. "Unbreakable" was nominated for the Song of the Year category at the 2010 Austrian music Amadeus Awards.
Radosław Jacek is a Polish footballer. Radosław Jacek was born on January 23, 1986 in Opole. Opole is a city in Poland.
North Boarhunt is a village located in the City of Winchester district of Hampshire, England. It is situated in the civil parish of Boarhunt. The nearest town to North Boarhunt is Fareham, which is approximately 3.5 miles (5.2 km) southwest from the village.
William mac Ulick Burke, 4th Clanricarde, died in 1430. His era is one of the more obscure reigns of a Clanricarde. The Annals of the Four Masters have only two references to his term. In 1424, Mac William of Clannrickard (Ulick Burke) died in his own house, after having vanquished the Devil and the world. In 1430, an army led by Mac William of Clanrickard, Mac Donough of Tirerrill, and Brian, the son of Donnell, son of Murtough O'Conor of Sligo, went into Conmaicne Cuile, where they caused great conflagrations, and slew Hugh, son of O'Conor Roe, and Carbry, the son of Brian O'Beirne, before returning home in triumph. "A New History of Ireland" IX states his year of death as 1430. His successor, Ulick Ruadh Burke, would reign until 1485.
Simone Motta is an Italian footballer. Simone Motta plays for the Serie D club Tamai. Simone Motta has scored 85 goals in Lega Pro Prima Divisione, 32 goals in Lega Pro Seconda Divisione, and 23 goals in Serie B. Simone Motta was born on August 26, 1977.
Townsendia scapigera is a flowering plant in the aster family, commonly known as tufted Townsend daisy. It is native to the western United States, specifically found in mountains and sagebrush habitats. This small perennial herb has a clumped form, growing just a few centimeters tall with leaves up to 5 centimeters long covered in rough hairs. The inflorescence consists of flower heads on erect peduncles, each head measuring 1 to 3 centimeters wide with hairy phyllaries. The yellow disc florets and white, pinkish, or purplish ray florets in each head can measure up to 1.6 centimeters in length. The fruit is a hairy achene with a pappus of bristles.
"Mlete is a village in the Ruvuma Region of Tanzania. Mlete is situated along the A19 road, east of Songea and west of Njuga."
"Gusti Syamsir Alam Airport, also known as Stagen Airport, is located on Laut Island in Kotabaru Regency, South Kalimantan, Indonesia."
"Colonia Tabacalera is a neighborhood in the Cuauhtémoc borough of Mexico City, located on the western border of the city's historic center. It was established in the late 19th century alongside other nearby neighborhoods like Colonia San Rafael and Colonia Santa María la Ribera. Over time, it evolved into a mix of mansions and apartment buildings, with notable landmarks such as the Monument to the Revolution and the El Moro skyscraper constructed in the early 1900s. By the 1950s, the area gained a Bohemian reputation attracting writers, artists, and exiles, including Fidel Castro and Ernesto “Che” Guevara who met and planned the Cuban Revolution here. Presently, the neighborhood faces challenges such as prostitution, crime, street vending, and traffic. Despite this, it still retains some of the traditional Mexican cantinas that were popular in its prime."
Jim Thijs is a Belgian pro triathlete. Jim Thijs was born on June 13, 1980 in Leuven. In 2010, he finished 10th at the Xterra Triathlon World Championships. In 1995, Thijs raced his first triathlon in Aarschot. From 1996, he focused on triathlon and left other sports behind. In 2003, 2004, and 2005, his main goal was participating in Ironman races. He won Ironman Malaysia and Ironman Lanzarote in the 18–24 age group and qualified for Ironman Hawaii twice, with his best result being 87th. After 3 years of Ironman training, Thijs switched to mountain biking. He excelled in Xterra races, placing among the best in Europe and finishing 10th at the 2010 Xterra World Championships in Maui, Hawaii.
Maria Sadowska, also known as Marysia Sadowska or simply as Marysia, is a Polish pop singer, music producer, screenwriter, and film director. Maria Sadowska was born on June 27, 1976 in Warsaw.
"Though I Am Gone" is a Chinese documentary film directed by Hu Jie. The film focuses on Bian Zhongyun, the vice principal of the Girls Middle School Attached to Beijing Normal University, who was tragically beaten to death by her students during China's Cultural Revolution in August 1966. The film includes commentary and photographs from Bian Zhongyun's husband, Wang Qingyao, an 85-year-old scholar from the Modern History Research Institute at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences. Due to its sensitive subject matter, the film is banned in China, as it sheds light on the violent actions of the Red Guard, many of whom were children of high-ranking officials. Hu Jie's documentary provides a unique perspective on the experiences and memories of ordinary Chinese citizens during the Maoist era and the Cultural Revolution, using personal records and subjective accounts. The film also highlights the extent of the terror unleashed during that time by listing the names of 201 teachers who were killed in Beijing in August 1966. This serves as a poignant reminder of the tragic consequences of the violent revolution and the atrocities committed by the Red Guards under Mao's leadership.
Vincenzo Crocitti was an Italian cinema and television actor. Vincenzo Crocitti was born in Rome. Vincenzo Crocitti won a David di Donatello and a Nastro d'Argento for the role of Mario Vivaldi in "An Average Little Man". Mario Vivaldi is a character in "An Average Little Man". David di Donatello and Nastro d'Argento are prestigious awards in the film industry.
Naheem Sajjad is a cricketer. Naheem Sajjad was born on September 26, 1966. Naheem Sajjad was born in Mirpur Khas, Sindh Province. Naheem Sajjad is a right-handed batsman who bowls left-arm fast-medium. Naheem Sajjad made his debut in County Cricket for Staffordshire in the Minor Counties Championship against Cumberland. Naheem Sajjad represented the Warwickshire Cricket Board in List A matches. Naheem Sajjad currently plays club cricket for West Bromwich Dartmouth Cricket Club in the Birmingham and District Premier League.
The Florida Department of Children and Families (DCF) is a state agency of Florida. The headquarters of the department are located in Room 202, Building 1 of the 1317 Winewood Boulevard complex in Tallahassee. The department provides social services to various groups including children, adults, refugees, domestic violence victims, human trafficking victims, the homeless community, child care providers, disabled people, and the elderly. The department was established in 1996 when the Florida Legislature divided the former Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services (HRS) into two separate departments: DCF and the Florida Department of Health. Additionally, the Department operates the Florida Civil Commitment Center in Arcadia.
Theobald Fischer was a German geographer. Theobald Fischer was born on October 31, 1846 in Kirchsteitz.
"Mac Aodh Ua Dubhda was a King. Mac Aodh Ua Dubhda was the ruler of Ui Fiachrach Muaidhe. Mac Aodh Ua Dubhda passed away in 1128."
"An Cosnmhaidh Ua Dubhda was the king of Ui Fiachrach Muaidhe. An Cosnmhaidh Ua Dubhda passed away in 1162. Dubh Essa Bean Uí Dubhda, the wife of An Cosnmhaidh Ua Dubhda, passed away in 1190."
Pharmaceutical medicine is a medical discipline focused on the discovery, evaluation, registration, monitoring, and clinical aspects of pharmaceutical development. The boundaries of pharmaceutical medicine are flexible, with a central focus on clinical testing of medicines, translating pharmaceutical drug research into new medicines, ensuring the safety and well-being of patients and research participants in clinical trials, and understanding the safety profile and benefit-risk balance of medicines. Pharmaceutical physicians work in various settings such as the pharmaceutical industry, universities, medical schools, drug regulatory authorities, and contract research organizations. Pharmaceutical medicine is an internationally recognized specialty with its own syllabus, training courses, examinations, qualifications, research methodologies, professional bodies, academic societies, journals, and texts. It adapts to new technologies and regulations to ensure the efficacy, safety, and effectiveness of medicines. The specialty is officially recognized in the UK, Ireland, Switzerland, and Mexico, with accredited education and training available for specialist pharmaceutical physicians. The Faculty of Pharmaceutical Medicine of the Royal College of Physicians provides accreditation for the specialty.The foundation of pharmaceutical medicine lies in clinical pharmacology. Pharmaceutical physicians require expertise in basic research, drug development, clinical trial structure and function, pharmacoeconomics, medical aspects of pharmaceutical marketing, business administration, and public health. Entry-level positions for pharmaceutical medicine specialists often include roles such as clinical research associate, clinical research analyst, pharmacodynamic data observer, clinical research project manager, and drugs and pharmaceutical control manager in clinical research projects.
Mount Whewell is a massive mountain (2,945 m) located between Ironside and Honeycomb Glaciers in the Admiralty Mountains, Victoria Land. It was named by Sir James Clark Ross on January 15, 1841, in honor of the Reverend Dr. William Whewell, who was the Master of Trinity College, Cambridge.
Whisnant Nunatak is a small coastal nunatak located between Rogers Glacier and Maris Nunatak, at the east side of Amery Ice Shelf. It was delineated in 1952 by John H. Roscoe from U.S. Navy Operation Highjump aerial photographs taken in March 1947. The nunatak was named after J.R. Whisnant, an air crewman on photographic flights during Operation Highjump over coastal areas between 14 and 164 East longitude.
Shahdan Sulaiman is a Singaporean professional footballer. Shahdan Sulaiman was born on May 9, 1988. Shahdan Sulaiman plays as a midfielder for Home United and the Singapore national team.
Inderpal Grewal is a professor of Women's, Gender and Sexuality Studies at Yale University. She is a feminist scholar known for her work in transnational feminist cultural studies. Grewal has a Ph.D in English from the University of California at Berkeley and an M.A. from Punjab University. She was born in Howrah, West Bengal, India, and was the valedictorian of her high school class at St. Agnes' School. Grewal has also taught at the University of California at Irvine and San Francisco State University. She is involved in various academic journals and book series in the field of feminist cultural studies. Grewal also blogs about gender issues for the "Huffington Post".
"Vegan soaps (or vegetable soaps) are made from fats or oils of vegetable origin rather than from saponified tallow or other animal fats. These soaps are preferred by vegans and may be preferred by vegetarians. They are also very sustainable and do not harm the environment due to their natural products. In addition to fats, the other main ingredient is either wood ash, potassium hydroxide, sodium hydroxide, and essential oils."
"Újlengyel is a village and commune located in the Comitatus of Pest in Hungary."
Vácszentlászló is a village and commune located in the comitatus of Pest in Hungary.
"Bullet Soul" is a single by the American alternative rock band Switchfoot. It is from their seventh studio album "Hello Hurricane" and was released on November 16, 2010, to Modern Rock/Alternative format radio stations.
Zladovska planina is a mountain located in southern Serbia, near the town of Trgovište. The highest peak of Zladovska planina is "Zelenčev vrh" with an elevation of 1,574 meters above sea level.
Mount Corbató is a peak located east of Mount Fairweather in the Duncan Mountains. The peak was geologically mapped on January 13, 1975, by the Ohio State University field party of the United States Antarctic Research Program. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Charles E. Corbató, a geologist with the party.
Counts Icefall is an icefall located at the junction of the Ford Massif and the western end of the Bermel Escarpment in the Thiel Mountains. It was surveyed by the United States Geological Survey Thiel Mountains party in 1960-61. The icefall was named after Lieutenant Commander William D. Counts, U.S. Navy, who tragically lost his life in a plane crash of a P2V Neptune aircraft shortly after take-off from Wilkes Station on November 9, 1961. Mount Counts is also named in honor of William Counts, who was serving with Air Development Squadron Six (VX-6) at the time of the accident.
"Cowell Island is a small island located on the Ingrid Christensen Coast of Princess Elizabeth Land, Antarctica. It is partly contained by the Flatnes Ice Tongue and is situated west-south-west of Hovde Island and Amanda Bay. The island was first mapped from aerial photographs by the Lars Christensen Expedition in 1936–37 and was visited by an Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions (ANARE) survey party led by M.J. Corry in February 1969. It was named after W.D. Cowell, who was a cook at Mawson Station in 1969 and a member of the ANARE Prince Charles Mountains survey party in the same year."
"Crary Fan is a fan named for A.P. Crary, an American geophysicist. The name was proposed by Dr. Heinrich Hinze of the Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research in Bremerhaven, Germany, and approved by the Advisory Committee for Undersea Features in June 1997."
Crandall Peak is a mostly snow-covered peak located in the Admiralty Mountains, Antarctica. The peak is situated on the west wall of Pitkevitch Glacier in Victoria Land. It was first mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after Lieutenant Eugene D. Crandall, U.S. Navy Reserve, who was an Aircraft Commander with Squadron VX-6 during Operation Deep Freeze 1968. The peak is located on the Pennell Coast, between Cape Williams and Cape Adare.
"Craw Ridge is a prominent ridge that trends northeast from Mount Lister along the south side of Lister Glacier, in the Royal Society Range, Victoria Land. Craw Ridge was named after D. Craw, a member of a 1980–81 New Zealand Antarctic Research Program geological party that reached Mount Lister by way of this ridge."
"Crossover Pass is a pass located between Gordon Glacier and Cornwall Glacier in the central part of the Shackleton Range in Antarctica. It was initially mapped in 1957 by the Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition. The pass was named as such because it, along with Gordon and Cornwall Glaciers, serves as a sledging route across the Shackleton Range from north to south."
"Crosswell Glacier is a glacier in the central part of the Sentinel Range, Ellsworth Mountains, Antarctica. It flows north-northeast from Mount Shinn between Sullivan Heights and Bearskin Ridge. Together with Patton and Pulpudeva Glaciers, it enters Ellen Glacier northwest of Mamarchev Peak and southeast of Mount Jumper. The glacier was first mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after Colonel Horace A. Crosswell, United States Air Force, for his leadership in establishing the scientific station at the South Pole in the 1956–57 season."
"Czamanske Ridge is a ridge located between Jaeger Table and Welcome Pass in the Dufek Massif of the Pensacola Mountains. It was named after Gerald K. Czamanske, a geologist from the United States Geological Survey (USGS) who was part of the USGS Pensacola Mountains party in 1976-77."
"Svendsen Glacier is a glacier located in the Usarp Mountains. It is 13 nautical miles (24 km) long and flows northeastward from Mount Marzolf. The glacier emerges between McCain Bluff and Lenfant Bluff onto an ice piedmont just west of the terminus of Rennick Glacier. Svendsen Glacier was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos taken between 1960 and 1962. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Kendall L. Svendsen, a geomagnetist with the United States Antarctic Research Program (USARP) at McMurdo Station during 1967–68."
The Provinces of Venezuela were administrative divisions used from Venezuela's independence from Gran Colombia in 1830 to 1864, when the States of Venezuela were created. There were initially 11 provinces, with 4 created later, until in 1856 the Law of Territorial Division divided Venezuela into 21 provinces. Some of the provinces at independence had previously existed in a similar form during the Spanish Empire, in some cases having been abolished during the Gran Colombia period. With the conclusion of the Federal War in 1863, a new constitution transformed the provinces into the States of Venezuela.
Swarsen Nunatak is a nunatak located in Palmer Land, 5 nautical miles southwest of Mount Jackson. Swarsen Nunatak is largely snow-covered. Swarsen Nunatak was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) in 1974. Swarsen Nunatak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Lieutenant Commander Ronald J. Swarsen, who served as a Medical Officer at Byrd Station in 1971 and at the South Pole Station in 1973. Lieutenant Commander Ronald J. Swarsen was a member of the U.S. Navy Reserve.
"Swift Glacier is a glacier located close west of Jefford Point on James Ross Island. The glacier is about 2 nautical miles (3.7 km) long. The name Swift Glacier was given by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) after surveys conducted by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) between 1958 and 1961. The name is descriptive, as this glacier is one of the most active on the island."
Stevens Cliff is a cliff located between Tiger Island and Cape Archer along the north side of Granite Harbour, Victoria Land. The cliff is straight, 3 nautical miles (6 km) long, and rises 200 m above the sea. It was named after Alan R. Stevens, who served as the Chief of the Science and Application Branch at the National Mapping Division. Stevens played a key role in the United States Geological Survey (USGS) Antarctic mapping and geodesy programs during the 1990s. He also worked in the McMurdo Sound area as a member of the USGS 1994-95 Antarctic field program.
The Sign and Display Trades Union (SDTU) was a British trade union that existed between 1917 and 1972. Formed in 1917 as the National Union of Sign, Glass and Ticket Writers and Kindred Trades, it represented workers engaged in sign, glass, poster, or ticket writing, as well as subsidiary and allied trades. The union remained active during World War II, handling general union matters such as wage claims and holiday allowances. In 1944, the Sign and Display Trades Union signed an agreement of mutual recognition with the National Association of Theatrical and Kine Employees (NATKE) in the cinema industry. The union changed its name to the Sign and Display Trades Union in 1945. In 1949, two other unions transferred their engagements to the SDTU. In 1958, the SDTU was involved in a dispute with Glasgow neon sign manufacturers, "Laird Neon," and Glasgow University Principal Hector Hetherington was appointed as arbitrator. In 1972, the union transferred its engagements to the National Society of Operative Printers, Graphical and Media Personnel, with fewer than 500 members at that time.
Jamie Reidy is an author, screenwriter, and Huffington Post blogger. Jamie Reidy was born on March 31, 1970. Jamie Reidy graduated from the University of Notre Dame in 1992. Jamie Reidy served as a U.S. Army officer. Jamie Reidy worked in pharmaceutical sales with Pfizer and Eli Lilly and Company. Jamie Reidy's first book is "Hard Sell: The Evolution of a Viagra Salesman". The film "Love & Other Drugs" was based on Jamie Reidy's book. Jamie Reidy's second book is "Bachelor 101: Cooking + Cleaning = Closing". Jamie Reidy's third book is "A Walk's As Good As A Hit". Jamie Reidy's third book was published by HumorOutcasts Press in 2013. Jamie Reidy maintains a non-political blog on the Huffington Post. Jamie Reidy has appeared on CNBC's "Power Lunch", "Squawk Box", and "Closing Bell", as well as on CNN's "In The Money".
The Historic Fairfax County Courthouse is one of the oldest buildings in Fairfax, Virginia. It was constructed in 1799 to serve as the seat of government in Fairfax County. During the American Civil War, the first Confederate officer casualty of the war took place on the courthouse grounds and the building was occupied by both sides in the conflict. Today, the original courthouse building is part of the larger courthouse site that serves the local government of Fairfax County.
"Rae Valentine, also known as Harold Ray Brown II, is the son of Harold Ray Brown Sr., the founder and original drummer of the musical band War. Rae worked on War's 1994 "Peace Sign" album and toured as a backing keyboards, percussion, and vocals from 1993 to 2001. Rae is also an actor who appeared in "Running Mates" (1992) with Diane Keaton and Ed Harris, "The Family Man" (2000) with Nicolas Cage, and "Sniper 2" (2002) with Tom Berenger and Bokeem Woodbine."
Shuwaikh Port is an urban industrial area within the Al Asimah Governorate in Kuwait. The area hosts a number of Kuwait's ports, educational institutions, hospitals, and offices. The major cargo ports are located in Shuwaikh Port. In the 2011 census, 185 people were recorded as living in the district. The port is bordered by the industrial area, Shuwaikh proper, the educational district, and the commercial district.
"The Infinites" is a science fiction short story by American writer Philip K. Dick. It was first published in 1953 in the May issue of "Planet Stories" and has been republished multiple times, including in "Beyond Lies the Wub" in 1988 and in "The Collected Stories of Philip K. Dick".
Qalhat LNG Terminal, also known as Port of Qalhat, is situated in Ash Sharqiyah Region of Oman near Sur. This port is owned by Oman LNG LLC S.A.O.C. Osaka Gas, Itochu Corporation, and Mitsubishi Corporation, three Japanese companies, have a 9% stake in Qalhat LNG and have entered into multi-year LNG supply agreements with Oman. The other shareholders in Qalhat LNG are the Oman Government (46.84%), Oman LNG (36.8%), and Spanish utility Unión Fenosa Gas (7.36%).
"Pati Patni Aur Tawaif" is a Hindi-language Indian feature film directed by Rajkumar Kohli. The movie stars Mithun Chakraborty, Salma Agha, Farha Naaz, and Om Prakash. It is a remake of Pakistan's 1988 Urdu language movie "Bazar-e-Husn", which is based on Premchand's novel Bazaar-e-Husn. Salma Agha played the same role in both "Bazar-e-Husn" and "Pati Patni Aur Tawaif".
"Fritz W. Scharpf is a German professor and Emeritus Director of the Max Planck Institute for the Study of Societies. Fritz W. Scharpf was born on February 12, 1935 in Schwäbisch Hall. Fritz W. Scharpf's areas of interest include organisational problems, decision processes in governments, political economy of inflation and unemployment, and comparative political economy of the welfare state. In 2000, Fritz W. Scharpf was awarded the Johan Skytte Prize in Political Science."
"Sex Quartet is an Italian comedy film. Sex Quartet was directed by Mario Monicelli, Mauro Bolognini, Antonio Pietrangeli, and Luciano Salce. The film starred Capucine, Claudia Cardinale, and Raquel Welch."
"Father of the Godfathers" is an Italian crime film directed by Pasquale Squitieri. The film stars Claudia Cardinale, Giuliano Gemma, and Tony Kendall. It is set in Sicily in the 1950s. Giuliano Gemma won the Best Actor award at the Montréal World Film Festival in 1979 for his role.
"Addio Alexandra is an Italian romantic drama film released in 1969. The film stars Pier Angeli, Glenn Saxson, and Colette Descombes. Addio Alexandra premiered out of competition at the 30th Venice International Film Festival."
Geležiai is a small town located in Panevėžys County, Lithuania. According to the 2011 census, the town has a population of 317 people.
Jūžintai is a small town located in Panevėžys County, Lithuania. According to the 2011 census, the town has a population of 412 people.
"Miežiškiai is a small town located in Panevėžys County, Lithuania. According to the 2011 census, the town has a population of 651 people."
"Ada Foah is a town located on the southeast coast of Ghana. The town is situated where the Volta River meets the Atlantic Ocean. Ada Foah is known for its palm-lined beaches and estuary islands. It is also the capital of the Ada East District, formerly known as Dangme East District, and serves as the seat of the District Assembly."
Sean E. McCance is an American orthopedic surgeon. Sean E. McCance is the Co-Director of Spine Surgery at the Leni and Peter W. May Department of Orthopaedics at the Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York City. Sean E. McCance is also an Associate Clinical Professor of Orthopaedics at the Mount Sinai School of Medicine and an Attending Spine Physician at Lenox Hill Hospital. McCance has authored a chapter in "Athletic Training and Sports Medicine" and was recognized as one of the "Best Doctors" for spinal fusion in Money Magazine. Sean E. McCance is a member of the Scoliosis Research Society and the North American Spine Society.
Panemunėlis is a small town in Panevėžys County, Lithuania. According to the 2011 census, the town has a population of 192 people.
"Suvainiškis is a small town located in Panevėžys County, Lithuania. According to the 2011 census, the town had a population of 175 people."
"Time and Mind is a peer-reviewed interdisciplinary academic journal. Time and Mind is published by Taylor & Francis (formerly by Berg Publishers). Time and Mind covers the cognitive aspects of cross-related disciplines such as archaeology, anthropology, and psychology. Time and Mind explores how findings about prehistory can help research on the brain and consciousness. The editors of Time and Mind are Paul Devereux, John Baker, Christopher Chippindale, Neil Mortimer, George Nash, and Michael Winkelman. Time and Mind explores ideas such as archaeoastronomy, the prehistory of mind, the cognition of memory of place, and ecopsychology."
"Fritz Suhren was a German SS officer and Nazi concentration camp commandant. Fritz Suhren was born on June 10, 1908 and passed away on June 12, 1950."
Kretingalė is a small town located in Klaipėda County, in northwestern Lithuania. According to the 2011 census, the town has a population of 936 people.
Vainutas is a small town located in Klaipėda County, in northwestern Lithuania. According to the 2011 census, the town has a population of 746 people.
"Vadžgirys is a small town located in Tauragė County, in western Lithuania. According to the 2011 census, the town has a population of 440 people."
Victoria Commercial Bank (VCB) is a private bank in Kenya. VCB is licensed as a commercial bank by the Central Bank of Kenya, which is the national banking regulator.
"A Choice of Two is a Canadian film. A Choice of Two was released in 1981. A Choice of Two is also known as Il Faut Choisir in French. A Choice of Two was written by Robert A. Duncan and directed by John Howe. The film stars Alexandra Bastedo, Mavor Moore, and Leslie Nielsen."
Charles Kinney was a Republican politician. Charles Kinney served as Ohio Secretary of State from 1897 to 1901. Charles Kinney was born on July 7, 1850 and passed away on September 15, 1918.
The Mecklenburg Railway Company was founded in 1845. The company was established to build a railway line connecting Hagenow to Rostock and Güstrow, which are now located in the German state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern. In 1873, the company was nationalized and later merged with the Grand Duchy of Mecklenburg Friedrich-Franz Railway.
"The Peugeot JetForce is a scooter manufactured by Peugeot Motocycles. It was produced from 2002 to early 2009. The scooter was available in both four-stroke and two-stroke versions, with various sub-types. Both the 125cc and 50cc variants utilize an EFI system sourced from SynerJect, which was originally a joint venture between the Orbital Engine Company and Siemens, now fully owned by Continental. The EFI system is a direct descendant of the OCP (Orbital Combustion Process) system. The 125cc 4-Stroke model uses a conventional port injected fuel system, while the 2-stroke model uses the OCP fuel and compressed air injection system. The EFI computers are manufactured by Philips in Europe, and the 125cc throttle body is made by Bing in Germany. Other components such as fuel pumps are sourced by Synerject. The brakes are disc brakes both front and rear, with ABS being an option on all models. The electrical system operates at 12V on both models."
"Singer Laren is a museum and concert hall located in the center of Laren, the Netherlands. The museum is dedicated to presenting and preserving the collection of the American artist William Henry Singer (1868–1943) and his wife Anna (1878–1962). Singer Laren is a cultural institution in Laren, Netherlands."
Ponticus was a fifteen-year-old boy martyred in 177 AD during the persecution in Lyons with a group of other Christians, including Saint Pothinus and Saint Blandina. Ponticus is venerated by the Roman Catholic Church as a martyr.
"Soft Beds, Hard Battles" is a 1974 British comedy film directed by Roy Boulting. The film stars Peter Sellers in multiple roles and features a cast including Curt Jurgens, Lila Kedrova, and Jenny Hanley. Sellers collaborated with the Boulting brothers for this farcical movie, where the women of a brothel aid in the war effort against the Nazi threat. The film had a limited release and was titled "Undercovers Hero" in the United States.
"The Buckskin Lady is a 1957 American film. The film was directed by Carl K. Hittleman. The film stars Patricia Medina as the titular character and Richard Denning as her leading man. The supporting cast includes Gerald Mohr, Henry Hull, and Hank Worden. The movie's tagline was, "She hid her scarlet past behind a pair of silver .45s!"."
Áodh Ó Flaithbheartaigh was the Lord of Iar Connacht and Chief of the Name. Áodh Ó Flaithbheartaigh passed away in 1538.
"Our Lady of Assumption College is a private and non-sectarian school located south of Metro Manila. Our Lady of Assumption College was established in 1989. Our Lady of Assumption College is recognized by the Department of Education and the Commission on Higher Education."
"Live at Pep's" is a 1964 album by the American Jazz tenor saxophonist and flautist Yusef Lateef. The album features other musicians such as bassist Ernie Farrow, pianist Mike Nock, drummer James Black, and trumpeter Richard Williams. Recorded at Pep's Lounge in Philadelphia, PA, this live album received high praise from jazz critics, earning five stars and being named AMG's "Album Pick" by Allmusic. Additional performances by Lateef at Pep's in June 1964 were released as "Club Date" (ABC-Impulse! ASD 9310) in 1976 and later as an expanded 2-LP set titled "The Live Session" (IA-9353/2). These recordings were reissued on CD in two volumes in 1993 and 1999 under the original title of "Live at Pep's".
Science and technology in the United Kingdom has a long history, producing many important figures and developments in the field. Major theorists from the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland include Isaac Newton and Charles Darwin. Isaac Newton's laws of motion and gravity are considered fundamental to modern science, while Charles Darwin's theory of evolution by natural selection was crucial to the development of modern biology. Major scientific discoveries in the UK include hydrogen by Henry Cavendish, penicillin by Alexander Fleming, and the structure of DNA by Francis Crick and others. Engineering projects and applications pursued by people from the United Kingdom include the steam locomotive developed by Richard Trevithick and Andrew Vivian, the jet engine by Frank Whittle, and the World Wide Web by Tim Berners-Lee. The United Kingdom continues to play a major role in the development of science and technology, with major sectors including aerospace, motor, and pharmaceutical industries.
Matías Claudio Cuffa is a footballer. Matías Claudio Cuffa was born on March 10, 1981. Matías Claudio Cuffa has dual citizenship of Italian and Argentine.
"The Kleiner Knollen is a mountain. The Kleiner Knollen is located in the Harz region. The Kleiner Knollen is 631 metres high. The Harz region is in the German state of Lower Saxony."
Howard M. Guttman is an American management consultant. Howard M. Guttman is the founder of Guttman Development Strategies, a consulting firm. Howard M. Guttman was born on January 17, 1951. Howard M. Guttman is known for his theories on corporate organizational hierarchies. Howard M. Guttman believes in the horizontal, high-performance organization model. In this model, decisions are made by cross-functional teams with equal authority. Howard M. Guttman's theories have gained popularity in top-management circles. Howard M. Guttman has written books on this topic and has worked with leaders of multi-national corporations to implement his ideas in their business operations. Howard M. Guttman also speaks regularly to corporate and academic audiences.
Florence McClung was an American painter, printmaker, and art teacher. She was born on July 12, 1894, in St. Louis, Missouri, to Charles W. and Minerva McCoy White. Florence McClung later moved to Dallas, Texas, with her family in 1899 and resided there until her passing in 1992. She was associated with the Dallas Nine, a significant group of artists based in Dallas.
Connor Scarlett is an English actor. Connor Scarlett was born in 1992 in Crowborough, East Sussex. Connor Scarlett is known for his role in the teenage drama series "The Cut" on the BBC. In the series, he portrays Alex Fitzpatrick and also plays the recurring character Quinn in "Wizards vs Aliens". Connor Scarlett joined "The Cut" in Series 2 and has become one of the leading characters in the show. He resumed his role for Series 3.
Brandon Burlon is a Canadian ice hockey defenceman. Brandon Burlon currently plays for Västerviks IK. Brandon Burlon previously played for the Stavanger Oilers in the GET-ligaen. Brandon Burlon was drafted by the New Jersey Devils in the 2nd round (56th overall) of the 2008 NHL Entry Draft. The New Jersey Devils are a team in the National Hockey League (NHL).
Detour Island is an island located west of False Cape Renard, on the west side of Lemaire Channel in the Wilhelm Archipelago. It was first charted by the French Antarctic Expedition, 1903–05, under Jean-Baptiste Charcot. The UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee named it in 1959 because the island is near the entrance to the ships' passage west of Booth Island, providing an alternative route to Lemaire Channel when the latter is blocked by ice.
"Devils Corrie is a large and very spectacular cirque, or corrie, located midway between Olivine Point and Amphibolite Point on the south coast of Coronation Island in the South Orkney Islands. Devils Corrie was named by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey during their survey of 1948–49. Devils Peak is named after the corrie."
Mount Dewar is a mountain located southwest of Aronson Corner in the Pioneers Escarpment, Shackleton Range. It was photographed by the U.S. Navy in 1967 and surveyed by the British Antarctic Survey from 1968–71. In 1971, it was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee after Sir James Dewar, a Scottish chemist and physicist known for inventing the thermos flask around 1892.
"Diaz Cove is a cove located near the Kupriyanov Islands at the mouth, northwest of Cape Disappointment, on the south coast of South Georgia. The cove was known to early sealers, as evidenced by the remains of a sealing vessel found there. It was rediscovered in 1929 by Captain Johannesen and named after his ship, the "Diaz"."
"Diaz Rock is a rock located 1 km north by west of Raduil Point, which is the northwest end of Astrolabe Island in Antarctica. The rock was surveyed and photographed by FIDASE from 1955 to 1957. The name Diaz Rock was given by the first Chilean Antarctic Expedition in 1947 in honor of sub-lieutenant Joaquin Diaz Martinez."
Enrique de Borbón y Castellví, 2nd Duke of Seville, was a Spanish aristocrat. He became the second Duke of Seville. Enrique was the eldest son of Infante Enrique, Duke of Seville, and the grandson of Charles IV of Spain. He was also the younger brother of Francis, Duke of Cádiz, who was the king consort of Isabella II of Spain. Despite his family ties, Enrique was never entitled Infante of Spain due to the unequal marriage of his parents, which did not receive approval from Queen Isabella II.
"Amma Rajinama" is an Indian Telugu film, also known as "అమ్మ రాజీనామా", released in 1991. The film was directed by Dasari Narayana Rao and cinematography was done by Chota K. Naidu. The character of the Mother is portrayed by Sharada. This movie addresses women's issues and is a musical film with a score composed by K. Chakravarthy. Some of the notable lyrics in the film praise the greatness of the Mother. Chota K. Naidu made his debut as a cinematographer in this film, under the guidance of Dasari Narayana Rao. The movie was later remade in Kannada as "Amma" in 2001, starring Lakshmi.
Muhammad Imran is a Pakistani field hockey player. Muhammad Imran was born on January 12, 1979.
The 1986 Monte Carlo Open, also known as Volvo Monte Carlo Open, was a men's tennis tournament held on outdoor clay courts at the Monte Carlo Country Club in Roquebrune-Cap-Martin, France. It was part of the 1986 Nabisco Grand Prix and marked the 80th edition of the tournament, taking place from April 21 to April 27, 1986. Joakim Nyström, seeded third, emerged as the winner of the singles title.
Elkouria Amidane is a Sahrawi student and human rights activist. Elkouria Amidane was born on September 29, 1985. Elkouria Amidane has been involved in a non-violent struggle for Western Sahara self-determination and has advocated for Saharawi student's rights against Morocco. Elkouria Amidane received the Student Peace Prize in 2009 for her human rights work. Elkouria Amidane was also awarded the Ordfront Democracy Prize at the Swedish parliament. Sahrawi students face discrimination in school due to their native language, Hassānīya. Elkouria Amidane has worked with international human rights organizations to expose Moroccan human rights violations against the Sahrawi population, with her evidence being published by Amnesty International. Amidane and her family have faced imprisonment and detention for their political activities, with their home being raided multiple times by the Moroccan police.
The legal profession in Puerto Rico is practiced at both the state and federal levels. Legal professionals in Puerto Rico must study both the Law of Puerto Rico and the Law of the United States. There are currently four law schools in the commonwealth: University of Puerto Rico School of Law (established in 1913), Pontifical Catholic University of Puerto Rico School of Law (established in 1961), Interamerican University of Puerto Rico School of Law (established in 1961), and Facultad de Derecho Eugenio Maria de Hostos (established in 1995). After obtaining a Juris Doctor Degree, lawyers must pass the Puerto Rico General Bar Exam to practice law. Lawyers who graduated from ABA accredited schools may also practice in Puerto Rico, but they must also take the bar exam. Until 2010, all lawyers had to be associated with the Puerto Rico Bar Association to practice law.
Gary Hodges is a British artist and publisher known for his graphite pencil wildlife art. He has sold original drawings and limited edition prints in the UK and worldwide. His work is collected by many ordinary citizens who may not consider themselves art collectors. Hodges has sold over 110,000 limited edition prints from 130 editions. His popularity has inspired other artists to develop intricate styles with pencil. He is closely connected to various environmental and wildlife conservation groups, providing significant financial support.
West Arlington station was a former railroad station in the Arlington section of Kearny in Hudson County, New Jersey. The station was used by the Erie Railroad along its New York & Greenwood Lake Railroad division. The second of two stations in Arlington, the station was located on North Midland Avenue, just off the intersection with County Route 699 (Passaic Avenue). Along with a passenger train portion, West Arlington station also held WR Tower, the interlocking tower to handle the nearby WR Draw swing bridge over the Passaic River. The station was first constructed in 1874, (and rebuilt in 1895) with a single story passenger train station and a double story WR Tower attached to the building. The station saw its last passenger train on September 30, 1966, a train along the Caldwell Branch of the New York and Greenwood Lake, which ended the need for the old station half, although that was not torn out. The last Erie-Lackawanna Railway train to cross the nearby swing bridge and use WR Tower was in 1976, when the system was turned over to Conrail. In 1976, the old West Arlington station burned down and was not replaced. The Montclair Connection caused the alignment and the swing bridge to no longer be needed. Passenger service along the alignment ended on September 20, 2002.
"Kareol was an Art Deco/Sezession style building located on the Van Lennepweg in Aerdenhout, Netherlands. It was the largest house built for a private owner in the Netherlands in the 20th century. Unfortunately, Kareol was demolished in 1979."
"Tauron Wytwarzanie S.A. is a power generation company based in Jaworzno, Poland. Tauron Wytwarzanie S.A. was formerly known as Południowy Koncern Energetyczny S.A. It is the second largest power producer in Poland. Tauron Wytwarzanie S.A. has a 14% stake in the domestic installed electrical power capacity and a 16% stake in the local heat generation market. The company is a part of the Tauron Group, one of Poland's largest business entities. In 2007, Tauron Wytwarzanie S.A. had a consolidated revenue of PLN 3.6 billion and a net profit of PLN 137.6 million."
"N'Famara Keïta was a Guinean economist and politician. He served in the council of the Politburo of the First Republic of Guinea as Minister of Trade. Keïta was born in 1924 in Molota in the Kindia Region. He completed some secondary schooling in Dakar and in 1947 was appointed a court clerk in Macenta. He was selected by the future President Ahmed Sékou Touré as a trade union activist and became a member of the Guinean Democratic Party. In 1956, he was elected mayor of Kindia. When Guinea gained independence from France, on 10 November 1958, he was appointed secretary of state in the Office of the Presidency. In April 1960, as Minister of Cooperatives, he unveiled a plan for the development of industry and agriculture that significantly increased collective ownership of the means of production. In 1962, he visited Moscow and signed a trade agreement. On 1 January 1963, he was appointed Minister of Trade, on 1 February 1964, he was named Vice-President, and on 8 November 1964, he became Minister for Macenta. On 19 January 1968, he was named a member of the politburo and Minister of Commerce, Transport, Posts, and Telecommunications. In February 1969, he visited China and met Mao Zedong in Beijing. In the 1972 cabinet, he became Minister of Social Affairs. In May 1972, he was among the members of the National Politburo who welcomed Fidel Castro of Cuba on his visit to Guinea. In a final cabinet reorganization on 1 June 1979, he was appointed Minister of Energy and for Konkouré. After the death of Sékou Touré, the military seized power, arrested Keïta, and later executed him."
Rans Designs, previously known as Rans Inc. (stylized as RANS), is an American aircraft and bicycle manufacturer. The company is based in Hays, Kansas, United States. The name Rans is a combination of the founder's first and last names, Randy Schlitter. Rans has produced over 3000 aircraft in kit form and as completed aircraft.
Weer Rajendra Rishi was an Indian linguist, diplomatic translator, and Romani studies scholar. He was born as Waliati Ram Rishi at Makarampur (Karnal) on September 23, 1917. In 1948, he changed his given names to Weer Rajendra. Rishi completed an MA in Russian language and literature, and in 1950, another MA in English at Nagpur University. He worked in the Indian Embassy at Moscow (1950–52) and later at the Indian High Commissions at Singapore (1962–65) and London (1969–71). Rishi's Russian language skills allowed him to work as an interpreter for various Soviet dignitaries including Khrushchev, Marshal Bulganin, Marshal Voroshilov, Marshal Zakharov, and Prime Minister Alexei Kosygin. He also served as an interpreter for the ex-President of India, Dr. Rajendra Prasad, on an official visit to the Soviet Union in 1960. Rishi retired from the Indian Foreign Service in 1973. He then served as the Director of the Indian Institute of Romani Studies at Chandigarh and the editor of "Roma - Half-Yearly Journal on the Life, Language and Culture of Roma." Rishi was later named Honorary President of the International Romani Union. He passed away in Chandigarh on December 1, 2002, at the age of 85.
"Eumetriochroa kalopanacis is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Japan, specifically the Hokkaidō and Honshū islands. The wingspan of this moth ranges from 6.4-7.2 mm for the autumnal form and about 5.7 mm for the aestival (summer) form. There are two seasonal forms, one in summer from July to August and the other in autumn from mid-September to October. The larvae of Eumetriochroa kalopanacis feed on the "Kalopanax pictus" plant by mining the leaves. The mine is located on the upper side of the leaf, narrow at the beginning and gradually widening towards the end. It may have irregular curves and a dark brownish line of frass in the center. At the end of the mine, there is a pupal chamber that is ellipsoidal in shape with a swollen lower side and a wrinkled upper side."
Metriochroa syringae is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Hokkaido island in Japan. The wingspan of Metriochroa syringae is 5.6-6.5 mm. The larvae of Metriochroa syringae feed on "Syringa reticulata". They mine the leaves of their host plant, starting with a narrowly linear mine that later widens into a long and irregularly curved gallery, sometimes forming a large blotch. The last sap-feeding larva creates an inter parenchymal mine, visible from the upper side of the leaf as pale greenish mottles. A pupal chamber, ellipsoidal in shape with slightly swollen upper and lower sides, is found within the mine, not always at the end.
La Sentiu de Sió is a municipality located in the Noguera "comarca" of Lleida province, Catalonia, Spain.
"Dollungmukh is a village located in the Kamle district of Arunachal Pradesh, India. The name Dollungmukh means "land of two river mouths", referring to the Dollung and the Subansiri rivers. The inhabitants of Dollungmukh are Nyishi. The village consists of regions known as Kherbari, Paro, Midpu, Kolaptukar, Bomte, and Rajali. Dollungmukh is home to the second largest dam in Asia, with a power generation capacity of 2000 MW."
Chrysaster ostensackenella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Canada (Québec and Nova Scotia) and the United States (Illinois, Kentucky, New York, Maine, Maryland, Michigan, Vermont, Arizona, Massachusetts, North Carolina, and Connecticut). The wingspan of Chrysaster ostensackenella is about 5 mm. The adults of this moth are brilliantly shiny with an orange forewing marked with transverse silvery-white bands that are narrowly edged with black along their basal margins. The larvae of Chrysaster ostensackenella feed on "Robinia" species, including "Robinia hispida", "Robinia neomexicana", "Robinia pseudacacia", and "Robinia viscosa". They mine the leaves of their host plant, creating a yellowish blotch mine. The mine usually occurs on the upperside, but occasionally on the underside, of the leaflet. It starts nearly circular in its early stages but later becomes irregular in shape.
The 2011 Women's Professional Soccer season is the third season for the WPS, the top level professional women's soccer league in the United States. The season started with the opening match on April 9, with the 2011 WPS Championship scheduled for the weekend of August 27–28.
"Dumari Kalan is a village in the Sitamarhi district of Bihar state, India. It is located in Majorganj Tehsil of Sitamarhi district. Dumari Kalan Urf Madhuban Jadu village is situated 5 km away from Majorganj and 30 km away from Sitamarhi. As per 2009 stats, Dumari Kala is the gram panchayat of Dumri Kalan Urf Madhuban Jadu village. The total geographical area of the village is 1107 hectares. The population of Dumri Kalan Urf Madhuban Jadu is 17,667 people living in about 3,651 houses. Sitamarhi is the nearest town to Dumri Kalan Urf Madhuban Jadu, approximately 36 km away."
The Boulevard de l'Amiral-Bruix is located in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, France. It is one of the Boulevards of the Marshals that encircle the outer parts of the city.
Christoph Rehmann-Sutter is a philosopher and bioethicist. Christoph Rehmann-Sutter was born on February 26, 1959, in Laufenburg. Christoph Rehmann-Sutter holds a professorship for theory and ethics in biosciences at the Institute for History of Medicine and Science Studies at the University of Lübeck in Germany.
The Aigi Tunnel is a railway tunnel located between Zenjino Station and Nishi Kani Station on the Meitetsu Hiromi Line in Japan. The Aigi Tunnel got its name from a combination of "Aichi" and "Gifu" as it sits on the border between Aichi Prefecture and Gifu Prefecture. The nearest stations to the Aigi Tunnel are Zenjino Station in Aichi Prefecture and Nishi Kani Station in Gifu Prefecture.
Philip Lavery is an Irish racing cyclist. Philip Lavery was born on August 17, 1990, in Dublin. Philip Lavery won the 2010 Tour of the North and a bronze medal at the 2010 Commonwealth Games in India as part of the Northern Irish team pursuit squad. In the summer of 2013, Philip Lavery joined the team as a "stagiaire" after achieving several victories in French domestic racing.
"Småsponen Nunatak is a nunatak located just northwest of Storsponen Nunatak, on the north side of Mount Hochlin in the Mühlig-Hofmann Mountains of Queen Maud Land. It was identified and named "Småsponen" ("the little chip") by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition (1956–60)."
Smalegga Spur is a rock spur located 3 nautical miles (6 km) south-southeast of Morkenatten Peak in the Shcherbakov Range of the Orvin Mountains in Queen Maud Land. It was mapped by Norway from air photos and surveys conducted by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition from 1956 to 1960. Smalegga Spur was named for its narrow ridge.
"Smaaland Cove is a cove located west of Doubtful Bay along the southeast coast of South Georgia in the southern Atlantic Ocean. The name Doubtful Bay was given to this feature during a survey by DI personnel in 1927. The SGS, 1951–52, reported that both names, Smaaland Bay and Doubtful Bay, are well established locally but are used in reverse positions on the DI chart. To conform to local usage, the name Smaaland Cove is approved for the described feature. The name Doubtful Bay has been approved for the bay to the east."
"Snøkallen Hill is a hill located south-southeast of Snøkjerringa Hill, on the east side of Ahlmann Ridge in Queen Maud Land. It was mapped by Norwegian cartographers during the Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition (1949–52) and was named "Snøkallen" which means "the snow man"."
"Snønutane Peaks are a group of rock peaks located east of Snøbjørga Bluff in the Mühlig-Hofmann Mountains of Queen Maud Land. These peaks rise above the elevated snow surface. The area was mapped by Norwegian cartographers during the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition (1956–60). The peaks were named "Snønutane" which means "the snow peaks"."
"Snuggerud Glacier is a glacier located in the Filchner Mountains of Queen Maud Land. Snuggerud Glacier flows north-northeast between Klevekapa Mountain and Smaknoltane Peaks. The glacier was mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos taken during the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition (1956–60). It was named after J. Snuggerud, who was a radio mechanic with the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition (1956–58)."
Stephan Hoffmann was a professional German footballer. Stephan Hoffmann was born on August 9, 1950. Stephan Hoffmann made 17 appearances in the Bundesliga and one appearance in the 2. Bundesliga for Tennis Borussia Berlin during his playing career. Stephan Hoffmann played for Tennis Borussia Berlin.
The Birnlücke is a border pass located at the western end of the Hohe Tauern mountains in Austria. It serves as the border between Austria and Italy since 1919, separating the Venediger Group from the Zillertal Alps. The pass marks the boundary between the Austrian state of Salzburg and the Italian region of South Tyrol, encompassing the valleys of the Krimmler Achental and Ahrntal, as well as the Rieserferner-Ahrn Nature Park and Hohe Tauern National Park. Prior to the Schengen Agreement, there was a border checkpoint at Krimmler Tauern (2,634 m) near the pass. The Birnlücken Hut, also known as "Rifugio Tridentina," is situated south of the border crossing and belongs to the Bruneck branch of the Italian Alpine Club. This hut was constructed in 1900 and named after the pass.
August Torma, originally born as August Schmidt, was an Estonian military officer, minister, and diplomat. He was a veteran of the Estonian War of Independence and was honored with the Order of the Cross of the Eagle, 1st Class, in 1936.
"Mickey's Covered Wagon is a 1933 short film in Larry Darmour's "Mickey McGuire" series starring a young Mickey Rooney. Directed by Jesse Duffy, the two-reel short was released to theaters on November 30, 1933 by Post Pictures Corp."
The Texas Film Commission is a state agency of Texas. The Texas Film Commission operates under the oversight of the Governor of Texas. The headquarters of the Texas Film Commission are located in Suite 3.410 in the Texas Insurance Building in Downtown Austin.
"Braemar Power Station is a complex of natural gas and coal seam gas fired combined-cycle power stations. Braemar Power Station is located in Kogan, Western Downs Region, Queensland, Australia. It is near Dalby in the Darling Downs region."
Regio Patalis is Latin for “the region of Patala”, that is the region around the ancient city of Patala at the mouth of the Indus River in Sindh, Pakistan. The historians of Alexander the Great state that the Indus parted into two branches at the city of Patala before reaching the sea, and the island thus formed was called Patalene, the district of Patala. Alexander constructed a harbour at Patala. Some scholars identify Patala with Thatta, a one-time capital of Sindh. But the identity of Patala is much debated among scholars.
"FC Veino is a Belarusian football club. FC Veino is based in the town of Veino, Mogilev Raion."
The Khanzada are a sub-group within the Khanzada community in eastern Uttar Pradesh, India. They also identify themselves as Gautam Thakurs. The Gautam Khanzada are Muslim converts from the Gautam community.
Uvita Island, also known as Isla Uvita (Spanish for "little grape island") or officially Isla Quiribrí, is a small island located off the coast of Limón on the Caribbean side of Costa Rica. The island measures long from north to south and wide from northwest to southeast. Currently uninhabited, there is at least one structure and a small dock on the island. Visitors can access the island by renting a boat and a driver from one of the fishing docks along the Cieneguita River.
"Punchinello was an American satirical magazine. Punchinello was inspired by the English publication "Punch". Punchinello ran in weekly editions from April 2, 1870 to December 24, 1870."
Chantal Rouleau is a Canadian politician. Chantal Rouleau was elected to the National Assembly of Quebec in the 2018 provincial election. Chantal Rouleau represents the electoral district of Pointe-aux-Trembles as a member of the Coalition Avenir Québec. Prior to her election to the legislature, Rouleau served on Montreal City Council. Rouleau became mayor of the borough of Rivière-des-Prairies–Pointe-aux-Trembles in June 2010 following a municipal by-election. Rouleau was a member of the Vision Montréal municipal political party until May 30, 2013, when she left to join Équipe Denis Coderre. Rouleau had previously been involved in sustainable development initiatives in Montreal's east end for more than 30 years.
"Jataria Khurd is a village in Kharian Tehsil of Gujrat District, Punjab, Pakistan. It is located about five km westwards from the town of Lalamusa. The term Khurd in Persian language means small, while Kalan means Big. When two villages have the same name, they are distinguished as Kalan for Big and Khurd for Small with the Village Name. Jataria Khurd is situated in the Ganja Union Council, along with other villages such as Gunja, Chak Ikhlas, Chakdina, Hail, Mughli, Dhalla, Chak Rajjadi, Jataria Kalan, Chatta, and Sarwani."
"Ladislau Rohony is a Romanian fencer. Ladislau Rohony was born on September 1, 1938. Ladislau Rohony participated in the individual and team sabre events at the 1960 Summer Olympics."
"Ion Santo is a fencer from Romania. Ion Santo competed in the 1952 Summer Olympics and the 1960 Summer Olympics."
Andri Steinn Guðjónsson is an Icelandic film editor. Andri Steinn Guðjónsson was born on March 12, 1979, in Reykjavík, Iceland.
Rich Ceisler was an American stand-up comedian, author, and director. Rich Ceisler was born on March 1, 1956, and passed away on August 4, 2014.
The West Angelas mine is an iron ore mine located in the Pilbara region of Western Australia, specifically 110 kilometres North West of Newman. The mine is owned by Robe River Iron Associates, with a majority stake held by Rio Tinto, and is operated by Rio Tinto Iron Ore. It is one of twelve iron ore mines operated by the company in the Pilbara region. In the calendar year 2009, the combined Pilbara operations produced 202 million tonnes of iron ore, marking a 15 percent increase from the previous year. The Pilbara operations contributed to almost 13 percent of the world's total iron ore production in 2009, which amounted to 1.59 billion tonnes. The Hamersley Range, where the mine is situated, holds 80 percent of all identified iron ore reserves in Australia and is recognized as one of the world's significant iron ore provinces.
The Todd Bolender Center for Dance and Creativity, named after the late Todd Bolender, is located in what used to be the Union Station Power House in Kansas City, Missouri. It opened on August 26, 2011. The center became the home for the Kansas City Ballet after extensive renovations on the historic building.
The 1897 Kentucky Derby was the 23rd running of the Kentucky Derby. The race took place on May 12, 1897.
The Ranzow-Sander House is a historic building located in the West End of Davenport, Iowa, United States. The Ranzow-Sander House has been listed on the National Register of Historic Places since 1983.
"David Nimmer is an American lawyer and law professor specializing in United States copyright law. He obtained his A.B. from Stanford University in 1977 and his J.D. from Yale Law School in 1980. Currently, he is of counsel to Irell & Manella LLP in Los Angeles, California, and serves as a Professor from Practice at University of California, Los Angeles Law School and Distinguished Scholar at the Berkeley Center for Law and Technology. In 2000, he was elected to the American Law Institute. Nimmer has also been recognized with various awards and honors in the field of intellectual property law. He is known for his contributions to the legal literature, including the renowned "Nimmer on Copyright" treatise. Additionally, he has been involved in significant copyright litigation cases and has provided expert testimony to various organizations and courts around the world."
The 1911 Canton Professionals season was their third season in the Ohio League. The team finished with a record of 8-1.
Mauricio Rosencof is a Uruguayan playwright, poet, and journalist from Florida, Uruguay. Mauricio Rosencof has been the Director of Culture of the Municipality of Montevideo since 2005. He was a founder of the Communist Youth Union and a leader of the National Liberation Movement (Tupamaros) (MLN-T). In 1972, Mauricio Rosencof was arrested and tortured. After the coup of 1973, he was held "hostage" with eight more prisoners. After twelve years in prison, he was released in 1985. Mauricio Rosencof has written several books, including "El regreso del Gran Tuleque," which inspired the film "El chevrolé." His 12-year tenure in prison with Eleuterio Fernández Huidobro and José Mujica was the basis for the film "A Twelve-Year Night." Mauricio Rosencof currently lives in Montevideo.
"Northern Trick was an American-bred, French-trained Thoroughbred racehorse and broodmare. Northern Trick had a racing career from April to October 1984, winning four out of six races. She was considered the best three-year-old filly in Europe after winning the Prix de Diane and the Prix Vermeille, and finishing second in the Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe. Northern Trick was then retired to stud and had some success as a broodmare."
The 2010–11 Welsh Football League Division Three started on September 1, 2010, and concluded on May 28, 2011. Monmouth Town emerged as the champions with a two-point lead. Caerau secured the third position on the last day of the season. In a remarkable feat, they defeated Treowen Stars 13–0 to clinch the final promotion spot based on goal difference, surpassing Goytre and Pontypridd Town.
"Diwangi Ne Had Kar Di is a 2010 Hindi romance/thriller film. The film was directed by Jiten Purohit and produced under the banner of Asheema Creations. Diwangi Ne Had Kar Di was released on November 19, 2010."
The 1898 Kentucky Derby was the 24th running of the Kentucky Derby. The race took place on May 4, 1898.
Auguste Toulmouche was a French painter. Auguste Toulmouche was known for his luxurious portraits of Parisian women. Auguste Toulmouche was born on September 21, 1829, and passed away on October 16, 1890.
Alfred McMinn was an English manager for Southampton F.C. from August 1896 to May 1897. In the spring of 1895, McMinn, then a club committee member, accompanied Charles Robson on a trip to the Potteries to recruit players. On this trip, Robson and McMinn signed six players: Jack Farrell, Samuel Meston, and Willie Naughton from Stoke, Watty Keay from Derby County, Joe Turner from Dresden United, and Alf Wood from Burslem Port Vale, as well as recruiting Stoke's long-serving trainer, Bill Dawson. The Saints committee signed them before the Football League season was over, leading to a complaint from Port Vale and Stoke about "poaching". An emergency FA meeting was held at Sheffield, resulting in severe censure for negligence. St Mary's were ordered to pay their own costs, plus £4 6s 3d to Stoke and £1 13s to Port Vale. McMinn was suspended for a year and Dawson for a month. Wood's registration with St Mary's was cancelled, and he moved to Stoke shortly afterwards. During the summer of 1896, Robson resigned as secretary to focus on his cricket career, with McMinn taking over, leading the team to their best season, winning the Southern League title and reaching the Second Round of the FA Cup. After one season, McMinn stepped down, with Arnfield replacing him. In July 1897, McMinn became the Hon. Secretary of the newly formed Southampton Football & Athletic Company Limited, remaining on the board until his resignation in the summer of 1900.
"Santiago Brouard, also known as Santi Brouard, was a doctor and Basque politician. He was born in Lekeitio in 1919 and passed away on November 20, 1984, in Bilbao. Brouard was a leader of Herri Batasuna and served as the deputy mayor of Bilbao. He was tragically killed by the Spanish government's death squad, the Grupos Antiterroristas de Liberación (GAL). Brouard was shot by GAL gunmen Luis Morcillo and Rafael López Ocaña outside his paediatric clinic in Bilbao."
James Mann, 5th Earl Cornwallis, was a British peer and Tory politician. James Mann was born on September 20, 1778, and passed away on May 21, 1852. James Mann was known as James Cornwallis until 1814 and as James Mann between 1814 and 1823. He was styled Viscount Brome between 1823 and 1824.
"Der stille Ozean is a 1983 Austrian drama film. Xaver Schwarzenberger directed the film. The film was entered into the 33rd Berlin International Film Festival. At the festival, it won the Silver Bear award for an outstanding single achievement."
"Via degli specchi is a 1982 Italian crime-drama film directed by Giovanna Gagliardo. It was entered into the 33rd Berlin International Film Festival."
Elise Christie is a British short track speed skater. Elise Christie is coached by Nicky Gooch. Elise Christie specializes in the 1000m event. Elise Christie has won ten European gold medals. Elise Christie has won two overall European titles in 2015 and 2016. In the 2017 World Championships in Rotterdam, Elise Christie won world titles in the 1000m and 1500m events, as well as the overall gold. Elise Christie is the first British woman and first European woman to achieve this.
The Council of Austerfield was an ecclesiastical synod held at Austerfield in Northumbria in 702 or 703. King Aldfrith called the council to discuss Wilfrid's return to the see of York. Wilfrid had been expelled in 686 and appealed to the papacy, leading to the council being convened. The council took place at Austerfield near Bawtry in South Yorkshire. Berhtwald, the Archbishop of Canterbury, presided over the council, attended by bishops, abbots, priests, deacons, and laymen. Wilfrid's desire to return to York was opposed by Aldfrith and Berhtwald, but supported by King Æthelred of Mercia. The council decided that Wilfrid should remain exiled from York and return to the monastery of Ripon. Wilfrid disagreed and appealed to the papacy again. He was eventually reconciled at the Council of Nidd in 705.
Buchan Bay is a small bay located between Cape Hartree and Cape Murdoch, near the southwest end of Laurie Island in the South Orkney Islands. It was charted in 1903 by the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition led by William Speirs Bruce, who named it in honor of Alexander Buchan, a renowned Scottish meteorologist.
"Buchanan Point is a headland located north-west of Cape Dundas and south-east of Mackintosh Cove. It is situated at the north-eastern end of Laurie Island in the South Orkney Islands of Antarctica."
"Budd Pass is a mountain pass located in the ridge extending southwest from Budd Peak on Heard Island. The pass is situated southwest of Budd Peak. It was surveyed by the Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions (ANARE) from 1948 to 1963. The pass was named by the Antarctic Names Committee of Australia in honor of G.M. Budd, who served as the ANARE officer-in-charge on Heard Island in 1954 and led the 1963 ANARE Heard Island expedition."
The Bugge Islands are a small group of ice-covered islands located near the Wordie Ice Shelf and northwest of Mount Guernsey on the west coast of the Antarctic Peninsula. They were first sighted and photographed by the British Graham Land Expedition in 1936 and later roughly mapped from the photographs. In 1947, the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition (RARE) under Finn Ronne observed them from the "Port of Beaumont, Texas" and named the islands after his niece, Ruth Bugge, who provided woolen clothing from Norway for the expedition. The Chilean Antarctic Expedition in 1947 also visited the islands and named them "Isla Aldea," "Isla Eleuterio Ramírez," and "Isla Latorre" after heroes of the naval battle of Iquique. The islands in the group from North to South are Ramírez Island, Aldea Island, and Landrum Island.
Buell Peninsula is an ice-covered peninsula terminating in Cape Williams, located between the lower ends of Lillie Glacier, George Glacier, and Zykov Glacier, at the northwest end of the Anare Mountains in Victoria Land, Antarctica. The peninsula is long and at its greatest width. It was photographed from U.S. Navy aircraft during Operation Highjump in 1946–47 and again in 1960–62. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey in 1962–63 and named after Lieutenant Commander Kenneth R. Buell, a U.S. Navy navigator on aircraft with Squadron VX-6 in Antarctica in 1965–66 and 1966–67. The feature lies situated at the extremity of the Pennell Coast portion of Victoria Land, lying between Cape Williams and Cape Adare.
Butcher Nunatak is a nunatak located at the south end of the Birchall Peaks, southwest of Swarm Peak, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after Robert S. Butcher, a builder in the U.S. Navy at Byrd Station in 1967.
Byrdbreen is a glacier located between Mount Bergersen and Balchen Mountain in the Sør Rondane Mountains. It was mapped by Norwegian cartographers in 1957 from air photos taken during U.S. Navy Operation Highjump in 1946–47. Byrdbreen was named after Rear Admiral Richard E. Byrd, U.S. Navy, who was the commander of U.S. Navy Operation Highjump.
Bystander Nunatak is a nunatak in New Zealand. Bystander Nunatak is located southwest of Forsythe Bluff, on the west side of Daniels Range in the Usarp Mountains. The name was given by the northern party of the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition, 1963–64, to reflect the aspect of this relatively isolated feature.
Amalie Mánesová was a Czech landscape painter. Amalie Mánesová was born in Prague on January 21, 1817, and passed away in Prague on July 4, 1883.
Equity Bank Kenya Limited is a financial services provider based in Nairobi, Kenya. It operates as a commercial bank licensed by the Central Bank of Kenya. In 2010, the bank introduced the Agency banking model, which has been successful and is regulated by the Central Bank of Kenya Prudential guidelines.
The Kintersburg Covered Bridge spans Crooked Creek in Rayne Township, Indiana County, Pennsylvania, United States. Built in 1877, it is one of four covered bridges in the county and the only one with a Howe truss design. The Howe design is rather rare in covered bridges, with only five in the state of Pennsylvania having that design. The other four are McConnell's Mill Covered Bridge in Lawrence County, Mean's Ford Covered Bridge in Bucks County, St. Mary's Covered Bridge in Huntingdon County, and Thomas Mill Covered Bridge in Philadelphia County. The Kintersburg Covered Bridge was placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1979.
Ribeira de Pena (Salvador) e Santo Aleixo de Além-Tâmega is a civil parish in the municipality of Ribeira de Pena, Portugal. It was formed in 2013 by the merger of the former parishes Salvador and Santo Aleixo de Além-Tâmega. The population in 2011 was 2,785, in an area of 52.85 km². Ribeira de Pena (Salvador) e Santo Aleixo de Além-Tâmega is located in Portugal. It is a civil parish. The municipality of Ribeira de Pena is its administrative division. The population of Ribeira de Pena (Salvador) e Santo Aleixo de Além-Tâmega was 2,785 in 2011. The area of Ribeira de Pena (Salvador) e Santo Aleixo de Além-Tâmega is 52.85 km².
"A Weaver on the Horizon is a Chinese television series. The series is based on the life story of Huang Daopo, who played a significant role in revolutionizing the textile industry during the Mongol conquest of the Song dynasty and the beginning of the Yuan dynasty. The story is considered to be historical fiction. The series focuses more on the female protagonists than their male counterparts. A Weaver on the Horizon premiered on Nanning Television on August 14, 2010, and consisted of 36 episodes."
The Order of Merit of the Bavarian Crown was established by King Maximilian Joseph I on March 19, 1808. The motto of the order is Virtus et Honos ('Courage and Honour'). The order was awarded in several grades: Grand Commander, Grand Cross, Commander, Knight, and medals in gold and silver.
Mount Bozdağ is a mountain located in the Caucasus Mountains near Mingechevir city in Azerbaijan. The Kura River flows near the mountain, and the Mingachevir reservoir was constructed in 1953.
"Ghanta is a ritual bell used in Hinduistic religious practices. The ringing of the bell produces an auspicious sound. Hindu temples generally have one metal bell hanging at the entrance, and devotees ring the bell while entering the temple as part of preparing for darshan. Priests ring a bell during Pūjā or Yajna ceremonies, such as when waving light, burning incense, bathing the deity, or offering food and flowers. There are bells specifically designed to produce the long strains of the sound Aum."
"Francis Chang-Sam is a barrister-at-law of Gray's Inn in London. He is also an attorney-at-law of the Supreme Court of Seychelles and a Notary. Francis Chang-Sam has been practicing law in Seychelles for over thirty years. He started his legal career as a state counsel in the Seychelles Department of Legal Affairs under the Attorney General. He later held the position of Registrar General in the same department, where he was responsible for duties such as Registrar of Companies, Registrar of Land, and Registrar of Trade Marks. Francis Chang-Sam then served as Legal Draftsman and later as Principal Legal Draftsman in the Attorney General’s Office, specializing in drafting legislations and legal documents. He also served as Attorney General for six years and headed the Secretariat responsible for drafting the Constitution of the Third Republic of Seychelles. In the public sector, Mr. Chang-Sam was a board member of various Government-owned corporations and statutory bodies, including the Central Bank of Seychelles and Air Seychelles. He has been in private practice for over 10 years, acting as local counsel for high-profile tourism projects, foreign investments, and major business developments in Seychelles. Recently, he chaired both the National Law and Order Committee and the Constitution Review Committee."
"Greater Kuala Lumpur is a geographical term that defines the boundaries of Metropolitan Kuala Lumpur in Malaysia. It is similar to the term 'Klang Valley' but there are differences between the two. It can be compared to Greater London and Greater Toronto. The area covered by Greater Kuala Lumpur is 2,793.27 square km."
The Hawkboard is a Single-board computer based on the Texas Instruments OMAP-L138. It features the OMAP ARM9 processor and a floating point DSP. The Hawkboard is a community supported development platform. Unfortunately, the Hawkboard project is currently closed due to common hardware issues.
"Third Party Risk is a British crime drama film. The film was released in the United States under the title Deadly Game. Third Party Risk was directed by Daniel Birt and stars Lloyd Bridges, Simone Silva, and Finlay Currie. The film is based on the novel of the same name by Nicholas Bentley."
"Pen Talar is a drama series on S4C. The series focuses on two families from west Wales starting in the 1950s. The main character, portrayed by Richard Harrington, appears from the third episode onwards. Filming took place in Cil-y-Cwm, Carmarthenshire, Aberystwyth, and Cardiff. The series was produced by Fiction Factory Films, with Gethin Scourfield as the producer and Gareth Bryn and Ed Thomas as the directors."
Mohamed Noman Galal is a former Egyptian Ambassador and author. Mohamed Noman Galal has served as a senior diplomat representing Egypt in China, Pakistan, India, the United Nations, and the Arab League. Mohamed Noman Galal was born in 1943. Galal has authored over 40 books since 1974 on various topics including Political-History, International Relations, Islam, and Human Rights. His writings are analytical and often interdisciplinary in nature.
Rhagium is a genus in the flower longhorn subfamily, Lepturinae, of the longhorned beetle family, Cerambycidae.
Walid Lounis is a footballer. Walid Lounis was born on April 7, 1983. Walid Lounis is Tunisian-born and Singaporean. Walid Lounis plays for Woodlands Wellington FC in the S.League. Walid Lounis is also an accredited football coach in Singapore. Lounis obtained Singapore citizenship in 2007. Despite this, he has not been called to the Singapore national football team.
"Aper-'Anati was a ruler of Lower Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period in the mid-17th century BC. Aper-'Anati was associated with the 16th Dynasty and considered a vassal of the Hyksos kings of the 15th Dynasty. However, recent studies by Kim Ryholt suggest that Aper-'Anati may have actually been an early Hyksos king of the 15th Dynasty. Aper-'Anati is known from a single scarab-seal, housed in the Petrie Museum, where he is referred to as "Heka-chasut" or "Ruler of the Foreign Lands," a title commonly used by the early Hyksos kings. Ryholt tentatively proposes that Aper-'Anati was the second ruler of the 15th Dynasty, although this identification remains uncertain."
"Epic Horse is a historical fiction series by author Victoria Holmes. The series consists of three books, each focusing on a new heroine and setting. The concept originated when Holmes was working for Working Partners and brainstormed a historical fiction narrative. Each book draws inspiration from different sources and influences from the time period and characters."
Mostafa Nazari is an Iranian futsal player. Mostafa Nazari was born on December 11, 1982. Mostafa Nazari is currently a member of Sunich Saveh in the Iranian Futsal Super League. Sunich Saveh is a team in the Iranian Futsal Super League.
"Ballroom Stories is a studio album by Waldeck released in 2007. Waldeck collaborated with Zeebee on this album. The album has a trip hop sound, different from Waldeck's previous works."
"Triantha is a genus of flowering plants in the family Tofieldiaceae. False asphodel is a common name for plants in this genus. Triantha was first described as a genus in 1879. There are four known species of Triantha, with one endemic to Japan and the other three native to North America. DNA sequence comparisons suggest that Triantha glutinosa might actually be two species. Before the establishment of the family Tofieldiaceae in 1995, Triantha and related genera were placed in Nartheciaceae, Liliaceae, or Melanthiaceae. Molecular phylogenetic studies have shown that including Triantha in these families makes them polyphyletic. Some authors have considered including Triantha within the genus Tofieldia, but Triantha is distinguished by its glandular-pubescent stems and seed appendages. A study in 2011 showed that Triantha and Tofieldia are monophyletic and closely related sister clades. The relationships among the species of Triantha are so close that they could not be resolved. The known species of Triantha include Triantha glutinosa (sticky asphodel) found in Canada, Alaska, the Great Lakes region, Maine, and other parts of the USA; Triantha japonica found in Honshu; Triantha occidentalis (western false asphodel) found in Western Canada (Alb, BC) and western United States (AK, WA, OR, CA, ID, MT, WY); and Triantha racemosa (coastal false asphodel) found in the Coastal Plain of the United States from TX to NJ."
"Borg Bastion is a prominent summit on Johns Hopkins Ridge, located northwest of Mount Rucker in the Royal Society Range, Victoria Land. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in 1994 after Scott G. Borg, a geologist who conducted field investigations in Antarctica from 1978 to 1994. From 1992, he served as the Program Manager for Polar Earth Sciences at the Office of Polar Programs, National Science Foundation."
"Borradaile Island is one of the Balleny Islands. Borradaile Island was the site of the first landing south of the Antarctic Circle. Borradaile Island features the "remarkable pinnacle" called "Beale Pinnacle" near Cape Beale on its south-eastern coast and Cape Scoresby on its north-western coast."
"Botnnuten is an isolated rock peak located in Queen Maud Land. Botnnuten is high and situated south of Havsbotn and southwest of Shirase Glacier. The peak was mapped by Norwegian cartographers during the Lars Christensen Expedition, 1936–37. It was named Botnnuten, possibly due to its proximity to Havsbotn and being the southernmost peak in the area."
"Bowers Corner is a peak located southeast of Lishness Peak in Owen Ridge, which is part of the main ridge of Sentinel Range in Ellsworth Mountains. The feature stands at the eastern side of the terminus of Nimitz Glacier where it bends, or makes a corner, on joining Minnesota Glacier. Bowers Corner was first mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after Lieutenant Richard A. Bowers, U.S. Navy Reserve, who was in charge of the construction crew which built the IGY South Pole Station in the 1956–57 season."
The 5th Rhode Island Infantry Regiment was an infantry regiment. The 5th Rhode Island Infantry Regiment served in the Union Army during the American Civil War.
Mount Bradshaw is a mountain peak located in the Bowers Mountains, Victoria Land, Antarctica. It is situated at the northeast side of the névé of Leap Year Glacier, northwest of Ian Peak. The mountain was named by the New Zealand Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1983 after J.D. Bradshaw, a geologist at the University of Canterbury, New Zealand. J.D. Bradshaw was part of the New Zealand Antarctic Research Program geological parties to the area in 1974–75 and 1981–82. Mount Bradshaw is located on the Pennell Coast, which is a region of Antarctica between Cape Williams and Cape Adare.
"The Breccia Crags are rock crags located west of Petter Bay in the southeast end of Coronation Island, within the South Orkney Islands. They were named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee after the 1956–58 survey conducted by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey. This geological feature is of interest due to the contact of brecciated schist (breccia) and conglomerate."
Mount Bresnahan is a flat-topped, mainly ice-free mountain located in Victoria Land, Antarctica. It is situated along the east side of the Helliwell Hills, north-northeast of Mount Van der Hoeven. The mountain was first mapped by the United States Geological Survey and named after David M. Bresnahan, a biologist with the United States Antarctic Research Program. Bresnahan worked at McMurdo Station on Ross Island and later on the staff of the Office of Polar Programs at the National Science Foundation. Mount Bresnahan is located on the Pennell Coast, between Cape Williams and Cape Adare.
The Briggs Peninsula is a small peninsula located on the west side of Inverleith Harbour on the northeast coast of Anvers Island, in the Palmer Archipelago. The northeast point of the peninsula was named Briggs Point in 1927 by DI personnel on the RSS "Discovery" after Able Seaman A.C. Briggs, a member of the survey party. Despite no distinct point being visible in air photos, the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee decided to apply the name to the entire peninsula in 1959.
Mount Brocklehurst is a dome-shaped mountain located in Victoria Land. It has a peak and is situated north of Mawson Glacier and west of Mount Murray. The mountain was first charted by the British Antarctic Expedition, 1907–09, and was named after Sir Philip Lee Brocklehurst, who was an assistant geologist on the expedition and contributed to it.
"Browns Glacier is a glacier located north of Chaos Glacier, flowing westward into the northern extremity of Ranvik Bay. The glacier was charted by Norwegian cartographers from air photographs taken by the Lars Christensen Expedition (1936–37) and was further identified in John H. Roscoe's 1952 study of this area from U.S. Navy Operation Highjump (1946–47) photography. It was named by Roscoe in honor of Lieutenant (j.g.) Eduardo P. Brown, U.S. Navy, who served as the photographic officer with the western task group of Operation Highjump."
Jacqueline Appart is a Belgian fencer. Jacqueline Appart was born on November 5, 1931. Jacqueline Appart participated in the women's individual foil event at the 1960 Summer Olympics.
"Buccinaria jonkeri is a species of sea snail. Buccinaria jonkeri belongs to the marine gastropod mollusk family Raphitomidae."
"Mohamed Yaghni is an Algerian footballer. Mohamed Yaghni was born on February 22, 1988 in Tiaret. Mohamed Yaghni currently plays for JSM Tiaret in the Algerian Ligue 2."
Tomáš Marcinko is a Slovak professional ice hockey forward. Tomáš Marcinko plays as a center for HC Oceláři Třinec in the Czech Extraliga. Tomáš Marcinko was selected by the New York Islanders in the 4th round (115th overall) of the 2006 NHL Entry Draft. However, he never played for the team. On June 26, 2011, the New York Islanders re-signed Marcinko to a one-year, two-way contract.
Ilija Batljan is a former Montenegrin-Swedish Social Democratic politician. Ilija Batljan has been working with real estate in Sweden since 2010. In the spring of 2016, he founded the company Samhällsbyggnadsbolaget, which has become one of the bigger real estate companies in Sweden, listed on Nasdaq First North. He moved to Sweden in 1993 during the breakup of Yugoslavia. In 1996, he earned a B.A. in economics at Stockholm University. Engaging himself in the Social Democratic Party under then-Prime Minister Göran Persson, he was elected municipal commissioner and Mayor of Nynäshamn in 2005. He resigned in 2009 to take up his former post as county commissioner. He is generally regarded as a fiscal liberal and a strongman of the social liberal wing of the Social Democratic Party. During the 2010 general election, he publicly criticized the party leadership for promising to reinstate wealth and property taxes levied by the Reinfeldt administration. His reformist agenda earned him harsh internal criticism but also made him an expected frontrunner for the party's 2011 leadership election, although he has publicly proclaimed his will not to run.
"Lardigo Peak is an ice-covered peak located on Snegotin Ridge in Trinity Peninsula, Graham Land, Antarctica. The peak is named after Lardigo Point, which is situated on the Bulgarian Black Sea Coast."
Narrative Inquiry in Bioethics is an academic journal established in 2011 and published by Johns Hopkins University Press on behalf of the Foundation for Narrative Inquiry in Bioethics. The editors-in-chief are James M. DuBois from Washington University School of Medicine and Ana S. Iltis from Wake Forest University. The journal serves as a forum for exploring current issues in bioethics through the publication and analysis of personal stories, qualitative and mixed-methods research articles, and case studies.
"Dobara is an Indian Hindi film directed by Shashi Ranjan. The film features Jackie Shroff, Mahima Chaudhry, and Raveena Tandon. It is an unauthorized remake of the film "Forever Lulu"."
Vesicular glutamate transporter 3 (VGLUT3) is a protein found in humans. VGLUT3 is encoded by the SLC17A8 gene.
"Something Short of Paradise" is a romantic comedy film released in 1979. The film was directed by David Helpern and written by Fred Barron. The main stars of the film are Susan Sarandon and David Steinberg.
Andrew Crossland was an English first-class cricketer. Andrew Crossland played for Sheffield Cricket Club. Andrew Crossland was born in Dalton, Huddersfield. Andrew Crossland passed away in November 1902 in Hull. Samuel Crossland, his son, also played first-class cricket.
Arctech Helsinki Shipyard is a Finnish shipbuilding company. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard is part of the Russian state-owned United Shipbuilding Corporation. The company specializes in icebreakers and other icegoing vessels for arctic conditions. Between 2011 and 2019, Arctech Helsinki Shipyard built a total of 10 icebreaking vessels at the Hietalahti shipyard in Helsinki, Finland. Due to economic sanctions against its Russian owner, the company had to transfer its shipbuilding business in Finland to a successor company, Helsinki Shipyard, which was later sold to a private Russian owner. Arctech is expected to continue shipbuilding in Russia as a shareholder of a smaller shipyard in Saint Petersburg.
Stephen of La Ferté was the Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem from 1128 until his death in 1130. He was a French priest and the abbot of Saint-Jean-en-Vallée at Chartres. Stephen was related to Baldwin II, the King of Jerusalem. His predecessor, Warmund, had a close alliance with Baldwin, but Stephen was less cooperative. He revived claims for church power made by Patriarch Dagobert. Stephen sought to revive an agreement between Dagobert and Godfrey of Bouillon for the possession of Jaffa and even Jerusalem itself as autonomous territories. Baldwin did not agree, leading to deteriorating relations between the court and the patriarchate. Stephen's death in 1130 raised suspicions of poisoning among his friends. Baldwin visited him on his deathbed, and Stephen responded, 'Sire, I am faring as you desire.' William of Malines succeeded him as the Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem.
The Bjälbo runestones are Viking Age memorial runestones located in Bjälbo, a village in Mjölby Municipality, Östergötland, Sweden. One of the inscriptions on these stones provides evidence of the existence of guilds in Sweden during this period.
Dragić Joksimović was a Serbian politician and attorney. Dragić Joksimović was born in Bačina, Kingdom of Serbia on July 18, 1893. He was politically active in the Independent Radical Party and later in the Democratic Party. In August 1945, he became a member of the Temporary National Assembly of Yugoslavia and led the Democratic Representatives Club within the assembly. Joksimović defended Draža Mihailović during the Belgrade Process and was later imprisoned in 1949, passing away in the Sremska Mitrovica prison in 1951.
Opostega amphimitra is a moth. Opostega amphimitra belongs to the family Opostegidae. Opostega amphimitra was described by Edward Meyrick in 1913. Opostega amphimitra is known to be from the area of the former Transvaal Province in South Africa. Adults of Opostega amphimitra have been recorded from December to February.
Ira Schuster was an American songwriter and pianist. He worked at various publishing companies on Tin Pan Alley in the early 20th century. Ira Schuster was also known as John Siras.
Tone Anne Alvestad Seland is a Norwegian handball player. Tone Anne Alvestad Seland represented the national handball team in twelve matches from 1989 to 1990. She also competed in the 1990 World Women's Handball Championship, where the Norwegian team finished sixth.
"Nuns of the Battlefield" is a public artwork created in 1924 by Irish artist Jerome Connor. It is located at the intersection of Rhode Island Avenue NW, M Street, and Connecticut Avenue NW in Washington, D.C., United States. This artwork pays tribute to the more than 600 nuns who provided nursing care to soldiers from both sides during the American Civil War. It is one of two monuments in the District that commemorate the roles of women in the conflict. "Nuns of the Battlefield" is a contributing monument to the Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C., and is listed on the National Register of Historic Places. In 1993, it was surveyed for the Smithsonian Institution's Save Outdoor Sculpture! program.
"The 4 Hours of Estoril is a sports car endurance race. The race takes place at the Autódromo do Estoril in Estoril, on the Portuguese Riviera. The race was first held in 1977 as part of the World Sportscar Championship. It was later revived in 2001 for the European Le Mans Series as a 6-hour race and continued until 2003 under the FIA Sportscar Championship. Between 2014 and 2016, the race was included in the European Le Mans Series, in the format of a 4-hour race."
"Saskatchewan Gaming Corporation, commonly known as Sask Gaming, is a Crown corporation owned by the Government of Saskatchewan. It was established in 1996 to set up and operate Casino Regina. In 2002, Sask Gaming also opened Casino Moose Jaw. The corporation is regulated by the Saskatchewan Liquor and Gaming Authority. In October 2008, Saskatchewan Gaming Corporation was recognized as one of "Canada's Top 100 Employers" by Mediacorp Canada Inc. and was featured in "Maclean's" newsmagazine."
The 1975 Virginia Slims Championships were the fourth season-ending Tour Championships, the annual tennis tournament for the best female tennis players in singles on the Virginia Slims Circuit. The tournament was held in Los Angeles, California, at the Los Angeles Sports Arena from March 31 to April 5, 1975.
Keith DeFini is an American soccer midfielder. Keith DeFini played professionally in the National Professional Soccer League and USISL.
Opostega pelocrossa is a moth. Opostega pelocrossa belongs to the family Opostegidae. Opostega pelocrossa was described by Edward Meyrick in 1928. Opostega pelocrossa is known to be found in Mazoe, Zimbabwe.
Karkidaka Masathil Theepeta Thampuran, also known as Virulam Thampuran, was an Indian monarch who ruled the Kingdom of Cochin from 1809 to 1828. His regnal name was Kerala Varma III. The British protectorate was confirmed on May 6, 1809 during his reign.
"Palanques is a town and municipality in the Ports comarca, Castelló province, Valencia, Spain. According to the 2009 census, it has a population of 35 inhabitants. Palanques is located near Morella. The town's main church is dedicated to the Assumption of Mary, and the Ermita de la Verge dels Dolors is a small church dedicated to Our Lady of Sorrows within the town's municipal limit."
Distorsio is a genus of medium-sized sea snails. Distorsio belongs to the family Personidae. Distorsio snails are marine gastropod mollusks.
Rotana Cinema is a Saudi Arabian free-to-air satellite television channel owned by Rotana Group network. It was launched in 2005 and exclusively broadcasts old and contemporary Egyptian films. Rotana Cinema has the largest Arabic movie library in the world, showcasing premium production films from golden oldies to the latest blockbusters. It was the first channel to use the direct-to-TV method, fast-forwarding the period between a movie's theater premiere and TV premiere. Since 2005, Rotana Cinema has become the Arab family's cinema at home, offering over 1000 films not yet seen on TV and airing more than 35 premier movies per year.
The Fort de Chaudfontaine, also known as the Fort de la Rochette, is one of the twelve forts constructed as part of the fortifications of Liège in Belgium during the late 19th century. It was designed by General Henri Alexis Brialmont and built between 1881 and 1884. Unlike the French forts of the same era built by Raymond Adolphe Séré de Rivières, this fort was constructed using unreinforced concrete instead of masonry. During the Battle of Liège, the fort endured heavy bombardment from German artillery. Today, the fort has been repurposed as an adventure park.
Nina Kleijweg is a retired Dutch fencer. Nina Kleijweg was born on April 18, 1938. Nina Kleijweg competed in the women's individual and team foil events at the 1960 Summer Olympics.
"Mahaw is a village located in Banmauk Township, Katha District, within the Sagaing Region of northern-central Burma."
The 2012 North Rhine-Westphalia state election was held on May 13, 2012. The election aimed to elect members of the Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia. The incumbent minority government, led by Minister-President Hannelore Kraft of the Social Democratic Party (SPD) and The Greens, was re-elected with a majority and continued to govern.
"Lotti Golden is an American singer-songwriter, record producer, poet, and artist. Lotti Golden was born on November 27, 1949. Lotti Golden is best known for her 1969 debut album "Motor-Cycle" on Atlantic Records. Lotti Golden won the ASCAP Pop Award for songwriting and has received RIAA certified Gold and Platinum awards as a writer/producer. Lotti Golden has written and produced Top 5 hits in the US and abroad. Lotti Golden is credited for her innovative work in early electro and Hip hop music. Lotti Golden is featured in the book "Rap Attack 3: African Rap To Global Hip Hop" by David Toop and "Signed, Sealed, and Delivered: True Life Stories of Women of Pop" for her pioneering work as a female record producer."
Manfred Kurzer is a German sports shooter and Olympic champion. Manfred Kurzer was born on January 10, 1970, in Berlin. He won a gold medal in the 10-meter running target event at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens. Manfred Kurzer placed sixth at the 2000 Summer Olympics. Currently, he is training soldiers of the army and resides in Frankfurt.
"So Appalled" is a song by American hip hop recording artist Kanye West from his fifth studio album, "My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy" (2010). The song was produced by West, along with No I.D. and Mike Dean, and features verses by Jay-Z, Cyhi the Prynce, Pusha T, Swizz Beatz, and RZA respectively, who all receive writing credits. Lyrically, the song explores topics such as the troubles produced from being famous, social concerns and features numerous pop culture references. The posse cut received mostly positive reviews from music critics, with West and Jay-Z's verses commonly being cited as the highlights. Critics generally praised the production of the song, though the verse given by Cyhi received a mixed reception. Originally released in an unmastered form through West's GOOD Friday initiative, a weekly free music giveaway started by the rapper to promote the album. Following this, "So Appalled" made its way onto "My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy" with the addition of an extended verse. "So Appalled" charted on the "Billboard" Bubbling Under R&B/Hip-Hop Singles singles chart. West performed the song with Jay-Z at their Watch the Throne Tour and with Pusha T on his own tour.
Miguel Samper Agudelo was a Colombian lawyer, politician, and writer. He was known for his advocacy of abolitionism and economic reform in Colombian politics. Miguel Samper Agudelo served as a Member of the Chamber of Representatives and became a prominent figure in the Liberal party. He was nominated as the Liberal Party candidate for the 1898 Colombian presidential election. Miguel Samper Agudelo was born on October 24, 1825, and passed away on March 16, 1899.
"Mandible Cirque is a cirque located on the coast of Daniell Peninsula in Victoria Land, Antarctica. It is situated west-south-west of Cape Phillips. The name 'Mandible Cirque' was given in 1966 by the New Zealand Antarctic Place-Names Committee due to its resemblance to a mandible in both plan and oblique views."
The Mandolin Hills are a group of nunataks located in Palmer Land, Antarctica. They rise above the ice to the east of Mount Noel in the Traverse Mountains. The UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee named the group in 1977 due to its shape resembling a mandolin when viewed from above.
The 2012 United States Senate election in Rhode Island took place on November 6, 2012, alongside the presidential election and other elections. Incumbent Democratic Senator Sheldon Whitehouse was reelected to a second term with a 30% margin, winning by 65% to 35%.
The National Smokejumper Association (NSA) is a non-profit organization based in Missoula, Montana. The NSA preserves the history of aerial fire management, or smokejumping, through various means such as interviews, rosters, photographs, films, letters, reports, and publications. It serves as a meeting area for individuals involved in wildland firefighting and contributes to the preservation of national forests and grasslands. Earl Cooley, one of the first smokejumpers for the United States Forest Service, was the first president of the NSA from 1993 to 1995. Subsequent presidents include Laird Robinson, Ed Courtney, Carl Gidlund, Larry Lufkin, Ron Stoleson, Doug Houston, and the current president, Jim Cherry.
"Villa Española is a barrio in Montevideo."
"Nuyts Land District is a land district in Western Australia. Nuyts Land District is located within the Eastern and Eucla land divisions on the Nullarbor Plain. Nuyts Land District spans roughly 31°00'S - 32°50'S in latitude and 124°00'E - 125°30'E in longitude."
Datla Venkata Suryanarayana Raju, also known as D. V. S. Raju, was an Indian film producer who made significant contributions to Telugu Cinema and Bollywood. He played a key role in relocating the Telugu film industry from Chennai to Hyderabad. Raju received several awards, including the Raghupathi Venkaiah Award, the Bhishma Award, and the Padma Shri for his outstanding work in Indian cinema. He served as a Jury Member at the 15th National Film Awards and as the Chairperson at the 46th National Film Awards. Raju was the Chairman of the National Film Development Corporation of India (NFDC) and the President of the Film Federation of India from 1979 to 1980. During his tenure at NFDC, he co-funded the production of the Oscar-winning film Gandhi directed by Richard Attenborough. Additionally, he held the position of Chairman at the State Film Development Corporation. Raju passed away on November 13, 2010, at the age of 82, after a brief illness. He is survived by his wife, a son, and two daughters.
Shawn Pittman is an American rugby union coach and former player. Shawn Pittman was born on January 22, 1988, in Bellingham, Washington, United States. Pittman played prop for Old Puget Sound Beach and represented the United States. He also played for his country at under-19 and under-20 levels. Shawn Pittman made his debut against Uruguay on November 8, 2008. He participated in the 2011 Rugby World Cup.
The Struma Corps or Usturma Corps of the Ottoman Empire, known as "Usturma Kolordusu" in Turkish, was a corps under the command of the Ottoman Western Army. It was formed in the Ustruma (Struma) area during the First Balkan War.
Taltola is a Vidhan Sabha constituency in Kolkata district, West Bengal, India. Taltola constituency is reserved for scheduled castes.
Roland Greene is a scholar specializing in early modern literature and culture of England, Latin Europe, and the colonial Americas, as well as poetry and poetics from the sixteenth century to the present. He holds the position of Mark Pigott KBE Professor in the School of Humanities and Sciences at Stanford University and also serves as the Director of the Stanford Humanities Center.
"Koala King was an Australian Standardbred pacing horse of the 1970s and 80s. Koala King won numerous races including the 1980 Inter Dominion Pacing Championship and the 1981 A G Hunter Cup. He won a total of seventy-eight races, including 40 races at Harold Park Paceway. Koala King was a bay colt foaled in 1972, sired by Koala Frost. He was purchased for $1,300 in the early 1970s."
"The Three Tenors in Concert 1994 is a live album featuring José Carreras, Plácido Domingo, and Luciano Pavarotti, conducted by Zubin Mehta. The album was recorded on July 16, 1994, at the concert in Los Angeles with the Los Angeles Philharmonic and the chorus of the Los Angeles Opera. The concert was watched by an estimated 1.3 billion viewers worldwide as a television broadcast special."
Mount Manke is a mountain in Antarctica, marking the eastern limit of the Harold Byrd Mountains. It was named after Robert M. Manke, a utilitiesman with the Byrd Station winter party in 1960.
Lower Layham is a village in the civil parish of Layham, located in the Babergh district of Suffolk, England. The village is home to St. Andrew's Church (Layham parish church) and The Queen's Head pub. Lower Layham is divided from Upper Layham by the River Brett.
"Cordón is a central barrio of Montevideo, Uruguay. Cordón is located directly East of the Centro. Cordón's main avenue is 18 de Julio Avenue. Cordón is delimited by Miguelete Str. and La Paz Str. to the North, Dr. Barrios Amorin Str. to the West, Canelones Str. to the South, and Dr. Joaquin Requena Str., Rivera Avenue, and Artigas Avenue to the East."
Mount Jumbo, known as "Sin Min Koos" in Salish language, translates to 'obstacle' or 'thing in the way'. Some locals also refer to it as "Mount Loyola". It is a prominent mountain that overlooks the city of Missoula, Montana. The majority of the mountain is publicly owned, with additional land parcels being purchased since 1996. The purchase of Jumbo was made possible through funding from an open space bond, federal and non-profit agencies, and contributions from thousands of local supporters. Currently, the easement of Mount Jumbo stands at 1,800 acres.
"Wigs on the Green" is a satirical novel written by Nancy Mitford in 1935. The novel is a roman à clef and is known for satirizing British Fascism, particularly the political beliefs of Mitford's sisters Unity Mitford and Diana Mosley.
Cornelis Visscher was a Dutch Golden Age engraver. Cornelis Visscher was born in Haarlem in 1629 and passed away in Haarlem in 1658. Cornelis Visscher was the brother of Jan de Visscher and Lambert Visscher. Haarlem is the birthplace of Cornelis Visscher. Jan de Visscher and Lambert Visscher were siblings of Cornelis Visscher.
The Master of Science in Global Finance (MSGF) program is a one-year executive-format master's degree program jointly offered by Hong Kong University of Science and Technology and NYU Stern School of Business since 2007. Professors who teach in the MSGF program include those aside. Students have access to resources at both schools and are members of each school's alumni network. The current cohort comes with an average work experience of 10 years and represents 17 nationalities from 12 work locations. The MSGF program takes place over one year and consists of seven modules - four in Hong Kong, two in New York City, and one in Shanghai. Students receive a Master of Science issued jointly by the two universities. Topics covered include Global Macro & Asian Markets, Foundations of Corporate Finance, Foundations of Investments, Asset Allocation, Derivatives Markets, Fixed Income Instruments & Markets, Applied Corporate Finance & Valuation, FinTech, Financial Markets and Corporate Finance in China, Risk Management in Financial Institutions, and Topics in Financial Markets & Innovation.
TeamDynamix is a company specializing in higher education-focused Web-based project management and portfolio management (PPM) software and consulting. TeamDynamix was founded in 2001 in Columbus, Ohio.
Deans Brook is a two-kilometre-long stream that runs between Mill Hill and Edgware in the London Borough of Barnet. It is a tributary of the Silk Stream, which in turn is a tributary of the River Brent, which eventually flows into the River Thames. The brook originates at Mill Hill Golf Course, where it is dammed to create Stoneywood Lake. It then passes under the M1 motorway through a culvert to Stoneyfields Park, where it is dammed again to form an ornamental lake. As it flows through suburban Edgware, it merges with the Edgware Brook to become the Silk Stream near Edgware Hospital. The stream's banks are mostly lined with wooden boards, and there is minimal aquatic vegetation. Kingfishers and grey wagtails are commonly spotted along the brook. A tributary, Edgwarebury Brook, joins Deans Brook behind Brook Avenue. The only accessible part of the brook to the public is in Stoneyfields Park. Deans Brook, Stoneyfields Park, allotments east of Edgware Hospital, and wetlands south of Edgware Underground station sidings collectively form a Site of Borough Importance for Nature Conservation, Grade II.
R-407A is a refrigerant. R-407A is a zeotropic blend of difluoromethane (HFC-32), pentafluoroethane (HFC-125), and 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane (HFC-134a). R-407A is designed as a close match to R-22's capacities and flow rates. It is suitable for energy-efficient retrofit in medium and low-temperature refrigeration systems for supermarket and food storage applications. However, it is not recommended for air conditioning systems or those with flooded evaporators. R-407A must be used with synthetic oils. Its global warming potential is 2107.
Cowanshannock Creek is a tributary of the Allegheny River. Cowanshannock Creek is located in Armstrong and Indiana counties in Pennsylvania, United States. The eastern section of Cowanshannock Creek is sometimes referred to as the North Branch Cowanshannock Creek.
Geoffrey Farmer is a Canadian artist. Geoffrey Farmer is based in Vancouver. Geoffrey Farmer was born in 1967.
"Phodoryctis dolichophila is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Phodoryctis dolichophila is found in South Africa and Zimbabwe. The larvae of Phodoryctis dolichophila feed on "Dolichos trilobus" and various "Vigna" species, including "Vigna unguiculata". They create blotch mines on the leaves of their host plant."
"Luighne Connacht was a territory. Luighne Connacht was located in north-central Connacht. Luighne Connacht was situated on the borders of County Mayo and County Sligo. Luighne Connacht was in Ireland."
Isaac Lee Possin is a journalist, entrepreneur, and film & television producer. Isaac Lee Possin is the executive chairman and founder of EXILE Content, a media company developing premium original content for audiences in the U.S. and Latin America. Isaac Lee Possin previously served as Chief Content Officer for Univision Communications and Televisa. Isaac Lee Possin is the founder of StoryHouse Entertainment, the Los Angeles-based scripted content development unit of Univision, producer of acclaimed scripted TV Series "El Chapo" (Netflix), as well as "Outpost" (HBO), "Residente," and "Hate Rising" docu-features. Isaac Lee Possin was born in Bogotá, Colombia to Jewish immigrants.
Marjanu Vella was a poet born in Tas-Sliema, Malta on December 14, 1927. He received his primary education at Stella Maris College and attended the Malta Lyceum for his secondary studies, obtaining the Matriculation Certificate in Maltese and Italian. At the age of 18, he joined the Franciscan order in Malta and was ordained as a Priest in August 1952. Vella's poetic career began during his time at the Lyceum when he wrote his first poem in 1941. He went on to publish several books of poems, including "Gizimin ahmar" (Red Jasmine), "Dghajjes tal-karti" (Paper boats), "Hitan tas-sejjieh" (Countryside Walls), and "Gargir mall-Herza" (Wild herb with a kerb). He received the Rotmans 1975 Prize for his work and was a member of the Maltese Literature Academy. Vella also wrote and published oratorios, such as "Oratorjo Madonna tas-Sacro Cuor" (Oratorio Our Lady of the Sacred Heart) and "Demm fuq il-Verna" (Blood on mount Alvernia), which were set to music by Professor Joseph Vella. His poems and prose were published in various magazines, and some were translated into Italian and English. Marjanu Vella passed away on February 25, 1988.
The Solleks River is a river in the U.S. state of Washington. The Solleks River is a tributary of the Clearwater River, which then flows into the Queets River. The Solleks River has a long length. The drainage basin of the Solleks River is in the area.
"Charles A. Chase Jr. Memorial Field is located in Dover-Foxcroft, Maine, United States."
"Sekotong is a peninsula located in the south-west of Lombok Island, Indonesia. Sekotong Peninsula is also known as "Semenanjung Sekotong" in Indonesian."
"Gillellus greyae, also known as the arrow stargazer, is a species of sand stargazer. It is native to the Atlantic coast of the Americas, spanning from Florida, United States to Brazil, including the Bahamas and Cuba, where it inhabits sandy patches on reefs. This species can grow up to a maximum length of approximately TL. Gillellus greyae is also commonly found in the aquarium trade. The specific name of this species, greyae, is in honor of the American ichthyologist Marion Griswold Grey (1911-1964) from the Division of Fishes at the Field Museum of Natural History in Chicago, Illinois."
Jimmy Suparno is an Indonesian former footballer. Jimmy Suparno was born on February 20, 1984. Jimmy Suparno played as a midfielder.
Arni Thorvaldsson is an alpine skier from Iceland. Arni Thorvaldsson was born on July 5, 1984. Arni Thorvaldsson competed for Iceland at the 2010 Winter Olympics. Arni Thorvaldsson has been a member of the Icelandic national team since 2006. Arni Thorvaldsson also competed for Iceland in the FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2009.
Alex Pettit is an American public administration official. Alex Pettit is currently the Chief Technology Officer for the State of Colorado Governor's Office of Information Technology. Alex Pettit was formerly the Chief Information Officer for the State of Oregon. As State CIO, Alex Pettit worked in the Department of Administrative Services and was responsible for all information and telecommunication systems for all state agencies. In March 2014, Alex Pettit was appointed interim CIO for Cover Oregon, the agency responsible for the implementation of the Health Care Exchange in compliance with the Affordable Care Act. Previously, Alex Pettit was the first CIO for the State of Oklahoma, serving from April 2010 until January 2014. Alex Pettit was appointed to his position by Governor John Kitzhaber on January 6, 2014.
Avram Iancu Solar Park is a large thin-film photovoltaic (PV) power system. It is being built on a 5 ha plot of land near the Avram Iancu commune in Romania. The power plant will be a 3-megawatt solar power system using state-of-the-art thin film technology and is expected to be finished by the end of 2012. The solar park is projected to supply 2,000 MWh of electricity per year and will be located in Bihor County in central-western Romania. The investment cost for the Avram Iancu solar park is estimated to be Euro 5 million.
Keistuolių Teatras, also known as "Weirdos' Theatre" or "Theatre of Eccentric Men," is a Lithuanian theatre troupe. It was founded in 1989 by actors Ilona Balsytė, Aidas Giniotis, and Sigutis Jačėnas, along with theatre director Romualdas Vikšraitis. The theatre produces plays and music for both the general public and children. In 1999, the theatre became a member of ASSITEJ. Over a span of 20 years (1989–2009), the theatre released 50 plays, 8 videofilms, 11 audiocassettes, and 10 CDs. In 2004, it was recognized in the "Book of Lithuanian Records" as the longest-running private theatre and the theatre with the most performances in a year (217).
Daniel Deribe Gebremichael is an Ethiopian footballer. Daniel Deribe Gebremichael was born on March 25, 1983. Daniel Deribe Gebremichael is currently playing for Hawassa City S.C. Daniel Deribe Gebremichael's name in Amharic is ዳንኤል ደርቤ. Hawassa City S.C. is a football club.
"Borokhula was one of Genghis Khan's generals. Borokhula was found after the destruction of the Jurhen tribe in Mongolia by Jebe and given to Hoelun. Borokhula saved Genghis Khan's son Ögedei during the battle of Khalakhaljid Sands by sucking clotted blood out of Ögedei's neck from an arrow wound. After rescuing Ögedei, Borokhula informed Genghis Khan of the enemy's whereabouts and was later sent to lead an invasion of the Khori-tumats. However, Borokhula was intercepted by enemy scouts and killed."
"Escape from Hell!" is a speculative fiction novella by Scottish writer Hal Duncan. The novella is strongly inspired by the movies "Jacob's Ladder" and "Escape from New York", as well as the works of William Blake and John Milton. It was first published in the United States by MonkeyBrain Books in 2008.
"Flashpoint Human Rights Film Festival was a four-day festival held in Mumbai, India between 8–10 December 2010. It screened eight films from around the world that dealt with human rights issues at a macro as well as at a micro level; from global concerns to indigenous issues. The festival coincided with the International Human Rights Day on 10 December 2010. Mumbai is the location where the festival took place. The festival showcased films addressing human rights issues. The festival featured films covering global concerns and indigenous issues. The festival took place on 8–10 December 2010. The International Human Rights Day fell on 10 December 2010."
"Baderbräu is a Czech-style pilsner beer. Baderbräu was first brewed in 1988 by the Pavichevich Brewing Company in Elmhurst, Illinois. After Pavichevich Brewing declared bankruptcy in 1997, Goose Island took over production of the beer until 2002. The acquisition of the Baderbräu trademark in 2010 by entrepreneur Rob Sama led to the creation of the Baderbräu Brewing Company, which resumed brewing the Baderbräu pilsner. Unfortunately, the Baderbräu Brewing Company went out of business in 2018."
"The Virginia Slims of Utah was a women's tennis tournament. The tournament was first held in 1980 and played three more times from 1983 to 1985. The tournament took place in Salt Lake City, Utah, in the United States. The matches were played on outdoor hard courts."
Julie Pinel was a French composer and harpsichord teacher. Julie Pinel was born into the Pinel family of court musicians. Very little is known about her life. Julie Pinel dedicated her published collection of songs to the "Prince of Soubize", believed to be Charles de Rohan, the patron of her family.
Walter Thomas Bailey was an American architect from Kewanee, Illinois. He was the first African American graduate with a bachelor of science degree in architectural engineering from the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and the first licensed African-American architect in the state of Illinois. He worked at the Tuskegee Institute and practiced in both Memphis and Chicago. Walter T. Bailey became the second African American to graduate from the University of Illinois.
"SET binding protein 1 is a protein. SET binding protein 1 is encoded by the SETBP1 gene. SET binding protein 1 is found in humans."
"Minehead Lifeboat Station is the base for Royal National Lifeboat Institution (RNLI) search and rescue operations at Minehead, Somerset in England. The first lifeboat was stationed in the town in 1901 but since 1976 two inshore lifeboats (ILBs) have been operated, a B Class rigid-hulled boat and an inflatable D Class. The station is located in Minehead, Somerset, England."
John Andree is a British physician. John Andree is the father of the surgeon. John Andree is an English surgeon. John Andree is the son of the physician.
"Pachydactylus geitje, also known as the ocellated gecko, ocellated thick-toed gecko or Cradock thick-toed gecko, is a tiny species of thick-toed gecko. Pachydactylus geitje is indigenous to the Western Cape of South Africa."
Rakovlje is a settlement in the Municipality of Braslovče in Slovenia. Rakovlje is located in the traditional region of Styria. The Municipality of Braslovče is part of the Savinja Statistical Region. In Rakovlje, there is a small roadside chapel-shrine that dates back to the early 20th century.
"Caloptilia betulivora is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Caloptilia betulivora is found in Canada (Nova Scotia and Québec) and the United States. The larvae of Caloptilia betulivora feed on various "Betula" species, such as "Betula alleghaniensis", "Betula papyrifera", and "Betula populifolia". They create mines on the leaves of their host plant."
"The Yarrie mine is an iron ore mine located in the Pilbara region of Western Australia, specifically 90 kilometres north-east of Marble Bar. The mine is majority-owned (85 percent) and operated by BHP. BHP operates seven iron ore mines in the Pilbara, along with two port facilities at Port Hedland, Nelson Point, and Finucane Island, as well as over 1,000 kilometres of rail in the Pilbara. The Yarrie mine is part of the Mount Goldsworthy joint venture, which includes the Area C mine and the Nimingarra mine (currently in care and maintenance since 2007). BHP Billiton is the second-largest iron ore mining company in the Pilbara, after Rio Tinto and ahead of the Fortescue Metals Group. As of 2010, BHP employs 8,000 people in its Pilbara operations. On February 25, 2014, BHP Billiton announced the indefinite suspension of iron ore output at Yarrie as part of cost-cutting measures."
Shu-tian Li was a Chinese-American hydraulic engineer. Shu-tian Li received a Ph.D. degree in engineering and economics from Cornell University in 1926. Li assumed a professorship at Peiyang University in China. He became the executive officer of the Northern China Hydraulic Commission in 1928. Li was a founder of the Chinese Hydraulic Engineering Society and served as its deputy president and then president for six terms. He later led the Yellow River Commission. At the age of 28, Li became the president of Tangshan College of Engineering, making him the youngest college administrator in China. In 1932, he was named the President of Peiyang Engineering College. Li established one of the first graduate engineering programs and the first hydraulic engineering laboratory in China at Peiyang. He also led the establishment of several national colleges and universities in western and southwestern China. During his leadership at the Si-kang Institute of Technology, the Panzhihua Mine was discovered. Li received awards from the Chinese government for his contributions to hydraulic engineering and China during World War II. He was elected to the National Peking Academy of Sciences in 1948. Li returned to the United States in 1950 to start private engineering practice and academic teaching/research. He received awards from the Chinese Institute of Engineers and the American Concrete Institute for his work. Li served on a US congressional advisory board and established the Phi Tau Phi Scholastic Honor Society of America. He published numerous research papers and books during his lifetime. Li passed away at the age of 88. He was also known as an active philatelist and a devout Southern Baptist.
Minodronic acid is a bisphosphonate drug. Minodronic acid is approved for use in Japan for the treatment of osteoporosis. The mechanism of action of Minodronic acid involves the inhibition of farnesyl pyrophosphate synthase activity.
"Dungeon Geomorphs is an accessory for the fantasy role-playing game Dungeons & Dragons."
The 1917 Dayton Triangles season was their seventh season in the Ohio League. The team posted a 5-1-2 record.
"Don Giovanni della Costa Azzurra /Beach Casanova is a 1962 Italian film directed by Vittorio Sala. The film stars Curd Jürgens, Annette Stroyberg, Martine Carol, and Gabriele Ferzetti."
"Lezioni di violoncello con toccata e fuga is a 1976 commedia sexy all'italiana film. The film stars actor Gabriele Ferzetti."
"Suggestionata is an Italian drama film. Suggestionata was directed by Alfredo Rizzo. The film stars Eleonora Giorgi and Gabriele Ferzetti."
"Basileus Quartet is an Italian film released in 1983. The film features actor Gabriele Ferzetti."
"Radisson Blu Daugava Hotel is a 4+ star hotel located in Riga, Latvia. It was the first hotel in the Baltic states to be managed by an international hotel brand after Latvia regained independence in 1991."
André-Pierre Nouvion is a French lawyer and historian of French law. He specializes in consular law and has published reference books on the law and history of consular institutions such as the Chamber of Commerce and Industry in France and the Commercial Court. He was a former Director of the Chamber of Commerce and Industry and has defended the French model of Chambers of Commerce during missions under the United Nations with the Cambodian and Mexican authorities. His work was used by the French Parliamentary Commission for the 2010 reform of the Chambers of Commerce and Industry. André-Pierre Nouvion holds a Doctor of Law and Political Science from Panthéon-Assas University and is a former auditor of the Institute of Higher National Defense Studies. His father, Henri Nouvion, was a researcher specializing in the treatment of tuberculosis, and his grandfather, Léon Faure, was a technical adviser to Mustafa Kemal Atatürk, the first president of the Turkish Republic.
"Pimpirev Ice Wall is an ice slope located near Emona Harbour in Livingston Island, Antarctica. It is approximately 50 meters high and extends 3,700 meters in a west-southwest direction from the north corner of Emona Harbour. The ice wall is named after Christo Pimpirev, who led the Bulgarian Antarctic campaigns in the 1990s and conducted geological field work on Alexander Island in 1987/88."
"Pioneer Heights is a group name in the Heritage Range, Ellsworth Mountains. It encompasses a large area of hills, ridges, and peaks located eastward of Schneider and Schanz Glaciers and between Splettstoesser and Union Glaciers. Among these features are the Inferno Ridge, Nimbus Hills, Gross, Buchanan, and Collier Hills. The Pioneer Heights were mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) from ground surveys and U.S. Navy air photos from 1961–66. The name was applied by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in association with the name Heritage Range."
Lucien Romier was a French journalist and politician. Lucien Romier was born in Moiré on October 19, 1885, and passed away in Vichy on January 5, 1944. He studied at the École des Chartes and wrote a thesis on Jacques d'Albon de Saint-André. Lucien Romier was a member of the French School in Rome. He had a successful career in journalism and served as the editor of the newspaper "Le Figaro" from 1925 to 1927 and again from 1934 to 1942. A personal friend of Pétain, he became a minister of State in Laval's fourth Ministry from April 18, 1942, to December 31, 1943. Unfortunately, he passed away due to a heart attack while being arrested by the Gestapo.
"Pirie Peninsula is a narrow peninsula located northward from the center of Laurie Island in the South Orkney Islands of Antarctica. The peninsula was surveyed in 1903 by the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition led by Bruce, who named it after Dr. Harvey Pirie, the surgeon and geologist of the expedition."
Piore Ridge is a prominent ridge located between Elder Glacier and Bowers Glacier in the Victory Mountains of Victoria Land. Piore Ridge is 11 nautical miles (20 km) long. Piore Ridge was mapped by the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (NZGSAE) in 1957–58 and the United States Geological Survey (USGS) in 1960–62. Piore Ridge was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Emanuel Ruben Piore, an American physicist who was a member of the National Science Board at the National Science Foundation from 1961 to 1972.
Polar Record Glacier is a glacier located between Meknattane Nunataks and Dodd Island, flowing towards the central part of Publications Ice Shelf. It was delineated in 1952 by John H. Roscoe from aerial photographs taken during U.S. Navy Operation Highjump in 1946–47. The glacier was named by Roscoe after the Research Institute in Cambridge, England.
"Ponce Island is located east of Ortiz Island and southeast of Largo Island in the Duroch Islands. The island is northeast of the Chilean scientific station, General Bernardo O'Higgins. Ponce Island was named by Martin Halpern, the leader of the University of Wisconsin field party during geological mapping of the area in 1961–62. The island was named in honor of Lautaro Ponce, Chief of Antarctic Operations at the University of Chile, as a token of appreciation for the Chilean logistical support provided to the Wisconsin field party."
"Pond Peak is an ice-free peak located at 1,430 m in the south side of the mouth of Baldwin Valley in Saint Johns Range, Victoria Land. Pond Peak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in 1964 after James D. Pond, a member of the U.S. Navy who was responsible for electronic repair and maintenance at Hallett Station in 1962."
Pontes Ridge is a mountain spur located eastward to McCraw Glacier, 4 nautical miles (7 km) south of Derrick Peak in Britannia Range. Pontes Ridge was named by a University of Waikato (N.Z.) geological party in 1978-79, led by Michael Selby. The name Pontes is associated with Roman Britain.
"Posey Range is a mountain range located in the eastern part of the Bowers Mountains. It is surrounded by the Smithson, Graveson, Lillie, and Champness Glaciers. The United States Geological Survey (USGS) mapped the area based on ground surveys and U.S. Navy air photos from 1960 to 1962. The range was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Julian W. Posey, a meteorologist who served as the scientific leader at South Pole Station during the winter party of 1959."
"Pothole Gulch is a gulch located on Vindication Island in the South Sandwich Islands. The gulch's bed is characterized by numerous potholes. The name was given by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in 1971."
"MacAlpine Hills are a chain of mainly ice-free, bluff-type hills in Antarctica. They extend from Mount Achernar southwestwards along the south side of Law Glacier to Sylwester Glacier. The hills were named after Ensign Kenneth D. MacAlpine, a member of U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6, who was injured in an airplane crash at McMurdo Sound in October 1956."
The 2011 Norwegian Football Cup was the 106th edition of the annual knockout football tournament in Norway. It started on April 6, 2011, with the first qualifying round matches and concluded on November 6, 2011, with the Final. Aalesund emerged as the winners and secured a spot in the second qualifying round of the 2012-13 UEFA Europa League.
Northern 911 is a company based in Sudbury, Ontario, Canada. Northern 911 provides 9-1-1 call centre services for VOIP & POTS providers such as Rogers Telecom, Primus Canada, and SaskTel as a Public Safety Answering Point. The company also offers fire dispatch, alarm monitoring, and telematics services. Northern 911 won the ATSI 2009 Award of Excellence and is the largest 911 provider in Canada.
"Het Brabants Orkest, also known as The Brabant Orchestra or The Europa Orchestra, was a Dutch symphony orchestra based in the province of North Brabant. The orchestra's principal concert venue was the Muziekgebouw Frits Philips in Eindhoven. They also performed at Theater aan de Parade in 's-Hertogenbosch, Concertzaal in Tilburg, and Chassé Theatre in Breda. The orchestra was founded in 1949 with Hein Jordans as its first chief conductor, followed by Lucas Vis, André Vandernoot, Arpad Joó, Marc Soustrot, and Alan Buribayev. In 2013, Het Brabants Orkest merged with Limburgs Symfonie Orkest to form the South Netherlands Philharmonic."
"Icaricia saepiolus, also known as the greenish blue, is a butterfly belonging to the family Lycaenidae. This species can be found in the northwestern United States, southern Saskatchewan, and Alberta. The wingspan of the greenish blue butterfly ranges from 21 to 28 mm. Adults of this species are active from June to August. The larvae of Icaricia saepiolus feed on plants such as Trifolium monathum, Trifolium longipes, and Trifolium wormskioldii."
Philip Moeller was an American stage producer, director, playwright, and screenwriter. He was born in New York and helped found the short-lived Washington Square Players. Along with Lawrence Langner and Helen Westley, he founded the Theatre Guild. Philip Moeller was educated at New York University and Columbia University.
"Preach Brother!" is an album by American saxophonist Don Wilkerson. The album was recorded in 1962 and released on the Blue Note label.
"We're Going to Eat You" is a 1980 Hong Kong horror comedy film directed by Tsui Hark. The film follows a secret agent named Agent 999 who is on a mission to capture a thief named Rolex. Agent 999's pursuit leads him to a village inhabited by cannibals. The film did not achieve the same level of success in Hong Kong as Tsui's later 1980 film "Dangerous Encounters of the First Kind".
"Artelida caligata is a species of the Lepturinae subfamily in the long-horned beetle family. This beetle is specifically found on the island of Madagascar."
Desmocerus californicus is a species of the Lepturinae subfamily in the long-horned beetle family. This species is found in the United States. The adult beetle primarily feeds on the pollen of "Sambucus" species.
"Piney Branch is a tributary of Rock Creek in Washington, D.C. Piney Branch is the largest tributary located entirely within the Washington city limits."
Carl Nielsen composed a rhapsody overture titled "An Imaginary Trip to the Faroe Islands" ("En Fantasirejse til Færøerne") for orchestra. The Royal Danish Theatre in Copenhagen commissioned this piece for a gala concert celebrating a visit from the Faroe Islands. The composer, Carl Nielsen, conducted the premiere of the piece on November 27, 1927.
Darrell Ioane is an American Samoan football player. Darrell Ioane was born on February 8, 1981. Darrell Ioane has played for the American Samoa national team.
Acmaeops proteus is a species of the Lepturinae subfamily in the long-horned beetle family. This beetle is distributed in Canada, Mexico, and the United States. Fungi, specifically "Paecilomyces farinosus," are entomopathogenic species that parasitize on adult beetles.
The Mount Whaleback mine is an iron ore mine located in the Pilbara region of Western Australia, specifically 6 kilometres west of Newman. The mine is majority-owned (85 percent) and operated by BHP. BHP also operates two port facilities at Port Hedland, specifically Nelson Point and Finucane Island, as well as over 1,000 kilometres of rail in the Pilbara. BHP is the second-largest iron ore mining company in the Pilbara, following Rio Tinto and preceding the Fortescue Metals Group. As of 2010, BHP employs 8,000 people in its Pilbara operations.
"Pothara Dam is an earthfill dam located on the Pothara river near Hinganghat in the Wardha district of Maharashtra, India."
Shahanoor Dam is an earthfill dam located on the Shahanoor river near Anjangaon Surji in the Amravati district of Maharashtra, India.
"Bajo Martín is a comarca in Aragon. Bajo Martín is located in Teruel Province, in the historical region of Lower Aragon. It is situated in the transitional area between the Iberian System and the Ebro Valley. The comarca borders Ribera Baja del Ebro, Campo de Belchite, Cuencas Mineras, Andorra-Sierra de Arcos, Bajo Aragón, and Bajo Aragón-Caspe. The name Bajo Martín comes from the Martín River, a right-side tributary of the Ebro that flows through the comarca."
"Pentakali Dam is an earthfill dam located on the Penganga river near Mehkar in the Buldhana district of Maharashtra, India."
Sina Kolegaon Dam is a dam located on the Sina River near Paranda in the Osmanabad district of Maharashtra, India.
Mehmet Ali Daylak is a Turkish wrestler. Mehmet Ali Daylak competed at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore. Mehmet Ali Daylak won the bronze medal in the boys' freestyle 54 kg event. Mehmet Ali Daylak defeated Yerzon Hernandez of Colombia in the bronze medal match.
"Jamkhed Dam is an earthfill dam located near Mukhed in Nanded district, Maharashtra, India. It is built on a local river."
"Comme un cheveu sur la soupe is a French comedy film from 1957. The film was directed by Maurice Regamey and written by Yvan Audouard, starring Louis de Funès. Shooting took place at the Franstudio film studios from December 26, 1956, until February 12, 1957. The film is also known as "Crazy in the Noodle" or "Kindly Kill Me" in the USA."
The Cabanada or War of Cabanos was a rebellion that took place in Brazil between 1832 and 1835. It began shortly after the abdication of Dom Pedro I, during the Regency period.
"Garret K. Osborn House and Barn is a historic site located in Saddle River, Bergen County, New Jersey, United States. The house was constructed in 1835 and was officially listed on the National Register of Historic Places on August 29, 1986."
Michael Linden is a German psychiatrist and professor of psychiatry, psychosomatic medicine, and psychotherapy at the Charité University Hospital in Berlin. He was born on July 30, 1948, in Simmern/Hunsrück in Rheinland-Pfalz. Michael Linden was the first to publish on Post-traumatic embitterment disorders. He is also the editor of the journals "Primary Care Psychiatry", "Rehabilitation", "Pharmacopsychiatry", and the "Journal of Cognitive Psychotherapy". In 1997, he received the Research Award in Psychogeriatrics from the International Psychogeriatric Association. Michael Linden is married to Evelyn Linden and has two sons and one daughter. He is a member of the Roman-Catholic parish of Mater Dolorosa in Berlin-Lankwitz and served on the board of directors of the legal, independent foundation Stiftung Mater Dolorosa Berlin-Lankwitz from 2009 to 2014.
Component-based usability testing (CBUT) is a testing approach that focuses on empirically testing the usability of an interaction component. An interaction component is considered as an elementary unit of an interactive system that allows for behavior-based evaluation. These components, such as radio buttons, sliders, or entire word processor applications, need to have an independent, user-perceivable, and controllable state. CBUT is a part of the component-based software engineering branch of software engineering.
"The Jakkals is an agile weapon carrier and utility vehicle designed for airborne units of the South African Defence Force and South African National Defence Force. It can be deployed by land, lifted by helicopter, air dropped, or delivered via aircraft. The weapons mounted on the Jakkals include the 106mm M40 recoilless rifle, M2 Browning heavy machine gun, various general purpose machine guns, and it can also act as a tractor for the Valkiri-5 multiple rocket launcher or anti-aircraft guns like the ZU-23-2. Additionally, it can be used with a small trailer for logistical support, especially for the 120mm mortars used in airborne artillery operations. The Jakkals has been utilized in defense operations by the South African Airborne Units during the South African Border Wars."
Alex Nodari is an Italian footballer. Alex Nodari plays for Riccione in Eccellenza Emilia-Romagna. Alex Nodari was born on February 15, 1982. Riccione is a football club based in Italy. Eccellenza Emilia-Romagna is a football league in Italy.
Blennophis striatus is a species of clinid known as the Striped klipfish. It is found in the subtropical waters of the Atlantic Ocean, specifically from Saldanha Bay to East London in South Africa. This species can be found in the subtidal zone as well as in tidepools. Blennophis striatus can reach a maximum length of TL.
"Ballygalget GAA is a Gaelic Athletic Association club. Ballygalget GAA is located in The Ards Peninsula in County Down, Northern Ireland. The club's main focus is on the game of hurling."
Rolf Milser is a German weightlifter. Rolf Milser was born on June 28, 1951. Rolf Milser competed in the Olympics in 1972, 1976, and 1984. Rolf Milser won the gold medal in the heavyweight I class in 1984. Rolf Milser won two world titles in 1978 and 1984. Rolf Milser set two world records in the clean & jerk in 1976 and 1979. Rolf Milser also won a European title in 1979.
"Friedrich Franek was an Austrian general in the armed forces of Nazi Germany during World War II. Friedrich Franek was born on July 16, 1891, and passed away on April 8, 1976. Along with Alois Windisch, Friedrich Franek was one of only two recipients of both the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross and the Knight's Cross of the Military Order of Maria Theresa. Friedrich Franek's father was a master baker. Friedrich Franek joined the Austro-Hungarian Army in 1910 and served with distinction in World War I, winning the Gold Medal for Bravery. On June 10, 1921, the Chapter of the Military Order of Maria Theresa awarded Friedrich Franek the Knight's Cross of the said Order in recognition of his conduct during the 11th Battle of the Isonzo. After the end of the war, Friedrich Franek remained in the army of the newly established Austrian republic. In 1925, Friedrich Franek graduated with a PhD in political science. After the Anschluss, Friedrich Franek transferred to the German armed forces. In the summer of 1944, Friedrich Franek was commanding the German 73rd Infantry Division as the Red Army was advancing through Poland. At the end of July, during the Lublin–Brest Offensive, Friedrich Franek joined battle at Garwolin with the Soviet 2nd Guards Tank Army under the command of Alexei Radzievsky, when the German forces were routed and Friedrich Franek was taken prisoner. Friedrich Franek was released in 1948."
"Jan Van Imschoot is a Belgian contemporary artist. Jan Van Imschoot was born in Ghent in 1963. Jan Van Imschoot's works are collected by various international museums. Jan Van Imschoot is represented by major galleries including Galerie Daniel Templon in Paris, Brussels, Switzerland, and Los Angeles. Jan Van Imschoot has received several awards in contemporary art. Jan Van Imschoot studied at the Stedelijk Secundair Kunstinstituut Gent (Municipal Secondary Art Institute of Ghent) and the Koninklijke Academie voor Schone Kunsten (Royal Academy of Fine Arts). Jan Van Imschoot significantly contributed to the discovery of the now very popular Flemish painter Michaël Borremans."
Lectionary 298, also known as Gregory-Aland, is a Greek manuscript of the New Testament written on parchment. It dates back to the 14th century and has complex contents.
"The William Goold House is a historic house located at 280 Windham Center Road in Windham, Maine. The house was originally built in 1775 and later rebuilt in 1802. William Goold, a prominent 19th-century historian of the state of Maine and a state senator, lived in this house for a long time. The William Goold House was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in August 1990."
"Daniel Braun is a German author and computer scientist. Daniel Braun is a writer and a professional in the field of computer science."
Sanda Thudamma or Shrichandra Sudhormo was an Arakanese king of the Mrauk U Kingdom. He was a controversial figure among Muslims in the Indian Subcontinent, described as an immoral ruler and womanizer. His atrocities included betrayal of the Mughal prince and Governor of Bengal Subah, Shah Shuja, murder of his three sons, rape and forced suicide of his daughter Banu Begum, and imprisonment of the pregnant daughter of King Narapdigyi who was starved to death. The Bengali poet Syed Alaol was in his court and translated Tohfa at his request. Prince Magan Thakur was the foster-son of the sister of King Shrichondro Sudhormo, and Saiyad Muhammad Musa was his army chief. In 1664, emperor Aurangzeb appointed Shaista Khan of Bengal to capture Sanda Thudamma, who was eventually captured in 1666. Chittagong remained a key port throughout Mughal rule.
Marti Emerald is a California politician and former television journalist. Marti Emerald served on the San Diego City Council in San Diego, California. She represented Council District 7 from 2008 to 2012 and Council District 9 from 2012 to 2016. Marti Emerald is affiliated with the Democratic Party, even though City Council positions are officially nonpartisan according to California state law.
The Action of 6 June 1942 was a single ship action fought during World War II. The German raider encountered and sank the American tanker while cruising in the South Atlantic Ocean off Brazil.
"Younger Us" is a 7" single by Canadian rock duo Japandroids. It was released by Polyvinyl Record Co. on July 20, 2010. The initial pressing was limited to 2500 copies on clear vinyl. The song has been later included on Japandroids' second album "Celebration Rock". Pitchfork Media awarded the song "Younger Us" a 'Best New Music' designation and ranked it #42 on its list of top 100 singles of 2010.
Konjiška Vas is a settlement in the Municipality of Slovenske Konjice in eastern Slovenia. It is located at the foot of the eastern end of the Mount Konjice hills southeast of Slovenske Konjice. The area is part of the traditional region of Styria. The municipality is now included in the Savinja Statistical Region. A Roman-era archaeological site in the hamlet of Podmočle in the settlement has been partially excavated and identified as a possible site of a Villa rustica.
The Strathglass Park District is located in Rumford, Maine. It is one of the nation's finest early 20th-century mill worker housing complexes. The district was funded by Hugh J. Chisholm, the owner of Rumford's paper mill, and designed by Cass Gilbert. It consists of 50 high-quality brick duplexes, built in 1901-2 on tree-lined streets with a small park at the center. In 1974, the district was listed on the National Register of Historic Places. Only one of the Gilbert-designed houses had been destroyed by that time. The company sold off the houses in the late 1940s, with most being purchased by their occupants.
Paramartyria baishanzuna is a species of moth. Paramartyria baishanzuna belongs to the family Micropterigidae. Paramartyria baishanzuna was described by Yang in 1995. Paramartyria baishanzuna is known from Mount Baishanzu in the Zhejiang Province of China.
Chuxiongosaurus is a genus of basal sauropodomorph dinosaur. Chuxiongosaurus lived during the Early Jurassic Period. Fossils of Chuxiongosaurus have been found in the Lower Lufeng Formation in Yunnan Province, southern China. The holotype of Chuxiongosaurus is CMY LT9401, which is a nearly complete skull with some similarities to Thecodontosaurus. Chuxiongosaurus was described as the first basal sauropod dinosaur from the Early Jurassic of China, more basal than Anchisaurus. Chuxiongosaurus was named by Lü Junchang, Yoshitsugu Kobayashi, Li Tianguang, and Zhong Shimin in 2010, and the type species is Chuxiongosaurus lufengensis.
Mahmoud Khamees Al-Hammadi is an association football player. Mahmoud Khamees Al-Hammadi is from the United Arab Emirates. Mahmoud Khamees Al-Hammadi plays for Al-Nasr. Mahmoud Khamees Al-Hammadi was born on October 28, 1987. Al-Nasr is a football club. Al-Nasr is based in the United Arab Emirates.
"Mrs. Brown's Boys" is a television sitcom created by Brendan O'Carroll and produced in the United Kingdom by BBC Scotland in partnership with BocPix and Irish broadcaster RTÉ. O'Carroll stars as his drag persona, Agnes Brown, with several close friends and family members making up the rest of the cast. The show adopts an informal production style where production mistakes and tomfoolery, mostly instigated by O'Carroll, are edited into each episode. Despite being criticized by critics, the show has become a ratings success in Ireland, Scotland, Australia, New Zealand, and Canada. It has also won numerous awards. The character, Agnes Browne, first appeared in stage plays, radio plays, books, and straight-to-DVD films. A stage show has continued to run, and a feature film, "Mrs. Brown's Boys D'Movie", was released on 27 June 2014.
"Nerkattumseval, also known as Nelkattanseval and called Nellitangaville by the British, is one of the 72 palaiyams of Madura. It has been in existence since the days of Nagama Nayaka and his son Visvanatha Nayaka. Nerkattumseval is located in the Sankarankovil taluk in the Tenkasi District of Tamil Nadu."
"Don Juan IV Coloma y Cardona, 1st Count of Elda, was a Spanish nobleman who held various titles and positions. He was born around 1522 in Elda, a province of Alicante, Spain, and passed away on October 19, 1586. He also served as the 3rd Sieur of Elda, Governor of Alicante Castle, Count of Elda, and Viceroy of Sardinia from 1570 to 1577."
Meaus is a village in the municipality of Baltar, Ourense, Galiza. The census for 2007 showed 38 inhabitants, with 19 men and 19 women. Until 1868, Meaus, Santiago, and Rubiás formed a "de facto" independent state called Couto Misto.
Northleigh is a village and civil parish in the East Devon district of Devon, England. Its nearest town is Colyton, which lies approximately south-east from the village. The church of St Giles was built in the Perpendicular style and has a western tower. Features of interest are the plain Norman south doorway, two screens, one to the chancel and one to the north chancel chapel, and the Jacobean pulpit. It is a grade II* listed building.
Evgeny Skachkov is a Russian professional ice hockey winger. Evgeny Skachkov was born on July 14, 1984. Evgeny Skachkov currently plays for HC Ugra in the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL). Evgeny Skachkov was selected by the St. Louis Blues in the 7th round (221st overall) of the 2003 NHL Entry Draft. Skachkov made his KHL debut playing with Traktor Chelyabinsk during the 2008–09 season.
Kyle Uyehara is a U.S. short track speed skater. Kyle Uyehara was born on November 27, 1989 in Whittier, California. Kyle Uyehara has been skating for 13 years.
The Waveney-class lifeboat was the first class of lifeboats operated by the Royal National Lifeboat Institution (RNLI). It was capable of operating at speeds in excess of . The class saw operational service between 1964 and 1999 at the RNLI's stations around the coast of the United Kingdom and Ireland. After being superseded by faster boats in the 1990s, many were sold for further use with lifeboat services abroad, notably in Australia and New Zealand. The class name comes from the River Waveney, which discharges into the North Sea at Great Yarmouth.
"Aridhu Aridhu is an Indian Tamil-language drama film. Aridhu Aridhu was written and directed by K. R. Mathivanan, who was an assistant of director Shankar and this was his first directorial venture. The film was produced by Jaya Krishnan under the banner JK Creations. The lead cast of the movie includes Harish Kalyan and Uttara Raj, both making their debuts. Thaman composed the music for the film under the audio label Five Star Audios. Aridhu Aridhu was released on December 24, 2010, but unfortunately, it performed poorly at the box office."
Rahkeim Calief Meyer is an American rapper, songwriter, and producer. Rahkeim Calief Meyer was born on February 11, 1978. Rahkeim Calief Meyer is also known by his stage name Roc Marciano.
James Arthur Mathewson was a Canadian politician. He was born in Montreal, Quebec. Mathewson received a Bachelor of Arts degree in 1912 and a Bachelor of Civil Law degree in 1917 from McGill University. He was called to the Quebec Bar in 1917. During World War I, he served as a captain in the 42nd Battalion Royal Highlanders of Canada. After the war, he practiced law in Montreal and was appointed a King's Counsel in 1926. Mathewson was a member of the Montreal City Council for Saint-André from 1926 to 1930. He ran for mayor in 1930 but lost to Camillien Houde. From 1939 to 1948, he served as the Liberal member of the Legislative Assembly of Quebec for Montréal–Notre-Dame-de-Grâce and was the treasurer of Quebec from 1939 to 1944. In 1943, he was awarded an honorary doctorate degree from McGill University.
Vital Kibuk is a Belarusian professional football player. Vital Kibuk was born on January 7, 1989. Vital Kibuk currently plays for Volna Pinsk.
Alexei Vorontsov is a Kazakhstani professional ice hockey forward. Alexei Vorontsov was born on January 18, 1986. Alexei Vorontsov currently plays for Barys Astana in the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL). Alexei Vorontsov represented the Kazakhstan men's national ice hockey team at the 2010 IIHF World Championship. Barys Astana is a team in the KHL.
Denis Tyurin is a Russian professional ice hockey winger. Denis Tyurin currently plays for HC Sibir Novosibirsk in the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL). Denis Tyurin was born on June 3, 1980. HC Sibir Novosibirsk is a team in the KHL.
Vid Belec is a Slovenian professional footballer. Vid Belec was born on June 6, 1990. Vid Belec plays as a goalkeeper in Italy for Salernitana. Salernitana is a football club based in Italy.
Kirill Koltsov is a Russian professional ice hockey defenceman. Kirill Koltsov was born on February 1, 1983. Kirill Koltsov is currently an unrestricted free agent. Kirill Koltsov most recently played with Avtomobilist Yekaterinburg of the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL). Kirill Koltsov was selected by the Vancouver Canucks in the 2nd round (49th overall) of the 2002 NHL Entry Draft.
The Lundby Old Church is a church located in Lundby, a borough of Gothenburg, Sweden. It is one of the seven preserved medieval churches in Gothenburg and the only one representing Gothic architecture. The church dates back to the 14th century, with the bell tower being added in 1634. It has undergone multiple renovations, with the most recent one in 1998. The church features coats of arms belonging to noble families such as Cronacker, Eketrä, Stålhandske, and Ihre. The Stålhandske and Ihre families constructed their own grave chapels on the southern wall, with the Ihre chapel still intact today. The Stålhandske chapel was demolished, and the coffins were relocated to the family grave in the churchyard.
"Pikesville Arsenal was a 19th-century fortification near Pikesville, Maryland. Pikesville Arsenal was under the control of the United States Army Ordnance Department."
"When the Last Morning Glory Blooms" is an album by American musician Peter Ostroushko. The album was released in 2010.
"Sergei Nemolodyshev is a Russian professional ice hockey winger. Sergei Nemolodyshev was born on March 30, 1985. Sergei Nemolodyshev currently plays for Avtomobilist Yekaterinburg in the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL)."
"Viktor Kalachik is a Russian professional ice hockey forward. Viktor Kalachik currently plays for Avtomobilist Yekaterinburg in the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL)."
"Mikhail Tyulyapkin is a Russian former professional ice hockey defenceman. Mikhail Tyulyapkin played with Amur Khabarovsk of the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL) before being released due to injury. Mikhail Tyulyapkin also played for Atlant Moscow Oblast of the KHL. Mikhail Tyulyapkin was selected by the Minnesota Wild in the 9th round (268th overall) of the 2002 NHL Entry Draft."
Denis Platonov is a Russian former professional ice hockey centre. Denis Platonov was born on November 6, 1981. Denis Platonov played for Metallurg Magnitogorsk of the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL). Denis Platonov was selected by the Nashville Predators in the 3rd round (75th overall) of the 2001 NHL Entry Draft. After the 2018–19 season with Metallurg Magnitogorsk, where he played only 24 games due to injury, Denis Platonov retired from his 21-year professional career and expressed interest in pursuing coaching.
"Euryte is a name in Greek mythology. Euryte means "width" in Ancient Greek. Euryte is associated with the following women: Euryte, the nymph mother of Halirrhothius by Poseidon, who may also be known as Bathycleia. Euryte is also the daughter of Hippodamas and granddaughter of Achelous. She was the mother of Oeneus, Agrius, Leucopeus, Melas, Alcathous, and Sterope by King Porthaon of Calydon."
Marat Fakhrutdinov is a Russian professional ice hockey forward. Marat Fakhrutdinov was born on November 27, 1988. Marat Fakhrutdinov currently plays with Traktor Chelyabinsk in the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL). Marat Fakhrutdinov previously played with HC Severstal in the KHL. In the 2014–15 season, Marat Fakhrutdinov played with HC Lada Togliatti before joining Traktor Chelyabinsk on November 16, 2014.
Klaus-Günter Stade is a German former professional footballer. Klaus-Günter Stade was born on May 24, 1953. Klaus-Günter Stade played in the Fußball-Bundesliga for Tennis Borussia Berlin and made a total of 3 appearances during his career.
Joseph Lamothe was the provisional President of Haiti from 26 July 1879 to 2 October 1879, when he was succeeded by Lysius Salomon. Following a stormy debate in the House of Representatives on 30 June 1879, there were riots in Port-au-Prince in which the Liberal leader Jean-Pierre Boyer-Bazelais exerted a significant role. President Pierre Théoma Boisrond-Canal resigned as president on 17 July 1879, unable to mediate between the Liberal and National parties. Lamothe was then appointed as provisional president. Solomon returned from exile in August 1879 and was brought on as president soon after.
"Abaciscus tristis is a moth species from the Geometridae family. Abaciscus tristis is the type species of the genus Abaciscus. It was described by Arthur Gardiner Butler in 1889. Abaciscus tristis is found in the Himalaya, western and southern China, Taiwan, and Borneo. It is primarily found in upper montane forests at altitudes ranging from 1,000 to 2,000 meters."
Inn signs have a history that extends beyond the Middle Ages. Houses were identified by a sign, often a heraldic charge, signifying that the premises were under the special care of a nobleman or a vivid image. The ruins of Herculaneum and Pompeii reveal that most of their street-front shops displayed an identifying sign outside. In Ireland and the United Kingdom, the tradition by which publicans were obliged to identify their premises by a sign, dating from the reign of Richard II, is carried on today. A selection of inn signs carved on slabs and rescued after the Great Fire of London is preserved in the Guildhall.
The Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Costume Design is an award given to individuals in the motion picture industry by the Broadcast Film Critics Association at the annual Critics' Choice Movie Awards. This award was first introduced in 2009. It is noteworthy that in 2016 and 2019, the winner of this award did not align with the winner of the Academy Award for Best Costume Design.
"Boil Point is located on the west side of the entrance to Retizhe Cove on the south coast of Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, Antarctica. Boil Point is named after the settlement of Boil in Northeastern Bulgaria."
The Battle of Tres Forcas took place on 7 August 1856 between boat crews from the Prussian Navy corvette SMS "Danzig" and the Berber Riffians at Cape Tres Forcas in Morocco. It was one of the first instances of Prussian or German gunboat diplomacy. The Treaty of Paris of 1856 had mandated a Prussian warship to be stationed at the River Danube's outlet into the Black Sea, but Prince Adalbert of Prussia, commanding the "Danzig," decided to explore the Rif coast of Morocco on the way. The Prussian warship "Flora" had previously been attacked by pirates in the same area in 1852. On 7 August 1856, Prince Adalbert led a landing operation with 14 officers and 53 non-commissioned officers, sailors, and marines after the boat crews came under fire. Despite initial success in forcing the Riffians back, continuous enemy reinforcements led to a Prussian withdrawal. The Prussian casualties included seven dead and 22 wounded, with Adalbert himself sustaining a thigh injury. A monument was later erected in Gibraltar in memory of the fallen. Despite the tactical failure, Adalbert and his sailors' bravery was praised by the Prussian people and the German Imperial navies.
"Glashütten bei Schlaining is an Austrian dependent hamlet in Burgenland. The official Hungarian placename until 1899 was Szalonok-Üveghuta. The village is located in the municipality of Unterkohlstätten within Oberwart district. It is situated on a narrow road in the forested area of the Kőszeg Mountains, 12 km from Oberwart. The road is part of a 19-km bicycle path (B 58–Kohlstatt) that includes Goberling, Unterkohlstätten, Holzschlag, Günseck, and Weissenbachl."
Charles Abraham Chasselat is a French historical painter. Charles Abraham Chasselat was born in Paris in 1782. Charles Abraham Chasselat was the son of Pierre Chasselat. Charles Abraham Chasselat became a pupil of his father and Vincent. In 1812, Charles Abraham Chasselat exhibited 'The Repose of Belisarius.' Charles Abraham Chasselat illustrated the works of Voltaire, Racine, Molière, and other authors. Charles Abraham Chasselat also worked on the first French translations of Jane Austen's novels in the 1820s. Charles Abraham Chasselat was involved in making drawings of state ceremonials, such as the 'Funeral of Louis XVIII' and the 'Coronation of Charles X.' Charles Abraham Chasselat passed away in Paris in 1843. Charles Abraham Chasselat's son, Henri Jean Saint-Ange Chasselat (1813-1880), was a pupil of Lethière and painted historical and genre subjects.
Verbania-Pallanza railway station serves the city and comune of Verbania, in the Piedmont region, northwestern Italy. The station was opened in 1905 and is part of the Milan-Domodossola railway. It is currently managed by Rete Ferroviaria Italiana (RFI), while the commercial area of the passenger building is managed by Centostazioni. Train services at the station are operated by Trenitalia, which is a subsidiary of Ferrovie dello Stato (FS), Italy's state-owned rail company.
The Moses Hepburn Rowhouses are a set of four historic rowhouses in Alexandria, Virginia, United States. They were built around 1850 and are two-story, two bay, side hall plan dwellings. Originally identical, the unit at 206 N. Pitt St. was updated in the late-19th century. Each has had one- or two-story additions in the rear. Moses Hepburn, a prominent African American businessman and citizen, was associated with these rowhouses. They were added to the National Register of Historic Places in 2004.
Derrick Cawthorne is a British fencer. Derrick Cawthorne was born on April 24, 1931. Derrick Cawthorne competed in the team foil event at the 1964 Summer Olympics.
Edward Ayscu, also known as Ayscough or Askew, was an English historian. He was educated at Christ's College, Cambridge, where he graduated B.A. in 1586-1587. Ayscu resided in Cotham, Lincolnshire, and dated the preface to his only work in London in 1607. It is important to note that Ayscu should not be confused with his cousin, Sir Edward Ayscu of South Kelsey.
Dalgliesh Bay is a bay located between Lainez Point and Bongrain Point on the west side of Pourquoi Pas Island, off the west coast of Graham Land. It was first surveyed in 1936 by the British Graham Land Expedition led by John Rymill. The bay was later resurveyed in 1948 by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) and named after David G. Dalgliesh, who was the FIDS medical officer at Stonington Island in 1948–49 and accompanied the 1948 sledge survey party to this area.
Mount Darnley is a mountain located in the south-central portion of Bristol Island in the South Sandwich Islands off Antarctica. It was charted in 1930 by Discovery Investigations personnel on the "Discovery II" and was named after E.R. Darnley.
The Davis Nunataks are a small cluster of rock nunataks northwest of Mount Ward, which is a southern outlier of the Dominion Range. The group was named after Ronald N. Davis by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names. Ronald N. Davis was a geomagnetist-seismologist with the United States Antarctic Research Program at South Pole Station during the winter of 1963.
DeBusk Scarp is a rock cliff located at the south side of the mouth of Bingham Glacier in Palmer Land, Antarctica. This feature was first photographed from the air in 1928 by Sir Hubert Wilkins and again in 1940 by members of the United States Antarctic Service. It was also surveyed by the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition (RARE) in 1947-48, led by Finn Ronne, who named it after Clarence DeBusk, the executive secretary of the Chamber of Commerce in Beaumont, Texas, for his assistance to the expedition.
The Jule Peaks are a small group of isolated peaks located about west-northwest of Borg Mountain in Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. They were mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos by the Norwegian–British–Swedish Antarctic Expedition (1949–52) and named Juletoppane (the Christmas peaks). The Annandags Peaks sit about 15 nautical miles (30 km) southwest.
"Joyce Peak is a peak located in Ross Island, Antarctica. Joyce Peak rises to over in the northern central part of Ross Island. It stands west of the main summits of Giggenbach Ridge and south-southeast of Wyandot Point. Joyce Peak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in 2000. The peak was named after Karen Joyce, who was a long-term employee of Antarctic Support Associates. Karen Joyce made 22 deployments to McMurdo Station, including a winter-over, and assisted with computers in the Crary Science and Engineering Center."
In the branch of abstract algebra known as ring theory, the Akizuki–Hopkins–Levitzki theorem establishes a connection between the descending chain condition and ascending chain condition in modules over semiprimary rings. A ring "R" (with 1) is considered semiprimary if "R"/"J"("R") is semisimple and "J"("R") is a nilpotent ideal, where "J"("R") represents the Jacobson radical. The theorem asserts that in a semiprimary ring "R" with module "M", the conditions of being Noetherian, Artinian, and having a composition series are equivalent. Without the semiprimary condition, the only true implication is that if "M" has a composition series, then "M" is both Noetherian and Artinian. The theorem was formulated in a 1939 paper by Charles Hopkins and Jacob Levitzki, hence often referred to as the Hopkins–Levitzki theorem. Yasuo Akizuki is sometimes credited as well for proving the result for commutative rings in 1935. As it is established that right Artinian rings are semiprimary, a direct consequence of the theorem is that a right Artinian ring is also right Noetherian. The same holds true for left Artinian rings. However, this does not apply universally to Artinian modules, as there exist examples of Artinian modules that are not Noetherian. Another immediate implication is that if "R" is right Artinian, then "R" is left Artinian if and only if it is left Noetherian.
John Nunatak is an isolated granite nunatak in Antarctica, located north of the Pirrit Hills. The nunatak was examined by geologists Edward Thiel and Campbell Craddock from the United States Antarctic Research Program on December 13, 1959, during an airlifted geophysical traverse along the 88th meridian West. It was named after steelworker Orlan F. John, U.S. Navy, who tragically lost his life in a construction accident at McMurdo Sound on November 2, 1960.
"If It Wasn't for the Nights" is a song recorded in 1978 by the Swedish pop group ABBA for their sixth studio album, "Voulez-Vous". The working title of the song was "Pandemonium". ABBA is a Swedish pop group. "Voulez-Vous" is their sixth studio album.
"Jeroboam Glacier is a glacier located in the north foothills of Mount Sara Teodora in Antarctica. It is a southwestern tributary glacier that joins Starbuck Glacier just east of Gabriel Peak in the Aristotle Mountains, on the east side of Graham Land. The toponym Jeroboam Glacier was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee, inspired by Herman Melville's "Moby-Dick". In the novel, "Jeroboam" refers to the ship that met the "Pequod"."
Demay Point is a headland located on the west side of the entrance to Admiralty Bay, King George Island, in the South Shetland Islands. This point was discovered by sealers in 1822 and later named by the French Antarctic Expedition, 1908–10, led by Jean-Baptiste Charcot. There is a Polish refuge at Demay Point, but it is uncertain whether it is currently in use.
Jefford Point is a point located on James Ross Island, Antarctica. It was first surveyed by the Swedish Antarctic Expedition, 1901–04, under Otto Nordenskjold. The point was later resurveyed by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) in 1948 and again in 1952. Jefford Point was named after Brian Jefford, a FIDS surveyor who worked at Hope Bay in 1948 and Admiralty Bay in 1949.
Jeanne Hill is a hill located northwest of Mount Guéguen and overlooking Port Charcot on Booth Island in the Wilhelm Archipelago, Antarctica. It was discovered by the French Antarctic Expedition, 1903–05, led by Dr. Jean-Baptiste Charcot, who named it after his sister.
The Departure Rocks are a group of 4 steep-sided rocks located north of Peake-Jones Rock in Holme Bay, Mac. Robertson Land. These rocks were mapped by Norwegian cartographers based on air photos taken during the Lars Christensen Expedition, 1936–37. They were named by the Antarctic Names Committee of Australia because Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions parties traveling west from Mawson Station on the sea ice always pass through or near these rocks.
Kyrkjetorget is a flattish ice-filled amphitheatre located on the east side of Jøkulkyrkja Mountain in the Mühlig-Hofmann Mountains of Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. It was mapped and named by the Sixth Norwegian Antarctic Expedition (1956–60).
"Kreitzer Glacier is a glacier located in Antarctica. Kreitzer Glacier flows northwest between Jennings Promontory and the Reinbolt Hills into the eastern part of the Amery Ice Shelf. Kreitzer Glacier was delineated in 1952 by John H. Roscoe from aerial photographs taken by U.S. Navy Operation Highjump, 1946–47. The glacier was named by Roscoe in honor of Lieutenant William R. Kreitzer, U.S. Navy, who was the commander of one of the three Operation Highjump aircraft used in photographing this and other coastal areas between 14°E and 164°E."
Interfor Corporation is one of the largest lumber producers in the world. The company's sawmilling operations have a combined manufacturing capacity of over 3 billion board feet of lumber with sales to North America, Asia-Pacific, and Europe. Interfor is based in Vancouver, BC and employs approximately 3400 people. In May 2014, Interfor opened its corporate office for the USA south-east region at Peachtree City, Georgia.
"Kvithovden Peak is a peak located at the north end of Kvitkjolen Ridge in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. The peak was photographed from the air by the Third German Antarctic Expedition (1938–39) and later mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos taken during the Norwegian–British–Swedish Antarctic Expedition (1949–52) and the Norwegian expedition (1958–59). It was named Kvithovden, which means 'the white peak'."
Krylen Hill is a hill located southwest of Valken Hill in the northern part of the Ahlmann Ridge in Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. It was mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos taken during the Norwegian–British–Swedish Antarctic Expedition (1949–52) and air photos from the Norwegian expedition (1958–59). Krylen Hill was named for its distinctive hump-like shape.
Mount Kurchatov is a peak located in the Humboldt Mountains of Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. It was discovered and plotted by the Third German Antarctic Expedition in 1938-39 and later mapped by the Sixth Norwegian Antarctic Expedition in 1956-60. The peak was remapped by the Soviet Antarctic Expedition in 1960-61 and named after Soviet academician I.V. Kurchatov.
"Kramer Island is an ice-covered island in the Marshall Archipelago, Antarctica. It is located between Nolan Island and Court Ridge on the Sulzberger Ice Shelf. The island was named after Michael S. Kramer, a meteorologist at Byrd Station, by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names. Kramer Island was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy from surveys and air photos taken between 1959 and 1965."
Kosky Peak is a peak located south of Mount Nordhill in the Welch Mountains of Palmer Land, Antarctica. The peak was mapped by the United States Geological Survey in 1974. It was named after Captain Harry G. Kosky, who was the Commanding Officer of the Antarctic Peninsula Ship Group during Operation Deep Freeze in 1971.
Mount Kostka is a mountain located on the west side of Zykov Glacier in the Anare Mountains of Antarctica. It was photographed during the U.S. Navy Operation Highjump in 1946–47 and surveyed by the Soviet Antarctic Expedition in 1958. The mountain was named after Czechoslovakian aerologist O. Kostka, who was a member of a later Soviet expedition and tragically died in a fire at Mirnyy Station on August 3, 1960.
Cape Kolosov is a point along the west side of the ice-covered peninsula that forms the east side of the entrance to Amundsen Bay, Antarctica. Cape Kolosov was photographed in 1956 from Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions aircraft and rephotographed in 1958 by a Soviet expedition. The cape was named after the polar aviation navigator V. Kolosov, who died in the Arctic.
Sunfix Glacier is a tributary glacier located in northern Palmer Land, Antarctica. It is 15 nautical miles long and 2 nautical miles wide, draining east-northeast between Grimley Glacier and Lurabee Glacier into Casey Glacier. The glacier was photographed from the air by the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition (RARE) on December 22, 1947, and surveyed by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) in November 1960. The name Sunfix Glacier comes from the important sun fix for latitude observed by FIDS at the head of this glacier, an area where cloud cover rarely allows such observations.
"She's Playing Hard to Forget" is a song written by Keith Stegall and Elroy Kahanek. The song was recorded by American country music artist Eddy Raven and released in June 1982 as the fourth single from the album "Desperate Dreams". It reached #10 on the "Billboard" Hot Country Singles & Tracks chart.
Fade Street is a reality television show produced by RTÉ Two in Ireland. The show follows the personal lives of a group of Dubliners, aged 20 to 29, who work in various jobs, some of which are associated with the Dublin-based "Stellar" magazine. The format of the show is loosely based on American reality-TV shows like "The Hills" and "The City". According to RTÉ, the show is unscripted and responses are spontaneous, although some scenes may be manipulated by the creators. The soundtrack of the show features songs from Irish music artists. In August 2011, the show was renewed for a second season on RTÉ 2 Television, excluding the webisodes portion on RTÉ Player.
Guiliam or Willem Backereel was a Flemish Baroque landscape painter. Guiliam or Willem Backereel was born in Antwerp in 1570 and passed away on August 10, 1626 in Rome.
Seikphyu is the principal town and administrative seat for Seikphyu Township in Pakokku District in the Magway Division of Myanmar. Seikphyu is located on the right bank of the Irrawaddy River, immediately below its confluence with the Yaw River. It is situated across the Irrawaddy river from Chauk and is connected by Anawrahta Bridge. Seikphyu is located 34 kilometers south-south-west of ancient Bagan City and 44 kilometers from Nyaung U Airport.
"The Mystery Trend was an American garage rock band formed in San Francisco, California in 1964. The band's music style leaned towards R&B, setting them apart from their contemporaries who later became psychedelic rock groups. The Mystery Trend's only single, "Johnny Was a Good Boy", was released in 1967."
Phyllocnistis stereograpta is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Phyllocnistis stereograpta is known from Maharashtra, India. The host plant for Phyllocnistis stereograpta is Stereospermum suaveolens. Phyllocnistis stereograpta mines the leaves of its host plant. The mine consists of a wandering gallery in the leaf.
La Tragedia del Vaquero is a studio album released by Mexican singer Vicente Fernández on November 14, 2006 by Sony Music. La Tragedia del Vaquero translates to "The Tragedy of the Cowboy".
"Narayani Temple is dedicated to the ten-armed goddess Narayani or Parvathi. It is located in Narayani village near Khalikote, Odisha, India. The temple is well-known for Durga Puja and a fair held in the Indian month of Chaitra. Renovated by the zamindars of Khalikote in the early 18th century, the temple follows the Khakhara Deula style similar to Vaital Deula. Believed to have been in existence before the 12th Century AD, the temple is admired for the scenic beauty of the surrounding countryside, including Chilika Lake."
Vítor Cruz de Jesus is a Brazilian footballer. Vítor Cruz de Jesus was born on February 1, 1987, in Vera Cruz, Bahia. Vítor Cruz de Jesus plays as a midfielder. Vítor Cruz de Jesus currently plays for Grêmio Catanduvense.
Adam Swift is a British political philosopher and sociologist. Adam Swift specializes in debates surrounding liberal egalitarianism. Adam Swift was born in 1961. Adam Swift has published books on communitarianism, on the philosophical aspects of school choice, on social justice, on the ethics of the family, and on how to make education policy, as well as an introduction to contemporary political philosophy.
"Under and In" is the only studio album by the shoegaze band Glifted. The album was released in 2002.
Stan Coster was an Australian country music singer-songwriter. Stan Coster was awarded the OAM. Stan Coster was born on May 27, 1930 and passed away on March 25, 1997. Stan Coster's songs were frequently performed by Slim Dusty and other artists. Tracy Coster, a country music singer, is the daughter of Stan Coster.
Stefan Pejic is a Welsh actor. Stefan Pejic was born in Swansea, Wales. Stefan Pejic was born on June 5, 1988. Swansea is a city in Wales.
"Caloptilia yasudai is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Caloptilia yasudai is found in Japan, specifically on the islands of Hokkaido and Honshu, as well as in Korea. The wingspan of Caloptilia yasudai ranges from 12 to 14.5 mm."
Otto Ehrenfried Ehlers was a German traveller known for his account of a long trip through inland Southeast Asia. His journey was documented in his 1894 book "Im Sattel durch Indochina", which has been recently republished by White Lotus Press of Thailand in English as a three-part series entitled "On Horseback Through Indochina". Otto Ehrenfried Ehlers lived from January 31, 1855, to October 3, 1895.
Diego Monar Firmino Martins, commonly known as Diego Monar, is a Brazilian footballer. Diego Monar plays for Real Noroeste as a Centre Back. Diego Monar Firmino Martins was born on February 15, 1989. Real Noroeste is the football club where Diego Monar plays.
Otto Wood was a Depression-era desperado born in Wilkes County, North Carolina in 1894. He began his life of crime at an early age, stealing a bicycle in North Wilkesboro. Wood hopped his first train at seven to visit relatives in West Virginia, where he learned various skills from the McCoy-feuding Hatfields. He suffered from a foot ailment and lost his left hand as a teenager, with conflicting reports on how it happened. Wood had multiple run-ins with the law for thefts and bootlegging, leading to incarcerations in several states. In 1923, he was convicted of second-degree murder and sentenced to 30 years in N.C. Central Prison. Despite multiple escapes, Wood was eventually killed by police officers in Salisbury, N.C. in 1930. The Carolina Buddies recorded a song about him, and a stage play about his life is produced annually in North Wilkesboro.
Transportes Aéreos da Índia Portuguesa (Air Transport of Portuguese India) or TAIP was an airline which operated from Portuguese India from 1955 to 1961. TAIP was created in 1955 as a public company linked to the General Government of the Portuguese India, initially named STAIP - Serviços de Transportes Aéreos da Índia Portuguesa (Air Transport Services of Portuguese India). The main objective of the creation of TAIP was to counteract the blockade that India had imposed upon Portugal's territories next to India, as part of Nehru's efforts to annex them. The creation of TAIP was accompanied by the development of airport facilities of Goa, Daman and Diu to allow the operation of large aircraft, allowing air links with these territories without any use of Indian infrastructure.
Mount Suggs is a mountain with a bare rock northern face. Mount Suggs is located 2 nautical miles (3.7 km) south of Mount Goodman in the Behrendt Mountains, Palmer Land. The mountain was mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos between 1961 and 1967. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in honor of Henry E. Suggs, an equipment operator of U.S. Navy Mobile Construction Battalion One, who took part in the deployment to the new Byrd Station during the summer of 1961-62.
Mike Arthur is an American former professional football player. Mike Arthur played as a center in the National Football League (NFL).
"Roger Eykyn was an English Liberal Party politician. Roger Eykyn served in the House of Commons from 1866 to 1874."
Saint Triduana, also known as Trodline, Tredwell, and in Norse as Trøllhaena, was an early Christian woman associated with various places in Scotland. She lived at an unknown time, probably between the 4th and 8th centuries CE. According to the 16th-century "Aberdeen Breviary," Triduana was born in the Greek city of Colosse and traveled from Constantinople with Saint Rule, who brought the bones of Saint Andrew to Scotland in the 4th century AD. A pious woman, she settled at Rescobie near Forfar in Angus, but her beauty attracted the attentions of a King of the Picts named Nectan. To stall these unwanted attentions, Triduana tore out her own eyes and gave them to Nechtan. Afterwards, she was associated with curing eye disorders. She spent her later years in Restalrig, Lothian, and healed the blind who came to her. She was buried at Restalrig when she died. The 17th-century "Acta Sanctorum" records a story of a blind English woman miraculously cured by Triduana. The saint appears to her in a dream and instructs her to travel to Restalrig. She does so and regains her sight at Triduana's tomb. The woman's daughter is later cured of blindness after praying to Triduana. In the 12th century, the Norse Earl of Orkney Harald Maddadsson punished bishop John of Caithness by having him blinded. According to the 13th-century Orkneyinga Saga, John prayed to "Trøllhaena" and later regained his sight when brought to her "resting place," possibly referring to a local northern shrine rather than Restalrig. The principal center of devotion to Triduana was at Restalrig, now part of Edinburgh. The parish church has been rebuilt, but the associated 15th-century St Triduana's Aisle (originally two-storeyed) survives. Other dedications to Triduana include chapels at Ballachly (Caithness), Loth (Sutherland), and on Papa Westray in Orkney. The Sicilian Saint Lucy is also said to have torn out her own eyes to put off an unwelcome suitor. In Buddhist scripture (Therigatha 14.1), the Buddhist nun Subha also removed her eye in response to admiration from a suitor. In that case, the act served as a lesson in non-attachment to worldly things.
The Mississippi Historical Society (MHS) is a historical society located in the U.S. state of Mississippi. The society was established in 1858 but was terminated due to the coming of the American Civil War. It remained in hiatus until 1890, publishing extensively over the next 35 years and helping to establish the Mississippi Department of Archives and History in 1902. After a second protracted hiatus, lasting from 1925 until 1952, the society re-emerged and has remained in continuous operation ever since. The society publishes the "Journal of Mississippi History" and the online publication "Mississippi History Now."
"Hurricane Beth was a tropical cyclone that occurred in August 1971. Hurricane Beth traveled from Florida to Nova Scotia. Hurricane Beth was the second named storm of the 1971 Atlantic hurricane season. Despite initially facing a cold environment, Hurricane Beth eventually developed into a Category 1 hurricane on the Saffir–Simpson Hurricane Scale. On August 16, Hurricane Beth made landfall in Nova Scotia before dissipating. The storm caused significant precipitation, leading to flooding that caused severe damage to infrastructure and crops."
"Machakos School, also known as Machakos High School, is a boys national school located in Machakos county, Kenya. The school was established in 1915 as a Boys’ Primary School at the current Machakos Girls grounds and was initially called African Government School. In 1939, it transitioned into a boys Secondary School, and in 1946, it became a mixed school with the admission of girls. The school used to educate students up to Form 2. The Principal at that time, Mr. Martin, led to the locals referring to the school as “KwaMatingi,” a corruption of “At Martins.” In 1950, the boys were relocated to the current site of Machakos School, which only admitted African students, leading to the name “GovernmentAfricanBoysSchool.” The first Foreign Principal in 1950 was Crowford, who served for 4 years."
"The Streets Were Not Paved With Gold: A Social History of Italians in Winnipeg" is a non-fiction book published in 1993 by Stanislaò "Stan" Carbone. The book was published by the Manitoba Italian Heritage Committee and focuses on the Italian Canadian community in Winnipeg, Manitoba. The title of the book refers to the misconception that Canada was a wealthy land, and Carbone argues that Italian immigrants struggled to adapt to the capitalist society in Canada.
"Dhak Manak is a village in Phagwara Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. It is located from Kapurthala, from Phagwara. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch who is an elected representative of village as per the constitution of India and Panchayati raj (India)."
Scholars Public School is a private higher-secondary co-education school located in the city of Patiala, Punjab, India. The school was established in 2002 and is affiliated with the Central Board of Secondary Education in India.
Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa is an Indian chess player. Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa is a chess prodigy. Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa achieved the title of Grandmaster (GM). Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa is the fourth-youngest person to achieve this title, following Sergey Karjakin, Gukesh D, and Javokhir Sindarov.
"One Hour of Happiness" is a German drama film released in 1931. The film was directed by William Dieterle and stars Evelyn Holt and Harald Paulsen. It was released by the German branch of Universal Pictures.
The Network of the Presidents of the Supreme Judicial Courts of the European Union is an association of the Presidents and Chief Justices of the Supreme Courts of the member states of the European Union. The Network was established on March 10, 2004, at the French Court of Cassation in Paris. Its members convene to discuss matters of common interest, exchange ideas and information, and provide a platform for European institutions to seek the opinions of Supreme Courts. The Network holds an annual colloquium and other meetings, and operates a shared portal for accessing the case law of the Supreme Courts. It also arranges internships for members of the Supreme Courts. The Network is headquartered at the French Court of Cassation in Paris and receives financial support from the European Union. Priit Pikamäe, president of the Supreme Court of Estonia, assumed the role of chair of the network in 2017, succeeding Susan Denham, the former Chief Justice of Ireland, who served as president from 2015. The presidents of the Supreme Courts of Liechtenstein, Montenegro, and Norway have observer status. The Presidents of the Court of Justice of the European Union and the European Court of Human Rights also participate in the general assemblies and colloquiums of the Network.
"When Lovers Part" is an American silent film produced by Kalem Company and directed by Sidney Olcott. The leading roles in the film are played by Gene Gauntier, Jack J. Clark, Robert Vignola, and JP McGowan. A copy of the film is preserved in the Desmet collection at Eye Film Institute in Amsterdam.
"Sarangwal is a village in Shahkot in Jalandhar district of Punjab State, India. Sarangwal is located from Shahkot, from Nakodar, from district headquarter Jalandhar, and from state capital Chandigarh. The village is administrated by a sarpanch who is an elected representative of the village as per Panchayati raj (India)."
Gerrit Lamberts was a Dutch painter and curator of the Rijksmuseum when it was located in the Trippenhuis. Lamberts was born in Amsterdam and was known for his work as a watercolorist, draughtsman, and engraver. He specialized in landscapes, architectural views, and watercolors of art galleries. In addition to his artistic pursuits, he was also a bookseller and became the curator of the museum in Amsterdam in 1825. He was a member of the Amsterdam academy and wrote a catalog of the book collection of Jacobus Koning in 1833. Lamberts passed away in Amsterdam.
Matea Samardžić is a retired Croatian swimmer. Matea Samardžić was born on January 17, 1995, in Split, Croatia. Matea Samardžić won a bronze medal in the 200m backstroke event at the 2016 European Aquatics Championships. Matea Samardžić qualified for the 2016 Summer Olympics, where she competed in the 100m backstroke and the 400m individual medley events.
Benthofascis sarcinula is a species of sea snail. Benthofascis sarcinula belongs to the family Conorbidae. These sea snails are predatory and venomous. They are capable of "stinging" humans, so live ones should be handled with caution or avoided altogether.
"Abstract Speed + Sound" is a painting by Italian Futurist painter Giacomo Balla. It was created in 1913–14 as part of a series of studies of motion. The painting is possibly the second in a triptych that depicts the passage of a racing car through a landscape, preceded by "Abstract Speed" (1913) and followed by "Abstract Speed—The Car Has Passed" (1913). These three paintings share elements of a single landscape and extend onto their frames. Balla used the automobile as a symbol of speed, in line with the Futurist manifesto's emphasis on the beauty of speed. The painting conveys the sensation of a passing car through crisscrossing lines that represent sound. It is considered a representation of Italian Futurism's ideals. The painting was featured on the 1980 British television series "100 Great Paintings". The Philadelphia Museum of Art houses a study for the painting done in watercolor and graphite.
The 1980 WDF Europe Cup was the 2nd edition of the WDF Europe Cup darts tournament. The tournament was organised by the World Darts Federation and took place in Copenhagen, Denmark from October 3 to 4.
Jacques-Paul Faure was an officer of the French Army. Jacques-Paul Faure studied at the French Ecole Polytechnique in the promotion of 1889. Jacques-Paul Faure led the French Military Mission to Japan from 1918 to 1919.
Dewi Safitri is an Indonesian weightlifter. Dewi Safitri competes in the 53 kg category. Dewi Safitri represents Indonesia at international competitions. Dewi Safitri competed at the 2015 World Weightlifting Championships and the 2016 Summer Olympics.
"North Express is a Finnish thriller film. North Express was released in 1947. The film is directed by Roland af Hällström and stars Ansa Ikonen, Leif Wager, and Tauno Majuri."
The Kuantan District is a district in Pahang, Malaysia. It is located in the north-east of Pahang and is bordered by Kemaman District of Terengganu to the north, the South China Sea to the east, Jerantut District and Maran District to the west, and Pekan District to the south. The major towns in the district are Kuantan and Bandar Indera Mahkota. Additionally, Panching, Sungai Lembing, Gambang, and Beserah are also located in this district.
Codonanthe elegans is a plant species. Codonanthe elegans belongs to the genus Codonanthe. Codonanthe elegans is found in Belize.
The 1949–50 SK Rapid Wien season was the 52nd season in club history.
"My PYT" is a song by American rapper Wale. The song features uncredited vocals from Sam Sneak and is part of Wale's studio album "Shine". "My PYT" peaked at number 54 on the Billboard Hot 100.
"RR Auction is an auction house. RR Auction is headquartered in Boston's North End with a production office in Amherst, New Hampshire. RR Auction was first established in 1976 and officially founded in 1980 by CEO Bob Eaton. RR Auction is known for its monthly auctions of rare documents, manuscripts, autographs, and historic artifacts. RR Auction often exceeds 1,000 lots per sale. RR Auction has developed global recognition with a worldwide client base. RR Auction publishes monthly catalogs in print and online via Issuu."
"Shape Shift with Me" is the seventh studio album by the American punk rock band Against Me!. It was released on September 16, 2016, on Total Treble Music and Xtra Mile. The title of the album comes from a lyric in the song "Norse Truth", which is track 10 on the album. The album showcases a shift in vocal style, with Grace being praised for a more spoken word-like structure in her singing on songs like "12:03", "333", and "Norse Truth". No non-promotional singles have been released from the album, but two b-sides, "Stabitha Christie" and "First High of the Morning", were released on a 7" single for Record Store Day 2017.
"View of the Cannaregio Canal" was painted by Francesco Guardi around 1770. It is a small oil on canvas painting measuring 48.9 × 77.5 cm. The painting now hangs in the reading room of the Frick Art Reference Library alongside "Regatta in Venice". Both paintings were gifted to the Frick Collection by Helen Clay Frick after her father's death. In the painting, Guardi captures a typical scene of Venetian life on the canals. Guardi depicts a section of the northern bank of the Cannaregio Canal, one of Venice’s largest canals, located in the Cannaregio district of the city. The Palazzo Surian Bellotto is the most prominent building in the painting, named after the Surian family and then the Bellotto family. The Ponte dei Tre Archi connects the northern bank with a small fragment of the southern bank. Another building featured in this view is the Santa Maria delle Penitenti, recognizable by its circular window below the roof and placement behind the Ponte dei Tre Archi. This church was designed by Giorgio Massari in 1725, and the façade was never completed. Guardi ensures its recognizability despite its modest appearance.
Tomás Óg na Fésóige Mág Samhradháin, also known as Thomas McGovern, Junior 'of the beard', was the chief of the McGovern Clan and the Baron or Lord of Tullyhaw barony in County Cavan from 1408 until his passing in 1458.
Barbara Matić is a Croatian judoka. Barbara Matić was born on December 3, 1994 in Split, Croatia. Barbara Matić is a two-time world junior champion in the women's 70 kg division. Barbara Matić won bronze at the 2014 European Judo Championships. Barbara Matić's younger sister, Brigita Matić, is also a successful judoka on the junior level. Barbara Matić competed at the 2016 Summer Olympics. In 2020, Barbara Matić competed in the women's 70 kg event at the 2020 European Judo Championships held in Prague, Czech Republic.
"Gautam Dutta is an Indian first-class cricketer from Assam. Gautam Dutta was born on October 28, 1973. Gautam Dutta made his debut for Assam in the 1989/90 Ranji Trophy. Gautam Dutta is a left-handed batsman and left-arm medium pace bowler. Gautam Dutta was a fast bowling all-rounder and was Assam and East Zone's strike bowler during the late 1990s and early 2000s. In 53 first-class matches, Gautam Dutta took 142 wickets at an average of 24.35 and an economy of 2.73 with a best of 9/52 in an innings. Gautam Dutta also scored many crucial runs for the teams he played, including 8 fifties. Gautam Dutta was also a member of the India under-19 team during the 1991/92 season."
Westwood Community High School is a public senior high school located in Fort McMurray, Alberta. It is part of the Fort McMurray Public School District and is situated in the community of Thickwood. The school currently accommodates approximately 2000 students and offers Advanced Placement courses.
The 1986 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships were held from June 4 to 7, 1986 at Carroll Stadium in Indianapolis, Indiana. The event determined the national champions of men's and women's collegiate Division I outdoor track and field events in the United States. These championships marked the 64th annual men's championships and the fifth annual women's championships. Indiana University in Bloomington technically hosted the event, even though it took place in Indianapolis. Carroll Stadium, the venue for the event, is located near IUPUI, another school within the Indiana University system. This was the second time the Hoosiers hosted the event, with the first time being in 1966 in Bloomington. SMU and Texas emerged as the top teams in the men's and women's categories, respectively. SMU claimed their second men's team title, while Texas secured their first women's team title.
"Five Bells" is a meditative poem by Australian poet Kenneth Slessor. The poem was published in 1939 as the title poem in the collection "Five Bells : XX Poems" by the author. It has since been included in various poetry anthologies.
"Grevillea fuscolutea is a shrub. Grevillea fuscolutea belongs to the genus Grevillea. Grevillea fuscolutea is native to a small area along the south coast in the Great Southern region of Western Australia."
Niklas Hauptmann is a German professional footballer. Niklas Hauptmann was born on June 27, 1996. Niklas Hauptmann plays as a midfielder. Niklas Hauptmann currently plays for Holstein Kiel on loan from 1. FC Köln.
"Badho Bahu is an Indian Hindi romantic drama television series that aired on &TV. The show premiered on September 12, 2016, and was produced by Sunny Side Up and Hum Tum Tele Films. Rytasha Rathore and Prince Narula starred in the lead roles as Komal and Lakhan respectively. The show ended on May 17, 2018. It has been remade in Kannada as "Brahmagantu", in Tamil as "Oru Oorla Oru Rajakumari", in Malayalam as "Swathi Nakshatram Chothi", and in Telugu as "Gundamma Katha"."
Mavis Chirandu is a Zimbabwean footballer. Mavis Chirandu plays for the sports team Weerams F.C. Mavis Chirandu is also a member of the Zimbabwe women's national football team. Mavis Chirandu was born on January 15, 1995. Weerams F.C. is a football club. Zimbabwe women's national football team represents the country in international competitions.
Sarah Bro is a Danish swimmer. Sarah Bro was born on March 4, 1996. Sarah Bro participated in the women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay event at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
"Franck Multon is a French bridge player. Franck Multon has the nationality of France."
"José Luis Sierra Cabrera is a Chilean footballer. José Luis Sierra Cabrera was born on June 24, 1997. José Luis Sierra Cabrera plays for Deportes Temuco."
The Long Beach State Beach women's basketball team represents California State University, Long Beach in Long Beach, California. The team competes in the Big West Conference.
"Oleksandr Prevar is a Ukrainian cyclist. Oleksandr Prevar was born on June 28, 1990. Oleksandr Prevar currently rides for the UCI Continental team."
Ma Yingnan is a Chinese judoka. Ma Yingnan was born on March 3, 1984. Ma Yingnan competed at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro in the women's 52 kg category.
Vladislav Mustafin is a swimmer from Uzbekistan. Vladislav Mustafin was born on September 26, 1995. Vladislav Mustafin competed in the men's 100 metre breaststroke event at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
"Dustin Tynes is a Bahamian swimmer. Dustin Tynes was born on March 7, 1996. Dustin Tynes competed in the men's 100 metre breaststroke event at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Dustin Tynes finished in 44th place with a time of 1:03.71. Dustin Tynes did not advance to the semifinals."
The WCA North Division Two is a second tier league for women in the sport of shinty, organized by the Women's Camanachd Association. The league was last played in the 2013 season and was won by Skye Camanachd. After a two-year experiment with a WCA National Division Two, the league structure was reorganized in 2016 to include regional second level set-ups, with the introduction of WCA North Division 2 and WCA South Division 2. These leagues are sponsored by Marine Harvest. Below these divisions is the WCA Development League, which consists of second teams and a team from the Outer Hebrides, with no relegation or promotion.
Klaus Brueske was a German truck driver. Klaus Brueske died at the Berlin Wall. Klaus Brueske died at the Heinrich-Heine-Straße border crossing. Klaus Brueske was the first Berlin Wall victim to die from suffocation. Klaus Brueske was born on September 14, 1938 and passed away on April 18, 1962.
Bechan Cave is a sandstone rock shelter located in Kane County, Utah, United States. The cave holds alluvial deposits containing the remains of Pleistocene megafauna, including mammoths, ground sloths, and even-toed ungulates. Archaeological excavation of the site in 1983 and 1984 unearthed animal bones, dung, hair, and teeth dating back to 11,555 BCE to 9720 BCE. The cave is also one of at least seventeen sites on the Colorado Plateau where Archaic-era Southwestern sandals have been discovered. The cave's name derives from a Navajo word meaning "big dung" or "big feces". The well-preserved dung layer was deposited over approximately 1,000 years by multiple animal species. Bechan Cave is located inside Glen Canyon National Recreation Area and is accessible on foot from Bowns Canyon.
Geoffrey Cheah is a competitive swimmer from Hong Kong. Geoffrey Cheah was born on November 10, 1990. Geoffrey Cheah qualified for the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro. Geoffrey Cheah represented Hong Kong in the men's 50 metre freestyle event.
The Taralga Wind Farm is a wind farm located near Taralga, New South Wales. It was CBD Energy/Santander's first and only wind farm. The wind farm has a capacity of 106.8 megawatts and consists of 51 turbines. The energy generated by the wind farm is sufficient to power approximately 45,000 average Australian households annually, resulting in a reduction of over 258,000 tonnes of greenhouse gas emissions per year.
Andrea La Torre is an Italian professional basketball player. Andrea La Torre was born on June 14, 1997. Andrea La Torre plays for Pallacanestro Cantù in the Italian Lega Basket Serie A (LBA). Pallacanestro Cantù is a basketball team in Italy.
Zohir Kedache is an Algerian boxer. Zohir Kedache was born on March 2, 1986. Zohir Kedache competed in the men's welterweight event at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
Kirill Shreitor is a Belarusian footballer. Kirill Shreitor plays for the team Baranovichi. Kirill Shreitor was born on August 6, 1986.
Anderson Peters is a Grenadian javelin thrower. Anderson Peters was born on October 21, 1997. Anderson Peters is the current world champion in javelin throw. Anderson Peters has won multiple CARIFTA Games championships. In 2016, Anderson Peters earned a bronze medal at the 2016 IAAF World U20 Championships in Bydgoszcz, Poland, setting new Grenadian national and OECS records.
"Ilya Khomenko is a Russian competitive swimmer. Ilya Khomenko specializes in breaststroke. In 2013, he became the world junior champion in the 100 meter breaststroke, setting a new championships record. He qualified for the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro in the 200 meter breaststroke. In the heats, he swam the 4th fastest time and advanced to the semifinals, where he finished 10th overall."
"Atlas Obscura is an online magazine and travel company. It was founded in 2009 by Joshua Foer and Dylan Thuras. Atlas Obscura catalogs unusual and obscure travel destinations through user-generated content. The editorial articles cover a variety of topics including history, science, food, travel, and exploration. Additionally, Atlas Obscura hosts a collaborative guide to the world's most obscure places."
Universal Bibliographic Control (UBC) is a concept championed by the International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions (IFLA). Under the theoretical UBC, any document would only be cataloged once in its country of origin, and that record would then be available for the use of any library in the world. In the 1974s, IFLA established an office for Universal Bibliographic Control. Dunsire, Hillman, Phipps, and Willer have suggested that Semantic Web technologies, including BIBFRAME, may allow UBC.
Cryptagama aurita, also known as the gravel dragon or hidden dragon, is an agamid lizard species found in the arid north-eastern interior of Western Australia and the adjacent area of the Northern Territory. Cryptagama aurita is the sole species in its genus.
The Dwyer-McAllister Cottage is a thatched cottage and National Monument situated in the Glen of Imaal, County Wicklow, Ireland.
CopperheadOS is a mobile operating system for smartphones, based on the Android mobile platform. It adds privacy and security features to the official releases of the Android Open Source Project by Google. CopperheadOS is developed by Copperhead, a Canadian information security company. It is licensed under Creative Commons BY-NC-SA 4.0. CopperheadOS supports smartphones in the Google Pixel product line. It has several security features not found in stock Android, such as a hardened version of the Linux kernel and the ability to use separate passwords for unlocking the device and for encryption. CopperheadOS ships with the F-Droid store instead of the Google Play Store to reduce the risk of users installing malicious apps. Development of CopperheadOS began in 2014, with an initial alpha release in August 2015, followed by a beta release in February 2016 targeting Google's Nexus and Pixel phones. The project's source code was initially located on GitHub but as of June 2020, it is limited to members of Copperhead's partner network.
Vida Milholland was a women's rights activist. Vida Milholland was the sister of Inez Milholland, a leader of the National Woman's Party. Vida Milholland was born on January 17, 1888, and passed away on November 29, 1952.
Wilma Roberts, also known as Wilma Louise McCarty, was an American photographer. She was born in The Dalles, Oregon, and learned photography from her mother, Laura Spencer McCarty, who captured the lifestyle of Native Americans around Butter Creek in the 1900s. Roberts is famous for her hand-colored black and white photographs created for Everett Olmstead's Elite Studio in The Dalles, where she worked for 35 years starting in 1939. She also established a camera shop for Olmstead's son, "Mel O," in the late 1940s. Roberts later published a photography book featuring a selection of her 1940s and 1950s photographs of the Celilo Falls during the salmon fishing season before the US Army Corps of Engineers constructed a dam in 1957, making this scene inaccessible. Her seasonal photographs became popular prints when the Union Pacific Railroad turned the area into a tourist attraction. Roberts' photography was acknowledged by the Photographic Society of America, where she eventually became a judge and was honored as a fellow in 1987. She passed away in The Dalles.
Jiowana Sauto is a Fijian rugby sevens player. Jiowana Sauto replaced Raijieli Daveau in the Fijian women's national rugby sevens team for the 2016 Summer Olympics in Brazil. She participated in the 2015–16 World Rugby Women's Sevens Series, the 2015 Dubai Women's Sevens, the 2016 USA Women's Sevens, and the 2016 France Women's Sevens. Jiowana Sauto hails from Vuna village on Taveuni Island in Fiji. She attended Saint John's College in Cawaci, Ovalau Island, where she represented the Fiji Rugby Women Youth Team at the Commonwealth Games in Samoa in 2015, marking the beginning of her journey to becoming a Fijiana.
The 1993 Slovak presidential elections took place from January 26 to February 15, 1993. Michal Kováč was elected as the first president of Slovakia through Parliament, requiring a candidate to secure 90 votes for election.
"Marc Sánchez is a swimmer. Marc Sánchez is from Spain. Marc Sánchez was born on November 6, 1992. Marc Sánchez participated in the men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay event at the 2016 Summer Olympics."
Claire Akossiwa is a Togolese competitive rower. Claire Akossiwa was born on August 11, 1996. Claire Akossiwa competed at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro in the women's single sculls event.
"I Brake for Brunettes" is a song. "I Brake for Brunettes" was co-written and recorded by American country music artist Rhett Akins. The song was released in January 1995 as the second single from the album "A Thousand Memories". The song reached No. 36 on the "Billboard" Hot Country Singles & Tracks chart. The song was written by Rhett Akins and Sandy Ramos.
Anthony M. Villane, Jr. is an American dentist and Republican Party politician. Anthony M. Villane, Jr. served seven terms in the New Jersey General Assembly from 1976 to 1988. Anthony M. Villane, Jr. was the head of the New Jersey Department of Community Affairs from 1988 to 1990. Anthony M. Villane, Jr. was named as the regional administrator of the United States Department of Housing and Urban Development.
Stanley Bish is a Dutch former professional footballer. Stanley Bish started his career with PSV in 1967. Stanley Bish became the club's youngest ever debutant. Stanley Bish had spells across the Eredivisie. Stanley Bish won the 1973 KNVB Beker with NAC Breda in 1973. Stanley Bish had a short stint in Belgium with Berchem Sport. Stanley Bish returned to the Netherlands where he retired in 1981.
Amadeus Serafini is an American actor. Amadeus Serafini was born on July 7, 1990. Amadeus Serafini hails from California. Amadeus Serafini is recognized for portraying Kieran Wilcox in the initial two seasons of MTV's slasher series "Scream".
Fleming Rutledge is an American Episcopal priest, author, theologian, and preacher. Fleming Rutledge was born in 1937. Fleming Rutledge was ordained to the diaconate in 1975 and was one of the first women to be ordained to the priesthood of the Episcopal Church. Rutledge is widely recognized in the United States, Canada, and the UK as a preacher, lecturer, and teacher of other preachers. Her expertise lies in the intersection of biblical theology with contemporary culture, current events, politics, literature, music, and art. She has preached in prominent pulpits such as the Washington National Cathedral, Duke University Chapel, Trinity Church in Boston, and the Harvard Memorial Chapel.
"Hale v. Henkel was a major United States Supreme Court case. The case was decided in 1906. The Court established the power of a federal grand jury engaged in an investigation into corporate malfeasance. The federal grand jury required the corporation in question to surrender its records."
Francesco Giangiacomo was an Italian illustrator and engraver. Francesco Giangiacomo lived from 1783 to February 22, 1864.
"José González Díez, O.P., was a Roman Catholic prelate. José González Díez served as Archbishop of Burgos from 1630 to 1631, Archbishop of Santiago de Compostela from 1627 to 1630, Bishop of Pamplona from 1625 to 1627, and Bishop of Palencia from 1616 to 1625."
Amargadh, also known as Jithari, is a village in Sihor, Bhavnagar district, Gujarat, India. The village is home to the famous K. J. Mehta T.B. Hospital, which was built on land donated by Maharaja Krishnakumar Sihji. Additionally, there is the College of Dental Science, which houses a research center on its campus.
"Kurdistan Institution for Strategic Studies and Scientific Research (KISSR) is a public institution located in Sulaymaniyah, Kurdistan Region - Iraq. KISSR is a significant scientific and cultural institution in Kurdistan region and Iraq, specializing in scientific research and strategy studies. The institution aims to conduct research in pure sciences, engineering, medical sciences, and strategic studies."
"Dancin' (on a Saturday Night)" is a song written by Lynsey de Paul and Barry Blue. Barry Blue recorded and released the song as a single in 1973 on Bell Records. One year later, the drummer John Richardson joined the Rubettes. Barry Blue's version of the song reached number 2 on the UK Singles Chart and number 1 on the "Melody Maker" top 30. It also reached number 2 on the Australian Kent Music chart, number 3 on the Austrian singles chart, number 4 on the Irish Singles Chart, number 9 on the German singles chart, and number 11 on the Dutch singles chart. The song was the 18th best-selling single in Australia in 1973 and the 23rd best-selling single in the UK in 1973. Barry Blue's version of the song has been featured on the soundtracks of the films "Anita and Me" and "American Swing". A remixed version of the original Barry Blue song was released in 1989, reaching number 86 on the UK Singles Chart. It is also included in the film "The Long Good Friday".
Frederick Drandua was a Ugandan Roman Catholic priest. Frederick Drandua served as the Bishop of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Arua in Uganda from May 27, 1986, until August 19, 2009. Frederick Drandua was born on August 12, 1943, and passed away on September 1, 2016.
"NGC 164 is a spiral galaxy. NGC 164 is located in the constellation Pisces. NGC 164 was discovered by the German astronomer Albert Marth on August 3, 1864. Albert Marth is a German astronomer."
"Lukas Schmidt is a German badminton player. Lukas Schmidt was born on September 19, 1988. Lukas Schmidt won a bronze medal at the 2007 European Junior Championships in the boys' doubles event with Peter Käsbauer. Schmidt was a champion at the 2012 and 2014 Croatian International in the men's singles event."
"Wiwat Thaijaroen is a Thai futsal Winger. Wiwat Thaijaroen is a member of the Thailand national futsal team. Wiwat Thaijaroen plays for the Department of Highways Futsal Club in the Futsal Thailand League."
Kanison Phoopun is a Thai futsal goalkeeper. Kanison Phoopun is a member of the Thailand national futsal team. Kanison Phoopun plays for Port Futsal Club in the Futsal Thailand League. Kanison Phoopun's Thai name is คณิศร ภู่พันธ์.
Krzysztof Siemion is a Polish weightlifter. Krzysztof Siemion was born on February 1, 1966. Krzysztof Siemion won the Silver medal in the 82.5 Kg category at the 1992 Summer Olympics in Barcelona.
"Lycée les Sept Mares (L7M) is a senior high school and sixth form college located in Maurepas, Yvelines, France, within the Paris metropolitan area."
CallTrackingMetrics is a Software as a service (SaaS) company based in Severna Park, Maryland, United States. CallTrackingMetrics provides call tracking tools and analysis to organizations. As of 2018, CallTrackingMetrics had over 30,000 customers in 25 countries. CallTrackingMetrics was named to the Inc 500 list in 2016, the Inc 5000 list in 2017, and the Inc 5000 list in 2018. CallTrackingMetrics is a private company owned by Laure and Todd Fisher.
Macaco Tião, also known as "Tião the Monkey", was a chimpanzee at the Rio de Janeiro Zoological Garden. He was very popular with children and visitors. Macaco Tião was named in memory of Rio de Janeiro's patron saint, Saint Sebastian, with "Tião" being a nickname for "Sebastião". He was born on January 16, 1963, in Rio de Janeiro and passed away on December 23, 1996, in the same city.
Type 346 radar is a highly digitized, multi-function, dual-band (S and C bands) naval active electronically scanned array (AESA) installed on Type 052C destroyers, Type 052D destroyers, Type 055 destroyers, and Type 002 aircraft carriers of the PLAN. The radar is named as the Star of the Sea (Hai-Zhi-Xing, 海之星) by its developer and it is one of the two competitors for PLAN’s SAPARS (Shipborne Active Phased Array Radar System) project/program. Type 346 radar has been frequently confused with Chinese fire control radar Type 348 and Sea Lion series C-band phased array radars. The radar system received the Chinese naval designation H/LJG-346 or Type 346 and the NATO reporting name Dragon Eye.
Norma Jean Nilsson is a former child actress. Norma Jean Nilsson was born on January 1, 1938. Norma Jean Nilsson appeared in old-time radio and films.
Husky Memorial, also known as Husky Monument, is a memorial for deceased motorcyclists in California's Mojave Desert. It is located on Bureau of Land Management (BLM) land, permitted by BLM but not officially endorsed. The memorial is a two-hour ride from U.S. 395, the closest paved road.
"Budhiana is a census town in Jalandhar district of Punjab State, India. Budhiana is located from Jalandhar, from Phagwara, from district headquarter Hoshiarpur and from state capital Chandigarh. The village is administrated by a sarpanch who is an elected representative of village as per Panchayati raj (India)."
The Alexandra Sports Club, also known as the Alex Sports Club, is a sporting complex located in Harare, the capital of Zimbabwe. The primary use of the venue is as a cricket ground, where it has hosted both international and domestic fixtures.
Camilla Gentili was an Italian Roman Catholic from Macerata. She was married to Battista Santucci, who murdered her in opposition to her faith and perceived disobedience. Gentili was beatified in 1841 after Pope Gregory XVI approved her 'cultus'.
Charles Townsend Ludington, also known as C. Townsend Ludington and Charles T. Ludington, was a businessman and socialite from Philadelphia. He was an aviation pioneer who played a key role in establishing an every-hour-on-the-hour air service between New York and Washington. Charles Townsend Ludington was born on January 16, 1896, and passed away on January 19, 1968.
Kent House and Hitchens House were a matched pair of historic homes located in Williamsport, Warren County, Indiana. They were built in 1854 in the Italian Villa style using brick. Each house features a two-story structure with a three-story corner tower set at an angle to the main part of the building. Originally, the houses were mirror images of each other. Unfortunately, the house located at 500 Main was destroyed by a fire in the 1990s. Both Kent House and Hitchens House were listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1984.
Eleanor Honnywill, also known as Eleanor Biscoe and later Lady Eleanor Fuchs, played a key role in supporting the work of the British Antarctic Survey (BAS).
The District Council of Apoinga was a local government area in South Australia from 1873 to 1932. The council was proclaimed on 6 November 1873. It opened council chambers at Logan Gap on 23 September 1876. The main business of the council in its early years was the construction and maintenance of roads, depasturing of sheep and cattle on reserves, and rabbit control. The council became responsible for the Apoinga Cemetery in February 1880. It gained the Hundreds of Bright and Bundey under the District Councils Act 1887 and was divided by May 1888 into three wards: Apoinga (three councillors), and Bright and Bundey (two councillors each). It merged with the District Council of English to create the District Council of Robertstown on 16 May 1932. The State Library of South Australia holds a photograph of the Apoinga council building from 1978. A plaque at the Robertstown Community Centre commemorates the oversubscription of the Apoinga council to the Commonwealth Peace Loan following World War I.
"Ivan Zhostkin is a Belarusian professional footballer. Ivan Zhostkin was born on May 8, 1991. Ivan Zhostkin currently plays for Gomel."
"Ultimate Brain is a British game show on CBBC about science. It is hosted by Duncan Wisbey as Dr. Brain and stars Imran Yusuf as Guinea Pig (also known as GP). Series 1 began on June 26, 2014, series 2 began on August 15, 2015 with a new set, and series 3 began on July 23, 2016. It is Zig Zag Productions' first children's series."
Hollister Pajotte is a former Trinidadian cricketer. Hollister Pajotte was born on October 30, 1976, in San Fernando, Trinidad. Hollister Pajotte played a single match for Trinidad and Tobago in West Indian domestic cricket. The match took place in October 2000, in a limited-overs match against the United States in the 2000–01 Red Stripe Bowl. Pajotte usually played as a wicket-keeper but was selected solely as a batsman in this match due to Keno Mason already taking the wicket-keeping gloves. He batted third in the order, after Lincoln Roberts and Andy Jackson, and scored four not out. Outside of cricket, Pajotte worked as a policeman.
Niculae M. Popescu was a Romanian theologian, historian, and priest of the Romanian Orthodox Church. He was born in Dâmbovicioara, Dâmbovița County. Popescu attended Nifon Seminary in Bucharest and Saint Sava National College. He studied theology and literature at the University of Bucharest, obtaining degrees in 1907 and 1908. He also attended the University of Vienna, where he earned a doctorate in history in 1913. Popescu served as a deacon at various monasteries and later became a priest at different parishes. He held various academic and administrative positions, including directing the Nifon seminary and heading the Romanian church history department in Bucharest. Popescu was a member of the Romanian Academy and served as its vice president. He taught religion to King Michael I of Romania and participated in various congresses and societies related to Byzantinology. Popescu published numerous studies on church history and Romanian culture. He donated his personal library to the Romanian Patriarchate and was buried at Bellu cemetery. Popescu had notable friends and correspondents, including Nicolae Iorga, Tit Simedrea, Vasile Pârvan, Sextil Pușcariu, and Ioan Bianu.
SuperNova Records was an independent record label founded and operated by Steve Austin, the frontman of the American noise rock band Today Is the Day. The name was first used in 1992 for the release of the band's demo album titled "How to Win Friends and Influence People" and the name was then used for the creation of the label in 2006. The label's initial purpose was to reissue then out-of-print Today Is the Day albums and to release video recordings of live performances of the band from the 1990s. Later Austin began to sign and promote other bands. SuperNova had a distribution and manufacturing deal with Sony. In order to help fund the label, Austin sold his firearm collection. In 2008, the label released a film based on the Today Is the Day album "Axis of Eden" as a digital download. Unfortunately, by 2010, the label shut down due to the stress of the business side of running the label.
Usdibad was a Gepid military commander ("dux") who sought refuge with Byzantine Emperor Justin II during the Lombard–Gepid War. In 566, Lombard king Alboin made a treaty with the Pannonian Avars, promising them the Gepids' land if they defeated them. The Gepids were ultimately destroyed by the Avars and Lombards in 567, with Gepid king Cunimund being killed by Alboin. The Avars then occupied "Gepidia" and established the Avar Khaganate. The Byzantine Emperor took control of Sirmium (now Sremska Mitrovica, Serbia) and provided refuge to Gepid leader Usdibad, while the rest of Gepidia fell to the Avars. According to István Bóna, Usdibad may have been a rival of Cunimund and switched sides to the Byzantines after the defeat.
Zhang Xiaonan is a Chinese modern pentathlete. Zhang Xiaonan was born on July 21, 1992. Zhang Xiaonan has qualified for the 2016 Summer Olympics.
The Bartlett State Jail was a privately operated minimum- and medium-security prison for men located in Bartlett, Williamson County, Texas. The facility was operated by Corrections Corporation of America (CCA) under contract with the Texas Department of Criminal Justice and housed state inmates. CCA ran the facility from 1995 to 2017 with an official capacity of 1049 inmates. A sexual assault lawsuit filed against CCA for a "hazing" incident in October 2013 alleged that the facility was deliberately understaffed to cut costs. The facility was closed in 2017 due to declining inmate populations in the state of Texas.
"Only Silence Remains is the second solo album of Christine Ott. It is an album of great variety, ranging from instrumental modern-classic to experimental music. The album features the piano as the focal point, accompanied by Ondes Martenot, harmonium, tubular bells, percussions, and vintage keyboards. The last track "Disaster" includes the spoken voice of Casey Brown. The album is linked to two original performances by the artist: "24 heures de la vie d'une femme" and the live soundtrack "Tabu"."
"Memories of the Desert" is a 2014 Brazilian-Chilean crime drama film directed and written by Jorge Durán. The film stars Daniel de Oliveira as a young Brazilian writer named Antonio, who travels to the Atacama Desert in search of inspiration for a tale. Daniela Ramírez and Álvaro Rudolphy also appear in supporting roles. The film premiered on March 9, 2014, at the Miami International Film Festival and was later released theatrically in Brazil on June 4, 2015.
Vivian Jeanette Kaplan is a Canadian writer and business owner. Vivian Jeanette Kaplan was born on June 17, 1946. Vivian Jeanette Kaplan's mother, Gerda Kosiner, was born in Shanghai. Gerda Kosiner and her husband were Jews from Vienna, and their mother tongue was German. Vivian Jeanette Kaplan came to Canada with her parents when she was two years old, and they settled in Toronto. She studied English, French, and Spanish at the University of Toronto. Vivian Kaplan operated Vivian Kaplan Oriental Interiors, a company that imported home furnishings from East Asia, for twenty years. She wrote her family's story in "Ten Green Bottles: The True Story of One Family's Journey from War-Torn Austria to the Ghettos of Shanghai". The book received the Canadian Jewish Book Award in 2003 and the Adei-Wizo Prize presented in Florence, Italy in 2007. A play based on the book was brought to the stage in Toronto in 2009. In 2012, Kaplan published a historical novel "Blind Vision".
The 12th Beijing College Student Film Festival took place in Beijing, China in May 2005. The event saw "" as the biggest winner, receiving two awards for Best Director and Grand Prix Award. Xia Yu was awarded Best Actor for his performance in "Waiting Alone", while Zhang Jingchu received recognition for her role in "Huayao Bride In Shangri-la". Golden Rooster-winner Lu Chuan's film "" won the Best Director Award, and "A Story of Dun Zi" was honored with the Best Film Award.
"Khok Kathiam railway station is a railway station located in Khok Kathiam Subdistrict, Lop Buri City, Lop Buri. It is located 144.238 km from Bangkok railway station and is a class 3 railway station. It is on the Northern Line of the State Railway of Thailand. The station opened on 31 October 1905 as part of the Northern Line extension from Lop Buri to Pak Nam Pho."
"Arunodaya University is a private University located in Itanagar, Arunachal Pradesh, India."
"Uppal Bhupa is a village in Jalandhar district of Punjab State, India. It is located 8.8 km from the postal head office in Nurmahal, 19.3 km from Phillaur, 37.3 km from the district headquarter in Jalandhar, and 140 km from the state capital Chandigarh. The village is administrated by a sarpanch, who is an elected representative."
"Ghungrana is a village. Ghungrana is located in the Ludhiana West tehsil of Ludhiana district, Punjab."
Mohammed Flayfel was a Lebanese composer and musician. He was born in 1899 in the Ashrafiyeh neighborhood of Beirut. Some of his notable compositions include "Mawtini" (the national anthem of Iraq and former national anthem of Palestine) and "Homat el Diyar" (the national anthem of Syria). In 1938, his composition "Homat el Diyar" was selected as the national anthem for Syria. Mohammed Flayfel also worked on patriotic songs, sometimes collaborating with his brother, Ahmad Salim Flayfel. He is credited with discovering the talents of a young Fairuz during a radio talent show and advising her to enroll in the Lebanese Conservatory. Mohammed Flayfel passed away in 1986.
Daniel Buess was a Swiss drummer, percussion player, and sound artist. Daniel Buess was born on January 28, 1976, in Basel.
Rehab Reunion is the sixth album (fourth studio album) by Bruce Hornsby with his current touring band, the Noisemakers. Released on June 17, 2016, the album is notable in that Hornsby, widely recognized for his piano capabilities, does not play piano on the album at all. Rather, he plays the dulcimer. The album also marks Hornsby's first release on 429 Records. Justin Vernon of Bon Iver sings background vocals on "Over the Rise" and Mavis Staples duets with Hornsby on "Celestial Railroad". Also noteworthy is a folk version of "The Valley Road", originally a hit in 1988 with Hornsby's first backing band, the Range.
The Manso Dam is a hydroelectric dam on the Manso River, a tributary of the Cuiabá River, in the state of Mato Grosso, Brazil. The dam was completed in 1999 and generates electricity for 300,000 people. The reservoir created by the dam is also a tourist attraction. However, the construction of the dam displaced many families and the submerged vegetation has negatively impacted water quality and fish stocks in and below the dam.
Tonny Azevedo is a Brazilian cyclist. Tonny Azevedo was born on August 9, 1969. Tonny Azevedo competed in the individual road race at the 1992 Summer Olympics.
"Majitha Assembly Constituency is a constituency in the Punjab Legislative Assembly. It is located in Amritsar district, Punjab state, India. VVPAT will be used in Majitha during the 2017 Assembly polls."
François Chevalier was a French historian known for his work on Latin America. His most famous publication is "Land and Society in Colonial Mexico: The Great Hacienda" (1963), originally published in French as "La formation des grands domaines au Mexique" (Paris 1952) and later translated into Spanish (1956). This work is a classic and pioneering study on agrarian history in colonial Mexico, sparking a discussion on the nature of Mexican haciendas as either feudal or capitalist.
Zak Waters is an American musician, singer-songwriter, DJ, and record producer from Los Angeles, California, also known as Pretty Sister. Waters began his music career forming the band Blueskyreality. After the group disbanded, Waters started his solo music career, releasing his debut extended play (EP), "New Normal" (2011). He featured on Madeon's 2012 multi-platinum single "The City", to positive acclaim, charting at number 20 on the US Hot Dance Club Songs chart and number 16 on the UK Dance Chart. He released his debut studio album, "Lip Service", on September 9, 2013. The following year, he released his second EP, "Now // Later" on Rostrum Records. He collaborated on Adventure Club's gold-certified single "Fade". He also collaborated on other popular singles including Adventure Club and David Solano's "Unleash (Life In Color 2014)" and Alex Gaudino and Manufactured Superstars's 2015 single "Lights Go Out". He appeared on the American songwriting competition series "Songland" in 2020. As Pretty Sister, he has released three extended plays; "Z Funk Era, Vol. 1" (2018), "Poolside Vibe" (2019), and "20" (2020). He has featured on other artists' singles including Nause's platinum-selling single "Dynamite" and Keljet's "Love At First Site". He featured on LDN Noise's "Tears", which was released in August 2016. He has collaborated and produced for various other music artists including Betty Who, Breathe Carolina, Nathan Sykes, Superfruit, and JoJo, among others.
"Lucas Simon-Meslet, also known as Cabochard, is a French professional player in the game League of Legends. Cabochard is currently the top laner for Team Vitality in the League of Legends European Championship (LEC). Prior to joining Team Vitality, Cabochard played for notable teams such as Gambit Gaming and Ninjas in Pyjamas."
The Ahwar of Southern Iraq: Refuge of Biodiversity and the Relict Landscape of the Mesopotamian Cities is a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in south Iraq. The Ahwar currently consists of seven sites, including three cities of Sumerian origin and four wetland areas of the Mesopotamian Marshes: Huwaizah Marshes, Central Marshes, East Hammar Marshes, West Hammar Marshes, Uruk Archaeological City, Ur Archaeological City, and Tell Eridu Archaeological Site.
Park Sa-rang is a South Korean actress. Park Sa-rang was born on March 4, 2003. Park Sa-rang started her career as a child actress. Park Sa-rang has appeared in television series and films such as "A Happy Woman" (2007), "Bestseller" (2010), and "Grand Prix" (2010).
"Chak Rame is a village in Shahkot in Jalandhar district of Punjab State, India. It is located from Shahkot, from Nakodar, from the district headquarters in Jalandhar and from the state capital Chandigarh. The village is administrated by a sarpanch who is an elected representative of village as per Panchayati Raj."
"Chak Yusafpur Allewal or Chak Yusafpur Allew is a village in Shahkot, Jalandhar district, Punjab State, India. The village is located from Shahkot, from Nakodar, from the district headquarter Jalandhar, and from the state capital Chandigarh. The village is administrated by a sarpanch who is an elected representative of the village as per Panchayati raj (India)."
"Dharmiwal is a village in Shahkot in Jalandhar district of Punjab State, India. Dharmiwal is located from Shahkot, from Nakodar, from district headquarter Jalandhar, and from state capital Chandigarh. The village is administrated by a sarpanch who is an elected representative of the village as per Panchayati raj (India)."
"Listen to My Word" is a single album by the South Korean girl group Oh My Girl. It was released on August 1, 2016, by WM Entertainment and distributed by LOEN Entertainment. The album features four covers of classic K-pop songs, including Papaya's "Listen to My Word (A-ing)" with reggae duo Skull and Haha. This album marks the final appearance of member JinE, who took a break from activities for recovery and treatment.
The IBSF World Championships 2017 were held at the Königssee bobsleigh, luge, and skeleton track in Königssee, Germany, from February 13 to 26, 2017.
"Indowal is a village in Shahkot in Jalandhar district of Punjab State, India. Indowal is located from Shahkot, from Nakodar, from district headquarter Jalandhar and from state capital Chandigarh. The village is administrated by a sarpanch who is an elected representative of the village as per Panchayati raj (India)."
"Grevillea calcicola is a tree or shrub belonging to the genus Grevillea and is native to a small area in the Gascoyne region of Western Australia. It typically grows to a height of , with non-glaucous branchlets and simple dorsiventral leaves. The plant produces an irregular inflorescence with white or cream flowers from May to August, followed by oblong rugose fruit. Grevillea calcicola is found in rocky or stony soils on limestone hilltops in the Cape Range IBRA subregion near Exmouth. This species is listed as threatened under the Australian Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act."
"Hoochie Cooche Man is a 1966 album by Jimmy Smith arranged by Oliver Nelson. The album title has also been spelled as "Hoochie Coochie Man"."
Eliseo Calenzio, also known as Calentius, was a 15th-century Italian new Latin humanist and poet. He was born in Apulia in 1430 and passed away in 1503. Calenzio served as a tutor to Frederick of Naples, the son of Ferdinand II of Naples, and was a close friend of Jacopo Sannazaro. His "Works" were published in Rome in 1503. One of his notable works is the "Combat des rais contre les grenouilles", which was inspired by Homer and later reprinted in 1738 in Rouen as part of the "Fables choisies" by Jean de La Fontaine in Latin verse. This edition was published by abbot Jean Saas.
"Kakar Kalan is a village in Shahkot in Jalandhar district of Punjab State, India. It is located from Shahkot, from Nakodar, from district headquarter Jalandhar and from state capital Chandigarh. The village is administrated by a sarpanch who is an elected representative of village as per Panchayati raj (India). Kakar Kalan is a village in Punjab State, India. Shahkot is the nearest town to Kakar Kalan. Nakodar is also close to Kakar Kalan. Jalandhar is the district headquarter near Kakar Kalan. Chandigarh is the state capital near Kakar Kalan. The village is governed by a sarpanch under the Panchayati raj system in India."
"Sang-e-Mar Mar, previously titled "Daasi," is a Pakistani romantic drama serial. It first aired on Hum TV on September 1, 2016. The cast includes Mikaal Zulfiqar, Kubra Khan, and Noman Ijaz. This is Noman Ijaz's fourth appearance on Hum TV, following his 2013 appearance in "Rehaai." It is also the second appearance of Uzma Hassan and Tipu Sharif after their 2015 appearance in "Mohabbat Aag Si," and Uzma Hassan's second appearance with Mikaal Zulfiqar after the 2014 serial "Tum Meray He Rehna." The production was shot in the Swat District, primarily in the village of Ronyal and its surroundings."
"Grevillea candolleana, also known as the Toodyay grevillea, is a shrub belonging to the genus Grevillea. It is native to a small area in the western Wheatbelt and the Swan Coastal Plain region of Western Australia. The spreading shrub typically grows to a certain height with non-glaucous branchlets. It has simple leaves that are a certain length and with a blade that is a certain width."
Jhal Thikriwala is a village in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. Jhal Thikriwala is located in Kapurthala, which serves as both the district and sub-district headquarters of the village. The village is governed by a Sarpanch, who is an elected representative.
Excelsior Convent School is a higher-secondary co-education private school located in Patiala city, Punjab, India. The school was established in 2003 and is affiliated with the Central Board of Secondary Education in India.
Xue Yanzhong is a politician from the People's Republic of China. Xue Yanzhong was born in Xiaoyi, Shanxi in February 1954. Xue Yanzhong was an alternate member of the 17th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China. In April 2008, Xue Yanzhong was appointed as the deputy party chief of Shanxi. In January 2009, Xue Yanzhong became the chairman of the Shanxi People's Political Consultative Conference.
The Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game Show is an award presented annually by the National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences (NATAS) and Academy of Television Arts & Sciences (ATAS). It is given in honor of a game show that features contestants playing a game involving answering questions or solving problems for money and prizes. Programs that have aired at least 15 original episodes for the calendar year are eligible to enter. The 1st Daytime Emmy Awards ceremony was held in 1974 with the game show "Password" receiving the award. The award category was originally called Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show before changing to its current title in 2013. The Emmy was named after an "Immy", an affectionate term used to refer to the image orthicon camera tube. The statuette was designed by Louis McManus, who modeled the award after his wife, Dorothy. The Emmy statuette is fifteen inches tall from base to tip, weighing five pounds and is composed of iron, pewter, zinc, and gold. Since its inception, the award has been given to ten game shows. In 1980, "The $20,000 Pyramid" and "Hollywood Squares" tied for the award, which was the first tie in this category. This situation repeated later only in 2011, with "Jeopardy!" and "Wheel of Fortune" both winning the award. In 2006, "Jeopardy!" became the series with the most wins in the category when it won a tenth time, surpassing "Pyramid"s previous record of nine; "Jeopardy!" went on to win in six additional years, ultimately receiving seventeen wins. "Jeopardy!" also has been nominated on 36 occasions, more than any other series. As of the 2020 ceremony, "Jeopardy!" is the most recent winner in this category.
Harry Carter Stuart, also known as Henry Carter Stuart, was a Virginia cattle breeder and trader. He served as the Democratic State Senator from the 18th District. Stuart was a lifelong Democrat and played a key role in the Byrd Organization's policy of Massive Resistance to racial integration in Virginia's public schools.
Masashi Chikazawa is a former baseball player from Japan. Masashi Chikazawa played in the Japan Pacific League for the Osaka Kintetsu Buffaloes. Masashi Chikazawa was born on June 26, 1982. Osaka Kintetsu Buffaloes is a baseball team based in Japan. Masashi Chikazawa later played for Reno.
Wheelchair sport classification is a system designed to allow fair competition between people of different disabilities. It aims to minimize the impact of a person's specific disability on the outcome of a competition. Wheelchair sports are associated with spinal cord injuries and include various types of disabilities such as paraplegia, quadriplegia, muscular dystrophy, post-polio syndrome, and spina bifida. The disability must meet minimal body function impairment requirements. The classification for spinal cord injuries and wheelchair sport is overseen by the International Wheelchair and Amputee Sports Federation (IWAS). The International Paralympic Committee (IPC) handles classification for spinal cord injuries internationally on a sport-specific basis. Wheelchair sport classification was first experimented with by Ludwig Guttmann at the Stoke Mandeville Hospital during the 1940s and was formalized in the 1950s. The system has evolved from a medical-based classification to a functional classification system, allowing people with spinal cord injuries to compete with different types of disabilities. The classes used for IWAS are based on track and field, with classes ranging from F1 to F8. The classification process involves both medical and functional aspects and is often sport-specific.
The Earlham Public School is a historic building located in Earlham, Iowa, United States. The town's name was chosen by the Quakers, who were the largest group of settlers in the community. They named it for Earlham College in Richmond, Indiana because they intended to establish a similar institution in the town. Fundraising got underway in 1869, and the following year plans were made to establish a public befitting a college town. Earlham Public School opened in 1871. Jennings P. Osborn, a local builder, constructed the two-story structure of smooth-faced limestone that rests on a rusticated limestone foundation. A brick addition was later added to the south side of the original building. The Quakers founded Earlham Academy in 1892 hoping it would grow into a college, but it did not. The building was sold to the local public school in 1900 and used as a high school. The building was later used by the elementary grades. School districts were consolidated in 1920, and a larger building was built to accommodate all grades in Earlham. This building was then used as a Masonic lodge until it was converted into a local museum. The building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982.
"Keep Me Singing" is the 36th studio album by Northern Irish singer-songwriter Van Morrison. The album was released on September 30, 2016, by Caroline Records. Van Morrison is the artist behind "Keep Me Singing". Caroline Records released the album on September 30, 2016.
"Progress in Energy and Combustion Science is a bimonthly peer-reviewed review journal published by Elsevier. The journal was established in 1975 and focuses on all aspects of energy and combustion science. Contributions to the journal are by invitation only. The founding editor of the journal is Norman Chigier from Carnegie Mellon University. The current Editors-in-Chief are Hai Wang from Stanford University and Christof Schulz from the University of Duisburg-Essen. According to the "Journal Citation Reports", the journal has an impact factor of 28.94 for the year 2019."
"Aules Hill Meadows is a Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) located in Northumberland, England. The site has been listed since 1992 and consists of four traditionally managed northern hay meadows, which are now rare in Northumberland."
The 2001 Sparkassen Cup - Singles was the tennis singles event of the twelfth edition of the Sparkassen Cup, a WTA Tier II tournament held in Leipzig, Germany. Kim Clijsters successfully defended her title by defeating Magdalena Maleeva in the final with a score of 6–1, 6–1.
Weldon Drew was the head men's basketball coach at New Mexico State University from 1979 to 1985. He succeeded Ken Hayes in 1979 and had previously been an assistant coach at the same university. Before joining NMSU, Drew coached high school basketball at Houston's Kashmere High School, where he achieved great success. He also coached at Langston University in Oklahoma after his time at NMSU. Drew was known for his basketball-related quote - "We have a great bunch of outside shooters. Unfortunately, all our games are played indoors." Drew passed away in an automobile accident near Stillwater, Oklahoma on November 22, 2012.
Ofelia Plads is a public space located on the Kvæsthus Pier near the Royal Danish Playhouse on the harbourfront in Copenhagen, Denmark. Ofelia Plads is owned by the Ministry of Culture and Jeudan. It serves as an open-air venue for the Royal Danish Theatre. Designed by Lundgaard & Tranberg, it was completed in 2016. Ofelia Plads is situated on top of an underground parking facility with a capacity for 500 cars.
"Gunning Shire was a local government area in New South Wales centered on Gunning, New South Wales north of the Australian Capital Territory. In February 2004, the local government organization was absorbed into the newly created Palerang Council and Upper Lachlan Shire."
Trans Amadi International School (TAIS), formerly known as Michelin School, is a private non-denominational preschool and elementary school located in Port Harcourt, Rivers State. It was established in 1980 to cater to the children of the employees of the Michelin Factory in Trans Amadi. In 1988, it was renamed Trans Amadi International School. Currently, the school serves children of all nationalities between the ages of 2 and 11. The school is situated at 32 St. Andrew's Street, Rumuobiakani, Trans Amadi in the Obio-Akpor local government area.
Mohammad Mehdi Goorangi is a musician and composer. Mohammad Mehdi Goorangi was born on June 23, 1975, in Shiraz, Iran.
"Bhullarai is a village in Tehsil Phagwara, Kapurthala district, Punjab, India. It is located away from Phagwara and 43 km away from Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch. Harbhajan Singh Rai(Master) runs Bhullarai."
"Fintan Monahan is the Roman Catholic Bishop of Killaloe. Fintan Monahan was born on January 23, 1967, in Tullamore, Co. Offaly, to Tom and Peg Monahan. Fintan Monahan has one brother and one sister. Fintan Monahan studied at Maynooth College and completed various degrees. Fintan Monahan was ordained as a priest in 1991 and served in Conamara, County Galway, before becoming a teacher at St. Jarlath's College, Tuam, Co. Galway. Fintan Monahan was appointed as Bishop of Killaloe by the Holy See in July 2016 and was consecrated in Ennis Cathedral on September 25, 2016."
Shilimb is a village in India. Shilimb is located in the Mawal taluka of Pune district in the state of Maharashtra.
Sheila Bishop was an English novelist. Sheila Bishop was born on October 3, 1916, and passed away on May 30, 2009. Sheila Bishop had 27 books published. Sheila Bishop's early work included plots set in the Tudor period and the contemporary 1960s, with some flashbacks to the 1930s and 1940s. In later years, Sheila Bishop focused on writing Regency romance novels, which became the majority of her work.
Findochty Castle is a ruined 16th century L-plan tower house located near Findochty in Moray, Scotland. It is situated about northeast of Buckie and approximately from the sea to the north. The castle is built on a rock at the end of a drained loch.
The 1987 Boise State Broncos football team represented Boise State University in the 1987 NCAA Division I-AA football season. The Broncos competed in the Big Sky Conference and played their home games at Bronco Stadium in Boise, Idaho. The team was led by first-year head coach Skip Hall, and they finished the season with a 6-5 overall record and a 4-4 conference record.
Tagelus is a genus of saltwater clams. Tagelus belongs to the family Solecurtidae. Tagelus are marine bivalve molluscs.
"Dave Mason Is Alive is an album of live recordings by Dave Mason. The album was recorded in 1971 at the Troubadour club in Los Angeles and was released in 1973 by Blue Thumb Records. It has also been re-released by MCA Coral (MCA 713)."
"Marius Louw is a South African rugby union player. Marius Louw was born on October 24, 1995. Marius Louw plays in Super Rugby, Currie Cup, and Rugby Challenge. Marius Louw's regular position is centre, but he also played as a flanker earlier in his career."
"Taringa robledales is a species of sea slug. Taringa robledales belongs to the family Discodorididae. Taringa robledales is a dorid nudibranch, a type of shell-less marine opisthobranch gastropod mollusc."
The 2016 NCAA Division I Field Hockey Championship was the 36th annual women's collegiate field hockey tournament organized by the NCAA. The tournament aimed to determine the national champion of Division I college field hockey in the United States. The semifinals and championship match took place at the L.R. Hill Sports Complex at Old Dominion University in Norfolk, Virginia from November 18 to 20, 2016. Delaware emerged victorious by defeating North Carolina in the final with a score of 3-2, securing their first national title.
Osvaldo Boretto is an Argentine former swimmer. Osvaldo Boretto was born on August 10, 1952. Osvaldo Boretto competed at the 1968 Summer Olympics and the 1972 Summer Olympics.
Michael Amir Murillo Bermudez is a Panamanian footballer. Michael Amir Murillo Bermudez was born on February 11, 1996. Michael Amir Murillo Bermudez plays as a right back. Michael Amir Murillo Bermudez currently plays for the Belgian First Division A club Anderlecht. Michael Amir Murillo Bermudez is also a member of the Panama national team.
"75 Dollar Bill is a musical duo. 75 Dollar Bill was formed in New York City in 2012. The members of 75 Dollar Bill are Che Chen, who plays the guitar, and Rick Brown, who plays the drums. Che Chen was formerly a member of True Primes, and Rick Brown was formerly a member of V-Effect and Curlew. Sasha Frere-Jones described their music as having a formal fullness and technical freedom that has introduced jazz to a new generation. Critics have noted Mauritanian influences in their music because Che Chen studied Moorish music in Mauritania with Jheich Ould Chighaly in 2013. Their first album, "Wooden Bag," was released in 2015 by Other Music Recording Company. Their second album, "Wood/Metal/Plastic/Pattern/Rhythm/Rock," was released in 2016 on the Los Angeles-based label Thin Wrist."
"Dark Scavenger" is a point-and-click adventure role-playing game developed and published by Canadian indie studio Psydra Games. It was released for PC and Steam on July 12, 2012 and May 16, 2014, respectively. The game follows a space traveler who is rescued by aliens called "Dark Scavengers" and helps them scavenge an unnamed planet to fix their ship. It offers over six hours of gameplay and features a crafting system with over a hundred items. The game received positive reviews from critics, praising its writing and gameplay mechanics, but some criticized its visuals for lacking moving graphics.
Anton Hettrich was a German-born architect who worked in Queensland, Australia. He emigrated from Germany to Queensland in 1870 and established himself as an architect in Bundaberg. In 1892, he married Karen Thomsen in Brisbane and they had one daughter and one son. Hettrich won design competitions for the Bundaberg Town Hall and the Bundaberg School of Arts soon after his arrival. He also designed the Primitive Methodist Church and Sacred Heart Roman Catholic Church in Childers. One of his pupils, Frederick Faircloth, went on to design many buildings in Childers. Anton Hettrich passed away at Dunwich Benevolent Asylum on February 4, 1946, due to Senility, and his body was cremated.
"Tellina radiata is a bivalve mollusc. Tellina radiata is commonly known as sunrise tellin. Tellina radiata belongs to the family Tellinidae."
"Pierre Huard was a French physician, surgeon, anatomist, historian of medicine, and anthropologist. Pierre Huard had a long career in Indochina and served as dean of several faculties of medicine in Hanoï and Paris. He also held the position of rector at the Université Félix Houphouët-Boigny. Pierre Huard was a pioneer in the history of medicine."
The Minnesota Territorial Legislature was a bicameral legislative body created by the United States Congress in 1849 as the legislative branch of the government of the Territory of Minnesota. The upper chamber, the Council, and the lower chamber, the House of Representatives, first convened on September 3, 1849. The two chambers served as the territory's legislative body until Minnesota was admitted as a state on May 11, 1858, when the Territorial Legislature was replaced by the Minnesota Legislature. St. Paul was consistently the territorial capital, wherein the Territorial Legislature held its sessions. The Organic Act established that the Territorial Council would have a minimum of nine members, while the House of Representatives would have a minimum of eighteen members. The 1st-6th Territorial Legislatures consisted of the minimum number in both houses, while the 7th and 8th consisted of fifteen councillors and thirty-eight representatives.
Olga Aleinikova is a pediatric-oncohematologist. Olga Aleinikova was born on November 10, 1951 in Leningrad. Olga Aleinikova holds a PhD and is a Doctor of Medical Science since 1999. Olga Aleinikova became a Professor in 2003. Olga Aleinikova is a Corresponding Member of the National Academy of Sciences of Belarus. Olga Aleinikova is the Director of the State Institution "Belarusian Research Center for Pediatric Oncology, Hematology and Immunology."
Upware South Pit is a Site of Special Scientific Interest in Cambridgeshire. It is a Geological Conservation Review site with rocks dating back to the Oxfordian stage, approximately 160 million years ago. The site was once a coral reef and contains fossils of bivalves, ammonites, and corals that are similar to those found in the Tethys Ocean. Natural England considers it a key site for studying the Oxfordian period. Access to the site is available from the Fen Rivers Way north of Upware. Additionally, a small pasture area in the north of the site, not open to the public, is part of the Cam Washes biological SSSI.
"Know The Score is an Irish sports quiz show. Know The Score is produced by RTÉ. Know The Score started airing on November 6, 2016 on RTÉ One. The show is presented by Jacqui Hurley. The team captains of Know The Score are Ruby Walsh and Shane Byrne."
"Behen Hogi Teri is a 2017 Indian Hindi-language romantic comedy film. The film stars Rajkummar Rao and Shruti Haasan. Originally scheduled for a worldwide release on May 26, 2017, the release was pushed back to June 9, 2017."
Sadie Forman was a South African teacher, librarian, and anti-apartheid activist. Sadie Forman passed away on December 11, 2014.
Radek Meidl is a Czech professional ice hockey player. Radek Meidl was born on November 25, 1988. Radek Meidl currently plays for Leeds Chiefs in the National Ice Hockey League (NIHL). Radek Meidl made his Czech Extraliga debut with HC Oceláři Třinec during the 2015-16 Czech Extraliga season. Radek Meidl has a younger brother named Václav Meidl.
"Don't Say You Don't Remember" is a song written by Helen Miller and Estelle Levitt and performed by Beverly Bremers. The song was originally recorded by The Goggles in 1970. Beverly Bremers' recording in 1971 reached No. 5 on the "Billboard Adult Contemporary" chart and No. 15 on the "Billboard" Hot 100. In Canada, it peaked at No. 17, in France at No. 5, in Italy at No. 12, and in Australia at No. 81. The song was featured on her 1972 album, "I'll Make You Music," and was arranged by Charles Calello. The single ranked 86th on "Billboard's" Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1972.
The Cross City Correctional Institution is a state prison for men located in Cross City, Dixie County, Florida. It is owned and operated by the Florida Department of Corrections. This facility has a mix of security levels, including minimum, medium, and close security, and houses adult male offenders. Cross City first opened in 1972 on the grounds of the decommissioned Cross City Air Force Station and has a maximum capacity of 1802 prisoners.
Jean-Paul Tony Helissey is a French foil fencer. Jean-Paul Tony Helissey was born on March 3, 1990. Jean-Paul Tony Helissey won a silver medal in the team competition at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
"Speak Hokkien Campaign is a social movement focused on revitalizing the Hokkien language. The campaign originated online with Hokkien speakers from Penang, Malaysia, and aims to preserve and promote the use of Hokkien."
Bakhodir Jalolov is a professional boxer from Uzbekistan. Bakhodir Jalolov was born on July 8, 1994. Bakhodir Jalolov competed in the super-heavyweight division as an amateur boxer. Bakhodir Jalolov won a bronze medal at the 2015 World Championships and a gold medal at the 2019 edition. Bakhodir Jalolov also competed at the 2016 Olympics and served as Uzbekistan's flag bearer during the opening ceremony.
Zhang Fusheng is a Chinese sports shooter. Zhang Fusheng was born on September 20, 1993. Zhang Fusheng competed in the men's 25 metre rapid fire pistol event at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
William H. Flett was an American attorney and politician. William H. Flett served as a member of the Wisconsin State Assembly. William H. Flett was born on May 10, 1856 and passed away on September 5, 1911.
"Sarat Sumpradit is a Thai weightlifter. Sarat Sumpradit was born on April 17, 1994. Sarat Sumpradit competes in the 94 kg division. Sarat Sumpradit won a gold medal at the 2013 Southeast Asian Games. Sarat Sumpradit placed fourth at the 2014 Asian Games and the 2016 Olympics."
"Sainik School, Jhunjhunu, is a military school located in Jhunjhunu, Rajasthan, India. It was established in 2012. Sainik School, Jhunjhunu is one of several Sainik Schools in India. The school focuses on preparing students for entry into the National Defence Academy. It is affiliated with CBSE."
Cris Kajd is a Swedish sport shooter. Cris Kajd was born on September 9, 1951, in Norrköping. Cris Kajd has competed in pistol shooting events at the Summer Olympics in 1984, 1988, and 1992.
Charles Alexandre was a French hellenist and philologist. He was born on February 17, 1797 in Amiens and passed away on June 6, 1870 in Paris. Charles Alexandre was also a general inspector of the Instruction publique and a member of the Institut de France. In 1814, he was a student at the École normale supérieure.
The Kinmen Bridge is a cross-sea bridge under construction in Kinmen, Fujian, Republic of China (Taiwan). The bridge will connect Greater Kinmen Island and Lieyu Island.
"Bernhard Hochwald is a German sport shooter. Bernhard Hochwald was born on June 27, 1957, in Schöneiche. Bernhard Hochwald has competed in skeet shooting events at the Summer Olympics in 1980, 1988, 1992, and 1996. Bernhard Hochwald is married to the shooter Katja Klepp. Raimund Bethge is Bernhard Hochwald's half-brother."
"Öjkroken is a village located on the island Öland in Sweden. Öjkroken is part of the municipality Borgholm."
Vokkaligara Sangha is a community organisation. Vokkaligara Sangha was founded in 1986 in Bangalore, now known as Bengaluru, in Karnataka, India. Vokkaligara Sangha aims to promote the social, cultural, and educational aspirations of the Vokkaliga community. The headquarters of Vokkaligara Sangha are located in Bengaluru, and there are several affiliated regional sanghas.
The Diboll Unit, also known as the Diboll Correctional Center, is a private state prison for men located in Diboll, Angelina County, Texas. It is operated by Management and Training Corporation under contract with the Texas Department of Criminal Justice. The facility was opened in June 1995 and has a maximum capacity of 518 male inmates. Diboll is situated next to the Rufus H. Duncan Geriatric Facility at 1502 South First Street, which is owned and operated by the state.
The Baltic Assembly Prize for Literature, the Arts and Science is an award given annually by the Baltic Assembly for achievements in three categories: literature, art, and science. The prize is awarded to a citizen of Estonia, Latvia, or Lithuania for outstanding achievements in these categories. It was first awarded in 1994 and includes a statuette, a diploma, and a sum of money, currently 5,000 euros. The award is presented during the formal session of the assembly. A joint jury of three persons per prize decides on the recipient. The purpose of the award, according to the Baltic Assembly, is to demonstrate the common interests of the countries in upholding their national identity and self-esteem, create an opportunity to learn about the achievements of neighboring countries, maintain interest in developments in the Baltic States, strengthen cooperation in literature, the arts, and science, encourage interest in the intellectual values and languages of the Baltic nations, and elevate the level of literature, the arts, and science in the Baltic States.
"My Catman is a Chinese-South Korean web-drama. My Catman stars Im Si-wan, Chae Soo-bin, and Kim Myung-soo. My Catman is a joint production of South Korea's MBC and China's Shanghai Ulike Media. My Catman will be streamed online on Tencent's QQLive."
"Siri Berg was a Swedish-born American abstract artist and teacher. Siri Berg's work is included in the permanent collection of the Guggenheim Museum in New York, as well as the National Museum of American Jewish History. Siri Berg was born on September 14, 1921, and passed away on April 8, 2020. Coca-Cola is also associated with Siri Berg."
The Hanoi International Film Festival, also known as HANIFF, is a biennial film festival. It was founded in 2010 as the first international film festival in Vietnam. Before 2016, only Asian films were part of the competition. The festival is organized by the Vietnamese Ministry of Culture, Sports, and Tourism.
"Regina Frank is a German artist specializing in text and textile installation and performance art. Since 1989, she has been known for combining performance art with technology, including the Internet and interactive social software installations. Her work focuses on social and political-social issues, linking digital media with traditional text transformed into textiles. Regina Frank has exhibited her installations internationally under the title “The Artist is Present” in various venues. She has also published a book with the same title in 1999. In 2015, she changed the title to "The Art is Present" and later in 2017 to “The HeArT is Present”. Regina Frank has lectured at various institutions around the world and has been artist in residence at multiple locations. Her works have been displayed at prestigious galleries and events globally. Additionally, her work has been featured in numerous publications."
Dagmar Patrasová is a Czech actress and singer. Dagmar Patrasová was born on April 27, 1956. Dagmar Patrasová is married to musician Felix Slováček. Dagmar Patrasová and Felix Slováček have two children.
The 2017 UCI America Tour is the thirteenth season of the UCI America Tour. The season began on October 24, 2016 with the Vuelta a Guatemala and will end on October 7, 2017. The points leader wears the UCI America Tour cycling jersey. Points are awarded to the top finishers of stages within stage races and the final general classification standings of each of the stages races and one-day events. The UCI ratings from highest to lowest are as follows: Multi-day events - 2.HC, 2.1, and 2.2; One-day events - 1.HC, 1.1, and 1.2.
Phyllidiella hageni is a species of sea slug. Phyllidiella hageni is a dorid nudibranch. Phyllidiella hageni is a shell-less marine gastropod mollusk. Phyllidiella hageni belongs to the family Phyllidiidae.
Rear Admiral Sir John Chicheley was a Royal Navy officer. He commanded a squadron at the Battle of Schooneveld and the Battle of Texel during the Franco-Dutch War. He later served as Commissioner of the Ordnance and then as Senior Naval Lord. Additionally, he was a Member of Parliament.
Georg Karl Pfahler was a German painter, printmaker, and sculptor. Georg Karl Pfahler was one of the leading proponents of post-war art in Germany. Georg Karl Pfahler was born on October 8, 1926, and passed away on January 6, 2002.
Panta Radosavljević-Dunavski, also known as Vojvoda Dunavski, was a Serbian army Chetnik commander and writer. He served as an army officer in Old Serbia and Macedonia during the early 20th century.
Philippe Hermann is a French writer. Philippe Hermann was born in Arras in 1962. In 2000, Philippe Hermann won the Prix des Deux Magots and the Cino Del Duca scholarship with his novel. Some of his notable works include "Technicien chair" in 1998, "La Vraie Joie" in 2000 (which won the Prix des Deux Magots), "Comment disparaître complètement" in 2001, "Souvenirs glorieux" in 2003, and "La Patrie nocturne" in 2016.
"Pazze di me is an Italian comedy film. Pazze di me was released in 2013. Fausto Brizzi co-wrote and directed Pazze di me."
"Himantolophus pseudalbinares is a species of footballfish, which is a type of anglerfish. The fish is bathypelagic and has been found as deep as the southeast Atlantic Ocean. Himantolophus pseudalbinares is endemic to the southeast Atlantic Ocean."
"Roger Muñoz is a Nicaraguan professional basketball player. Roger Muñoz was born on January 20, 1984. Roger Muñoz currently plays for the Leones de la Alcaldia club in the Liga Nicaragüense de Baloncesto. Roger Muñoz represented Nicaragua men's national basketball team at the 2016 Centrobasket."
Hereford DMU Sidings are located in Hereford, Herefordshire, England. Hereford DMU Sidings are situated on the Welsh Marches Line near Hereford station.
"Iris Rezende Machado is a Brazilian politician. Iris Rezende Machado is a member of the Brazilian Democratic Movement (MDB). Iris Rezende Machado was born on December 22, 1933."
"Square Hammer" is a song by the Swedish rock band Ghost. It was released as the lead single from their second EP "Popestar". The song reached No. 1 on the "Billboard" Mainstream Rock chart in January 2017, making Ghost the first Swedish band to achieve this. "Square Hammer" was also featured as one of the official theme songs for NXT TakeOver: San Antonio.
"Arlette Conquers Paris" is a German comedy film directed by Viktor Tourjansky. The film stars Johanna Matz, Karlheinz Böhm, and Claus Biederstaedt.
"Monsieur Scrupule, Gangster is a 1953 French crime film. The film was directed by Jacques Daroy and stars Tilda Thamar, Yves Vincent, and Howard Vernon."
Bryce Treggs is an American football wide receiver. Bryce Treggs is currently a free agent. Bryce Treggs played college football at California. Bryce Treggs was signed by the San Francisco 49ers as an undrafted free agent after the 2016 NFL Draft. California is where Bryce Treggs played college football. San Francisco 49ers signed Bryce Treggs after the 2016 NFL Draft.
"Gerald Evard is a Swiss former swimmer. Gerald Evard was born on May 23, 1948. Gerald Evard competed in three events at the 1968 Summer Olympics."
Sam Cross is a Welsh rugby union player. Sam Cross plays for Wales and club rugby for the Ospreys as a flanker. Sam Cross is an experienced rugby sevens player. Sam Cross has played for the Wales Sevens team in over a hundred matches. Sam Cross captained the Wales Sevens team at 24 years old. Sam Cross was a part of Team GB at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio and won a silver medal. Sam Cross was selected for the Wales national team in 2017 and made his debut as a substitute against Australia. Sam Cross later had his first international start against Georgia.
Olger Merkaj is an Albanian professional footballer. Olger Merkaj was born on July 23, 1997. Olger Merkaj plays as a right winger or forward. Olger Merkaj is a member of the Italian club US Breno.
Crystal Weekes González is a Puerto Rican taekwondo practitioner. Crystal Weekes González qualified for the 2016 Summer Olympics.
Scott Bowden is an Australian mountain biking and road cyclist. Scott Bowden was born on April 4, 1995. Scott Bowden currently rides for a UCI Continental team. Scott Bowden participated in the road race and cross-country events at the 2016 Summer Olympics.
"Stanislav Katana is a Ukrainian footballer. Stanislav Katana was born on July 11, 1992. Stanislav Katana is currently playing with Kingsman SC in the Canadian Soccer League. Kingsman SC is a soccer club based in Canada."
"Sergey Yakshin is a Kazakhstani sport shooter. Sergey Yakshin was born on May 9, 1968 in Astana. Sergey Yakshin participated in the men's skeet event at the 2000 Summer Olympics and finished in 7th place."
Marcelo Yarad is a Chilean sport shooter. Marcelo Yarad was born on October 4, 1969. Marcelo Yarad participated in the 2000 Summer Olympics in the men's skeet event. Marcelo Yarad tied for ninth place in the competition.
Joseph J. Rotman was a Professor of Mathematics at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. He was born in Chicago on May 26, 1934, and did his undergraduate and graduate work at the University of Chicago. Rotman received his doctorate in 1959 with a thesis in abelian groups under the direction of Irving Kaplansky. He spent his entire mathematical career at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, retiring in 2004. Rotman's research interests included algebra, abelian groups, modules, homological algebra, and combinatorics. He served as the Managing Editor of the "Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society" in 1972-1973 and was the Annual Visiting Lecturer of the South African Mathematical Society in 1985. Some of Rotman's notable publications include "An Introduction to Homological Algebra" (1979), "An Introduction to Algebraic Topology" (1988), "An Introduction to the Theory of Groups" (1995), "A First Course in Abstract Algebra" (2000), "Advanced Modern Algebra" (2002), and "Journey into Mathematics: an introduction to proofs" (2006).
"Oleksa Storozhenko was a Ukrainian writer, anthropologist, playwright, and criminalist. He was born on November 24, 1806, in Lysohory, Chernihiv region, Ukraine, and passed away on November 6, 1874, in Berestia, Belarus. Storozhenko's works are based on Ukrainian folklore and stories from the lives of Ukrainian peasants. He initially wrote in Russian but later became known as a Ukrainian-language writer. His works were published in the "Osnova" journal in Saint Petersburg. Storozhenko's writing style is characterized by earthy Ukrainian language and vivid representation of folk proverbs, anecdotes, sayings, and songs. His works focus on Ukrainians' everyday life, customs, folklore, demonological beliefs, and historical events, particularly kozaks and Zaporozhian Sich. Some of his notable works include the novella "Zakokhanyi Chort" (Devil in Love) and the novel "Marko Prokliatyi" (Damned Marko), which are examples of Gothic-Romantic literature. Storozhenko's other titles include "Rasskazy iz Krestyanskogo Byta Malorossiian" (Stories from the Peasant Life of Little Russians), "Bratiya Bliznetsy" (Twin Brothers), "Ukrainski Opovidannia" (Ukrainian Stories), and more."
The 22321 / 22322 Hool Express is a superfast express train operated by Eastern Railway, connecting Siuri and Howrah. It was previously a Regular Mail/Express train (13051/13052) but has now been upgraded to a Superfast train with the number combination of 22321/22322. Passengers are charged a superfast fee starting from October 1, 2016. The train was inaugurated on July 30, 2007.
Karin Schnaase is a German badminton player. Karin Schnaase was born on February 14, 1985. Karin Schnaase represented Germany at the 2016 Summer Olympics. Karin Schnaase placed 2nd in her group during group play and did not advance to the next round. Karin Schnaase is well known for the broken shoe incident with Laura Sarosi at the 2016 European Badminton Championships. Laura Sarosi handed her spare shoe to Karin Schnaase to continue the match. Karin Schnaase later won the match, preventing Sarosi from gaining more points for Olympic badminton qualification.
The 77th Tank Division was a mobilization tank division of the Soviet Army. The division was formed as the 119th Motor Rifle Division in the early 1970s. It became the 77th Tank Division in 1982 and was based at Lyalichi in Primorsky Krai. The division became a territorial training center in 1987 and a storage base in 1989.
Delisser Land District is a land district of Western Australia. Delisser Land District is located within the Eastern and Eucla land divisions on the Nullarbor Plain. Delisser Land District spans roughly 29°00'S - 31°00'S in latitude and 126°30'E - 129°00'E in longitude. Delisser Land District was named after E.A. Delisser. E.A. Delisser surveyed and described the Nullarbor Plain in the 1860s. The district was created on October 20, 1916, and was defined in the "Government Gazette".
"Wayne Rooney's Street Striker is a British reality television series broadcast on Sky1 and Sky1 HD. The show is also known as Coke Zero Street Striker due to a sponsorship deal with Coca-Cola. The winners of the competition have received trips to football training camps in Brazil and South Africa for the 2010 FIFA World Cup Final."
"Goofy's Sky School is a steel wild mouse roller coaster located at Paradise Gardens Park in Disney California Adventure, Anaheim, California. The ride is inspired by Disney's 1940 short film "Goofy's Glider" and was rethemed and opened on July 1, 2011."
"Dancing Madly Sideways is the fourth studio album by Marcella Detroit, a British-based American musician. The album was released in July 2001."
Lectionary 284 is a Greek manuscript of the New Testament written on parchment. It dates back to the 10th century. Scrivener identified it as 163e. Unfortunately, only one leaf of the manuscript has survived.
Thompson Nunataks are three nunataks located 4 nautical miles south of Navigator Peak in the Heritage Range, Ellsworth Mountains. These nunataks surmount the central part of White Escarpment. They were mapped by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) based on surveys and U.S. Navy air photos from 1961 to 1966. The Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) named them after Russel W. Thompson, a meteorologist with the United States Antarctic Research Program (USARP) at Wilkes Station in 1963.
"Shadows and Faces" is a 2010 Turkish drama film directed by Derviş Zaim. The film follows the story of a young girl who gets separated from her father, a Karagöz shadow play master, during the conflict between Turks and Greeks in Cyprus in 1963. The film premiered at the 47th International Antalya Golden Orange Film Festival and won the Turkish Film Critics Association Award. It is the final part of a trilogy of films centered around traditional Turkish arts, including "Waiting for Heaven" (2006) and "Dot" (2008).
Harriet Merrill Johnson was born in 1886 in Bangor, Maine. She graduated from the Massachusetts Homeopathic Hospital and worked as a district nurse at the Henry Street Settlement. Johnson, along with Lucy Sprague Mitchell and Caroline Pratt, founded the Bureau of Education Experiments in 1916, now known as Bank Street College of Education. Their goal was to study experimental education by bringing specialists and researchers together. Johnson established the bureau's nursery school, which later became Bank Street's School for Children. She authored several texts on education. The Harriet Johnson Nursery School opened in 1918 on West 12th and West 13th Street. The staff included teachers, psychologists, and researchers who observed children's learning environments. Graduates from Johnson's nursery school attended Caroline Pratt's City and Country School. The nursery school emphasized creative expression and recognized education beyond traditional curriculum. Children had the opportunity to explore New York City as part of their learning experience, visiting places like ferries, zoos, and bridges.
The Heppner flood of 1903 was a major flash flood along Willow Creek that destroyed a large portion of Heppner, Oregon, United States, on June 14, 1903. The death toll was 247 people, making it the deadliest natural disaster in Oregon and the second deadliest flash flood in the entire United States. The flood caused over $600,000 in damage. After an exceptionally dry spring, strong thunderstorms moved over the Heppner area on June 14, 1903. Torrential rain and hail began falling on the watersheds of Willow Creek and its tributaries, Balm Fork and Hinton Creek. The arid climate and lack of vegetation, coupled with the already wet ground from a previous storm, led to minimal water absorption by the soil, resulting in flooding. A steam laundry building acted as a dam, failing under the stress and sending a wall of water down Willow Creek, destroying many structures in Heppner. Despite some residents escaping to higher ground, 247 people died. The flood also affected the cities of Lexington and Ione downstream, with raw sewage contaminating wells and leading to deaths from typhoid fever. Flood control studies were conducted in the following years, leading to the construction of the Willow Creek Dam in 1983, the first major roller-compacted concrete dam. Photographer Walter S. Bowman captured images of the aftermath in Pendleton, Oregon.
Mount Tidd is a rock peak located in Pirrit Hills. The peak was identified by the U.S. Ellsworth-Byrd Traverse Party on December 10, 1958. It was named after Lieutenant Paul Tidd of the U.S. Navy, who served as the Officer-in-Charge of Ellsworth Station in 1958.
Tierney Peninsula is an ice-covered peninsula between Savage Glacier and Morgan Inlet in the east end of Thurston Island. The east extremity of the peninsula is Cape Annawan. These features were discovered on helicopter flights from the USS Burton Island and Glacier of the U.S. Navy Bellingshausen Sea Expedition in February 1960 and named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN). The peninsula was named for J.Q. Tierney, oceanographer aboard the Burton Island on this expedition. The cape was named for the ship "Annawan" of the United States Expedition of 1829–31, which with the Penguin sailed west from the South Shetland Islands in February 1830, exploring as far as 103W, northward of this cape. Two nautical miles west of the base is Pallid Crest, a solitary ice-covered ridge visible from a considerable distance and various directions. It was named by US-ACAN because of its whitish appearance.
"Cameraria mediodorsella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from California, United States. The wingspan of Cameraria mediodorsella is 7-8.5 mm. The larvae of Cameraria mediodorsella feed on various "Quercus" species such as "Quercus garryana", "Quercus kelloggii", "Quercus lobata", and "Quercus suber". They create mines on the leaves of their host plant, which are oblong to quadrate in shape. The epidermis of the mine is opaque with a yellow tan color. The mine is typically located in a lobe or at the base adjacent to the midrib."
Ben Hibon is a Swiss animation director. He was born in Geneva, Switzerland, and studied Fine Art there. Later, he moved to London to study Graphic Design at the Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design. Hibon created in-game sequences for Capcom's video game "Killer7" and also worked on a segment for the Japanese horror film "Tokyo Zombie" by Sakichi Sato. His short film "Codehunters" premiered at the MTV Asia Awards 2006 in Bangkok, Thailand, and has been showcased at numerous festivals worldwide, winning several awards. Hibon was commissioned by Sony PlayStation to direct an animated series based on the game "Heavenly Sword". He also assisted David Yates in directing an animated short for "The Tale of The Three Brothers" in "Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 1". Currently, he is set to direct "Pan", a modern adaptation of "Peter Pan". Hibon's work has been recognized by various awards and festivals, and he has worked with clients such as Sony PlayStation, Electronic Arts, Renault, MTV, Sega, and more. In August 2020, it was announced that he will lead Nickelodeon's "Star Trek: Prodigy".
Cameraria hamameliella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Canada (Québec and Nova Scotia) and the United States (including Massachusetts, Kentucky, Maine, Maryland, Michigan, New York, and Connecticut). The wingspan of Cameraria hamameliella is about 7 mm. The larvae of Cameraria hamameliella feed on "Hamamelis" species, including "Hamamelis virginiana". They mine the leaves of their host plant, creating a blotch mine on the upperside of the leaf. The mine is whitish and sometimes almost circular. The pupa of the summer brood of Cameraria hamameliella is formed beneath a flat silken cocoon.
The Hanoverian Western Railway was a line from Löhne to Emden. It was built by the Royal Hanoverian State Railways in the mid-19th century in the west of the Kingdom of Hanover, which is now part of the modern German states of Lower Saxony and North Rhine-Westphalia.
"Something Personal" is an album by American jazz pianist Jack Wilson. The album was recorded and released on the Blue Note label in 1967.
"Cremastobombycia ambrosiaeella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Quebec in Canada and various states in the United States including Illinois, Kentucky, Texas, Maine, and New York. The wingspan of Cremastobombycia ambrosiaeella is 5.5-6.5 mm. The larvae of this moth feed on various plant species including Ambrosia, Helianthus, Heterotera squarrosa, Ridania alternifolia, and Verbesina. They create tentiform mines on the underside of the leaves of their host plants. The cocoon of Cremastobombycia ambrosiaeella is dense, white, and fusiform, suspended hammock-like in the mine."
Vishnu Vardhan, also known as J. Vishnuvardhan, is a professional tennis player from India. Vishnu Vardhan won a bronze medal in men's doubles at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, China. He also won a silver medal in mixed doubles at the same event, partnering with Sania Mirza. Vishnu Vardhan was recognized as the ITF player of April 2011. He clinched the national singles title for the fourth time by winning the Men's final of the Fenesta Open Tennis Championship on October 8, 2016.
Loewe Massif is a rock massif located in the eastern part of the Aramis Range within the Prince Charles Mountains in Antarctica. The massif features an undulating plateau, with Mount Loewe and the Medvecky Peaks rising from it. The plateau has an average elevation above sea level and above the ice on its northern side. It was discovered by an Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions (ANARE) team led by W.G. Bewsher in 1956. The name of the massif is derived from Mount Loewe, named after Fritz Loewe, a member of the ANARE reconnaissance party during the French expedition at Port Martin, Adélie Coast, in 1951.
"The Littlewood Nunataks are a group of four lichen-covered nunataks located between Schweitzer Glacier and Lerchenfeld Glacier on the Luitpold Coast of Antarctica. These nunataks, which are brick red in color, were discovered and roughly charted by the Second German Antarctic Expedition, 1911–12, led by Wilhelm Filchner. They were later visited by John C. Behrendt of the United States Geological Survey and Lieutenant Erickson, U.S. Navy, via helicopter on January 28, 1959. Behrendt named them after oceanographer William H. Littlewood of the U.S. Navy Hydrographic Office, who was involved in Operation Deep Freeze 1957 and 1959 in the Weddell Sea area."
"Lindstrøm Peak is a peak located in the Queen Maud Mountains of Antarctica. It stands northwest of Mount Kristensen on the west side of Nilsen Plateau. The peak was named after Adolf Lindstrøm, who was the cook for the land party at Framheim during Amundsen's South Pole expedition of 1910–12. This naming honors the commemoration of "Mount A. Lindstrom," a name given in 1911 to an unidentified mountain in the same area."
"Fukuoka Financial Group is a Japanese company. Fukuoka Financial Group has assets worth $128.9 billion as of 2015. Fukuoka Financial Group is listed on the Nikkei 225, which is a stock market index in Japan."
Ed Berry is a former defensive back in the National Football League and a CFL all-star. Ed Berry was born on September 28, 1963. Ed Berry played college football at Utah State University. In the 1986 NFL Draft, Ed Berry was selected in the seventh round by the Green Bay Packers. He played 16 games in 1986 with the Green Bay Packers and 2 games the following season with the San Diego Chargers. Ed Berry played 9 seasons in the CFL with the Toronto Argonauts, Edmonton Eskimos, Memphis Mad Dogs, and again with the Toronto Argonauts. He was named an Eastern All-Star in 1989 and won two Grey Cups with the Toronto Argonauts in 1991 and 1996.
Joseph Aston was an English journalist, dramatist, and miscellaneous writer. Joseph Aston passed away on October 19, 1844.
Hans-Georg Kraus is a German footballer. Hans-Georg Kraus was born on October 25, 1949. Hans-Georg Kraus played for Fortuna Düsseldorf and Tennis Borussia Berlin in the Fußball-Bundesliga.
"Aukrasanden is a village in Aukra Municipality in Møre og Romsdal county, Norway. Aukrasanden is located on the southeast side of the island of Gossa, just south of Varhaugvika village and the municipal centre of Falkhytta. There is a ferry connection south of Aukrasanden to the village of Hollingen across the Julsundet strait. Aukra Church is situated in Aukrasanden. The village had a population of 968 in 2018."
Bandar Baru, known locally as 'BB', is a village in Deli Serdang Regency, North Sumatra. It is situated on the road from Medan to Berastagi, in the Sibolangit subdistrict by the Bukit Lawang river, close to Karo Regency. The village features cafes, restaurants, shops selling tourist goods, and tourist bungalows. It is also designated as a "lokalisasi" or government licensed prostitution area. In 1904, a battle took place at the village between the local Karo people and the colonial soldiers sent to pacify the unruly highlanders.
Rashida Bee is an Indian activist from Bhopal. Rashida Bee was awarded the Goldman Environmental Prize in 2004. Champa Devi Shukla was awarded the Goldman Environmental Prize in 2004. Rashida Bee and Champa Devi Shukla have fought for justice for the surviving victims of the 1984 Bhopal disaster. The 1984 Bhopal disaster resulted in the death of 20,000 people. Rashida Bee and Champa Devi Shukla have organized campaigns and trials against those responsible for the disaster.
The Flat Classroom Project is a global collaborative project for students in Grades 3-12. It was inspired by Thomas Friedman's book, "The World is Flat", and utilizes Web 2.0 tools to facilitate communication, interaction, collaboration, and creation among students and teachers from classrooms worldwide.
Charles Tuff was a British businessman and Conservative Party politician from Rochester, Kent. He served in the House of Commons from 1903 to 1906. Tuff was born on September 4, 1855, in Plumstead, but spent most of his life in Rochester. He was involved in local politics and was the mayor of Rochester from 1900 to 1902. In 1903, he was elected as the Unionist candidate for a by-election in Rochester. Tuff was also a Justice of the Peace for Rochester and Kent. He passed away at the age of 74 on January 27, 1929, at his home in Gravesend. Two of his sons, including Frank Tuff, were killed in World War I.
Mount McGhee is a mountain located south of Mount Smethurst in Enderby Land, Antarctica. It was identified from air photos taken by Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions aircraft in 1957. The mountain was named by the Antarctic Names Committee of Australia in honor of J. McGhee, who served as a mechanic and driver at Wilkes Station in 1961.
Frontier Communications of the Southwest Inc. is a Frontier Communications operating company providing local telephone services in Arizona, California, and Nevada. The company was created as a subsidiary of New Communications ILEC Holdings by Verizon in 2009 and sold to Frontier on July 1, 2010. The service region includes rural customers served by Verizon California and customers originally served by Contel through Contel of California. Contel of California had been merged into GTE California in 1993.
"McKay Valley is located in the Darwin Mountains of Antarctica. McKay Valley is the central of three ice-free valleys that trend east from Midnight Plateau. The valley was named after physicist Christopher P. McKay from the NASA Ames Research Center in Moffett Field, California. McKay conducted investigations in the McMurdo Dry Valleys on topics such as micrometeorology, ice thickness in frozen lakes, and ground ice stability during 15 austral summers starting around 1980."
Charla Baklayan Faddoul is an Armenian-American reality television personality. Charla Baklayan Faddoul was born on July 23, 1976. Charla Baklayan Faddoul appeared on "The Amazing Race 5" and "The Amazing Race: All-Stars" television shows. Charla Baklayan Faddoul was born with achondroplasia, the most common form of dwarfism, and is 4 feet tall. Charla Baklayan Faddoul's partner on "The Amazing Race" was her cousin Mirna Hindoyan. Mirna Hindoyan is Charla Baklayan Faddoul's cousin.
McMahon Glacier is a glacier in the Anare Mountains of Victoria Land, Antarctica. McMahon Glacier is about long and drains north between the Buskirk Bluffs and Gregory Bluffs into Nielsen Fjord. The glacier was named after F.P. McMahon by the Antarctic Names Committee of Australia. F.P. McMahon was a Logistics Officer with the Australian Antarctic Division and led expeditions to Macquarie Island and Antarctica.
"McWhinnie Peak is a peak located northeast of Mount Harker in the Saint Johns Range, Victoria Land, Antarctica. It was named after Mary Alice McWhinnie, a biologist from the United States Antarctic Research Program. Mary Alice McWhinnie spent the winter at McMurdo Station in 1974 and participated in various Antarctic cruises between 1962 and 1972."
"Median Snowfield is a large snowfield located in the Pensacola Mountains of Antarctica. It is situated between the Torbert Escarpment in the Neptune Range and the southern part of the Forrestal Range. The United States Geological Survey mapped Median Snowfield from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos taken between 1956 and 1966. The name of Median Snowfield was given by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names to reflect its position between the Neptune and Forrestal Ranges."
The Medley Rocks are a group of reefs and rocks located near the northeast side of D'Urville Island in the Joinville Island group, Antarctica. These formations were surveyed by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey in 1953–54 and were named in 1956 due to the abundance of reefs and rocks in the area.
"Megaw Island is the easternmost of the Bennett Islands in Hanusse Bay, Antarctica. It was mapped from air photos taken by the Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition (1947–48) and the Falkland Islands and Dependencies Aerial Survey Expedition (1956–57). The island was named after Irish physicist Helen Megaw by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee for her accurate measurements of the cell dimensions of ice."
The 2014 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup was an international association football tournament and the world championship for women's national teams under the age of 20. Grant Connell presented the tournament, which was organized by FIFA. It was the seventh edition of the tournament and took place from 5–24 August 2014 in Canada. Canada was named the host nation for the tournament in conjunction with its successful bid for the 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup. Germany emerged victorious by beating Nigeria 1–0 after extra time in the final, securing their third title while Nigeria lost their second final.
Rebecca Prichard is an English author and playwright. Rebecca Prichard was born in 1971. Rebecca Prichard is known for being one of the major contributors to the In-yer-face theatre movement.
"Hamid Reza Fathi is an Iranian professional football player. Hamid Reza Fathi currently plays for PAS Hamedan in the Azadegan League."
Alfred Grosser is a German-French writer, sociologist, and political scientist. Alfred Grosser was born on February 1, 1925, in Frankfurt am Main. Alfred Grosser is recognized for his efforts in promoting Franco-German cooperation post-World War II. Alfred Grosser is also known for his critical views on Israel.
Matney Peak is a peak located in Antarctica. Matney Peak is a mostly ice-free peak, high, near the middle of the line of peaks at the east side of Webster Glacier in the Heritage Range of the Ellsworth Mountains. Matney Peak was mapped by the United States Geological Survey from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1961–66. Matney Peak was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Chief Aviation Boatswain's Mate William R. Matney of the U.S. Navy. Chief Aviation Boatswain's Mate William R. Matney contributed significantly to improving fuel operations in Antarctica and for a portion of Operation Deep Freeze 1966, acted as fuels officer.
Tomás Ó Flatharta is a Gaelic football manager. Tomás Ó Flatharta is originally from County Kerry.
"Palauk is a town in the Myeik District, Taninthayi Region, Myanmar. It is situated on Route 8, the main coastal road between Tavoy and Palaw. Palauk serves as the administrative seat of the Palauk Subtownship."
Bo Aung Kyaw Street, formerly known as Sparks Street, is a major street in southern Yangon, Burma. The street passes through Kyauktada Township and Botataung Township, starting at an intersection near the Yangon River with Strand Road and eventually joining Bogyoke Aung San Road. Bo Aung Kyaw Street is home to historical buildings such as Saint Mary's Cathedral and Sri Sri Durba Bari Hindu Temple. It is also a hub for businesses, with headquarters of Burmese airlines, travel companies, "The Myanmar Times," and the Burmese Central Post Office located along the street. Additionally, Aye Yar Hotel can be found at 170/176 Bo Aung Kyaw Street.
"Always Leave Them Laughing" is a 1949 musical comedy-drama film. The film was directed by Roy Del Ruth and stars Milton Berle and Virginia Mayo.
The 2010 United Kingdom general election took place in Wales on May 6, 2010. All 40 parliamentary seats in Wales were contested. The Labour Party, despite remaining the party with the most seats in Wales, experienced a net loss of 4 seats and a 6.5% drop in its share of the vote. The Conservatives gained 5 seats, while the Liberal Democrats and Plaid Cymru saw minimal changes in both seats and vote share.
"McCain Bluff is a rock bluff located at the north side of the mouth of Svendsen Glacier in the Usarp Mountains of Antarctica. McCain Bluff was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy from surveys and air photos taken between 1960 and 1962. The bluff was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in honor of John C. McCain, a biologist who worked at McMurdo Station as part of the United States Antarctic Research Program during 1967-1968."
"Maurizio Lauro is an Italian footballer. Maurizio Lauro was born on March 12, 1981. Maurizio Lauro played as a left back."
"Grossite is a calcium aluminium oxide mineral with the formula CaAl4O7. Grossite is a colorless to white vitreous mineral that crystallizes in the monoclinic crystal system. Grossite was first described in 1994 for an occurrence in the Hatrurim Formation of Israel. Grossite was named after Shulamit Gross (1923–2012) of the Geological Survey of Israel. Grossite occurs within high-temperature metamorphosed impure limestone of the Hatrurim Formation and also within calcium-aluminium rich inclusions in chondritic meteorites. Associated minerals in the Hatrurium include brownmillerite, mayenite, and larnite. In meteorites, grossite occurs with perovskite, melilite, hibonite, spinel, and calcium-rich pyroxene."
Les Tornallyay was an Australian fencer. Les Tornallyay participated in the individual and team sabre events at the 1964 Summer Olympics.
Samuel Osborne Habershon was an English physician. He was born in Rotherham in 1825 and studied medicine at Guy's Hospital in London. He graduated from the University of London with an M.B. in 1848 and an M.D. in 1851. Habershon held various positions at Guy's Hospital, including demonstrator of anatomy, lecturer in pathology, assistant physician, and full physician. He was also involved with the Royal College of Physicians of London and the Medical Society of London. Habershon had a high reputation in abdominal diseases and was known for proposing the operation of gastrostomy for stricture of the œsophagus. He was one of the founders of the Christian Medical Association. Habershon authored several papers and books on medical topics related to abdominal diseases, mercury effects, stomach diseases, liver diseases, and the pathology of the pneumogastric nerve. He passed away on August 22, 1889, from a gastric ulcer, leaving behind one son and three daughters.
"Laurice Guillen is a Filipino actress, director, and college professor. Laurice Guillen was born on January 31, 1947."
Central Westmoreland Career and Technology Center, also known as CWCTC, is situated in New Stanton, Pennsylvania. CWCTC is a part-time Career and Technical Educational School with 10 sending school districts. Students at the center also receive their Physical And Health Education and are assigned a student-services counselor based on their last name.
"Ballot Measure 9 is a 1995 documentary film directed and produced by Heather Lyn Macdonald. The film focuses on the cultural and political conflict surrounding Oregon Ballot Measure 9 in 1992, a citizen's initiative that aimed to label homosexuality as "abnormal, wrong, unnatural, and perverse." Oregon Ballot Measure 9 was a controversial proposition."
Neoclitocybe byssiseda is a species of fungus in the family Tricholomataceae. Neoclitocybe byssiseda is the type species of the genus "Neoclitocybe". Initially described as "Omphalia byssiseda" by Giacomo Bresadola in 1907, it was later transferred to "Neoclitocybe" by Rolf Singer in 1961. Neoclitocybe byssiseda is an edible mushroom.
"Gus van Go is a Juno-nominated music producer, mixer, and musician. He is best known for his work with the Montreal band The Stills. Gus van Go has credits for production, mixing, writing, and arranging three albums and one EP with the band. He has also produced and mixed material for various artists including Arkells, The Sam Roberts Band, Whitehorse, Wintersleep, Michael Rault, Terra Lightfoot, Hollerado, Said The Whale, The Trews, and Priestess. Gus van Go is a member of the band Megative, along with Tim Fletcher (ex-lead-singer of The Stills) and Jamaican reggae vocalist Screechy Dan."
"Natural Illusions" is an album by American jazz vibraphonist Bobby Hutcherson. The album was recorded in 1972 and released on the Blue Note label.
Leroy Lansing Janes was an American educator. Leroy Lansing Janes was hired by Kumamoto Domain in early Meiji period Japan. Leroy Lansing Janes was a native of Ohio. Leroy Lansing Janes was a veteran of the Civil War. Leroy Lansing Janes served in the artillery with the rank of captain after graduation from the United States Military Academy at West Point. In 1871, Leroy Lansing Janes was approached by the Hosokawa clan, feudal lords of Kumamoto, to teach at the domainal school that promoted western studies. Leroy Lansing Janes established a curriculum entirely in English, covering mathematics, history, geography, and natural sciences. Leroy Lansing Janes lectured on western morals and waited for three years to broach the subject of Christianity with his students. Some 30 of his pupils converted to Christianity under his influence, including Tokio Yokoi, Kozaki Hiromichi, and Ebina Danjo. The "Kumamoto Yōgakkō" was forced to close in August 1876 due to opposition from conservative elements within Kumamoto domain. Leroy Lansing Janes and his students relocated to Kyoto, where they joined the Dōshisha school, which had been founded a year earlier by Niijima Jō. Leroy Lansing Janes returned to the United States in 1878. Leroy Lansing Janes returned to Japan to teach again from 1893 to 1899 as an "oyatoi gaikokujin".
"Dairo José Esalas is a Colombian professional boxer. Dairo José Esalas was born on January 27, 1974 in San Onofre, Sucre, Colombia. Dairo José Esalas competes in the Welterweight division."
"Kvarnsvedens IK is a Swedish football club. Kvarnsvedens IK is based in Borlänge in Dalarna County."
Muhammad Bahtiar Ude is an Indonesian professional footballer. Muhammad Bahtiar Ude was born on November 26, 1987. Muhammad Bahtiar Ude plays as a midfielder for the Liga 2 club Mitra Kukar. Muhammad Bahtiar Ude previously played for Persiba Balikpapan.
"Syamsidar is an Indonesian footballer. Syamsidar was born on July 15, 1982. Syamsidar is currently playing for PSS Sleman as a goalkeeper. PSS Sleman is a football club."
Earl Ohlgren was a defensive end in the National Football League. Earl Ohlgren played for the Green Bay Packers during the 1942 NFL season. Prior to that, he was a player for the Milwaukee Chiefs in the American Football League. Earl Ohlgren was born on February 21, 1918, and passed away on December 31, 1962.
The Semenov Institute of Chemical Physics of Russian Academy of Sciences (RAS), also known as the Semenov ICP in Moscow, was founded in 1931 by Professor Nikolay Semyonov, a Nobel Laureate in Chemistry (1956). It originated from the Physico-Chemical Sector of the Leningrad Physical Technical Institute (Ioffe Institute). The Institute, located in Moscow since 1943, has around 450 researchers and is associated with Moscow State University, Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology, and other higher education institutions. Its primary focus is on applying physical theories and methods to chemistry, the chemical industry, and other sectors of the economy. Research areas include kinetics and mechanisms of chemical reactions, catalysis, elementary processes, physics and chemistry of solids, polymers, combustion, shock waves, and detonation. In 1956, a branch was established in Chernogolovka, later becoming the independent Institute of Problems of Chemical Physics (IPCP RAS) in 1997. Another department evolved into the N. M. Emanuel Institute of Biochemical Physics in Moscow under the Russian Academy of Sciences in 1994.
Charles Baily was an English architect and archaeologist. Charles Baily initially worked in Nottinghamshire and later moved to London. Charles Baily was born on April 10, 1815, and passed away on October 2, 1878.
"Llanwnnog is a village in Powys, Wales. Llanwnnog is located one-and-a half miles north of Caersws in the community of the same name, on the B4568 road. The Ordnance Survey spells the name with a single 'n'. John Ceiriog Hughes, the Welsh romantic poet, is buried in the village churchyard in an ornamental grave with cast iron railings and a memorial plate. John Ceiriog Hughes was employed on the Cambrian Railways at Caersws as a stationmaster and Manager of the Van Railway from 1868 until his death in 1887."
John Bowack was a British topographer. John Bowack was a writing-master at Westminster School. John Bowack lived in Church Lane, Chelsea. John Bowack started publishing 'The Antiquities of Middlesex' in 1705-6. The work covered the parishes of Chelsea, Kensington, Fulham, Hammersmith, Chiswick, and Acton. John Bowack was skilled in ornamental handwriting as seen in Harleian MS. 1809. In July 1732, John Bowack was appointed clerk to the commissioners of the turnpike roads. In 1737, John Bowack became assistant-secretary to the Westminster Bridge commissioners with a salary of £100 a year. The date of John Bowack's death is unknown.
Samuel Boyce was an English engraver and poet. Samuel Boyce passed away in 1775.
Dr. Zlatan Čolaković was a Homerist, philologist, and researcher. He graduated with a degree in Comparative Literature and Philosophy in 1979 from the University of Zagreb Faculty of Philosophy. He completed his Masters in 1982 and his Doctorate in 1984. As a Fulbright scholar from 1984-1988, he worked with Albert Lord at Harvard University in the Milman Parry Collection at the Slavic division of the Widener Library. He also lectured at Harvard University and Waterloo University in Ontario, Canada. At Harvard, he transcribed and edited texts and audio tapes of over 90,000 verses of Bosnian epic songs. He published an essay titled "South Slavic Muslim Epics, Problems of Collecting, Editing, and Publishing" in California Slavic Studies. In 1989, he collected Bosnian epics on film with his wife Marina Rojc-Čolaković. He moved to Canada and conducted research on epic transcriptions, resulting in two volumes and his theory of Post-Tradition and the Post-Traditional Homer. He worked as a court translator in Canada and published his father's works. In 1989, he published "The Eagles of the Tragic World" and received the Government of Canada Award for his contribution to folklore in 1991. He founded the project "The Essence of Bosniak Epics" and wrote a book with his wife Marina Rojc-Colakovic. He was a member of various literary societies and died in Boston on December 20, 2008.
The .416 Ruger is a cartridge. The .416 Ruger is a .41 caliber (10.4 mm) cartridge. The .416 Ruger was designed in 2008 as a joint venture by Hornady and Ruger.
The 1972–73 ABA season was the sixth season of the American Basketball Association. The Pittsburgh Condors and The Floridians had folded, leaving the league with nine teams. The ABA awarded an expansion franchise to Dr. Leonard Bloom, President, and CEO of the United States Capital Corporation, for $1 million to play in San Diego, California, named the San Diego Conquistadors. However, due to a feud, they did not play in San Diego Sports Arena, instead playing at Peterson Gym. This move resulted in the Memphis Tams (formerly the Memphis Pros) moving to the Eastern Division. The Indiana Pacers, led by playoff MVP George McGinnis, won the championship, 4 games to 3 over the Kentucky Colonels, despite having the 4th best record in the league.
Acrocercops convoluta is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Acrocercops convoluta is known from West Bengal, India, Sri Lanka, and Vietnam. Acrocercops convoluta was described by Edward Meyrick in 1908.
Heritage Action for America, also known as Heritage Action, is a conservative policy advocacy organization founded in 2010. It is a sister organization of the conservative think tank The Heritage Foundation. Heritage Action has been led by executive director Jessica Anderson since April 2020. The organization launched a campaign in August 2013 linking the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act (ACA or "Obamacare") with laws to keep the federal government open or increase the federal debt limit, playing a role in the government shutdown of October 2013.
"Acrocercops diatonica is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. Acrocercops diatonica was described by Edward Meyrick in 1916. Acrocercops diatonica is known from Karnataka, India, West Malaysia, Papua New Guinea, and Thailand. The hostplant for Acrocercops diatonica includes "Theobroma cacao" and "Mangifera" species."
"Lechia Zielona Góra is a Polish football club based in Zielona Góra, Poland. The team's colors are blue and yellow. In 2012, the club merged with the local academy UKP Zielona Góra and competed under the name Stelmet Zielona Góra. However, the club folded in 2015. The club then became the foundation for a new club called Falubaz Zielona Góra. In 2019, the football club Lechia was reactivated based on its previous history."
Barometer World is a barometer museum located in Merton, near Great Torrington, Devon, England. Barometer World specializes in making, selling, and restoring barometers of various types. The museum was founded in 1979 by Philip Collins.
"Acrocercops galeopa is a moth. Acrocercops galeopa belongs to the family Gracillariidae. Acrocercops galeopa is known from Assam and Meghalaya, India. Acrocercops galeopa was described by Edward Meyrick in 1908."
"Dactyloscopus moorei, also known as the speckled stargazer, is a species of sand stargazer. It is native to the Atlantic and Gulf coasts of the United States, specifically from North Carolina to Texas. This species can be found on sandy bottoms at various depths. Dactyloscopus moorei can reach a total length of TL. The specific name of this species, moorei, is in honor of the American archaeologist Clarence Bloomfield Moore (1852-1936)."
"Fritz Gromotka was a Luftwaffe ace during World War II. Fritz Gromotka was awarded the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross. Fritz Gromotka achieved 29 aerial victories, with 27 on the Western Front and 2 on the Eastern Front."
The Deir ez-Zor Museum is a museum dedicated to the archaeology and history of northeastern Syria, also known as the Jezirah or Upper Mesopotamia. It is located in Deir ez-Zor, the capital of Deir ez-Zor Governorate, Syria. The museum was established in 1974 and initially housed in a gallery of a shopping mall. Between 1983 and 1996, it was situated in an old law court built in 1930 before moving to its current specially designed location in 1996. The exhibition halls cover an area and are arranged around a courtyard. The museum's collection has grown from 140 objects donated by the National Museum of Damascus and the National Museum of Aleppo in 1974 to around 25,000 objects, including clay tablets from Mari and artifacts from various archaeological sites in the Upper Khabur area. The collection is organized into five chronological themes: prehistory, ancient Syria, the Classical period, the Islamic era, and ethnography. It includes life-size reconstructions of buildings from different periods, such as a house from the Pre-Pottery Neolithic B site of Bouqras and the gate of the Islamic Qasr al-Heer al-Sharqi. In 2015, the collection was reportedly removed from the museum by the Syrian Army due to increased ISIS presence in Deir ez-Zor.
"Fulmar Bay is a bay located between Moreton Point and Return Point at the west end of Coronation Island in the South Orkney Islands. It was first sighted and roughly charted by Captain George Powell and Captain Nathaniel Palmer in December 1821. The bay was surveyed in 1933 by personnel from Discovery Investigations and was officially named in 1954 by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee. The bay was named Fulmar Bay because it is a nesting area for large numbers of Antarctic Fulmars (Fulmarus glacialoides)."
Fuller Island is an island in the Highjump Archipelago. Fuller Island is located south of Thomas Island on the south side of Cacapon Inlet. Fuller Island was mapped from air photos taken by U.S. Navy Operation Highjump in 1946–47. Fuller Island was named after H.F. Fuller, an air crewman on the Operation Highjump seaplane commanded by D.E. Bunger, which landed in this area in February 1947.
Mount Fritsche is a snow-capped coastal mountain with many steep rock faces. Mount Fritsche is located on the north side of Richthofen Pass in eastern Graham Land, Antarctica. This mountain was likely first seen by Otto Nordenskiöld of the Swedish Antarctic Expedition, 1901–04. Sir Hubert Wilkins observed the feature from the air on December 20, 1928, and named it "Cape Fritsche" after Carl B. Fritsche of Detroit, MI. The generic term has been amended in keeping with the nature of the feature.
"Frio Peak is a peak located east of Salient Peak on Salient Ridge in the Royal Society Range, Victoria Land, Antarctica. The name Frio was suggested by K. Brodie, a member of R.H. Findlay's New Zealand Antarctic Research Program field party in 1979-80. Frio is a Spanish word for cold and commemorates work conducted in the area in 1979 in piercing cold wind."
John Cart Burgess was an English watercolour painter known for his work with flowers and landscapes. He was also an author of two books on art technique. John Cart Burgess was a part of the Burgess dynasty of painters that thrived during the 18th and 19th centuries.
"Harvey Milk Day is organized by the Harvey Milk Foundation and celebrated each year on May 22. Harvey Milk Day is in memory of Harvey Milk, a gay rights activist assassinated in 1978. Harvey Milk was a prominent gay activist during the twentieth century. Harvey Milk ran for office three times before becoming the first openly gay person elected into California public office, where he served as a city supervisor. Harvey Milk Day is a day to remember and teach about Milk's life and his work to stop discrimination against gays and lesbians."
"Moonlight in Maubeuge" is a French comedy film from 1962. The film was directed by Jean Chérasse and written by Claude Choublier. It stars Claude Brasseur and Louis de Funès (uncredited). The international English title of the film is also "Moonlight in Maubeuge".
Enrico Saroldi was an Italian sculptor and medallist. Enrico Saroldi was born in Carmagnola on March 19, 1878, and passed away in 1954. Enrico Saroldi primarily focused on monumental sculptures, which can be found in various churches and public places across Italy. Enrico Saroldi studied at the Brera in Milan under the guidance of Enrico Butti. Throughout his career, Enrico Saroldi lived and worked in Milan.
United States Industrial Alcohol Company was an alcohol distiller in the United States. Charles Edward Adams was the chairman of the board. In 1919, they were held responsible for the Boston Molasses Disaster through their subsidiary, the Purity Distilling Company. 125 lawsuits were filed against the company in the aftermath.
"Mickey's Minstrels" is a 1934 short film in Larry Darmour's "Mickey McGuire" series starring a young Mickey Rooney. The two-reel short was directed by Jesse Duffy and released to theaters on January 11, 1934 by Post Pictures Corp.
Abbes Harchi is a Moroccan fencer. Abbes Harchi was born on May 11, 1936. Abbes Harchi competed in three events at the 1960 Summer Olympics.
Richard Ferris was a wealthy merchant from Barnstaple in Devon, England. Richard Ferris served as a Member of Parliament for Barnstaple in 1640. Richard Ferris served twice as Mayor of Barnstaple in 1632 and 1646. Richard Ferris founded the Barnstaple Grammar School, also known as the "Blue School".
The United Trade Unions of the Free Territory of Trieste, initially called the United Trade Unions of the Julian March, was a trade union confederation in the Free Territory of Trieste. The confederation was politically connected to the Communist Party of the Free Territory of Trieste.
"Berthella is a genus of sea slugs. Berthella belongs to the family Pleurobranchidae. Berthella are marine gastropod mollusks."
André Birabeau was a French novelist, playwright, and screenwriter. André Birabeau was born on December 6, 1890, and passed away on October 1, 1974.
The Mao tribe is a major tribe among the Nagas, a group of tribes located in the easternmost part of India and the western border region of Myanmar. The Maos primarily inhabit the northern part of Manipur State in India, surrounded by other Naga tribes such as the Angami, Chakhesang, Maram Naga, Zeme Naga, Tangkhul, and Poumai tribes. In their own language, the Maos are also known as Memei or Ememei. The term 'Mao' also refers to the area where the original villages are located, distinct from the newer settlements in their expanded habitation area.
William Leap is an emeritus professor of anthropology at American University in Washington DC. He is also an affiliate professor in the Women's, Gender and Sexuality Studies Program at Florida Atlantic University in Boca Raton FL. William Leap specializes in the fields of language and sexuality studies, queer linguistics, and queer historical linguistics. He obtained his bachelor's degree from Florida State University in 1967 and his Ph.D. from Southern Methodist University in 1970 under the guidance of his dissertation advisor, George Trager.
Augustin Friedrich Kraemer, also known as Krämer, was a German naturalist and ethnographer. He served as a Navy surgeon and worked in Polynesia during the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Kraemer contributed to the ethnographic documentation of the Hamburg Südsee Expedition, focusing on Palau. He also undertook a second voyage to Hawaii, Ostmikronesien, and Samoa to study atolls and their inhabitants. His detailed study of Samoan culture in "Die Samoa Inseln" is highly regarded, particularly for its genealogies, village honorifics, and chiefly rhetoric. However, it has been noted that Kraemer received significant assistance from a Samoan chief named Tofā Sauni, raising questions about authorship and ethical standards in ethnography.
"Palaeoagaracites is an extinct monotypic genus of gilled fungus in the order Agaricales. It contains the single species Palaeoagaracites antiquus. The genus is solely known from the Lower Cretaceous, Upper Albian stage (about 100 Ma), Burmese amber deposits in Myanmar. Palaeoagaracites is one of only five known agaric fungal species in the fossil record, the oldest to be described, and the only genus from Burmese amber."
"We Love Danger is a punk rock band. We Love Danger is also known as WLD. We Love Danger was formed in Quebec City, Canada in January 2009. We Love Danger is known for playing a 90's style of melodic punk rock."
Jórunn Viðar was an Icelandic pianist and composer. Jórunn Viðar was born on December 7, 1918. Jórunn Viðar passed away on February 27, 2017.
"The Taula del Sénia or Mancomunitat de la Taula del Sénia is a commonwealth or free association of municipalities. It is made up of 22 towns, totaling up to 100,000 people. These towns are located in the comarcas that make up the center of the historical region of Ilercavonia, which includes southern Aragon and Catalonia, as well as northern Valencia in Spain. The name originates from the fact that all municipal terms involved are situated within 15 km of the Sénia River, which is considered the center of the region in its upper course."
Crédit Mobilier, officially known as the Société Générale du Crédit Mobilier, was a French banking company founded by the Pereire brothers in the mid-19th century. It played a significant role in financing various railroads and infrastructure projects by utilizing the savings of middle-class French investors. The investments made by Crédit Mobilier led to substantial debts for countries that accepted these loans, indirectly impacting the European occupations during the economic depression of the 1870s. The bank was involved in funding major projects in France, Europe, North Africa, and beyond, including real estate speculation in collaboration with Hausmann for the development of neighborhoods like rue de Rivoli, Opéra, and place de l'Etoile. Additionally, Crédit Mobilier specialized in mining development, funded other banks such as the Imperial Ottoman Bank and the Austrian Mortgage Bank, supported railway construction, insurance companies, building contractors, transatlantic steamship lines, urban gas lighting, a newspaper, and the Paris public transit system. However, in 1866/7, the bank faced a severe crisis leading to the resignation of the Pereire brothers at the insistence of their rival, the Banque de France, from which Crédit Mobilier never fully recovered.
Daniel Snowman is a British writer, lecturer, and broadcaster. He focuses on social and cultural history. Daniel Snowman was born on November 4, 1938. He has worked in both the academic world and the BBC. Some of his notable works include "Kissing Cousins," a comparative study of British and American social attitudes, critical portraits of the Amadeus Quartet and Plácido Domingo, a study on the cultural impact of "The Hitler Émigrés," an anthology of essays about leading historians, and "The Gilded Stage: A Social History of Opera."
"Kaliyil Alpam Karyam is a 1984 Indian Malayalam-language film directed by Sathyan Anthikad. The film stars Mohanlal, Neelima, Rahman, Jagathy Sreekumar, and Lizy in the lead roles."
"Rauna is a village in Vidzeme, Latvia. Rauna is the administrative center of both Rauna Parish and Rauna Municipality. The community developed around a medieval bishop's castle."
The Hanriot H.35 is a French intermediate training monoplane. The Hanriot H.35 was designed and built by Avions Hanriot in the 1920s.
"Mijek, also known as Mijik, Miyek, or Miyec, is a small town in the Río de Oro region of Morocco. It is situated east of the Moroccan Wall, controlled by MINURSO, 80 km north of the Mauritanian town of Zouérat, and 250 km east of Dakhla. Mijek has a hospital, and there are plans to open a school during the 2012–2013 academic year. Mijek serves as the headquarters of MINURSO."
Ambrose Phillipps was an English landowner and Tory politician. He was born around 1707 in Garendon Park, Leicestershire. Ambrose Phillipps sat in the House of Commons from 1734 to 1737. He was also known as an amateur architect. Phillipps was the eldest son of William Phillipps and Jane Dashwood. He studied at Magdalen College, Oxford and inherited Garendon in 1729. Phillipps traveled to France and Italy, where he developed an interest in architecture. He used his architectural knowledge to design the gardens and extensions of Garendon Hall. Phillipps was a member of the Society of Dilettanti around 1732. He became a Tory Member of Parliament for Leicestershire in 1734 and voted against the Government on the repeal of the Septennial Act. Phillipps passed away unmarried at the age of 30 on November 6, 1737. His brother completed Garendon Hall.
The Scripting Layer for Android, abbreviated as SL4A, is a library that allows the creation and running of scripts written in various scripting languages directly on Android devices. SL4A is designed for developers and is still alpha quality software. The main branch is no longer under active development, but other developers have forked the code to enable it to run on Android Lollipop and Android Marshmallow. Some examples include the "kuri65536" branch of SL4A and "droid-python". These scripts have access to many APIs available to Java Android applications with a simplified interface. The supported languages are Python using CPython, Perl, Ruby using JRuby, Lua, BeanShell, JavaScript using Rhino, Tcl, and Rexx using BRexx. SL4A was first announced by Google in June 2009 and was originally named "Android Scripting Environment" (ASE). It is not an official Google product, although many developers have worked for Google. Damon Kohler originally developed SL4A, and it has grown through the contributions of many developers.
"Bleu noir" is the eighth studio album by French singer Mylène Farmer, released on December 6, 2010. Farmer's label launched a website to promote the album on November 3, 2010. The album has been compared favorably to "Innamoramento" and previous albums like "Anamorphosée". Farmer wrote the lyrics for the album, with music composed by Moby, Archive, and RedOne. The first single, "Oui mais... non", was composed by RedOne and released on October 11, 2010. The music video for "Leila" premiered on the album's website on November 22, 2010. "Bleu noir" debuted at number one on the French Digital Chart and physical chart, setting sales records. In 2010, the album sold 328,783 copies. The second single, the title track "Bleu noir", was set to be released in February 2011 but was delayed due to remix production. The music video for "Bleu noir" premiered on March 16, 2011. On December 4, 2013, "Diabolique mon ange" was released as a single from Farmer's live album "Timeless 2013".
"Sineleutherus is an extinct genus of euharamiyids that existed in Asia during the Jurassic period. The type species is "Sineleutherus uyguricus", described by Thomas Martin, Alexander O. Averianov, and Hans-Ulrich Pfretzschner in 2010, living in what is now China during the late Jurassic (Oxfordian age) Qigu Formation. Another species, "Sineleutherus issedonicus", was described by A. O. Averianov, A. V. Lopatin, and S. A. Krasnolutskii in 2011, residing in what is now Sharypovsky District (Krasnoyarsk Krai, Russia) during the middle Jurassic (Bathonian age) from the upper part of the Itat Formation. However, it is now believed to represent several euharamiyid taxa not closely related to "Sineleutherus". Mammalian tooth marks on dinosaur bones may belong to "Sineleutherus", suggesting that some haramiyidans scavenged on dinosaur remains."
"Mike Springston is an American football coach. Mike Springston was born on December 24, 1956."
"Insaaf Main Karoongaa is a Hindi film directed by Shibu Mitra, produced by B.S. Seth and presented by S.K. Kapur. The film stars Rajesh Khanna, Tina Munim, and Padmini Kolhapure. Kishore Kumar sings 2 songs for Rajesh Khanna, while Bappi Lahiri sings another 2 songs picturised on Rajesh Khanna - "Ek Baras Mein Ek Baar Hi" and "Honey Honey Kuch Maanga Toh Dena". It is a remake of the Malayalam movie "Thushaaram". The movie was started after the success of Souten with the same starcast and was a Golden jubilee hit upon its release."
The Dzongkha Development Commission, also known as the DDC, is the primary authority on matters related to the Dzongkha language. It was officially established in 1986 by Jigme Singye Wangchuck, the fourth king of Bhutan, with the aim of preserving and promoting Dzongkha as the national language. The DDC is located in the Kawajangtsa area of Thimphu, near the National Library of Bhutan and the Ministry of Education. The Commission consists of nine members chaired by the Prime Minister of Bhutan, and the DDC Secretariat handles the daily operations. The DDC's responsibilities include promoting the use of Dzongkha, conducting research, publishing official dictionaries and grammar, developing new terminology, and creating software and fonts to support the language.
Perivale Halt railway station was a station on the New North Main Line of the Great Western Railway. It served the London suburb of Perivale from 1904 to 1947. In 1947, it was replaced by Perivale station on the Central line of the London Underground.
"The Deutschland Cup is an in-season international ice hockey tournament. The Deutschland Cup is hosted by the German Ice Hockey Federation. The Deutschland Cup has been contested in most years since 1987."
"Hatch Plain is a small debris-covered area located on the eastern margin of the Du Toit Nunataks in the Read Mountains of the Shackleton Range, Antarctica. It was photographed by the U.S. Navy in 1967 and surveyed by the British Antarctic Survey from 1968 to 1971. The UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee named it in 1971 in honor of Frederick H. Hatch, a British consulting geologist known for his work in igneous and sedimentary petrology."
"Hauge Reef is a chain of islands and rocks located in South Georgia. It was first charted in 1819 by a Russian expedition led by Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen. The reef was later surveyed by the South Georgia Survey in 1951-52 and named after Captain Ole Hauge, who was a sealer on the ship "Albatros" and provided valuable knowledge about the coasts of South Georgia."
Strelište Sports Hall is an indoor arena located in Pančevo with a capacity of 1,100 people. It serves as the home arena for KK Tamiš.
Heteroclinus whiteleggii, also known as Whitelegg's weedfish, is a species of clinid found in the reefs of New South Wales, Australia. This species can grow up to a maximum length of TL. The specific name of this species, whiteleggii, is in honor of the naturalist Thomas Whitelegge (1850-1927), who was a friend of Ogilby and collected the type specimen.
"Poteria is a genus of tropical land snails. Poteria belongs to the family Neocyclotidae. Poteria has gills and an operculum. Poteria is a type of terrestrial gastropod mollusks."
"Myxodes ornatus is a species of clinid. Myxodes ornatus is native to the Pacific coast of Chile, which is located in South America."
"Havfruen Peak is located in the eastern part of Bristol Island, South Sandwich Islands. It is a high peak that is easily visible from both the north and south. The peak was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1971 after the Norwegian barque "Havfruen," which sank off the South Sandwich Islands on December 1, 1911 due to ice damage."
"Hawker Island is an island located in Antarctica. It is situated about long, lying some 7 km south-west of Davis Station between Mule Island and Mule Peninsula, Vestfold Hills, in the eastern part of Prydz Bay. The island was mapped by Norwegian cartographers from aerial photographs taken by the Lars Christensen Expedition in 1936–37. It was later remapped by the Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions in 1957–58. Hawker Island was named after Alan Charles Hawker, who was a radio supervisor at Davis Station in 1957."
Mount Hedden is a nunatak located north of Brattskarvet Mountain in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. The name "Hedden-Berg" was given to the area by the Third German Antarctic Expedition (1938–39) in honor of Karl Hedden, a sailor with the expedition. The correlation of the name with this nunatak may be arbitrary but is recommended for the sake of international uniformity and historical continuity.
"Heckmann Island is the largest island in the eastern part of the Thorfinn Islands, located north of Byrd Head, Mac. Robertson Land, Antarctica. It was mapped by Norwegian cartographers from air photos taken during the Lars Christensen Expedition, 1936–37. The island was later remapped by the Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions and named after B. Heckmann, who was the chief officer on the "Nella Dan" in 1965."
"Heksegryta Peaks are a group of peaks located in Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. They are situated between Belgen Valley and Tverregg Glacier, within the Kirwan Escarpment. These peaks were mapped by Norwegian cartographers during the Norwegian–British–Swedish Antarctic Expedition (1949–52) using surveys and air photos. They were further documented in additional air photos taken in 1958–59. The peaks were named Hekesegryta, which translates to 'the witch's cauldron'."
The Motor Company of Botswana (Pty.) Ltd. was a joint venture between the Hyundai Motor Company and its local dealership Hyundai Motor Distributors (Pty.) Ltd. It was founded in 1992 with headquarters in Gaborone, Botswana. The company assembled Hyundai CKD kits from February 1993 until its closure in 2001. The company was co-founded by Billy Rautenbach, a wealthy businessman from Zimbabwe who also owned "Wheels of Africa," a large cargo trucking enterprise. Hyundai provided the CKD kits for the production of Hyundai models. Finished vehicles were sometimes imported from Mozambique, disassembled, reassembled, and exported to South Africa to take advantage of tax benefits. In 2000, the company, along with the Swedish Motor Corporation at the same location, went bankrupt due to high debts.
"Hudman Glacier is a glacier located in the Ellsworth Mountains of Antarctica. It is situated south of Mount Landolt between Marze Peak and Miller Peak in Petvar Heights at the south end of the Sentinel Range. The glacier flows south-southeast to Minnesota Glacier. Hudman Glacier was mapped by the United States Geological Survey and U.S. Navy from surveys and air photos taken between 1957 and 1959. It was named in honor of Captain Rayburn A. Hudman, a member of the United States Marine Corps who tragically passed away in a plane crash in Antarctica on October 18, 1956. The plane, a Lockheed P2V-2n Neptune, was modified for extreme range and equipped for landing on ice runways at McMurdo Sound."
The 1933 International University Games were organized by the Confederation Internationale des Etudiants (CIE) and held in Turin, Italy. The event took place from 1–10 September, with 27 nations competing in nine sports. Women participated in athletics, swimming, fencing, and tennis, with the latter two being debut events for women. This edition also saw the first appearance of African athletes at the competition, with delegations from South Africa and Egypt participating for the first time.
The 1937 International University Games were organized by the Confederation Internationale des Etudiants (CIE) and held in Paris, France. The games took place from August 21 to 29, with 22 nations competing in fourteen sports. Boxing, cycling, field hockey, handball, and shooting made their debut at the games. However, the gymnastics competition was omitted and did not return until 1961. This event also marked the first participation of a South American nation, Brazil.
"Strip Me" is the third studio album by the English singer and songwriter Natasha Bedingfield. It was released on December 7, 2010, by Phonogenic Records. "Touch" was released as the first single from the album on May 18, 2010, and "Strip Me" was released as the second single on August 31, 2010. The album's title song peaked at number twenty-three on the adult contemporary chart. The album debuted at number 103 on the US "Billboard" 200 with 10,000 copies sold. In Europe, "Strip Me" was released in May 2011 under the title Strip Me Away, charting only in Germany and Switzerland.
"The Rob Brydon Show is a British chat show hosted by comedian Rob Brydon. The first series of the show started on September 17, 2010, and included six regular episodes, a compilation episode, and a Christmas special. The second series also had six regular episodes, a Christmas special, and a compilation episode. The third and final series of the show consisted of six regular episodes."
Joe Shea was the editor-in-chief of "The American Reporter", the first daily Internet newspaper, which was started on April 10, 1995. He was also the named plaintiff in the First Amendment case, "Shea v Reno", which resulted in the Communications Decency Act being declared unconstitutional in Manhattan Federal Court and affirmed in the U. S. Supreme Court in 1997. Joe Shea was a community activist known for his efforts to clean up a dangerous neighborhood in Hollywood, California, which was praised as a national model for Neighborhood Watch. He was born in Goshen, New York, to Mr. & Mrs. John S. Shea, Jr., of Monroe and New York City. Joe Shea's grandfather, John S. Shea, was elected Sheriff of New York in 1909, the first Republican to be elected in Manhattan since Reconstruction. Joe Shea also started the Committee to Draft U.S. Senator John Kerry, aiming to get the Massachusetts senator into the 1988 Presidential race.
"Oothikachiya Ponnu is an Indian Malayalam-language film. Oothikachiya Ponnu was directed by P. K. Joseph and written by V. K. Pavithran. The film reunited Mohanlal, Shanker, and Poornima Jayaram after 'Manjil Virinja Pookkal' (1980). The film also features Mammootty."
Oggar is a fictional character known as the World's Mightiest Immortal. He originated from Fawcett Comics and later became part of DC Comics in the 1970s. Oggar was a villain in the Captain Marvel chronology during the Pre-Crisis era but did not appear in the Post-Crisis stories. His first appearance was in "Captain Marvel Adventures" #61 in May 1946 by Fawcett Comics. In DC Comics, he first appeared in "World's Finest Comics" #264 in August 1980. Oggar was a significant adversary of the Marvels in the DC Comics stories before the "Crisis on Infinite Earths" miniseries in 1985.
Olaine Station is a railway station located on the 22nd kilometer of the Riga - Jelgava Railway in Olaine, Latvia. Olaine Station was opened on November 21, 1868.
Oliver Samuel was a Member of Parliament from the Taranaki Region of New Zealand. Oliver Samuel was born in Saint Helier, Jersey in 1849. Oliver Samuel emigrated to New Zealand with his family in 1855. Oliver Samuel was educated at Nelson College from 1863 to 1865. He represented the New Plymouth electorate until 1890 when he retired. On January 22, 1907, he was appointed to the Legislative Council and was reappointed on July 14, 1914, and July 14, 1921. Oliver Samuel remained a member until his death on January 11, 1925. From November 19, 1918, until his death, he served as the Chairman of Committees.
Shafqat Rasool is a Pakistani field hockey player. Shafqat Rasool was born on December 10, 1988 in Toba Tek Singh.
"The Marshalleck Stadium is a football stadium located in Benque Viejo Town, Belize. The stadium was created in 1950 by Corporal Marshalleck, who cleared the tropical bush to build it. It serves as the home stadium for the Belize Premier Football League team, Hankook Verdes United, with a capacity of 2,000 people."
The 2005 Cork Senior Hurling Championship was the 117th staging of the Cork Senior Hurling Championship since its establishment by the Cork County Board in 1887. The draw for the 2005 fixtures took place at the Cork Convention on December 12, 2004. The championship began on May 27, 2005, and ended on October 16, 2005. Na Piarsaigh were the defending champions, however, they were defeated by University College Cork at the quarter-final stage. On October 16, 2005, Newtownshandrum won the championship following a 0-15 to 0-09 defeat of Cloyne in the final. This was their third championship title overall and their first in two championship seasons. Cloyne's Paudie O'Sullivan was the championship's top scorer with 3-19.
Jeremy Gibbons is a computer scientist and professor of computing at the University of Oxford. Jeremy Gibbons serves as Deputy Director of the Software Engineering Programme in the Department of Computer Science. Jeremy Gibbons is also a Governing Body Fellow at Kellogg College and Pro-Proctor of the University of Oxford.
Parfait-Louis Monteil was a French colonial military officer and explorer. He made an epic journey in West Africa between 1890 and 1892, travelling east from Senegal to Lake Chad, and then north across the Sahara to Tripoli. Parfait-Louis Monteil passed away on September 29, 1925.
Stadion FK Baník Sokolov is a multi-purpose stadium located in Sokolov, Czech Republic. It serves as the home ground for FK Baník Sokolov football club. The stadium has a capacity of 5,000 spectators, with 770 seats as of 2012.
Vice Admiral Charles Fellowes was a Royal Navy officer. Vice Admiral Charles Fellowes served as Commander-in-Chief of the Channel Fleet. Vice Admiral Charles Fellowes lived from October 19, 1823, to March 8, 1886.
"Tantsud tähtedega" (Estonian: "Dancing with the Stars") is an Estonian television reality show airing on Kanal 2. It debuted on October 8, 2006, and has become a popular television show in Estonia. The show is based on the British reality show "Strictly Come Dancing" and is produced by BEC productions. The show features eight Estonian celebrities paired with professional ballroom dancers who compete each week to impress a panel of judges and the viewing public to avoid elimination. Viewers vote for their favorite couples through a telephone poll, with 50% of the public votes and the judges' scores determining who stays and who leaves. The proceeds from the voting go to charity. The show has had four seasons produced in 2006, 2007, 2008, and 2010.
Thorsten Görke is a German former footballer. Thorsten Görke was born on September 22, 1976.
George Hazlett was a Scottish professional footballer. George Hazlett played as an outside-forward. George Hazlett was born in Glasgow on March 10, 1923. During the Second World War, he served in the Royal Navy and played as a guest player for Plymouth Argyle and Celtic. After the war, he joined Celtic permanently for two seasons before moving to Belfast Celtic in 1948. He later played for Football League side Bury, making over 100 appearances in a three-year spell. George Hazlett also spent one season with Cardiff City before joining Millwall in 1953, where he made more than 130 league appearances before transitioning into non-league football.
"Arestorides is a genus of sea snails. Arestorides belongs to the family Cypraeidae, which are marine gastropod mollusks. Cypraeidae are commonly known as cowries."
"Dobele Station is a railway station. Dobele Station is located on the Jelgava – Liepāja Railway. Jelgava and Liepāja Railway are connected through Dobele Station."
Faavae Faauliuli is a weightlifter from Samoa. Faavae Faauliuli won Samoa's first-ever gold medal at the Commonwealth Games by lifting 334 kg in the New Delhi Games in 2010. Faavae Faauliuli was rewarded with US$21,000 by the Samoan Government. Faavae Faauliuli also competed in Glasgow.
"Tore Station is a railway station. Tore Station is located on the Jelgava – Liepāja Railway."
"Clear the Ring" is a French comedy drama film from 1950. The film is directed by Pierre Billon and written by Christian-Falaize. It stars Grock and Louis de Funès. The French title of the film is "Au revoir M. Grock". The German title of the film is "Grock: Der Mann der die Welt zum Lachen brachte" or "Manege frei".
The 325th Air Control Squadron was a part of the 325th Fighter Wing, based at the United States Air Force's Tyndall Air Force Base in Florida. Originally constituted as the 325th Fighter Control Squadron in March 1943, the 325th served in the Mediterranean Theatre of Operations during WWII. Radar operations and maintenance have been taught to tens of thousands of personnel of all ranks over the past decades. Following the transfer of the 325th Fighter Wing to Air Combat Command, the 325th Air Control Squadron was replaced by the 337th Air Control Squadron under the 33rd Fighter Wing at Eglin Air Force Base on October 12, 2012.
Level 5 Motorsports was an American auto racing team founded in 2006 by Scott Tucker. Scott Tucker is currently serving a sentence of 16 years and 8 months in federal prison. Level 5 Motorsports competed in the United SportsCar Championship and Ferrari Challenge, winning multiple American Le Mans Series championships and endurance races such as the 24 Hours of Daytona, 12 Hours of Sebring, and Petit Le Mans. The team started with Tucker competing in the Sports Car Club of America and Ferrari Challenge Series. In 2007, Tucker entered events in the Rolex Sports Car Series and Koni Challenge Series with co-driver Ed Zabinski. Tucker also participated in the IMSA GT3 Cup Challenge.
Mount Schicht is a prominent mountain with several summits, located 4 nautical miles (7 km) west-southwest of Ritscher Peak in the Gruber Mountains of Queen Maud Land. The feature was discovered by the German Antarctic Expedition under Ritscher in 1938–39 and named Schichtberge (stratum mountains) due to its appearance. Ufsebotnen Cirque is situated 1 mile (1.6 km) north of the summit and was discovered and plotted from air photos by the German Antarctic Expedition in 1938–39. It was later re-plotted from air photos and surveys by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition in 1956–60 and named Ufsebotnen (the bluff cirque).
Scarlett Point is a point located on the west side of Phyllis Bay at the southern end of Montagu Island in the South Sandwich Islands. It was charted in 1930 by DI personnel on the "Discovery II" and was named after E.W.A. Scarlett, who was an accountant on the staff of the Discovery Committee.
"Savoia Peak is a peak, 1,415 m, located at the northeast end of Sierra DuFief, a mountain range in the southwest part of Wiencke Island, in the Palmer Archipelago. It was discovered by the Belgian Antarctic Expedition under Gerlache in 1898 and scaled by members of the French Antarctic Expedition under Charcot from 1903 to 1905. The peak was named by Charcot in honor of Luigi di Savoia, Duke of the Abruzzi."
Amadou Karim Gaye was a Senegalese veterinarian, physician, and politician from Saint-Louis. Amadou Karim Gaye served as the Foreign Minister of Senegal from 1968 to 1972.
"Tornes is a village in Hustadvika Municipality in Møre og Romsdal county, Norway. The village is located along the Julsundet strait at the mouth of the Frænfjorden. Tornes is about west of the municipal center of Elnesvågen and about south of the village of Bud. The village has a population of 557 as of 2018."
Sandneset Point is the northern point of Furdesanden Moraine in the Conrad Mountains of the Orvin Mountains, Queen Maud Land. Sandneset Point was discovered and photographed by the German Antarctic Expedition, 1938–39. It was mapped by Norway from surveys and air photos by the Norwegian Antarctic Expedition, 1956–60, and named Sandneset (the sand point).
